<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DO INEVITABLE IN FIRING HARRIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; In these days of change, when the Lakers' nose rings outnumber
their championship rings, isn't it comforting to know they still do
one thing the old-fashioned way?
</P>
<P>
   They fired Del Harris on Wednesday for the oldest reason in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   The team was off to an unimaginably rotten start _ 6-6, tied for
fourth, with !ital!Sacramento _ and, as they've been saying
probably since John Kundla was the Minneapolis Lakers' coach in the
'40s, you can't fire the players.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers finished 1997-98 with a four-and-out playoff loss to
the methodical Utah Jazz that highlighted their weaknesses and set
the bar for their improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Then they showed little evidence of improvement in the first
three weeks of the condensed NBA season. They were humbled again at
the Forum by the Jazz, which used the same pick-and-roll tactics as
last spring. They were outsmarted at the end of a tight game at the
Forum by the Indiana Pacers, a veteran team with a Jazz
resemblance. They were 0-4 against teams with winning records at
tipoff, and then they lost back-to-back to hapless Denver and
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents had been saying things like this, from Indiana's
Antonio Davis: ``I think they just need to learn to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Lakers are talented but would need time to
acquire the intelligence and !tal!esprit de corps to get over the
Utah hump.
</P>
<P>
   Unless . . . you thought the coach was at fault for failing to
drum those qualities into them. Which, it developed, Lakers vice
president Jerry West or owner Jerry Buss or both determined to be
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Bill Bertka is in charge for tonight's game
against the Clippers at The Pond, or until the front office chooses
between assistants Kurt Rambis and Larry Drew, or until Phil
Jackson can hop a plane.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth Lakers season for Harris, 61. His most
impressive accomplishment was coaxing higher regular-season win
totals out of the team in each of the first four. His most damning
failure was finishing second or third in the Pacific Division each
time and never reaching the NBA final.
</P>
<P>
   The departure last summer of the team's most divisive figure,
point guard Nick Van Exel, inspired visions of Aquarian harmony in
the locker room and a breakthrough year for the young Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when they lost three straight this week _ an embarrassment
mitigated only a bit by the fact they were playing the first
all-on-the-road back-to-back-to-back games by an NBA team in Kobe
Bryant's lifetime _ Lakers players cited a continued lack of
chemistry as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to, I guess, point the finger at somebody,'' forward
Corey Blount said after the firing. ``I guess it was just time for
a change. To me you can't put all the blame on the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But coaching is a bottom-line business and Harris was headed for
a 14th season as an NBA head coach without a division title to his
credit.
</P>
<P>
   And he walked a short plank to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   By declining to extend his contract, which runs out in June,
Lakers executives signaled that Harris hadn't accomplished what
they'd hoped and perhaps never would. He began the season as a
gimpy, if not lame, duck.
</P>
<P>
   A calm and courtly man, holder of degrees in religion and
history, noted for painstakingly precise speech, Harris never
played basketball after Milligan College in Tennessee, making it
harder to connect with NBA players who appreciate war wounds.
</P>
<P>
   When Lakers players needed somebody to light a fire under them,
Harris had the look of a wet match.
</P>
<P>
   His firing _ sooner, later or at the end of the season _ seemed
as inevitable as a Lakers losing streak under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   They've played a hard schedule _ already facing Utah, Indiana,
San Antonio and Seattle in the first 10 games. They've played every
game but one with a predicted opening-night starter in street
clothes for health reasons _ Robert Horry, Shaquille O'Neal and/or
Rick Fox.
</P>
<P>
   They might just miss Van Exel more than they expected,
especially in light of third-year point guard Derek Fisher's crisis
of confidence, brought on by playing fewer minutes than Derek
Harper most nights and then getting benched.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense continues to run one direction _ through O'Neal,
who has led the Lakers scoring in every game he has played.
</P>
<P>
   And they've spent the month trying to figure out what's more
distracting _ the Dennis Rodman contract circus or having to deny
it's a distraction over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those problems are Del Harris' fault, some aren't.
Whatever, it was time for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Change usually doesn't mean signing a guy with nose rings. But
it always means firing the coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
