<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-SPIERS-HNS     02-25 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-SPIERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Bill Spiers is regarded as a jack-of-all-trades
player who can help his team in just about any capacity imaginable.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the trait that often goes unnoticed is an unselfish approach
that makes Spiers the ultimate team player. Sure, he can play every
position on the diamond with the exception of pitcher and catcher _
and that may be only because no one has asked him _ but Spiers also
has the rare ability to swallow his pride and act in the best
interests of the team.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it might have appeared Spiers was pushed into
the background when the Astros signed free-agent third baseman Ken
Caminiti. But Spiers was one of the people working behind the
scenes to pave Caminiti's way back to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers and Caminiti never have been teammates prior to this
season, but they share common friends in Jeff Bagwell and Craig
Biggio. Caminiti was well aware of how highly Spiers is regarded in
the Astros' clubhouse, and the last thing he wanted to do was
ruffle feathers unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people probably thought this caught me off-guard, but
it really didn't,'' Spiers said. ``Before Cammy signed, he called
me and asked how I would feel about him coming to the Astros, and I
told him I'd love to have him as a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten to know him through some of the other guys on the
team, and I know he can help us. That's really the only thing that
matters. To me, you can't get caught up in worrying about a lot of
other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know I'd rather have him on the team than not have him.
He makes us better, and I've always dreamed of being on a team like
this. He has a personality that fits right in with our club. I was
all for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Caminiti would have signed with the Astros
regardless of Spiers' response, but the fact he asked is an
indication of how Spiers is regarded by his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for Billy Spiers,'' Caminiti said.
``I just felt like I should ask him about it as a courtesy. I
didn't want to step on anybody's feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Caminiti's signing made the Astros a better overall
team, it raised all sorts of questions regarding Spiers' role. For
the past two seasons, Spiers shared third base with Sean Berry, but
it's safe to say Caminiti will get a large majority of the playing
time at third base in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiers is Mr. Versatility,'' Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said. ``He can play every position on the infield, and
he'll most likely be our top lefthanded pinch hitter off the bench.
I'm not sure (manager) Larry (Dierker) would be opposed to running
him out to the outfield every now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   The outfield? Now, there's an intriguing possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, Richard Hidalgo is the starting left fielder
now that Moises Alou is likely out for the season. But the Astros
are exploring all of their options with regard to outfield depth,
and Spiers might figure into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only played a few innings in the outfield since I've been
in the big leagues,'' said Spiers, who has a .283 batting average
in his three seasons with the Astros. ``But I'm willing to leave
that possibility open.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that type of attitude that makes Spiers one of Hunsicker's
most cherished acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Spiers is the consummate team player,'' said Hunsicker,
who signed Spiers as a free agent in 1996. ``He has no problem
putting the team before himself. In my mind, he's going to be just
as important to our team as he has been the past two seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiers is likely to get the bulk of his playing time at
shortstop, depending on how he plays the position during the
spring. The 32-year-old former first-round pick of the Milwaukee
Brewers broke into the big leagues as a shortstop in 1989, but
there is some concern about his range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortstop is going to be the key to his playing time,''
Hunsicker said. ``If, in fact, Dierk has the confidence to put him
there, that's another real option.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what the higher-ups decide, Spiers seems willing
to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win, and I want what's best for the team,'' he
said. ``Somehow, some way, I know I'm going to get my
opportunities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
