r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     02-25 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS' DEMISE INEVITABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the more dramatic 24-hour periods in the history of
the Los Angeles Lakers, the team Wednesday hired a wacky Generation
X cult figure, Dennis Rodman, and fired their 61-year-old coach,
avuncular-looking Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The two monumental events are unrelated, but they do reflect a
restlessness and impatience uncommon to a revered Southern
California athletic team whose hallmark throughout the seasons has
been its stability. The gentleman who pulled the trigger on both
decisions, Jerry Buss, owner of the Lakers, is not a man given to
such intemperate deportment, having hitherto run a well-respected
franchise that has won five NBA championships since he bought it
from Jack Kent Cooke in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Buss only twice before has a detached a coach during a
season, with the first coming on Nov. 19, 1981, when he replaced
Paul Westhead with Chick Hearn's radio partner, fellow named Pat
Riley. The second time came on March 23, 1994, when Magic Johnson
took over for Randy Pfund.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that Buss finally came to the conclusion that his
vice-president of basketball operations, Jerry West, came to in the
middle of last season that Del Harris wasn't the proper fit for
this Laker team.
</P>
<P>
   Buss ignored West's advice to get rid of Harris then, and also
ignored West's advice to get rid of Harris in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   But, apparently, Buss had a drastic change of heart after
watching his wealthy, underachieving Laker players Shaquille O'Neal
alone earns $16 million a season lose back-to-back road games this
week to the lowly Denver Nuggets and Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   Many Laker players long had been voicing off-the-record
misgivings about Harris, despising his slow-motion,
pitch-the-ball-into-Shaq attack, abhorring his unpredictable
substituting patterns, hating his constant chattering at practices
and during games, just plain loathing him as their leader.
</P>
<P>
   The grumbling from people like O'Neal and Kobe Bryant had
reportedly reached a reverberating crescendo in recent days with
the team performing below expectations during a 6-6 start in this
abbreviated NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' long-time assistant coach, Bill Bertka, 71, will
assume the head coaching duties for the team's game tonight against
the Los Angeles Clippers at the Pond, but Laker sources say another
assistant, Kurt Rambis, is Buss' top choice to permanently succeed
Harris. Larry Drew, another Laker assistant, also has been
mentioned as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The question now being asked by many observers keen to Laker
goings-on is not why Jerry Buss fired Del Harris, but, instead, why
he didn't fire him a year ago, when Jerry West recommended he do
so.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time that Buss unfailingly listened to West, but
that no longer appears to be the case, with the signing of Rodman
the latest example of Buss' defiance toward West.
</P>
<P>
   West was the architect of the mighty Lakers' Showtime dynasty of
the 1980s, and one of its enduring legacies was its remarkable
avoidance of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   It was West's policy to stock the Laker roster with solid
citizen types who preferred spending more time in gyms than in
gambling casinos, tattoo parlors, hair salons, etc. There were a
few bumps along the way James Worthy being nabbed for soliciting a
prostitute in Houston being the most notable exception but Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, Magic Johnson, Byron Scott, Michael Cooper, Jamaal
Wilkes and the others usually got their names mentioned by the
media for their basketball heroics, not for claiming to sleep with
Madonna, or for coloring their hair, or for festooning their bodies
with tattoos, or their faces with rings.
</P>
<P>
   West always has shied away from players carrying heavy baggage,
and it would take a couple Fed-X jets to haul around all the
luggage Dennis Rodman brings with him to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As do all people in their later years, especially rich ones
nearing 70, Jerry Buss has changed, and the impact of such a
metamorphosis already has been negatively felt by the Lakers when
Buss nixed an Eddie Jones-for-Mitch Richmond trade that West had
made a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see what will develop in the upcoming
weeks from Buss' risk-laden acquisition of Rodman, although the
feeling here is that a Laker turnabout will take more than adding
Rodman and subtracting Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it about time the Lakers go out and locate a legitimate
point guard and dump those two impersonators who've been laughably
playing the position, Messrs. Derek Fisher and Derek Harper?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it about time someone informs their 20-year-old prodigy,
Kobe Bryant, that he isn't Michael Jordan, will never be Michael
Jordan, and that he should stop gunning and making foolish passes
and just start learning how to become a team player like, say,
Michael Jordan was?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it about time someone tells Shaquille O'Neal that there is
more to playing basketball than dunking it, and that one of his
noble predecessors, Wilt Chamberlain, to this day has been unable
to live down his deserved image as a loser because he performed in
the same I-want-to-score-my-points,
the-heck-with-getting-down-on-defense style throughout so much of
his career?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it about time the Lakers either trade Elden Campbell and
Eddie Jones, or send them to Kosovo to do peace monitoring duties
for NATO, or at least desist with their policy of letting them
dangle haplessly from the precipice?
</P>
<P>
   Now that Del Harris follows Paul Westhead and Randy Pfund into
Laker coaching oblivion, is this team that has stumbled so
erratically set to rebound under the guidance of a new coach as it
did 18 years ago, when it won 17 of its first 20 games under Pat
Riley?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Laker players, who had grown to detest Harris even
though the past three years he had led them to 170 regular season
victories, will emerge from their season-long funk under the new
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Derek Harper or Derek Fisher will start doing what the
departed Nick Van Exel was able to do on occasion when a game was
on the line make big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Shaquille O'Neal will start blocking more shots and making
more of his free throws and maybe Kobe Bryant will start displaying
more discipline and shooting accuracy and maybe Eddie Jones finally
can find consistency and Elden Campbell can find passion.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Kurt Rambis, or Larry Drew, or both can inspire these
Lakers to heights they never were able to reach under Harris, a
nice man who found himself in the wrong place at the wrong time
with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and maybe Dennis Rodman will not create a tense locker
room atmosphere with his zany antics, and maybe I one day will be
mistaken for Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   There may not have been a coach in the NBA who knew more about
X's and O's than Del Harris, but such clinical knowledge seemed
quite irrelevant on a young, spoiled Laker team comprised of
players who simply couldn't relate to a silver-haired coach from
another era.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss was left with no alternative, in light of the Lakers'
unpromising beginning and hatred of Harris.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't fire O'Neal or Bryant, or any of the others. So Del
Harris had to go even though his departure doesn't figure to make
that much difference on a team that still has too many open wounds
festering on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
