<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-INJURIES-     02-25 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-INJURIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Carroll Dawson, the Rockets' executive vice president of
basketball, stood in the tunnel leading to the Compaq Center court
last week, watching his players blow out the Phoenix Suns.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A passer-by jutted a thumb toward the court and said, ``That's
one heck of a team you have there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson nodded but couldn't resist the obvious reply: ``The team
we have in the training room isn't bad, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, how else to best sum up the Rockets' season so far?
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten amid an interminable road trip and agonizing schedule
is the fact the Rockets have managed to keep their heads above
water, taking a 7-4 record into tonight's home game against the
Atlanta Hawks while playing without four of their key players.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, Antoine Carr, Rodrick Rhodes and Stanley
Roberts, all of whom are expected to play big roles in any
championship drive, have been out with injuries for much or all of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the trainer's-room All-Stars are almost ready to return.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes and Carr participated in their first real basketball
workouts Wednesday, and both are lobbying for a quick return to the
roster, perhaps as soon as tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Relief, at last, for Rudy Tomjanovich and his coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to push the issue (of returning to the lineup)
now,'' said Rhodes, who had been out after undergoing surgery to
repair a torn right pectoral tendon. ``I took some licks on my
shoulder, and it didn't hurt it at all. I took some real good pops
today. I don't know how they (the coaches) feel, but I want to
start playing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited, and I'm just happy that this is over with my
chest. It was frustrating. I was getting tired of just not doing
anything. I want to get back, and I don't care what they think or
what the doctors say, my chest is fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   As is Carr's right knee, which underwent arthroscopic surgery to
repair an ``acute chondral injury'' on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great being able to get back on the floor,'' Carr
said. ``I finally got some banging in. I just have to keep going
from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr, like Rhodes, said he wants to return as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully within the next few games,'' said Carr. ``I just
have to keep working and get my aerobic conditioning back up, since
I wasn't able to do much (conditioning work) with the knee. Other
than that, I'm ready to bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley reiterated that he wants to be back for either Sunday's
game in Los Angeles against the Lakers or Tuesday's home game
against the San Antonio Spurs. He went through his first hard
workout since undergoing surgery to repair torn cartilage in his
left knee and will go through another tough workout today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I originally got hurt, we said that I would be back in
two to three weeks,'' Barkley said. ``Hopefully, it will go well
for me (today) when I have the big test. It's going to be sore for
a couple of weeks, but I'm going to try and do a lot more (today)
and see how it goes. Worst-case scenario, it will be Tuesday (when
he returns).''
</P>
<P>
   And Barkley, like the others, intends to return full-force.
There will be no easing back into the grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play sports like that,'' Barkley said. ``You either
go out there and play hard the whole time, or you shouldn't be out
there. If you have to pace yourself, you can't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous to go out there when you're taking a little bit
off,'' he said. ``A lot of times, that's when you get hurt. I think
you have to play your natural game, whatever that is. It seems to
work better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he hasn't had any of the players come to him
and demand to be put back in the rotation, even though he
understands they might be getting antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been put in that position yet,'' Tomjanovich said.
``Today is like a test day for Antoine, going contact right now,
and Charles still hasn't had any contact. But he (Barkley) is
always whispering in my ear, `I'm just about there, coach.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to what the doctors say _ that's their field. We'll
see how it goes. We want to keep our focus on the big picture, and
that's being ready at the end, when it really counts _ in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich has been busy trying to draw up a game plan that
will best take advantage of what new starters Scottie Pippen,
Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley bring to the team. And having
all these players coming in at roughly the same time will make that
job even more taxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of guys close to coming back,''
Tomjanovich said. ``We've got to be patient and get them in
physically but also the mental part. We're still changing things
and trying to find out what's best for this personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a transition _ what plays are best for these
new guys? We have three new guys in the starting lineup, so we're
looking at a lot of different things. And our guys have been very
patient. Hopefully, we'll hit on some basic sets and basic tactics
that everybody will be comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody'' is exactly right with this team. After all the
injuries, the Rockets find themselves with a roster full of guys
who are ready _ and able _ to contribute to a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people forget that we're 12 deep,'' Carr
said. ``We have a lot of good players. A lot of guys can do other
things, and we're going to have to use all of that. But the four
guys that were out are definitely guys that can make a
difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
