<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8552 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXAS-BAYLOR-HNS &LR;      02-25 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-BAYLOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Texas coach Rick Barnes inherited a team in turmoil and
watched his players lose seven of their first nine games this
season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That difficult transition must have seemed like a distant memory
Wednesday night when the Longhorns clinched the Big 12
regular-season championship, capping one of the most amazing
turnarounds in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Texas easily defeated hapless Baylor 62-52 at the Ferrell Center
in a game that displayed two teams at opposite ends of the
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   The 22nd-ranked Longhorns (18-10, 13-2 Big 12) claimed their
first outright conference championship since the 1993-94 Southwest
Conference season. The Longhorns were co-SWC champs with Texas Tech
in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a regular-season championship, you have to have mental
toughness, and you have to have discipline over a two-month
period,'' Barnes said. ``It says a lot about these players. I think
what meant the most to me tonight was the support of our fans. They
came up here and let our players know how much they appreciate what
the team has done.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 5,711, most of whom were UT fans, made it seem like
a home game for the Longhorns. Late in the second half, the Texas
fans began chanting ``Big 12 champs'' and did it again when the
players stood in front of them after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has won eight of its last nine games and 14 of its last
16. Baylor (6-22, 0-15), on the other hand, is one loss away from
becoming the first Big 12 team to go winless in league play.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Clack led the Longhorns with 21 points, and Nnadubem
``Gabe'' Muoneke added 16. Center Chris Mihm had his 15th double
double of the season, amassing 12 rebounds, 10 points and five
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so exciting for us,'' Muoneke said. ``I'm just so
happy that coach Barnes came here and did what he did. Now, we want
to win the Big 12 Tournament and put all the doubters to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear early in Wednesday's game that Baylor wasn't going
to challenge the Longhorns. Texas led 34-17 at the half after
holding the Bears to 31.6-percent shooting (6-of-19) and
outrebounding Baylor 19-12 in the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had its biggest lead at 40-19 after a baseline jumper by
Clack with 16:30 to go. Baylor never made a serious run, but the
Bears cut an 18-point deficit to 10 in the final three minutes.
Baylor forward Jamie Kendrick was the top scorer with 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has come a long way,'' said Baylor coach Harry Miller.
``They are a tough outfit that is well-coached. If they continue to
get a little perimeter shooting, they are going to be tough to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   While Barnes is headed for conference Coach of the Year honors,
Miller's time at Baylor might be coming to an end. There have been
rumors and speculation for weeks that Baylor will have a new
basketball coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a tough year, but all the guys have continued to
play hard,'' Miller said. ``I just hope we can play a few games in
the (Big 12) tournament and go out on a good note.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has one league game left, a home date with Missouri on
Saturday. Regardless of the outcome, the 'Horns will be the top
seed in the Big 12 Tournament, which begins a week from today in
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   UT will have a bye in the first round before playing at noon
March 5 against the winner of a first-round matchup. Baylor will be
the 12th seed and play at 2:20 p.m. March 4 against the No. 5 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Having a bye in the opening round should be beneficial to a
Texas team that rarely uses more than eight players. It has been an
amazing season for the Longhorns, who were 4-8 when conference play
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back from LSU (at 2-7), that's when we decided to
become a team,'' Barnes said. ``Everyone put his ego aside, and the
chemistry started to click. Each person truly evaluated what he
could bring to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes took over a team in disarray after Tom Penders was fired
last spring because of a players revolt. Two key players _ shooting
guard Luke Axtell and point guard Bernard Smith _ transferred to
other schools. When it was all settled, Barnes was left with only
eight scholarship players, and he lost one of those _ backup center
Marlon Drakes _ to a broken foot early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also was making a 180-degree change from the style of
play Texas used under Penders, going from a run-and-gun,
offensive-minded team to an aggressive, half-court defensive team
with a structured offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I wanted them to become one of the best half-court
defensive teams in the country, and I wanted them to prepare hard
in practice,'' Barnes said. ``We committed to a style of play,
locked in on it and went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to develop better habits, and it took some time. I told
them there are many seasons within a season. First preseason, then
came our trip to Hawaii, then conference. The Big 12 Tournament
will be a new life, and postseason will be another. This is not a
sprint; it's a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Clack said the players never lost faith in what Barnes was
trying to teach them early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of putting it together as a team,'' Clack
said. ``We stayed positive, and we knew we had the players to do
it. We are looking for bigger and better things now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
