<HEADLINE>
DUNN GETS TOP FUEL INSPIRATION FROM GWYNN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mike Dunn had listened to his father, he wouldn't be driving
a Top Fuel dragster today.
</P>
<P>
   If Dunn had given in to his critics, he would have called it
quits during winless 1997 and 1998 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a grinning Dunn graces the cover of the current issue
of ``National Dragster'' as owner of the national elapsed-time
record and winner of the prestigious NHRA Winternationals.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn got all that done during the rain-plagued season opener at
Pomona Raceway in California. He collected every point available
under National Hot Rod Association rules and earned overdue
recognition for himself and inspirational team owner Darrell Gwynn.
Dunn heads into the NHRA event at Firebird International Raceway
this weekend in Phoenix as the Top Fuel points leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had set the national elapsed-time record, and I've
been doing this for 18 years,'' said Dunn, 42, who earned the No. 1
qualifying spot by covering Pomona's quarter-mile in 4.503 seconds.
That ET became the record when it was backed up by a first-round
pass in 4.513 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Those are message-sending numbers by Dunn, runner-up to Gary
Scelzi at four races last year. Three of those final-round defeats
came in consecutive national events in midsummer, and helped propel
Scelzi to his second Winston Top Fuel title.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn finished fifth in points in 1998, the sixth season in which
he has placed in the Top Fuel top 10. During the off-season,
however, Dunn said Gwynn and tuner Ken Veney decided they were
going to stop racing the Team Mopar car like also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell's always talking about going to the next level. That
competitive spirit has never died in him,'' Dunn said of Gwynn, 36,
whose Top Fuel driving career ended when he was paralyzed in a
crash on Easter Sunday 1990 in England. ``All you \Rmedia\S guys
talk about is Scelzi and Cory McClenathan and Kenny Bernstein and
Joe Amato. Now we hope that you're going to mention us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's love affair with drag racing was sparked by his father,
Jim, a pioneer match-racer from Southern California in the 1970s
and subject of the classic movie ``Funny Car Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father never encouraged me to do this,'' Dunn said. ``He
was a fireman and did it as a hobby on the weekends. He never
really thought you could make a living at it. But like most kids, I
never listened to my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was a part-time Top Fuel shoe in 1993 when he joined Gwynn,
who motors around the pits in a wheelchair. Through the trying
times since their last victory in 1996, it is Gwynn who has emerged
as Dunn's everyday hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't get me wrong, because we do argue,'' Dunn said.
``Darrell, since I've been with him, has never complained about the
cards he's been dealt. When I'm not winning a race, I've got no
right to complain. There's going to be another race in two weeks.
He can't \Rdrive\S and he's not complaining. That has helped me out
immensely in my career. I think it's helped me mature.''
SPOTLIGHT ON... Arie Luyendyk LUYENDYK EXIT MAY FOIL TEXAS MOTOR
SPEEDWAY
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk's intention to retire after running the 83rd
Indianapolis 500 on May 30 presents a potentially sticky marketing
situation at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   As in, what if Luyendyk wins The Greatest Spectacle in Racing?
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of
TMS, has promoted and built the Pep Boys Indy Racing League event
in Fort Worth on two premises the past two Junes _ as the first
nighttime Indy-car race in modern history, and as the first
appearance of the new Indy 500 champion since the victory at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   If Luyendyk wins his third Indy 500 and hangs up his helmet,
Gossage will have to come up with another ticket-selling hook.
</P>
<P>
   Or will he?
</P>
<P>
   ``You better believe I'll be talking to Arie in Victory Lane at
Indianapolis, threatening him if necessary,'' Gossage said
good-naturedly Tuesday. Earlier, Luyendyk had unveiled the No. 5
Sprint PCS G Force/Aurora he will drive for car owner Fred
Treadway, and a commemorative ``Arie's Final 500'' logo during a
news conference at the Speedway Hall of Fame Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Dutchman reiterated that his decision to run
Indy and retire is firm. The Longhorn 500K on June 12 will have to
go on without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind this is my final race,'' Luyendyk said. ``I
put all my thought into it at the end of last year. My wife
\RMieke\S said it best: `Even when you're 60 you'll still have the
urge to drive a race car.' Well, I'm 45 and I'm going to end my
career here. A lot of athletes have retired and somebody throws a
lot of money at them \Rto return\S. But if I win at Indy, that will
be the ultimate and perfect way to end my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk carved his place in motorsports history with Indy 500
victories in 1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The latter victory was followed by the inaugural and
controversial True Value 500K at TMS on June 6, 1997. The race was
plagued by a series of electronic scoring glitches, and when Billy
Boat was declared the winner, Luyendyk crashed the party in Victory
Lane to protest that he had won. Luyendyk was promptly slapped
upside the head and knocked to the ground by car owner A.J. Foyt in
what has become one of TMS' signature moments.
</P>
<P>
   After an overnight audit by the U.S. Auto Club, Luyendyk was
declared the winner the next day. Foyt, however, has stubbornly
refused to return the trophy. Gossage has awarded Luyendyk a copy
of the original hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if Arie comes to Texas, I'll go get him the real trophy
from A.J.'s office,'' said Gossage, who added that he sincerely
hopes Luyendyk runs the race of his life this May.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a guy that has won two Indy 500s, the
first IRL race at Texas, and he's been a personal friend for better
than 15 years,'' Gossage said. ``But I'll do what I've got to do to
twist his arm to convince him he really needs to come to Texas.
After all, the Indy 500 is just a warm-up for the Longhorn 500.''
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Charting Arie Luyendyk's Indy 500 victories Year
Chassis/engine Qualifying speed Start Laps led 1990 Lola/Chevy Indy
V-8 223.304 mph 3 37 1997 G Force/Olds Aurora V-8 218.263 mph 1 62
QUICK HITS RATINGS SAVED ``THE ROCK''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of empty seats Sunday on the windy backstretch
at North Carolina Speedway, and now we know where many of those
missing fans were.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sitting outside in 40-degree weather in Rockingham,
N.C., the fans apparently were among those at home watching on TNN.
The Nashville Network earned a 6.2 national cable rating for its
telecast of the Dura-Lube/Big Kmart 400. The rating was up 10
percent from last year's 5.6, according to Nielsen Media Research.
The 4,524,000 households are also a record for NASCAR Winston Cup
coverage on cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Given the unsettled weather in the Carolinas in February,
perhaps NASCAR ought to consider date-swapping next year. For
instance, why not take the week after the Daytona 500 off to give
the champion a chance to make the talk-show circuit, etc., and to
allow teams to regroup. Race No. 2 could be at Texas Motor
Speedway, followed by a trip to Las Vegas for hopefully more nice
weather. Then head back to North Carolina Speedway and Atlanta
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Because, other than the weather, it does not make sense for the
same series that drew an estimated 195,000 fans at Daytona on Feb.
14 to perform before 45,000 at ``The Rock'' one week later.
CUP TEAMS BOOK TMS TESTS
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR teams will begin descending on Texas Motor Speedway next
week for testing leading to the Coca-Cola 300 Busch Grand National
and Primestar 500 Winston Cup races March 27-28.
</P>
<P>
   Testing begins Monday and Tuesday, when Team Sabco's Sterling
Marlin and Joe Nemechek are scheduled to be joined by two-time
Winston Cup champion Terry Labonte of Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Busch Grand National champion Randy LaJoie, the current
points leader, will attend the session to shake down the Cup car he
plans to run in five events this season beginning at TMS. The car
is owned by Cup regular Ernie Irvan and Trans-Am racer Mark Semo.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin Jr., the 1998 Cup rookie of the year, is also
tentatively scheduled to test the Busch car owned by Cup star Dale
Jarrett and Green Bay Packers quarterback Brett Favre. Irwin will
debut the No. 11 Ford in the Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are closed to the public.
AERO PACKAGE ENDORSED
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Cup race featured 25 lead changes among six drivers _
and that rates as an endorsement of NASCAR's revised rear spoiler
and front air dam rules.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the lead-swapping, there was plenty of
side-by-side racing around the tight, 1.017-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it definitely made the racing a lot better,'' said
Ford driver Dale Jarrett, who finished second to Mark Martin's
Taurus. ``We could go in the corner side-by-side and not feel like
we were gonna spin out or slide up and get loose and get in the
other guy. I think that we'll see even better racing as we go to
some racetracks where the tires don't wear quite as quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was likely referring to the series' next stop, at the
1.5-mile Las Vegas Motor Speedway on March 7. Bruton Smith's most
recent acquisition features a smooth surface and flat, wide,
12-degree banked turns that put a premium on downforce. In other
words, it's a Taurus track.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't feel sorry for nobody in this sport, because those
suckers will stomp right on you. When you're down, that's good
because they don't have so far to kick you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rusty Wallace, on the competitive nature of NASCAR's Winston
Cup Series
</P>
</TEXT>
