<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOPS BAYLOR, GRABS BIG 12 TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WACO, Texas _ A team that turned for the better on Hawaiian shores
in December became the best in the Big 12 last night on the banks
of the Brazos River. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas, which stood 2-7 when it embarked for a post-Christmas
tournament in Honolulu, Hawaii, won for the 14th time in 16 games
and clinched the Big 12 conference championship with 62-52 victory
over Baylor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas, 18-10 overall and 13-2 in the Big 12 with a home game
remaining at home Saturday against Missouri, also captured the No.
1 seed in next week's Big 12 tournament. The Longhorns became the
first team other than Kansas to win a regular-season title in the
three-year-old conference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can hardly explain it,'' said forward Gabe Muoneke, who
had 16 points and seven rebounds. ``I'm so excited for everyone who
worked so hard for this. This was our goal after we came back from
Hawaii, and it started with Colorado. We said this is a new season
and we're going to win this conference.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The No. 22 Longhorns crowned themselves in an arena that,
instead of echoing with the hollow losses of the last two seasons,
resounded with cries of ``Big 12 Champs!'' by orange-clad fans who
dominated a Ferrell Center crowd. Texas won for the eighth time in
nine Big 12 road games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senior Kris Clack led with 21 points as Texas was up as much as
21 and led by no fewer than 10 from 8:44 of the first half to the
end of the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard all year, and we're deserving of this,'' Clack
said. ``It was just a matter of putting it all together as a team
and expressing on the court all the hard work we did in practice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of orange up in the crowd, and that was
wonderful. We didn't end the game like we wanted to, but we came
out with a 10-point win, and that's fine with us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (6-22, 0-15) closed with a 10-2 spurt, which upset Texas
coach Rick Barnes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I'm very happy for the players and the fact we are
where we are today,'' Barnes said. ``To win a regular-season
championship in these days of expanded conferences where you're
playing 16 games shows that you've got to be mentally tough and
have a lot of disipline over a two-month period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't have very good practice yesterday ... and got a
little too happy there at the end tonight, got a little careless
wanting to make home-run plays and score too quick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand there's more out there, more basketball
to be played. We have another conference game that to me is as
important as any game we play.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas' most recent outright regular-season championship was in
the Southwest Conference in 1994; the Longhorns shared the SWC
title with Texas Tech in '95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
