<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE CHANGE LEADS TO DEATH BY INJECTION FOR GERMAN
NATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ariz. _ Giving a thumbs up and mouthing ``I love you''
to his minister, convicted murdered Karl LaGrand was executed by
Wednesday night after a wild hour in state government of figuring
out to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   The case of LaGrand, a German national, attracted widespread
attention in Europe, and his attorneys had selected death by gas as
a grounds for reversal on appeal and to illustrate the horrors of
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the tactic worked.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals granted a stay early
Wednesday but the execution was reinstated when the U.S. Supreme
Court refused to take up the case.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about an hour before the scheduled execution, LaGrand
changed his mind about being gassed and selected lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   That set off a mad scramble in the offices of Gov. Jane Hull and
Attorney General Janet Napolitano as LaGrand's attorneys continued
to file appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano said she and Hull decided to grant his request
because of the lateness of the hour and ``rather than create
another avenue of appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Strapped to a gurney, LaGrand apologized profusely to the family
of Kenneth Hartsock, a Marana bank manager he repeatedly stabbed in
a bungled 1982 robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry this took so long and dragged out,'' said LaGrand,
35. ``But from the bottom of my heart I'm sorry for what I did. I
hope one day you can find it in your heart to forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   LaGrand also looked in the direction of Dawn Lopez, a former
teller at the bank who is now a policewoman. She survived an attack
by LaGrand's brother, Walter, who is scheduled to be executed next
Wednesday for the same crime.
</P>
<P>
   Karl LaGrand apologized to her also.
</P>
<P>
   She looked down and closed her eyes as the poison began to flow
through his veins.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   The case was front page news in Germany, which has no death pen
alty.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands' mother married an American serviceman and moved to
the United States when they were boys. German officials, including
that country's ambassador to the United States, testified on Karl
LaGrand's behalf at a clemency hearing Tuesday and remained adamant
Wednesday that his life should have been spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they're doing this. It churned my stomach,''
said Steffen Ufer, an attorney from Munich, Germany, who was
assisting the LaGrand brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. would probably threaten us with an atomic bomb if we
did this to one of your citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ufer also said he would not participate in any more of what
referred to as ``alibi hearings.'' Walter LaGrand is scheduled to
have a clemency hearing Tuesday, a day before his execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm through with this,'' Ufer said. ``Now it is time to go
mobilize Germany's politicians on behalf of Walter.''
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands were sentenced to death for the January 1982 murder
of Hartsock, a Marana bank manager who was stabbed 23 times and had
his throat cut during a bungled robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrand brothers also critically wounded Lopez. Lopez
recounted the horror of the attack Tuesday at Karl LaGrand's
clemency board hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, now a Pima County Sheriff's deputy, recalled that she and
Hartsock were bound with electrical tape and recounted the frenzy
of the attack after Hartsock kicked Karl LaGrand in the shins.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands were born into poverty in a Bavarian town at the
height of the Cold War between the U.S. and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Both LaGrand brothers and their sister have different U.S.
soldiers for fathers and each abandoned them.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands were later adopted by yet another GI and brought to
Arizona in 1967 when the GI was transferred to Fort Huachuca in
Sierra Vista.
</P>
<P>
   But their adopted father left the family after becoming
dependent on alcohol and drugs in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were left to fend for themselves, bouncing among
juvenile homes and families who would shelter them for short
periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Karl began drinking at age 9,
running away from home at age 10 and regularly suffering alcohol
``blackouts'' by age 12. Shortly before the Marana holdup attempt,
both Karl and Walter had been released from the state prison
system. They had robbed three Tucson supermarkets in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Karl LaGrand had claimed that he turned his life
around in prison, earning a G.E.D. and becoming a legal assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Corrections officials said LaGrand had been
disciplined repeatedly for fighting, trying to saw through his cell
bars, having handcuff keys, and testing positive for drugs in urine
tests.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrand was being investigated at the time of his death for ties
to a White supremacist group that was shipping drugs into the
prisons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from The Associated Press. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
