<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PREDATORS-STARS-T     02-25 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PREDATORS-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LOSE GAME, LOSE HULL FOR AT LEAST TWO WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ The injury bug caught up with the Stars last night, just
as the Nashville Predators did. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Predators threw the Stars a changeup in a 2-1 Nashville
victory, and the injury bug claimed Brett Hull and Joe Nieuwendyk.
Hull is expected to be out ``a minimum of two weeks,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said, after Hull pulled a hamstring muscle when he
caught the edge of his skate in a rut on the ice. Nieuwendyk is
listed as day-to-day after missing last night's game with a
sprained ankle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine those injuries with a knee injury to Darryl Sydor
(expected out two weeks) and the Stars are hitting a wall in the
82-game season. The loss was sealed when Sergei Krivokrasov scored
with 28.6 seconds remaining. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned that's a loss where the schedule just
caught up to us,'' Hitchcock said of the Stars' playing on
back-to-back nights in two cities, as well as playing their sixth
game in 10 nights. ``We need to rest and regroup.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They also need some contributions from their role players. Hull
scored his 26th goal of the season last night and his 12th in the
past 15 games. However, the Stars will have to learn to live
without his scoring presence for a while. Nieuwendyk tested his
ankle in the pregame skate then was scratched from the game. He
could play tomorrow against the Pittsburgh Penguins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to learn from this game and pick it up,'' said
winger Mike Keane, who likely will play on the first or second
line. ``When we lose players like that, we all have to step in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars last night showed the aftereffects of expending a ton
of energy the night before to claim a 4-3 come-from-behind victory
in Nashville, Tenn. A night after getting a season-high 45 shots
against the Predators, the Stars were held to 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They also struggled to adapt to Nashville's change of pace _ a
game plan heavy on trapping and team defense _ as well as bad ice
conditions at Reunion Arena. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers said.
``When you have \RMike Modano\S and \RSergei Zubov\S fumbling the
puck, you know there's a problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars saw a seven-game unbeaten (6-0-1) streak snapped and
fell to 36-11-9, still 11 points better than Phoenix for first
place in the Western Conference. The Predators, meanwhile, extended
their road success, pushing themselves to 5-1-1 in their past seven
road games, good for a 21-32-6 record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars suffered their first loss to the expansion team in
stunning fashion when Predators winger Krivokrasov stole the puck
from Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher in the final minute of
regulation and rushed up ice. Krivokrasov stopped at the right side
of the crease, faked an onrushing Hatcher off his skates and tried
to look to pass. With no opening available, Krivokrasov instead
pushed a backhand past Stars goalie Roman Turek for the game-winner
with 28.6 seconds remaining. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turek (10-2-2) suffered his first loss since Jan. 10, stopping a
four-game winning streak for him. He registered 23 saves and had
given the Stars the chance to hang on for a tie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping for the tie,'' Hitchcock said. ``A point would
have been good tonight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Predators coach Barry Trotz didn't see it that way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a game we deserved to win,'' Trotz said. ``Taking
nothing away from Dallas, but we stuck to our game plan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored first with Hull wristing in a loose puck at the
10:51 mark of the second period, but the Predators tied the game
six minutes later when Andrew Brunette was allowed to get to a
loose rebound on the power play. Both teams then played chess until
the end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Stars will have to make a few moves, altering their
lineup and also trying to get refreshed while playing five games in
the next eight nights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to buckle down and look at winning games 1-0 and
2-1,'' Hitchcock said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
