A8576 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-GALLOWAY-T JIMMYJOHNSONDEFENDSJER   02-25 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOWAY
</HEADLINE>
 TEN YEARS LATER, JIMMY JOHNSON DEFENDS
JERRY JONES (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By RANDYc.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
It was 10 years ago this morning when Jimmy Johnson, having sampled
the hostile mood of the local populace, decided immediately upon
his most sensible course of action.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I got the hell outta Dodge,'' Johnson said yesterday,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday afternoon _ Feb. 25, 1989 _ Johnson hitched a ride
to D-FW and grabbed the next flight for home, which was, then as
now, Miami. He would return in a few days and stay a few years.
</P>
<P>
   But later that evening at Valley Ranch, in what is still
considered by many as the darkest moment in North Texas sports
history, a fellow from Arkansas took the podium, introduced
himself, and life with the Dallas Cowboys would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the 10th anniversary of the infamous ``Saturday Night
Massacre.'' Or, to be fair, today is the 10th anniversary of the
Jerry Jones era, which has produced the most Super Bowl success in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, admit it, Jerry hasn't been that bad. Granted, Jones'
first impression on that Saturday night long ago did cause massive
gagging. For some, the gagging continues to this day. And for four
of his 10 years at Valley Ranch, Jones allowed a pair of empty
shoes to serve as head coach, simply because of ego. Plus, Jerry
also seems to top everybody's least-likely-to-be-trusted list.
</P>
<P>
   But. . .
</P>
<P>
   Three Lombardi Trophies in a four-year span is unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry is good. Jerry is bad. And there hasn't been much
grey-matter in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of course, would be at the top of any
least-likely-to-defend-Jones list. There is, however, an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one criticism that sticks with Jerry 10 years later, and
it's the thing many people in Texas will never forgive him for,''
he said, ``is also the criticism he never deserved. Not then or
now.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would be how Jones ``handled'' the firing of
Tom Landry in the ``Saturday Night Massacre.'' And count me among
the chorus that has repeatedly said it wasn't done the proper way.
</P>
<P>
   An excited Jones, overcome with joy about buying the Cowboys
from Bum Bright, ran smack into media hostility that night a decade
ago. Most of it centered on the Landry issue. Such hostility was a
reflection of outrage throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   A novice at dealing with the media, Jones was easy prey on that
evening. He basically came across as a greaser from the Arkansas
outback, as opposed to an astute businessman who had just wrangled
a $140 million loan to buy the most popular football franchise in
the land.
</P>
<P>
   But in a Dallas newspaper that Saturday morning, there was a
front page picture of Jones and Johnson enjoying Tex-Mex at Mia's
on Lemmon Ave. Actually, they were dining on enchiladas, and not
Landry's carcass. But the ``buzzard'' impression stuck. Landry had
been told nothing, but here was the rumored new owner of the
Cowboys feeding freely in Dallas with his rumored new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   And for irony, Landry's favorite Tex-Mex restaurant, then and
now, is Mia's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, it looked bad,'' said Johnson of the front page
photo. ``We were staying at a hotel and Jerry came by the room and
said he wanted to take me to a little out-of-the-way place. I told
him I didn't think it was a good idea. It was Friday night. Every
place would be packed. But he was positive no one would recognize
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry just forgot he was suddenly a long way from little ol'
Little Rock. But on that same Saturday morning, the sale of the
team was finalized. Only one obstacle remained _ how to deal with
the Landry issue.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson: ``Tex \RSchramm\S was there with us at Bum's office,
and he's a savvy guy, so he advised Jerry to send me back to Miami
and not have the coaching part of the press conference until the
next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, however, had to tell Landry, and Bright immediately
volunteered to personally fire the only coach the Cowboys ever had,
removing the heat from Jones and taking it himself. Other
suggestions then followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard Tex on the phone with Tom, all but telling him a
coaching change was coming,'' said Johnson. ``These were men I had
great respect for; coach Landry and Tex Schramm were idols of mine
growing up in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't going to be easy. I felt bad. But Jerry stood
right up to it. He would not let Bum do the firing. He would not
let Tex inform Tom with a phone call. He would not phone Tom
himself. Jerry said the deal couldn't get done until he told Tom
face to face. And Tom had gone to Austin to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry then put everything on hold, got on a plane, flew to
Austin, and found Tom on the golf course. Contrary to popular
opinion, Jerry was not a close friend of mine and I hadn't been
around him much. But after seeing that, I walked out that afternoon
really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Public perception, however, was just the opposite. And remains
so. ``But on this part,'' said Johnson, with a laugh, ``I strongly
defend Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, and miracles do happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
