A8578 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-CARDINALS     02-25 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-CARDINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MAC BACK WITH POWER ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. Sullivan 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
JUPITER, Fla. _ The winter after hitting 70 home runs, Mark McGwire
met Pope John Paul II, spoke with John Glenn, did a voice over for
[ix]The Simpsons[nm] and kissed Helen Hunt. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he showed up at the St. Louis Cardinals' training camp for
the first full-squad workout yesterday, he convincingly
demonstrated his off-season hobnobbing with the rich and famous
hardly diminished his slugging prowess. McGwire smacked 13
baseballs over the left-field fence during batting practice despite
hitting into a stiff wind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every ball crushed was accompanied by the rapid clicking of
dozens of cameras and the oohs and ahhs of several hundred fans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My body has been itching to go the last three weeks,'' McGwire
said. ``As soon as the Super Bowl is over, I feel it's baseball
season. I started hitting around Jan. 10 as I always do. I'm not
going to change anything just because of what I did last year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals general manager Walt Jocketty confirmed that at
McGwire's first news conference by announcing, ``We're here to
dispel any rumors Big Mac is leaving baseball to pursue a career in
acting.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God,'' McGwire said, fresh off his cameo appearance on
[ix]Mad About You.[nm] &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, McGwire is back in uniform for an encore performance
after becoming a national sensation last year with his assault on
baseball's single-season home-run record. He went into spring
training last year with people anticipating he might assault the
record. Turns out he shattered it, hitting nine more than Roger
Maris hit in 1961 and four more than Sammy Sosa did for the Chicago
Cubs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more pressure keeping the home-run \Rlead\S than in
breaking the record,'' said McGwire, who hit his historic 62nd home
run on Sept. 8 off of Cubs pitcher Steve Trachsel. ``Sammy Sosa had
a darn good year. He was right there with me. Breaking the record
that night, I knew there was a lot of time left. To hold and keep
the record, that was tough.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did so with a spectacular final weekend, hitting five
home runs in three days against Montreal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire enters this season with the simple goal of hitting 50
home runs, something he has done the past three years. The
possibility of reaching greater heights than 70 home runs seems
remote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible, but I think it would be foolish to sit
here and think you can break your own record from last year,''
McGwire said. ``What I did last year, ballplayers have been trying
to do for the last 38 years. To hit 70 home runs, you would have to
have 40 at the All-Star break. I can only imagine the pressure. I
know how hard it was hitting 61 or 62; imagine trying to hit 10
more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in awe of what I did last year. I'm still in awe.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said, ``expectations are always tough but the only
expectations I have to live up to are the ones I set for myself. I
know what I can do. Last year was a magical year. It may never
happen again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, it may.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he had a relatively uneventful off-season, even
with the guest appearance on Mad About You and the opportunity to
meet the Pope. He took two trips to Mexico and one to Australia.
The Australians didn't recognize him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd take one look at me and look away,'' McGwire said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He didn't receive the same treatment in the United States or
Mexico. McGwire is trying to become accustomed to being mobbed as a
hero wherever he goes. He said there was not one time he was able
to go to dinner in the off-season without being recognized. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so many people join me for dinner, it's amazing,''
McGwire said. ``If I walk into a place and just one person
recognizes me, it was all over. People will just walk up and sit
down and tell me their stories, where they were last year, what it
meant to them, how they were never going to watch baseball and now
they're watching it again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty neat. People have been great. I don't think I
had a problem this whole winter with anybody. I deal with it every
day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
