<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-LABOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE CONCERNED ABOUT LABOR FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
JUPITER, Fla. _ St. Louis Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire said
he is ``scared to death'' about what might happen the next time
owners and the Players Association negotiate a new Basic
Agreement. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McGwire's feelings are based on what happened during the
off-season with the record-breaking contracts handed out to some
free agents. The current agreement expires after the 2001 season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can get something done before then,'' McGwire said
yesterday. ``I sure hope what happened in 1994 _ salaries are
getting up there _ doesn't happen again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be so disgusted, I'd walk away from the game. I don't know
how we baseball players and owners could let that happen again
after what we did last year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baseball enjoyed a sensational season in 1998, mainly because of
McGwire's 70 home runs and the 66 hit by Chicago Cubs outfielder
Sammy Sosa. The feeling in the industry was that the Great Home Run
Chase helped to heal the wounds left over from the 1994-95 players
strike and the cancellation of the World Series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But new fears about what might happen during the next
negotiations were renewed this off-season with the further widening
of the gap between big-market and small-market clubs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most notable was the Los Angeles Dodgers giving pitcher Kevin
Brown a seven-year contract worth $105 million and California
Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn setting a standard for position
players with a six-year, $80 million deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it now. Let's sit down and be reasonable, and let's
keep the game on top,'' McGwire said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Labor relations was one controversial issue McGwire addressed
yesterday during a news conference. The other was Androstendione,
his controversial dietary supplement. It is legal in Major League
Baseball but has been banned by the International Olympic Committee
and other organizations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he will continue to use it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legal,'' McGwire said. ``Major League Baseball is not the
IOC, and it has absolutely nothing to do with hitting a baseball.
It has something to do with getting me through workouts with my
body being worn down.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is studying the possibility of banning
Androstendione. But McGwire said if that happens, it would not
tarnish his record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody has any common sense, they'd know it has nothing to
do with hitting a baseball,'' he said. &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
