<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-SECURITY-     02-25 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SECURITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCIDENT PUTS FOCUS ON SPRING-TRAINING SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Tuesday's altercation between Rangers
hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo and a 23-year-old man might
result in the organization reducing spectators' access at its
Charlotte County Stadium complex. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We'll discuss it and see if we need to make any changes or
consider this an isolated incident and leave things as they are,''
Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said yesterday. ``I'd hate to
see a lot of fans hurt because of the incident Tuesday, but it is a
possibility.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he plans to discuss the issue with Rangers president
Tom Schieffer, who is scheduled to attend the first full-squad
workout today with owner Tom Hicks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The incident points to the larger issue of safety and security
for players, coaches and fans at the more accessible spring
training facilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the Cardinals, knowing that interest in home-run
king Mark McGwire will be more intense than ever this spring,
stepped up security at their training complex in Jupiter, Fla. But
fans have easy access to his batting practice _ if they can see
over all the cameras _ and he spent 15 minutes signing autographs
behind a fence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a bodyguard,'' McGwire said, responding to a
story that he would be followed by an off-duty police officer.
``The security here is for the St. Louis Cardinals. We had to bump
up security because of the number in attendance here at Jupiter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to hear I was coming to camp with three
bodyguards. I don't need a bodyguard. I don't want a bodyguard. I
just want to be myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo tussled with Dave Davison, 23, Tuesday after Davison
failed to return baseballs hit beyond the left-field fence at a
practice field. A sign near where their scuffle occurred requests
that spectators return all baseballs to the playing field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo and Davison exchanged shoves, and the latter's shirt
was torn.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy admits he was wrong,'' Melvin said. ``He never should
have let that happen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo acknowledged regret for the incident and declined to
comment further. Melvin spoke yesterday with Davison on the
telephone and offered an apology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The event, though, demonstrated to Rangers officials that one
spectator can instigate an incident that can escalate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers employ two off-duty deputies from the Charlotte
County Sheriff's Department as security guards. The officers keep
unauthorized personnel out of the Rangers' clubhouse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, those who roam the complex to watch workouts have no
organized supervision. Melvin pointed to several people seated in
the shade of a practice-field dugout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We allow fans in those dugouts to stay out of the sun,'' he
said. ``We don't say anything to them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' complex is fan-friendly, and that might be an
understatement, said Jerry Hill of North Richland Hills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the sixth year Hill and her husband have visited Florida
for spring training. They have been to Arizona, where 10 other
major-league teams have camp, twice. They have visited more than 20
spring-training sites, and Hill said the Rangers allow more
accessibility to players than anywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These people park in the lot with the players,'' she said.
``You don't find that at any other ballpark.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That might change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid it's going to be the fans who lose out because of
one person, one obnoxious person,'' Grant Hill said. ``I wasn't
here Tuesday and didn't see the incident, but it just takes one
person to ruin it for everyone else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lack of security, though, does not appear to concern Rangers
players.this decade. ] &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to walk through a wave of fans every day here,''
pitcher Rick Helling said of the 400-yard hike from the clubhouse
to the field where the Rangers begin most workouts. ``There's
definitely a greater opportunity for something bad happening here.
I think it could happen, but I don't think any of us worry about
it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither does manager Johnny Oates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That never enters my mind,'' he said. ``Maybe I'm naive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oates' greater concern is for spectators' safety. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they have too much access out there?'' Oates said. ``Yes,
in my opinion, they do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oates watched a boy almost get hit by a batted ball yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He never knew that ball went by him,'' Oates said. ``It's too
late after it hits him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he also fears children or the elderly might be run
over by those chasing baseballs for souvenirs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want my children or father out there,'' he said.
``It's all fun until someone gets hurt badly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider Davison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him \RTuesday\S,'' Melvin said. ``What a nut. He was
running around everywhere chasing down balls. He could play center
field for some teams.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watching batting practice from beyond the outfield might soon be
a thing of the past for those who visit the Rangers' training
complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It has absolutely nothing to do with the baseballs,'' Oates
said. ``We go out there with 50 dozen baseballs and come back with
25 dozen. That's no big deal. We just go get another 25 dozen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safety of players and spectators is the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take a look at this,'' Melvin said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
