A8592 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVS-WALKER-TEX     02-25 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-WALKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON CRITICIZES SAMAKI WALKER'S PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson criticized the
play of Samaki Walker yesterday and disputed recent comments made
by his agent, Norm Nixon, who said the team is not treating the
power forward fairly. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nelson said the Mavericks don't play well when Walker is on the
floor, which is why Walker hasn't been on the floor much lately.
The third-year veteran has played a total of six minutes in the
past three games, and is battling John ``Hot Rod'' Williams for
12th-man status on the Mavericks' 12-man roster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys would care enough to look it up _ which is pretty
easy to do _ the minutes that Samaki is on the floor, the team has
not done well,'' Nelson said. ``That's what a coach looks at; what
are the pluses and minuses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some big minuses when he's on the floor. We've
played him at different times with different lineups and the
results are often the same.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walker is averaging 5.9 points, 4.1 rebounds and 15 minutes, and
is shooting 39.4 percent from the field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nixon said Nelson is controlling Walker's minutes on
the court in an effort to control the amount of money his client
can earn on his next contract. Walker can be a free agent after
this season, and Nixon said the former Louisville standout stands
to lose a lot of money if he's not able to get on the court and
prove his worth. The Mavericks say they want to re-sign him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said backup power forward Gary Trent is the main reason
why Walker isn't getting more playing time. He also praised the
play of starting power forward A.C. Green. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you who's limiting \RWalker's\S playing time is
Trent, not me,'' Nelson said. ``If Samaki was playing as good as
Trent is, Samaki would be playing. It's really that simple. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A.C. has played pretty darn well, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trent averaged 18.5 points, 9.3 rebounds and 27 minutes during a
recent four-game stretch. In the Mavericks' past three games,
Walker did not play against the Los Angeles Clippers, played the
last six minutes in a loss to Phoenix, and did not play in
Tuesday's victory against Atlanta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nelson pointed out that Trent, like Walker, will be a free agent
at the end of this season, and that he isn't limiting Trent's
minutes in order to squash his earning potential. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So by playing the game that Mr. Nixon says I play, why
wouldn't I do it with Trent?,'' Nelson asked. ``I don't like being
accused of things like that. That's unfair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes Samaki better than I do. I wish he was playing
better. But Trent is the man right now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon has instructed Walker not to make any comments about his
contract or lack of playing time. But Nixon says he steadfastly
believes Nelson is not treating his client fairly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaki loves Dallas and wants to be there,'' Nixon said. ``But
he has to be ready to go play somewhere else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Nixon are seeking one of two proposals for a contract
extension with the Mavericks: $30 million over four years or $42
million over six years. The Mavericks offered a four-year, $20
million deal, but might let the March 13 deadline to sign Walker
pass. Walker then could test the free-agent market, beginning July
1.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite his remarks about Walker, Nelson said the 6-foot-9
third-year pro remains in the team's plans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of our talented young players,'' Nelson said. ``Do
you think we would have offered him what we offered him if he
wasn't in our plans for the future?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if the four-year, $20 million offer to Walker is
still on the table, Nelson said: ``I don't really know. I really
don't even want to know, because I'll get accused by Mr. Nixon of
something else.'' &QL; 
Trent's deal &QL; 
If he keeps playing the way he has played lately, Trent could be
one of the most sought-after free agents in the NBA this summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are limited in what they can offer the third-year
veteran, but Nelson said they will make every effort to re-sign
Trent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Gary Trent very much,'' Nelson said. ``And he's proven
to be everything I thought he was.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trent said he would consider re-signing with the Mavericks after
the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
