<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR ASSUMES TV RIGHTS FOR WINSTON CUP RACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ NASCAR, the only sport with television-ratings
increases each year this decade, plans to consolidate broadcast
rights to cash in on the accelerating popularity of stock-car
racing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR announced yesterday it no longer will allow racetracks to
negotiate separate TV deals, returning to the setup it employed
until 1978. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the biggest news story of the year in
motorsports,'' said Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and
general manager of Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth. ``This could
well mark the true beginning of the success of modern-day Winston
Cup racing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tracks generate about $100 million in rights fees for 34 Cup
races from CBS, ABC, NBC, ESPN, TBS and The Nashville Network.
Gossage and his cohorts at Speedway Motorsports Inc., say they
believe current premium events on the schedule should see broadcast
rights fees double. In some instances, the value of rights could
increase five-fold. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said CBS is paying approximately $4.1 million for rights
to broadcast the Coca-Cola 300 NASCAR Busch Grand National race
March 27 and the Primestar 500 Cup race March 28. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TMS' four-year contract with CBS expires after the 2000 race,
and Gossage said he is unsure how the impending deal would affect
rates at the Fort Worth facility.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on fees in general, Gossage said, ``I think we're
looking at $400 million or better in the year 2001.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials intend to continue the current TV rights fee
distribution formula of 65/25/10 as it pertains to tracks,
competitors and the sanctioning body, respectively. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wins in this deal,'' Gossage said. ``Twenty-five
percent goes into the purses for competitors, and if it increases
to $400 million, that's $100 million that goes into purses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The \Radded\S revenues also will help us to keep our costs
down. We're probably close to tapping out our fans' revenue right
now. Ticket prices are plenty high. Now, we're making headway.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 0110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
