</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-EXCOMMUNICATED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISSIDENT PRIEST IS EXCOMMUNICATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic priest in Rochester, N.Y., who was suspended
for expanding the roles of women, homosexuals and non-Catholics has
``excommunicated himself'' by starting his own church, the Diocese
of Rochester said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, the Rev. James Callan, formerly of the Corpus
Christi Roman Catholic Church, has been renting out a Protestant
church and holding Sunday services there since Feb. 14. The
hundreds of parishioners who attend Callan's services inside Salem
United Church of Christ _ he said his flock numbered about 1,100 _
have been excommunicated, too, the diocese said.
</P>
<P>
   People who are excommunicated cannot celebrate Mass or give or
receive communion. According to Roman Catholic doctrine,
excommunication takes place automatically when a Catholic creates a
schism by attempting to take on independent authority in the
church. But the Rev. Kevin McKenna, the chancellor of the diocese,
said that Callan and his followers would be welcomed back into the
faith if they renounced the upstart church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church would consider this to be a medicinal remedy, in
the hopes that Father Callan and the other individuals would return
to the church,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Callan said he had no such plans. ``I was kind of hoping they
wouldn't do this because it looks bad for them,'' he said on
Wednesday night, ``but as far as I'm concerned, this doesn't affect
me, and I don't think it affects most of the other people either.''
</P>
<P>
   Callan built Corpus Christi's flock up from about 200 when he
started there in the mid-70s to more than 3,000 last year, but his
increasingly liberal practices put him in conflict with the church
at a time when the pope is urging Catholics to adhere to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Callan invited all people who considered themselves followers of
Jesus to take holy communion, a privilege the church generally
reserves for Catholics. He opened the church's marriage preparation
program to gay couples and has blessed five same-sex unions. And he
allowed a woman in the parish, Mary Ramerman, to preach, offer
blessings and stand behind the altar and raise the chalice during
consecration.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the diocese transferred Callan to a small church
in Elmira, N.Y., about 70 miles from Rochester. In October, Ms.
Ramerman, the associate pastor at Corpus Christi, was dismissed.
And in December, Callan was suspended with pay for refusing to
follow church rules.
</P>
<P>
   Also in December, Corpus Christi dismissed six staff members
whom Callan had signed to one-year employment contracts in
September, shortly before his transfer. On Wednesday, four of the
workers sued the church and the diocese, charging breach of
contract and seeking 10 months' pay. McKenna said that the
dismissal was Corpus Christi's decision, and the new pastor at
Corpus Christi, Daniel McMullen, was not available on Wednesday
night, church personnel said.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese, which covers 12 counties in western New York, said
in a statement on Wednesday that it would consider dismissing
Callan from the priesthood, a more serious penalty that can only be
reversed by the Vatican, if he did not toe the line. It added that
the bishop, Matthew H. Clark, was reluctant to take such a step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a happy situation,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Callan disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' he said. ``It helps us a little bit because
we've been not celebrating Masses all this time. We've been holding
communion services with preconsecrated hosts, just to hold out an
olive branch to the diocese. But now that we've been
excommunicated, we can go back to celebrating the Eucharist and
operating the way we're used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Callan confidently predicted that ``within 10 or 20 years,'' the
church establishment would embrace his views and said he was
willing to work outside the system until then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not starting our own denomination,'' he said. ``We
consider ourselves a Catholic church _ we're parallel. You know how
they say pork is the other white meat? Well, we're the other
Catholic church.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
