<SLUG> BC-BKN-COACHES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INTERIM, IT LOOKS LIKE RAMBIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Phil Jackson has six NBA championship rings
to his credit and a lot of time on his hands, but Del Harris'
successor as Lakers coach will come from within the Forum, at least
for now.
</P>
<P>
   With the firing of Harris on Wednesday, the Lakers will probably
hand the reins to assistant coach Kurt Rambis, although a decision
has not yet been announced. Lakers management planned to interview
both Rambis and assistant coach Larry Drew on Wednesday, and will
hire one of them as interim head coach as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have historically made our coaching choices from people
within our own organization, and we feel confident that one of
those two will be the person that will get us to where we want to
get,'' Lakers executive vice president Jerry West said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that decision is made, 18-year assistant coach Bill Bertka
is in charge and will lead the Lakers into tonight's game against
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Either Rambis or Drew will then get the chance to make a mark as
head coach and try to earn the job permanently. West won't look for
a permanent replacement until the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson? The former Chicago Bulls coach is probably the best
available candidate, but he's taking the year off, and West
declined to comment on him.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Rambis is viewed as a logical successor to
Harris, particularly because of his strong ties to the franchise's
glory years, as a player in the 1980s. He was a hot commodity last
summer, interviewed for head coaching positions by both the
Sacramento Kings and the Clippers, but Rambis ultimately decided to
stay with the Lakers, perhaps because the team knew Harris' tenure
was coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two assistant coaches, Rambis is the more laid-back, and
Drew, also 40, is the more aggressive. Rambis has been an assistant
for most of the last five years (interrupted by a few returns as a
player) and currently coaches the Lakers' centers and forwards.
Drew, a former point guard for the Kansas City Kings and later the
Lakers, is in his seventh season as an assistant and coaches the
guards.
</P>
<P>
   Players said they would be happy with either coach, and Harris
said both have promising futures as head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only hope is they do give it to one of my assistant coaches
to finish it out,'' Harris said, ``and what a tough choice that
would be. I think they're both terrific. . . . I just find both of
them to be just great prospects for being coaches. And I hope that
in the next two or three years, each of them is a head coach
somewhere in this league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
