<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON OFFICIALLY QUIETS DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ After a chat with the NHL's czar of off-ice
discipline, Kings coach Larry Robinson has agreed to keep his
``Holy Macaronis'' to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Following Saturday's 2-2 tie in Calgary, Robinson erupted while
discussing the performance that night of referee Stephen Walkom.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst officiated game I've ever seen,'' Robinson
said that night in a tone of high-decibel exasperation. ``I'm
disgusted. I'm sorry. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break. You're not supposed to criticize (officials)?
Holy Macaroni. I'll get a young kid out of the stands who can do
just as good a job. It's awful. I've never seen anything like it in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   According to NHL spokesman Frank Brown, Robinson's phone
conversation Tuesday with league vice president Colin Campbell
closed the matter, with Robinson agreeing not to disparage
officials again in such vivid terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, what really happened was that public comments
made in Calgary were intended to be in jest,'' Robinson said
Wednesday. ``But I probably shouldn't have made them. I was upset
at the time. I was told not to make such comments publicly. The
issue is at rest. There's nothing more to be said.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Admiring words: Luc Robitaille, the hockey player, is having
a difficult time getting wins.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, the horse, is another matter. The 6-year-old pacer
has won 10 of his last 12 races and placed in the top three in 68
of his last 73 outings.
</P>
<P>
   Bred in Bakersfield, the horse was purchased three years ago by
Kevin Wallis of Windsor, Ontario, which is minutes from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Told about his equine namesake's success, the Kings' left wing
said, ``He's faster than me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Blast from the past: Petr Klima has returned to the NHL with
the Red Wings after spending most of the past two seasons playing
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old winger began his career with the Wings in
1985-86, then bounced around the league for more than a decade,
scoring 312 goals along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of stint No. 1 in the league was an eight-game
stint at the start of the 1996-97 season with the Kings, for whom
he produced all of four assists and was a defensive liability.
</P>
<P>
   After attending the Red Wings' training camp, he began this
season in Germany, staying only long enough to collect a bonus he'd
been promised if he remained there through Jan. 1. He returned to
North America last month, playing 13 games for the Wings'
Adirondack farm team in the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed a contract (with the Wings), there were no
guarantees,'' Klima told the Detroit News. ``I went down (to
Adirondack) to play and wait to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Klima did not play against the Kings and has one goal in four
NHL games this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
