<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMYS-2NDLD-WRITETH     02-25 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A YEAR OF THE WOMEN, LAURYN HILL LEADS AT THE GRAMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lauryn Hill won five Grammys, a record for a
female artist, with the first hip-hop recording to be named album
of the year, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' at the 41st
Annual Grammy Awards ceremony at the Shrine Auditorium here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill, in accepting the award for best album, which mixes
rhythm-and-blues, gospel, pop and rap, exclaimed, ``This is crazy
because this is hip-hop music.'' Among her other Grammys was the
one for best new artist.
</P>
<P>
   The two other top awards on Wednesday night went to ``My Heart
Will Go On,'' sung by Celine Dion, which won record of the year
(presented to a song's performer) and song of the year (presented
to songwriters, in this case James Horner and Will Jennings). The
song, from the unsinkable ``Titanic'' soundtrack, also won an award
for best pop vocal performance.
</P>
<P>
   The other big winners at Wednesday night's ceremony, which was
broadcast on CBS with Rosie O'Donnell as host, were also female,
including Alanis Morissette, Sheryl Crow, Shania Twain, Madonna and
the Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter in the Grammys press room asked Ms. Dion what
she thought of all the female winners, she was rankled. ``I don't
like that question,'' she said, and then added: ``It's wonderful
that there are a lot of women coming forward in politics and show
business. Good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Grammy voters are well-known for their erratic,
unpredictable and often outlandish choices, few were surprised when
the Grammy favorite Ms. Dion and the favored newcomer Ms. Hill
walked away with armloads of prizes. In her acceptance speech for
best new artist, Ms. Hill brought a Bible onstage and read Psalm
40. With so many awards, she could have held an entire service on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill's five Grammys surpassed by one the number won by
Carole King for her ``Tapestry'' album in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill, a member of the rap group the Fugees who released her
first solo album to rave reviews and millions of sales last year,
even beat herself in two categories. For best rhythm-and-blues song
and the best female rhythm-and-blues vocal performance, her own
song telling women to respect themselves, ``Doo Wop (That Thing),''
won Grammys at the expense of Aretha Franklin's ``A Rose Is a
Rose,'' which was written by Ms. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about Lauryn Hill the day I heard that record,''
said Michael Greene, the president of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, which presents the Grammys, in an
interview before the show. ``I sweated bullets because I wondered
if the academy membership would get it. But they got it. They got
it big time.'' Ms. Hill received 10 Grammy nominations, more than
any other artist this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many have called this year's Grammy celebration the year of the
woman, but the awards show could also be called Madonna's revenge.
Despite a decade and a half of recording, she had only previously
received one award, for best long-form video in 1991. Now, in her
latest guise as a raven-haired spiritualist, Madonna, who opened
the show with a Japanese-flavored performance of ``Nothing Really
Matters,'' has three more Grammys to her name: best pop album, best
short-form video and best dance recording.
</P>
<P>
   The country trio the Dixie Chicks pulled an upset by winning the
best country album award over Shania Twain. In their acceptance
speech, the Dixie Chicks feigned surprise that a country act that
actually played its own instruments and sang what it wanted won an
award.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Twain responded with wounded pride backstage when asked
about losing to the Dixie Chicks. ``You never know what to expect
with these things,'' she said. ``I'm the biggest seller.'' She also
won two more awards.
</P>
<P>
   Though the rock group Garbage didn't win any awards, its singer
Shirley Manson _ heeding Ms. Hill's advice in ``Doo Wop'' by
petulantly refusing to let Billy Corgan of the Smashing Pumpkins
put his arm around her while they were presenting an award _
deserves points for capturing a free advertisement by wearing a
dress with the artwork from her record on it. In another rarity for
the night, the Grammys presented a Latin pop contender unfamiliar
to mainstream pop fans, the former Menudo singer Ricky Martin, who
took advantage of his big break with one of the biggest production
numbers of the night for the song ``La Copa de la Vida.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapper Jay-Z learned on Wednesday night that snubbing the
Grammys doesn't lose a musician any points. The gangsta rapper had
announced that he was boycotting the Grammys for overlooking
rappers and asked that his name be withdrawn from the running. He
was specifically upset with Grammy voters for not nominating his
fellow rapper DMX for best new artist and at the music industry in
general for paying more attention to violence in rap than to his
upcoming tour. Nonetheless, his ``Vol. II . . . Hard Knock Life,''
won the award for best rap album. True to his word, Jay-Z was not
here to accept the award.
</P>
<P>
   In a year of major changes for the music business, particularly
the sale of Polygram to Seagram and the industry's resistance to
the distribution of music via the Internet, Sheryl Crow was the
only award winner to acknowledge the upheaval. During her speech
for best rock album (for ``The Globe Sessions'') she delivered a
eulogy for her record label, A&AMP;M, which was shut own by Seagram,
and the executives who lost their jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners of top awards won again this year. There was Ms.
Dion, who won the album of the year award in 1996. Eric Clapton,
the big winner in 1993, won best male pop vocal performance for
``My Father's Eyes'' and Alanis Morissette, who swept up in 1996,
won best rock song and best female rock vocal performance for
``Uninvited.''
</P>
<P>
   One Grammy favorite, though, Tony Bennett, lost this year: to
Elmo of Sesame Street for best children's musical album.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, previously neglected artists received long
overdue Grammys. In her acceptance speech for best traditional pop
vocal performance for her ``Live at Carnegie Hall'' album, Patti
Page said that when her grandchildren asked what name to call her:
``I said Grammy because I'll never get one. Now they have to call
me granny.'' And Shirley Horn, after six previous nominations, won
her first Grammy for best jazz vocal performance for ``I Remember
Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Grammy critics who've complained after watching Elvis Costello
get snubbed year after year were temporarily quelled. Costello won
a Grammy by collaborating with a four-time winner, Burt Bacharach,
on an album, a song from which (``I Still Have That Other Girl'')
won best pop vocal collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Over half a century since its heyday, swing is officially pop
music again. The Brian Setzer Orchestra, led by the former member
of the rockabilly revivalists the Stray Cats, won best pop
instrumental performance for ``Sleepwalk'' and best pop vocal
performance by a duo or group for ``Jump Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   In the classical field, the conductor Pierre Boulez won, adding
to his 20 awards, for best opera recording (``Bluebeard's
Castle''), and best orchestral performance (``Mahler: Symphony No.
9'').
</P>
<P>
   Recordings released between Oct. 1, 1997, and Sept. 30, 1998,
were eligible for an award. The winners were selected by the 10,000
voting members _ from musicians to producers to industry executives
to liner note writers _ of the recording academy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
