<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TAGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGLERS PROUDLY DISPLAY TAGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Calif. _ Like tiny badges of honor, the metal
clips stamped with ``CAL-DFG'' are displayed proudly on stained
fishing vests and the worn lapels of lucky flannel shirts. But
their significance is largely a mystery to anglers, even to the
most experienced fishing guides.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery only deepens after the source is vividly determined
when a huge rainbow trout is landed bearing such a tag pinned to
its gill plate. But what does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``The word isn't getting out to the angling public exactly what
our program is about,'' said Mike Seefeldt, assistant manager of
the Eastern Sierra's Mount Whitney and Black Rock state fish
hatcheries.
</P>
<P>
   The tags identify rainbows that are reared in the DFG's
3-year-old trophy trout program, and anglers who catch a tagged
trout have every reason to beam. Released at weights of 1 to 5
pounds after at least 10 months' growth in larger pens than most
hatchery fish swim in, the tagged trout represent less than 2
percent of the total production of any given hatchery. Most trout
average a half-pound when they are stocked in angling waters,
Seefeldt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are definitely thrilled when they get a tagged fish
because they are so much larger than most of our catchables,'' said
Greg Kollenborn, a fish culturist at Hot Creek State Fish Hatchery,
east of Mammoth Lakes, where the staff fields weekly calls from
anglers curious about the tags. ``I've seen people with tags on
their hats. They want to show them off. It's cool, like saying, `I
caught the big one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the Mount Whitney and Black Rock hatcheries, for example,
just 6,700 of an estimated 334,000 fish annually earmarked for
planting are set aside and raised as trophy trout, which are larger
because they have more room to grow. When ready for release, the
trophy trout are rounded up in their pens, individually placed into
plastic-foam cradles and tagged, then planted the next week in
various waters. The process is repeated throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   While the hatcheries produce rainbow, brown and golden trout,
the trophy program is limited to rainbows. Similar programs in the
Eastern Sierra are found at Hot Creek and Fish Springs state
hatcheries. A small percentage of large brood stock, the majority
of which are planted after two years in the hatchery, are also
tagged as a supplement to the trophy trout program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tags are like trophies for the anglers. It's nice to hear
from people who catch them,'' said Seefeldt, who recently posted on
his office wall a newspaper clipping of a woman holding a 5-pound,
23-inch tagged rainbow. ``Sometimes people bring them here, but
mostly we see them at campgrounds or along streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling for everybody, including the hatchery
crew, which works very, very hard to put out a very good-looking
fish and a healthy fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired of private entrepreneurs, such as Tim Alpers and his
renowned Alpers trout, getting the lion's share of credit for
planting trophy trout, the DFG initiated its program so that
anglers could easily identify rainbows raised with revenues derived
from the purchase of state fishing licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anglers know by the tag this fish was paid for by them,''
Seefeldt said. ``And it's also our way of saying thank you to the
angler for their support.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no state financing for studies on the tagged
trout that are caught, the hatcheries don't want the tags back.
Instead, they want anglers to keep the tags as souvenirs. Those who
practice catch and release can photograph the tagged fish for a
keepsake, as the metal clip shows prominently on the trout's gill
plate. &QL; 
!hair! &QL; 
!ital!For more details on the Department of Fish and Game's trophy
trout program, call the Mount Whitney State Fish Hatchery at (760)
878-2272. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EASTERN SIERRA HEADS UP
</P>
<P>
   While the Eastern Sierra opens to angling for the most part
April 24 this year, an early trout-fishing season opener is slated
for March 6 along the western edge of Inyo County.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing grounds include all waters bounded by the Inyo County
line to the west and south, Independence Creek (which runs through
the town of Independence) to the north and Highway 395 on the east.
The daily bag limit is five trout; a total of 10 fish can be in
possession. The season runs through Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information, contact the Department of Fish and
Game in Bishop at (760) 872-1171.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a couple of Eastern Sierra angling tournaments will
take place next month:
</P>
<P>
   __ Anglers will gather at Diaz Lake, 1{ miles south of Lone
Pine, from sunrise to 3 p.m. March 6 to compete for prizes. Diaz is
open year-round. Information: (760) 876-4444.
</P>
<P>
   __ The annual Blake Jones Fishing Derby at Pleasant Valley
Reservoir northwest of Bishop, slated from sunrise to 4 p.m. March
13, will also feature a plethora of prizes. The derby is named for
the late Owens Valley resident and prominent Eastern Sierra-fishing
promoter. Information: (760) 873-8405.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
