<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-SYRACUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC IS NO MATCH FOR SYRACUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is almost over now. Twenty-five down. Two to go.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's 73-56 loss to the No. 24 Syracuse
Orangemen before a Conte Forum crowd of 4,165, that seemed to be
the only consolation for the Boston College men's basketball team
in its grueling torture test of a season. All that remains now for
the Eagles is a final regular-season game at Notre Dame Sunday
afternoon, then a likely rematch next week against the Orangemen in
the first round of the Big East tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Only then will the Eagles be able to look ahead to next season
with scarcely as much fear and trepidation as they did this season.
But Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night the Eagles (6-19 overall, 3-14 conference)
were forced to deal with the present, coming one game closer to
finishing last in the conference and earning the dreaded No. 13
seed in next week's conference tournament at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's Etan Thomas did all he could to make that a certainty
by leading the Orangemen (19-9, 10-7) with a game-high 25 points,
including 18 in the first half, despite sitting out 14 minutes in
the second half with three fouls. Ryan Blackwell had 15 points and
9 rebounds while guard Jason Hart chipped in 15 with 4 assists and
7 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we tried to get the ball to Etan,'' said Syracuse
coach Jim Boeheim. ``He did his best job all year of posting up
strong, and when we missed, getting on the offensive glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who had nine rebounds and one blocked shot, helped
Syracuse outrebound BC, 49-20, which was two shy of the conference
record for rebounding margin. The Orangemen were so dominant they
had more offensive rebounds (21) than BC had total rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some nights when people are just better than you,
plain and simple,'' said BC coach Al Skinner. ``He created such a
mismatch for us that we attempted to compensate and made it easier
for everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for sophomore guard Kenny Harley, who led BC with 20
points on 8-of-16 shooting, or for freshman forward Brian Ross, who
scored 11 points on 5-of-9 shooting but faced the unenviable task
of fronting Thomas in the low post. Though he is listed as 6 feet 8
inches, Thomas played as though he stood 7 feet, especially when
juxtaposed against BC's small frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big kid and very strong,'' said Ross. ``We're smaller
and not as strong as them, but when you play a guy like that you've
got to keep fighting. If we play them again we've just got to go
play harder next time, be more physical. To be honest, they just
beat us up.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Thomas long to get into the groove, scoring
Syracuse's first 11 points. All in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 13-6, BC went on a 7-0 run to tie it, but Thomas went
to work down low and helped Syracuse surge to a 38-23 halftime
lead. The Orangemen came out in the second half and thrice led by
22 (48-26, 52-30, and 56-34) before BC pulled within 16 (64-48).
But that was as close as the Eagles would get as they absorbed yet
another loss and drew another game closer to calling it a season. A
very long season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
