<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS DO TEXAS TWO-SLIP, SHOOT BLANKS IN ALAMODOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vin Baker sat alone in an empty locker with his
left eye just about closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics forward had been poked in the eye and discomfort was
evident by the redness. Even worse, Baker staggered around with
blurred vision, which was symbolic of the Sonics' 99-81 loss to the
San Antonio Spurs Wednesday night at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, the Sonics stumbled around on
offense. And one has to wonder what they see because this team
cannot seem to locate the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make free throws, we missed open shots. Same old
story,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal, whose team lost 98-86 at
Houston on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is time to put a suggestion box on Seattle street
corners. For the record, Westphal is willing to try just about
anything to invigorate an inept offense.
</P>
<P>
   That it was the Sonics' fourth loss in five games is enough for
concern. However, the team struggled through its worst shooting
night (34 percent) this season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Sonics (7-4) are downright mystifying.
</P>
<P>
   They were never really in this game. A late rally made the final
quarter interesting, but the Sonics were dominated by the Spurs'
frontline as David Robinson and Tim Duncan combined for 47 points
and 30 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Gary Payton's 20 points, the Sonics were flat. Detlef
Schrempf shot 2-for-8, Hersey Hawkins was 1-for-5 and Baker
suffered with 1-for-7 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some confidence with guys making plays,'' Schrempf
said. ``Right now, we don't have confidence. It's off and on. We've
got to start rolling offensively. I'm sure we're looking at a lot
of different scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal actually tried to rewrite what has been an awful and
predictable script when the Sonics have had the ball this season.
He changed the starting lineup, inserting veteran Dale Ellis to
replace rookie Rashard Lewis at shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Ellis hadn't started an NBA game since the
1996-97 season with the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't been working too well. We've got to find some
scoring somewhere,'' Westphal said. ``Rashard did fine. We lost a
few, and it's time to go with the veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   The move was intended to give the Sonics an early scoring boost,
and it did. They shot 50 percent in the first quarter, and trailed
by only three.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Sonics fell apart, shooting a mere 30 percent
(18-for-60) the rest on the game.
</P>
<P>
   Since beating Utah at home Feb. 16, the Sonics have managed to
upend only the struggling Los Angeles Lakers. That was the only
time this season the Sonics benefited from balanced scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got starters who have made shots their whole careers,
and they're not making them,'' Westphal said. ``Why is a mystery to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were equally as bad at the foul line, sinking just 27
of 45.
</P>
<P>
   Baker missed all four of his free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was determined. Unfortunately, the eye really threw me off.
I kind of never got back in it because I was seeing double all
night,'' Baker said. ``It's disappointing. This team is doing
everything it can to win games, and I'm not playing well. I'm not
playing my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's first field goal originated from the right low block.
With Duncan defending, Baker turned toward the baseline and made a
strong move toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   However, that diligence didn't last long in the first half.
After attempting his second shot from the post, Baker started
launching from outside and missed four of his first five shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics still managed to stay close in the first half,
trailing 47-41 at the break. But they missed seven straight shots
at the start of the third quarter, many of them layups and
wide-open jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring drought lasted for five minutes until Payton hit a
short jump shot. Payton scored the Sonics' first six points in the
quarter, but his one-man act couldn't keep the Sonics from falling
behind 68-49 with 3:04 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Vladimir Stepania gave the Sonics their only spark when
he started the fourth quarter. Stepania, who was active on the
boards, finished with nine points. He was also effective defending
Robinson long enough to help the Sonics get within 87-77 with 3:05
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as Stepania was, he could not stay with Robinson the
entire period. The Spurs pulled away for good after Robinson dunked
the ball twice over Stepania in the game's last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully in the fourth quarter, two things happened: One, we
scored and two, we hit our free throws,'' Spurs coach Gregg
Popovich said. ``Those are the two things that have been tough for
us all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Westphal, the Sonics are still dealing in the
present tense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
