<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-25 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKY BOOSTERS SHOULD THROW MONEY LAMBRIGHT'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the news conference in which Rick Neuheisel was announced
as University of Washington football coach, I asked Rob Aronson,
faculty representative and a member of the coaching search
committee, whether he expected former coach Jim Lambright to sue
the school.
</P>
<P>
   Aronson, in his fifth year as rep and familiar with the athletic
department, seemed taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no,'' he said. ``I don't think he would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Really?
</P>
<P>
   Makes one wonder what else was assumed by the UW search
committee. Maybe they figured Neuheisel knew the NCAA rule book,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows Lambright reasonably well had to know he wasn't
going to go down without an embarrassing public fight.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's story that he was dissatisfied with terms of his UW
settlement and was contemplating filing a lawsuit was as shocking
as wet shoes in February.
</P>
<P>
   It was classic Lambo _ stubborn, prideful, reckless, unthinking
and money-driven.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention divisive. His backers, and they are numerous and
wealthy, want the university and athletic director Barbara Hedges
to pay, in cash and image, for what is perceived to be an abrupt,
disloyal end to a noble Husky career.
</P>
<P>
   Even more numerous and wealthier are those who wanted him out.
They helped facilitate the hijacking of Neuheisel from Colorado,
and feel that the $276,000 settlement was more than Lambright
deserved, given how he imperiled the program with his political and
tactical blunders.
</P>
<P>
   In between, sort of, is Hedges. She was eager to see Lambright
gone, but now is equally eager to get him out of the headlines,
given how many headlines she's having to explain with her new hire.
</P>
<P>
   The football coaching change has had more snags than barbed wire
on panty hose, and guess what? Neuheisel's contract still isn't
done, more than six weeks after his hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always takes a while for these things,'' Hedges said
Wednesday. ``It (the delay) really means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if the crew hasn't controlled the old fire, it's
hard to bear down on the fresh flames.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the diplomat, Hedges avoided saying she wished Lambo would
go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (a lawsuit) is in anyone's best interests,'' she
said. ``He's taken the position he felt he needed to. That's the
only thing I can think or know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said she is unable, by terms of Lambright's state
contract, to offer more than the maximum buyout ($176,000 for one
year's base salary, and a $100,000 annuity). And since the contract
says he can be fired at will, there is no dispute about the
university's rights.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to Lambright's Seattle attorney, Tracy
Codd, is the way it was done _ with no public indication of
trouble. Hedges' unqualified endorsement of Lambright in November
led the coach to believe he was secure. If Lambright had known of
the jeopardy, Codd said, he might have sought another job during
the narrow window of annual coaching openings.
</P>
<P>
   There's also some thought that, since Lambright's final contract
extension was not completed and signed until January 1998, after
the Aloha Bowl win against Michigan State and six months after
negotiations started, the ax had been out for a while. Codd
speculates there may be grounds for a violation of contract law
called fraud in the inducement.
</P>
<P>
   The merits of any case, if filed, are unknowable. What is known
is that Lambright is hacked off and the university by law can't
appease him, even though numerous other settlements involving
Division I coach firings are for much more money.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, undoubtedly lost on Lambright, is that he is seeking
the same kind of respect and appreciation that he failed to accord
Shane Fortney and Nick Lentz, two players who left the program
because of Lambright decisions, yet were denigrated publicly and
privately by Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hedges and her booster backers need to consider
the trouble an embittered Lambright will make. His is a
black-and-white world where you are with him or against him, where
loyalty and betrayal are his primary, if not exclusive, definers of
behavior. Don't expect compromise or subtle persuasion to work.
</P>
<P>
   If athletic department money is unavailable, the boosters who
encouraged his ouster might give serious consideration to passing
the hat among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of anything like that going on,'' Hedges said.
``It certainly could be done, as long as it's private money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person was interested in doing that, I'd encourage them
to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   By law and perhaps by conscience, Lambright doesn't deserve
more. But the the athletic department's million-dollar decision to
hire Slick Rick has sufficiently irritated the college football
nation to the point that the purple throngs are finding trouble
where they never imagined it.
</P>
<P>
   The Lambright dilemma needs to be in the past, and there is one
tried-and-true business solution: Throw money at it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the athletic department isn't familiar with the
trick.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
