 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2523 - February 25, 1999   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2523 -- Feb. 25, 1999 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. COLONEL QADDAFI IN HIS TENT A Western journalist travels to
Libya for an exclusive interview with Colonal Mu'ammar Qaddafi and
finds a country struggling to modernize. Tired of suffering under
the U.N. embargo, Libya may be ready to hand the suspected
Lockerbie bombers over for trial. After being pariahs for over a
decade, most Libyans seem eager to re-enter the international
community. But power in their country is divided between
bureaucrats who favour the West and the old, fiercely anti-colonial
revolutionaries who still cherish Qaddafi's defiance. By Milton
Viorst. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
THE GOALS OF CHINA'S GROWING MILITARY STRENGTH Whether or not China
becomes a global threat in the future is irrelevant to its
activities in Asia today. China is definitely on the move, and its
full intentions are far from clear. James Webb, secretary of the
U.S. navy under President Reagan, discusses China's growing
military strength. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,000 words. 3. STUDY
FINDS LITTLE RISK OF CANCER FROM CARCINOGENS
</P>
<P>
   IN COOKED MEAT People who eat more meat have higher rates of
colon and rectal cancers, two of the most common causes of cancer
death. But just why eating more meat increases a person's risk of
cancer is unknown. One theory holds that chemicals formed when meat
is fried, grilled or roasted at high temperatures are to blame. But
Swedish researchers now report that they could find no strong link
between cancer rates and the amount of these chemicals people ate
in their diet. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
AMERICA SPEAKS LOUDLY BUT ISN'T AT ALL SURE There is a remarkable
gap between the role America seems to seek in the world when it
talks of leadership and a new ``strategic concept'' for NATO to
meet an assortment of global challenges and how Americans see
themselves. The end of the Cold War hasn't brought any clear idea
of what to do now. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
WHAT'S DOING IN MADRID The city of Madrid is the epicentre of
Spain's new-found prosperity and pride. By Penelope Casas. From The
New York Times Way To Go! 1,500 words + photos. 6. TO KILL A
SUPERBUG Zip-forming, gene-blocking, bug-killing, life-saving ...
Helen Gavaghan investigates the latest hope in the relentless quest
for potent new antibiotics. From New Scientist magazine. 2,500
words. (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.)
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NEW YORK TIMES SCIENCE TIMES:
</P>
<P>
   A. SOME RARE PEOPLE SEE A SOUND AND HEAR A COLOUR Some people
have a rare condition called synesthesia, in which the customary
boundaries between the senses appear to break down, sight mingling
with sound, or taste with touch (e.g. the number 5 is seen as
yellow; the month of January as red.) The arrival of imaging
techniques and other new technologies for studying the brain at
work has revived interest in synesthesia. Researchers hope that the
condition will give a greater understanding of all kinds of
perception or even shed light on the nature of consciousness
itself. By Erica Goode. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. HEALTHY FEET FOR WEEKEND ATHLETES Feet that spend Monday
through Friday under a desk can be damaged by Saturday sport
enthusiasm. With just a few basic cautions, weekend athletes can
avoid injuries. By John O'Neil. 750 words + graphic. 8. exile.com
Five years behind bars for hacking wasn't punishment enough. Meet
the Amazing Modemless Man. By Kevin Poulsen. From WIRED magazine.
(N/A Japan.)
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
E-MALADIES A clever hacker could insert a virus in an
innocent-looking e-mail and wreak havo for the unwary computer
owner. So far, that hasn't happened, although flaws have been found
in certain e-mail programs that could allow such an intrusion. The
greater danger, experts believe, is an interloper finding his or
her way into an Internet service provider. By Corey E. Powell. From
Discover magazine. 750 words + photo. 
