<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV28-C     02-25 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GORE BECOMES A PUNDIT'S PEN PAL
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In ramping up for his coming presidential race, Al
Gore has sent a two-page letter to more than 100,000 people,
inviting them to become members of his ``National Steering
Committee'' _ a group that will never meet and has no formal
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The mailing, a Gore spokesman said, was targeted at folks who
have contributed to President Clinton's past campaigns. Although as
a working journalist I've never given any politician a dime, I made
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   True, I've contributed to charities and schools that also
interest Gore and his wife. (Charitable giving has been a sore
topic for Gore since last April, when Republicans branded him
``Vice President Scrooge'' for donating only $353 to charity on
1997 income of $197,729.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's lifestyle remains well beyond the reach of most
millionaires. His cocoon comes complete with a mansion, planes,
cars and bodyguards, all courtesy of the taxpayers. (When Gore's
charitable gifts for 1998 and 1999 come to light, you can bet
they'll top $353.)
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always thus. When Harry Truman served in the vice
presidency, he lived in an apartment that's a five-minute walk from
my home. Old-timers recall Truman strolling and shopping in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the letter (prepared by Gore 2000 Inc. and crafted
by the unionized Allied Printing Trades Council on recycled paper)
does make a stab at human contact. He concludes, ``I need your
advice.'' So here goes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Your advisers say that you'll need to put some political
distance between yourself and the president to highlight ``the Gore
agenda.'' Don't. You're forever joined at the hip to Bill Clinton.
To act otherwise will make you look like a phony.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prepare for the day that Ken Starr comes after your old pal
Nathan Landow. As your longtime top fund raiser, Landow got into
Starr's sights for allegedly pressuring Clinton volunteer Kathleen
Willey to clam up. (When called before Starr's grand jury, he took
the Fifth.) Perhaps you'll get off the hook if Attorney General
Janet Reno finds a way to shut Starr down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ditch ``Earth in the Balance,'' your 1992 best-seller in which
you wrote that ``the froth and frenzy of industrial civilization
mask our deep loneliness.'' Jimmy Carter took a huge hit for his
``malaise'' speech; the same thing could happen to you. For the
1992 campaign, your staff wrote an internal memo warning you that
to equate ``the failure to recycle aluminum cans with the
Holocaust,'' as you did in your book, shows ``no sense of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep laughing at yourself before most audiences. But ease up
on the ``I'm-a-stiff'' jokes: They cut too close to the bone.
Successful pols usually marry their public and private personas. So
should you.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, you took it in stride when my son beat out your
daughter by one vote to become president of the joint school
government club. (She got to serve as his vice president.) Now,
I'll take no offense at being tagged as a ``good friend to the
president and me'' if you'll buy the notion that pundits should
look out solely for the best interests of their readers.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
