<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     02-25 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gun industry, you can save yourself
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a great idea for gun manufacturers, though they won't
think so right away: Their industry should start thinking about
supporting national gun control.
</P>
<P>
   No, really.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the industry faces a growing chaos of federal, state
and city regulations and laws _ and lawsuits, too _ whose
inconsistency and often ad hoc nature pester and confuse legitimate
owners, aid criminals by creating as many cracks as barriers and
nudge the manufacturers themselves into strategies that threaten in
the long run to be their own undoing.
</P>
<P>
   The long-standing but inanimate public support for control is
finally beginning to exert itself.
</P>
<P>
   A Brooklyn jury recently bought the argument, and brought in a
$4 million judgment for seven victim families, that 15 major gun
makers were legally negligent for flooding low-regulation states
with firearms they had to know would be smuggled to black markets
in strong-control states. Ninety percent of the guns criminals use
in New York state are bought elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A number of cities, bloodied by gun violence, are filing similar
suits, and the NAACP is thinking of joining in to give the claims
some national oomph. And gun-control organizations, like Handgun
Control, have acquired enough political and lobbying savvy and
popular support that they've pretty much established a standoff
with the gun lobby in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has even managed to get two useful bills
enacted _ the Brady law and the ban on military-style assault
weapons _ and seems likely to win funding to add 10 cities to his
successful program in 27 that is tracing guns used by young
criminals back to their buyers. (Contrary to myth, most weapons
used by youths are not stolen but were bought for the kid market by
straw buyers.)
</P>
<P>
   Blocked in Congress, the National Rifle Association, the
manufacturers' faithful dogsbody, is resorting to frantic measures
in state legislatures, where its money still talks. Georgia's
Legislature has passed a law forbidding its cities to sue the
industry, and blocking bills are pending in nine other states.
</P>
<P>
   The industry as well is resorting to what look like desperate
means. With hunting slumping in an ever less rural America,
manufacturers increased the number of pistols they produced by 92
percent between 1985 and '93 and upped the firing speed and
caliber. Some are now making so-called ``pocket rockets'' _ small,
lightweight, easily concealed and still more powerful than older
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   It is inconceivable that the public will put up with this
escalation forever. The backlash, when it hits, could be furious
both in legislatures and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be better to act before the human damage piles up
still higher? It is perfectly possible to draw national firearms
regulations that equally recognize the legitimate interests of
owners and protect public safety.
</P>
<P>
   (And thus incidentally secure a predictable and durable market
for the business itself, but it's OK if Colt, Smith &AMP; Wesson and
the rest don't thank me for that.)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
