<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERFUME-GUERLAIN26-CO     02-25 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFUME-GUERLAIN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Algae? Hay? Romantic? Makes scents, says French perfumer (whose
nose obviously knows)
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fl.a _ Jean-Paul Guerlain can smell you.
</P>
<P>
   Get within spitting distance, and he just can't help it. Got
deodorant? Apply liberally. Nothing, not even garbage in Manhattan
in July, insults his nostrils like a case of B.O.
</P>
<P>
   Guerlain is known as the ``nose'' of his family's famous
Paris-based perfume business. He recognizes thousands of scents and
has created 14 perfumes (among them Shalimar), the formulas for
which, until recently, he kept in a safe. And only he could open
it.
</P>
<P>
   His talent is not so much physical _ ``He doesn't have a bionic
nose,'' his publicist warns _ as mental. Growing up nearly blind,
he was called on by his grandfather to memorize the smells of
jasmine, sandalwood and other materials and become a company
catalog of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Guerlain, now 62, calls himself a master perfumer. ``There are
not more than 10 or 12 in the world who deserve the title,'' he
sniffs.
</P>
<P>
   He visited his Palm Beach boutique at The Breakers last week
(where one 1 ounce of his Vega costs $1,200) and had a few minutes
to chat. It was his first trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: How many smells can you recognize?
</P>
<P>
   A.: A girl who worked with me for 35 years once counted all the
smells I really remember. She arrived at about 3,000. People are
always amazed by that. But the Chinese and Japanese know ten
thousands of writing characters. Surely, that's more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: When did you first know you had a great nose?
</P>
<P>
   A.: When I was 16. I was more or less blind. I was really unable
to go down the staircase. My grandfather said to my father, ``Send
him to my place.'' I would go every afternoon to the factory. He
put me in a room with 100 raw materials and said, ``Try to memorize
them.'' Every evening, he would dip a blotter (he waves his hand in
front of his nose) and ask, ``What's that?'' Then, one day, he gave
me a bottle of perfume and said, ``Try and do something like
that.'' He called my father and said, ``It's not your eldest son
who will work with me; it's Jean-Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Can you see now?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Now I am able to see. I had 17 operations. The last one, the
18th, was only five years ago. I still suffer in a lot of light.
(The day is overcast, but he wears sunglasses.)
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What scent do you wear?
</P>
<P>
   A.: The lady with whom I'm in love wishes me to wear Derby (a
Guerlain perfume). We've been together for 14 years. I created
Samsara for her.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What smell do you wake up to?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I always travel with a bottle of her perfume. First thing, I
take and smell it. And I never go to sleep without smelling
something.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What does Florida, or Palm Beach, smell like?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I must say not much.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What are the most romantic scents?
</P>
<P>
   A.: The ocean, surely, with the algae. New-mown hay. And what I
smell when I go through India _ jasmine, the pepper, the coffee.
India is the most romantic because everything smells.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Have you ever had odd requests to use your nose?
</P>
<P>
   A.: When I was young, a researcher working on mushrooms brought
me his collection and asked me to try to identify their smells. I
was quite amazed by the question.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Did you do it anyway?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Do you do anything special to take care of your nose?
</P>
<P>
   A.: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Are you allergic to anything?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Stupid women. And garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Can you ``turn off'' your nose?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Unfortunately not. I think it's worse when I'm in a
restaurant _ this happens unfortunately too often _ and the server
has a bad perspiring smell. And since I don't smoke anymore, I'm
disturbed by the tobacco smell.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Can you tell things about people by their smell?
</P>
<P>
   A.: No, but by their perfume, yes. You can tell a girl by her
perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: An example?
</P>
<P>
   A.: (Pause) No, I don't want to get into a mess. (Smiles.)
</P>
<P>
   Q.: How would you compare the smell of Americans and the French?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Americans will buy what the best salesgirl convinces them to
buy. Many buy the latest perfume and don't even smell it. A pity.
They give too much importance to the advertising, not the quality
of the liquid inside. The French say, ``A meal without wine and
cheese is like a day without the sun.'' Perfume is very important.
When you switch off the light, it's the only thing left but the
charm of her voice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
