<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES26-COX     02-25 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Katz decamps, reaps `Mountain' of rewards
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some men deal with midlife by buying new sports cars
and shedding wives. Jon Katz bought a ramshackle cabin on a
mountain and read books by the Trappist monk Thomas Merton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really a midlife crisis,'' says Katz, a contributing
editor for Rolling Stone and the author of the Suburban Detective
mystery series. ``The only crisis was that it dawned on me I was
entering the final stage of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he admits, it was quite a comfortable life. As a free-lance
writer, he had spent several years looking after his daughter while
his wife worked as a reporter for The Washington Post. He carpooled
so much he became known as ``the Prince of Rides.'' Once his
daughter turned 17 and was getting ready for college, that part of
his life was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want to continue to write the same mysteries
and do the same things I had always done,'' Katz says. ``More and
more we had drifted into the baby boomer habit of defining
ourselves by our children, rather than by the things we ourselves
were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the summer of 1997, Katz ignored the advice of his wife
and friends and left his suburban New Jersey home to spend six
months in a cabin in upstate New York. He chronicles his
experiences in ``Running to the Mountain: A Journey of Faith and
Change'' (Villard, $20).
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did, although I didn't realize it at the time, is a
bigger fantasy for middle-aged men than sex. They would come up to
me and say, `What you did is what I want to do.' They're harried,
they're worried about their parents and their kids. They don't want
to spend the rest of their life being hassled.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz admits his timing couldn't have been worse. His daughter
was getting ready to leave for college, his house needed extensive
repairs and his free-lance writing career was as risky as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely could not afford it,'' Katz says, ``but I thought
if I didn't do this, I didn't know what I would do. My wife
reluctantly agreed when she saw how important this was to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz was prepared to spend a lot of time repairing the cabin.
What he was not prepared for was the solitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence was the loudest sound I had ever heard,'' Katz
says. ``The second night I was there, I drove to a liquor store and
got a big bottle of Glenlivet and drank most of it. I didn't drink
after that. I came to treasure being alone. I loved it so much it
scared me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came down off the mountain, he had had no epiphanies,
experienced no revelations, but he was a changed man. For one
thing, his publisher had canceled his mystery series and he felt as
if a great burden had been lifted. And he'd learned that
spirituality was possible outside of organized religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around beautiful, quiet things is spiritual. Growth
doesn't have to come from religion; it can come from the kind of
father and the kind of husband you are.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wordplay: Every time a revised edition of a dictionary
appears, a big deal is made about all the new words that have been
created. Words such as cybersurf and nerd and e-mail. But what
about all the words that drop off the map? Well, you can read all
about them in Jeffrey Kacirk's ``Forgotten English'' (Quill, $11
paperback), a bizarre and entertaining guide to archaic words.
Among the gems Kacirk has uncovered are ``isabelline,'' an
adjective indicating a grayish-yellow or parchment color, named for
a princess who vowed not to change her underwear until her unlucky
father won a certain battle; ``piggesnye,'' a term of endearment
for one's sweetheart; or ``amober,'' a medieval Welsh legal term
for a ``maiden fee,'' a payment imposed by the lord of the manor as
compensation for forgoing his right to sleep with a servant girl on
her wedding night. Kacirk's stories behind the words offer a
fascinating glimpse into history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Story search: Paul Cossman at Humpus Bumpus Books in Cumming
is looking for a few good writers for his ``O, Georgia!'' and ``O,
Georgia, Too!'' anthologies. Cossman, who had to cancel the ``O,
Georgia!'' competition last year because of lack of participation,
says the anthologies are a good opportunity for Georgia writers to
showcase their work. Plus, he says, there are cash prizes of $250
for the best adult writer and $100 and $50 prizes for the top three
student writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``O, Georgia!'' is open to adults, ``O, Georgia, Too!'' to
students from kindergarten through grade 12. For entry forms and
information, call 770-781-9705 or send e-mail to
paulcossman(at)mindspring.com. The deadline is March 15.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
