<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Duane's Depressed' familiar new offering by McMurtry
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry McMurtry apparently has run out of country song titles for
his novels. There were ``All My Friends are Gonna Be Strangers''
and ``Moving On,'' the old Hank Snow hit, and ``Leaving Cheyenne''
and ``Somebody's Darling'' and ``Streets of Laredo.'' They didn't
come in sequence, but they were in there along with other titles
such as ``The Last Picture Show'' and ``Terms of Endearment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archer City, Texas, native has turned out a passel of good,
not-so-good, and very, very good novels including the one that
pushed him over the line, apparently, into a national superstar and
Pulitzer winner, ``Lonesome Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think ``Lonesome Dove'' was his best, but I did like it
very much. My favorites at this moment anyway are, ``Moving On''
and ``Leaving Cheyenne.'' From remarks attributed to him over the
years, I have the impression McMurtry never has particularly liked
``Leaving Cheyenne,'' for reasons I could never fathom. Maybe
because so many of his fans loved it so much back in his early
years and he didn't want to be tied to an early bird like that. I
have great respect for McMurtry as a writer. I like him fine as a
person, too, despite the popular notion that he is hard to talk to
and generally unfriendly at times.
</P>
<P>
   I've been around McMurtry from time to time over the years and
never found him to be off-putting in any way. I have heard stories
from others, however, and figure that's his business. If he wants
to occasionally be unapproachable, he has as much right to that as
those who approach him have a right to do so. Maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   Actors and singers and even professional athletes may be obliged
to interact with their fans, since their fans pay money _
increasing amounts of money _ to watch them do what they do. But
writers must do their work in private, alone, so it seems different
to me. But I digress....
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry's new novel is titled ``Duane's Depressed.'' The Duane
in question is, of course, the one we first met in ``The Last
Picture Show'' as a teen-ager and later as a husband and father
approaching middle age in ``Texasville.''
</P>
<P>
   Duane's gotten relatively rich in the ``awl bidness'' and is
now, in this latest, in his early 60s and wondering whether his
life has been meaningful or not.
</P>
<P>
   The opening chapter is hilarious, especially if you grew up in
Small Town, Texas, where nobody walked anywhere. Duane suddenly
decides to park his pickup and walk everywhere he needs to go. This
not only upsets his wife, Karla, it stirs up a controversy all over
the town of Thalia. Friends and neighbors wonder if Duane has come
down with Alzheimers or completely lost his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Karla's first thought is that Duane has decided to divorce her.
She is even more upset when Duane decides to walk the six miles to
his cabin and live there indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   All the ``Last Picture Show'' characters are accounted for in
this story, that comes closer to having the familiar McMurtry tone
and flavor than some of his other books have in recent years. If
you liked ``The Last Picture Show'' and ``All My Friends are Gonna
Be Strangers,'' you'll probably like this one.
</P>
<P>
   We discover what happened to Jacy, the town's prettiest girl who
caused Duane and others so much angst in their teens. Duane's
problems now usually involve his children and grandchildren, all
except those who are serving time in jail seem to live with, or
very near, him and Karla and depend on Duane for their basic needs.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite character in ``Duane's Depressed'' may be Shorty,
Duane's dog, who is loyal to a fault as dog's so often are.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then you hear that McMurtry has decided to quit writing
books. ``Duane's Depressed'' makes me hope that's just another
baseless rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
