<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSHMORE-DIRECTOR26-C     02-25 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSHMORE-DIRECTOR26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner was the inspiration for `Rushmore' millionaire
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you've seen the movie ``Rushmore,'' you might think
Bill Murray _ who plays a millionaire steel tycoon _ reminds you of
somebody. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of modeled his look on Ted Turner,'' says Wes
Anderson, co-writer and director of the critically acclaimed prep
school comedy, now playing. ``I had these photographs of Ted Turner
that I took to the makeup woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Funnily enough, he's speaking only two blocks from CNN Center,
sitting on a couch in the back of a bright yellow tour bus. You
know, the rock 'n' roll kind of bus, complete with claustrophobic
sleeping berths and a seasoned driver accustomed to bad behavior
and long hours.
</P>
<P>
   So is this bus fulfilling some sort of rock star fantasy for the
young director?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not,'' Anderson says with a sigh, a shake of the
head, then a yawn. ``Someone at Disney came up with the idea. We
arrived in Atlanta about midnight last night. I got four hours'
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's got resilience. He's only 29, though his gangly, pale,
spiky-haired looks could make you think he's younger.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving raves, ``Rushmore'' earned several critics' awards for
Murray, as well as a Golden Globe nomination for best supporting
actor. He plays a middle-aged man who runs afoul of 15-year-old
preppieMax Fischer (Jason Schwartzman) when both guys fall for the
same woman.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson co-wrote the script with actor Owen Wilson
(``Armageddon''). They met during college in Austin, Texas; made a
short movie called ``Bottle Rocket'' about a band of hapless,
would-be thieves; and enlisted the aid of producer-director James
L. Brooks (``As Good as It Gets'') in turning it into a feature
film. The '96 comedy earned good reviews, but didn't do much
business.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Wilson (who's now acting opposite Liam Neeson and
Lili Taylor in DreamWorks' summer ghost flick ``The Haunting of
Hill House'') decided to write ``Rushmore'' because they both went
to prep schools. Wilson's was in Dallas, Anderson's in Houston; in
fact, the director's old alma mater stood in for the fictional
academy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie doesn't take place in Texas, per se, but in a
fablelike atmosphere. ``In the real world, this kid would never be
able to do what he does,'' Anderson says. ``So it was important to
have a world with its own logic, different from reality. We did
things with the design that makes it unreal. The walls are colors
you'd never get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson visited his old school several times to ``do the
politics'' of getting permission to shoot there. ``It was fun,
because one of my classmates is teaching there now,'' he says. ``He
introduced me to a lot of people he thought I'd like to cast. Like
the `Serpico' play is all cast from the school and a lot of the
supporting, bit players.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder to come by was his Max. He auditioned around 1,800 teens
for the lead role. ``A lot of them were on tape. But I saw hundreds
and hundreds in person. I spent a year. We wanted somebody you'd
never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman fit the bill, though he wasn't without Hollywood
connections. He's the son of actress Talia Shire, nephew of Francis
Ford Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Wilson share a house in Los Angeles with Owen's
brother, actor Luke Wilson (``Home Fries''). They're already
writing their next movie, about a New York family of geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they're really geniuses,'' he qualifies, ``but
they each have some kind of inspired area. It'll be a big cast, and
hopefully we'll try to shoot it sometime at the end of the year.
But we have to do a lot of work first.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no script yet. But Anderson has a couple of small,
spiral-bound notebooks, laid on the table in front of him. They're
crammed with precise notes in capital letters, and tiny sketches.
``You can flip,'' he says, handing a notebook to a reporter.
``Don't read.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
