<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURES-BJT26-COX     02-25 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, February
26, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SKI-CANADA _ BANFF, ALBERTA _ Skiing, etc. at Banff/Lake
Louise: You should be as lucky as me right now: I am stamping my
Australian lamb-lined soft-leather Uggs on a glittering frozen pond
in the middle of western Canada. My right hand is wrapped around a
steaming, very strong Irish coffee. My left hand is deep inside the
pocket of a fleece ski parka. It's cold: minus-something Celsius,
but I'm dressed for it. And the sky is the clearest, darkest black
you've ever seen, and the Big Dipper is turned upside down and
spilling stars all over the place, while the man in the full
Canadian moon is grinning a big, goofy, McKenzie brothers smile.
That bright grin lights up everything: three soaring peaks of
Canadian Rockies that run along the frozen river behind me; the
castle-like Banff Springs Hotel that rises on the steep hill to my
right; the snow-bloated pines that scent the air
everywhere.(Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, FEB. 28.
</P>
<P>
   SKI-HANGOUT _ PARK CITY, UTAH _ A ``Greetings From . . . ``
Travel photo page on Park City, Utah, a
mining-outpost-turned-hip-ski-hangout where past and present
collide. (Tulis/Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, FEB. 28.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES _ Going Places (travel notes) column. Thrasher.
</P>
<P>
   ADVENTURES-COMMENTARY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Adventure travel
used to mean something along the lines of riding a camel through
dust storms in Morocco, hot on the trail of the mysterious Blue
People. Or hacking your way with a machete through Peru's jungles,
looking for a lost tribe that, you hope, isn't associated with the
Shining Path. But lately, the word adventure has become a marketing
term to make tame tours sound more thrilling. Do you really think
15 people packed on an enormous raft, an inflated version of a tour
bus, drifting down a river is an adventure? A group hike on a
national park trail as crowded as a city sidewalk is thrilling?
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post). 22.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-NGEORGIA _ A father and son make the five-mile trek to
Amicalola Falls State Park's new Len Foote Hike Inn in the North
Georgia mountains and then kick back and enjoy nature. (Williams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-WRINKLES _ Aging baby boomers want to defy the inevitable
aghing process, and cosmetic manufacturers have dozens of products
on the market to help them. From Clinique to Lancome and Estee
Lauder, women can take their pick of anti-aging, wrinkle free
creams. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY 0228
</P>
<P>
   PERFUME-GUERLAIN _ An interview with perfumer Jean-Paul
Guerlain. Photo available. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). 22 WITH PHOTO.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FASHIONWEEK-WRAP _ NEW YORK _ Fashion editors sound off on what
didn't fly during fashion week. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-ENTERTAINMENT 0226 _ The phenomenon began a long time ago
in a cineplex not so far away. Now it's coming back _ in 83 days,
to be precise. And leading up to its May 21 release, George Lucas'
fourth ``Star Wars'' film will be one hyped-up ``Menace'' to
society. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITES -- Web sites focusing on the release of ``The Phantom
Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CHANNEL -- Turner South, Turner Broadcasting's 18th cable
TV channel, is scheduled to debut sometime this fall with a focus
on the South. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- Think of ``Ronin'' as a postmodern action
movie. This guilty pleasure from director John Frankenheimer casts
Robert De Niro as a member of an ad hoc band of secret warriors,
along with Jean Reno, Stellan Skarsgard and Sean Bean. (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Once upon a time, Blondie was arguably the coolest
band in the world. Fronted by Deborah Harry, the perfect new wave
pinup girl, this New York combo churned out a string of
chart-topping hits. ``No Exit,'' Blondie's first album in 17 years,
shows how much times have changed. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONDUCTOR-DEPREIST _ A visit with conductor James DePreist, 62,
who leads the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra this weekend. The
62-year-old has studied with the best, and survived polio. He grew
up in South Philly, the birthplace of musicians from Mario Lanza to
Frankie Avalon. The great contralto Marian Anderson was his aunt.
Though a well-regarded possibility to succeed Yoel Levi, whose
contract with ASO expires in 2000, DePreist denies any
``candidacy.'' He's been music director of the Oregon Symphony for
19 seasons. (Green, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM _ Next month, ``Star Wars'' prequel fans will get their
second big fix _ a new 2.5 minute trailer to ``The Phantom Menace''
with more than 100 fresh images from the film. And coming in late
April and early May is Lucasfilm Ltd.'s officially sanctioned
three-day ``Star Wars Celebration'' fanfest to be held at Denver's
Wings Over The Rockies Museum (it'll have sneak peeks at
``Phantom,'' visits by some of the film's stars, including young
Jake Lloyd (Anakin Skywalker), and of course lots and lots of
merchandise to sell). (BLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/PHANTOM-INTERNET _ May the rumors be with you. With the first
``Star Wars'' prequel set to open May 21, the Internet is abuzz
with ``The Phantom Menace'' spy reports, apparently pilfered sound
clips and much innuendo. We tour several sites, including renegade
www.theforce.net which boasts a purported frame-by-frame rundown
(in words only, sorry) of the coming trailer. (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ NBC airs ``Alice In Wonderland'' in
a three-hour blitz on Sunday; plus The Learning Channel looks at
Rodney King on Saturday. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SMILEY _ A day with Pulitzer Prize-winning author Jane
Smiley (''A Thousand Acres,'' ``Moo'') at Wesleyan College in
Macon, Ga., where she's talking to students about women's education
and writing. (Weaver, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY 0228
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Of all forms of fictions, the spy novel draws
most on sensory response. In ``Archangel,'' Robert Harris immerses
us in the torpor and heaviness of Moscow and the forested expanses
of Siberia. Not only that but he reacquaints us with Joseph Stalin.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY 0228
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-RAYCHARLES _ Review of Michael Lydon's ``Ray Charles: Man
and Music.'' (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY 0228
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-PAPERBACKS _ List of new paperbacks. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Some men deal with midlife by buying new sports
cars and shedding their wives. Jon Katz bought a ramshackle cabin
on a mountain and read books by the Trappist monk Thomas Merton.
Then he wrote a book about his own ``journey of the soul.''
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ McMurtry's new novel is titled ``Duane's
Depressed.'' The Duane in question is, of course, the one we first
met in ``The Last Picture Show'' as a teen-ager and later as a
husband and father approaching middle age in ``Texasville.'' A
review. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   RUSHMORE-DIRECTOR _ We get on the bus with Wes Anderson, the
29-year-old co-writer and director of one of the best-reviewed
movies in a long time, ``Rushmore,'' which opened nationwide Feb.
12. Anderson swept through town, sleep-deprived and yawning, on a
tour bus sent by Disney. We chat with him about the writing
process, the buzz about Bill Murray's performance, and what's next.
(Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-CIGARETTES _ Review of ``200 Cigarettes,'' a comedy/drama
about a collection of young adults (Ben Affleck, Courtney Love,
Janeane Garofalo) trying to cope with relationships and neuroses.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-8MM _ Review of ``Eight Millimeter,'' a thriller starring
Nicolas Cage and Joaquin Phoenix. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SISTER _ A Disney drama for the romantically challenged,
starring Juliette Lewis and Diane Keaton. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS _ In honor of Texas Independence Day, we take a look at 10
of the best films about Texas and Texans, films that have explored
and challenged, defined and redefined the myths, stereotypes and
realities that make up the Lone Star State. Choices include the
obvious (''Giant,'' ``Red River,'' ``Hud,'' ``The Last Picture
Show'') and the not so obvious (''Bonnie and Clyde,'' ``Hands on a
Hard Body,'' ``Slacker''). Others on the list: ``The Border,''
``Blood Simple,'' ``Tender Mercies.'' (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EIGHT _ Review of the movie ``8 mm.'' A reel of crudely shot 8
mm film sends a small-time private eye down a gritty and
frightening path. A thriller with Nicolas Cage; directed by Joel
Schumacher. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ A column about QTIII, the Tarantino-hosted film
festival at the Alamo. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN _ Review of ``The 24-Hour Woman.'' A comedy about the
difficulties of a woman having it all in the '90s; from director
Nancy Savoca (``Household Saints''). (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SISTER _ Review of ``The Other Sister.'' Middle-aged parents
face big changes when their mentally challenged adult daughter
moves back in with them. With Diane Keaton, Tom Skerritt, Juliette
Lewis. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
