<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-25 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Feb. 25, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CALIF (San Francisco) _ President Clinton will try to
kick-start a Democratic effort to regain control of Congress in
2000 with a 24-hour trip to San Francisco that fuses money,
politics and a speech to foreign policy buffs. The president's
whirlwind trip demonstrates once again the Bay Area's reliable role
as a kind of ATM for Democratic politicians. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ABORTION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Many Republican presidential
candidates, including Elizabeth Dole, former Vice President Dan
Quayle and Sen. John McCain, arrive here this weekend for a state
GOP convention. But the candidates' beauty pageant threatens to be
overshadowed by a debate over abortion. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   PIE-SENTENCES (San Francisco) _ Three assailants convicted of
creaming Mayor Willie Brown in the face with pies got what
prosecutors believe to be their just desserts: six months in county
jail, the maximum possible punishment. By MacKENZIE WARREN.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-STING (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco freelance journalist
arrested in an Internet sting will have to stand trial on a felony
charge of attempted child molestation, a Sacramento judge has
ruled. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PALM-ORGANIZER (San Francisco) _ You can't be too skinny, too
bright or too connected. Especially when it comes to a handheld
organizer. 3Com has embraced this high-society truism with the
latest in its popular line of Personal Information Managers (PIMS),
the Palm V, which appeared on store shelves Monday. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-FEE (San Antonio) _ Mexico plans to charge tourists a $15
entry fee beginning July 1, a move critics say could harm tourism.
Mexico Tourism Minister Oscar Espinosa Villarreal announced the new
fee in Texas, where he is campaigning for foreign investment in
Mexico's tourism industry. The fee will be collected both from air
passengers and from tourists arriving by auto or bus. By DAVID
HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TOMATOES-HEALTH (Undated) _ There's no escaping the tomato. And
who would want to? This ubiquitous fruit is not only good, but
doctors say that a tomato a day can reduce a person's risk of
developing prostate, colon, rectal and breast cancers, as well as
cut the risk of heart attack. By JOHN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLD-STARS (Undated) _ Unsubstantiated death accounts of
long-forgotten entertainment personalities are nothing new on the
Web. Fortunately for some living actors who have been killed off by
gossip, fans determined to keep their idol's names alive have built
sites that have become staples of the Internet. By IHOSVANI
RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ER-LASALLE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Until the latest episode of
``ER,'' Eriq LaSalle (Dr. Peter Benton) never got his shot in the
spotlight as the sole focus of the hit ensemble. That has changed.
Why so long? ``I've been asking that for five years,'' LaSalle
says. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-QUESTIONS (Undated) _ Q: Why do recipes that call for bay
leaves always say to remove them before serving the food? A: The
bay leaf's edges are very sharp and have been know to perforate
people's intestines, so be sure to remove the herb after cooking.
By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTER-POTERIE (Undated) _ As kitchen gadgets go, the Butter
Poterie is one of the better ones. It's small, attractive and
actually works. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVERS (Undated) _ I often answer a question with a question.
Asked if it's safe to use a crate of canned tomatoes purchased
three years ago, I reply: ``Is the $12 you're saving by not
replacing those tomatoes worth a bout of food poisoning?'' Or, ``Is
wasting a bowl of pasta salad so bad you'll risk a case of
salmonella?'' Or, ``So, how big is the insurance policy on your
spouse?'' By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIATHLON (Albany, N.Y.) _ The U.S. Biathlon Team is hosting a
World Cup event this weekend at the Mt. VanHoevenberg Olympic
Sports Complex in Lake Placid. It's the first time a World Cup
event has been contested on American soil, and the first
significant international biathlon event in the United States since
1987. By TIM REYNOLDS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (San Francisco) _ In a stunning move that may signal
the end of Eddie DeBartolo's long association with the San
Francisco 49ers, DeBartolo's sister, citing her older brother's
past use of team and company funds, has officially cut DeBartolo
out of the famed organization. By CHUCK FINNIE, JOHN CRUMPACKER and
SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ First, this bit of rudeness in
the toniest part of Pacific Heights. On Wednesday morning fliers
appeared saying, ``Neighborhood Alert! Sexual predator headed our
way.'' The fliers referred to President Clinton's appearance at
Gordon and Ann Getty's home for a fund-raiser Thursday night.
There's no escape for the guy. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
