<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN26-CO     02-25 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The joys of travel in the comfort
of your home
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ I used to think I wanted to be a world
traveler. Be careful what you think you want to be.
</P>
<P>
   These past 10 years, toiling in the vineyards for Cox
Newspapers, I've been here, there and yonder. Of the three, I
prefer here.
</P>
<P>
   If you think otherwise, have at it. Even if you don't have the
price of a ticket to take you halfway around the world, you can
still experience the thrill, the romance and the excitement of
traveling to faraway places.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how:
</P>
<P>
   Pack a suitcase with everything you'll need for the next couple
of weeks _ clothes to wear, books to read, pills for what ails you.
But pack light. The reason they call it luggage is because you have
to lug it.
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to friends and family. You'll be on your own, a long
way from home and lonesome. Of course, this being a pretend
journey, you'll have to instruct them to treat you like a stranger
when they do happen to see you around town.
</P>
<P>
   Set your TV and radio on a Spanish station or, better yet, one
playing 24-hour rap music. Just so that it's incomprehensible,
that's the main thing. That's what travel is: going to places where
you don't know what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plane trip itself, it's easy to simulate. Decide
where you're heading. Europe is about eight hours away; Asia,
closer to 13. Just go to your downtown bus station. Spend that
amount of time sitting in a chair in the waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   You can get up to go to the bathroom, but otherwise keep your
seat. Eat your meals from a vending machine. Stare at a blank wall,
as if you're staring out the window of the plane. If there's a TV,
watch that instead. Inflight movies, don't you know. Personally, I
prefer a blank wall.
</P>
<P>
   By the time your behind is totally numb, you can figure you're
about halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know what it's like to go through customs, when
you leave the bus station, look for a cop and start staggering as
if you're drunk. You'll be treated accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget your luggage. You're going to be hauling it with
you wherever you go, loading it and unloading it in taxis, city
buses and subways.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think about driving a car. You're in one of those
countries where the traffic is upside down and backwards on the
wrong side of the street. You wouldn't last until the radiator got
hot.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be sleeping at home, of course, this being make-believe.
But you can sample the comfort of a foreign hotel easily enough.
Try sleeping on the couch _ better yet, an old couch in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   As for the facilities, run a garden hose through the bathroom
window to the tub. That'll be your shower. Little or no hot water
when you're shaving, either. Otherwise ... well, let's just say
toilet paper will be similarly rationed.
</P>
<P>
   Meals? That's tricky. There's nothing like foreign food.
Leastwise, nothing that we consider edible.
</P>
<P>
   The thing to do is pick local dishes you hate the most. Then
flavor them with castor oil. You'll get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, all this time you'll be jet-lagged. Simply
follow the above instructions at a time when you're just back on
your feet after a bout with the flu. That oughta do it.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
