   &UR; INTIMATE ENGINEERING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIVE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By MARY ROACH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Diane Kelly describes her unusual field of study, her
listeners, especially the men, tend to squirm. That's because she
spends her days doing experiments on the penises of mammals from
rats to armadillos. She is, to her knowledge, the first and only
scientist to study the biomechanics of the male organ _ in other
words, the principles of engineering and physics that enable the
penis to do what it's supposed to do. Mary Roach, a contributing
editor of Discover magazine, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-STUDY-OF-MALE-SEX-ORGANS-NYTSF. Sent to category
codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKTHROUGHS IN SCIENCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (900 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Forensic scientists use the presence of pollen in decades-old
remains to try to establish the season that a mass slaying in
Germany took place _ and thereby the probable culprits, the Nazis
or the Soviet secret police. Also, researchers test a revolutionary
new device to help totally paralyzed people communicate through
brain waves; and a fossil of a newly discovered species of
saber-toothed cat is unearthed.
</P>
