<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8968 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYCLUB-AZR &LR;      02-25 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA SCHOOL GAY CLUB ALLOWED TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
 CLUB-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILBERT, Ariz. - It's a typical high school club: socializing on
campus, volunteering with other school organizations, holding
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Only its status is unique.
</P>
<P>
   Gays, Lesbians and Straight Supporters, or GLASS, is believed to
be the only club in Phoenix area schools for gay or lesbian
students and their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, GLASS was not just a club with an untraditional
standing at Gilbert High School, but also one at risk of having no
standing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Since GLASS formed in January, the student council tried
unsuccessfully to ban the club, an Arizona lawmaker introduced a
bill that would have effectively done the same, and school and
district administrators looked into whether the club had a legal
right to be on campus.
</P>
<P>
   One state representative wrote the founder of GLASS, saying his
sexual orientation amounted to ``a death style, not a lifestyle'''
and she hoped his club would not be allowed to exist.
</P>
<P>
   None of which have fazed Jesse Evans, a 17-year-old senior who
formed GLASS. Openly gay, Evans said he's had people spit on him,
hurl gay-bashing epithets and throw trash at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilbert is the last place you would expect this club,'' Evans
said, calling it a religious and socially conservative enclave.
``Being openly gay at Gilbert High is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He and 20 other students formed the club to give gay and lesbian
students a haven where they don't feel different, where they aren't
misunderstood, and where they find support to navigate through
life. About half of the members are gay or lesbian; the others are
straight students who believe in supporting their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who are gay have not even told their parents of
their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's paramount to the youth to have a positive support
environment, whether it be in the home or school,'' said Lyle
Miller, executive director of Valley of the Sun Gay and Lesbian
Community Center. Miller said that gay youths are several times
more likely to attempt suicide and to drop out of school because of
derision and attacks from their peers.
</P>
<P>
   School clubs for gays and lesbians are rare locally. One emerged
last school year at Corona del Sol High School in Tempe, but it
dissolved when some of the members graduated last spring. A gay and
lesbian support group took its place, and other support groups have
cropped up at several other schools, including Chandler and Central
high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Several parents have told GLASS members that they don't believe
high school is the proper place for such a group and that the
students should seek counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The student council initially sought a change in the bylaws that
would have prevented clubs that don't have an academic bent,
students said. The council eventually decided against the move.
</P>
<P>
   And when Evans wrote her an e-mail about GLASS, Rep. Karen
Johnson, R-Mesa, fired one back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him that in my opinion that the particular
lifestyle that he has chosen, which he has every right to choose,
is something that I don't think is especially good for young people
that are still in their formative years, and that, in fact, I
looked at it as a death style not a lifestyle,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rep. Linda Gray, R-Glendale, introduced a bill
prohibiting school clubs that encourage criminal or delinquent
conduct, promote a specific sexual orientation or conduct that
contradicts abstinence. She since has decided to hold off on the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Such attempts have occurred elsewhere. Three years ago in Utah,
lawmakers passed a bill banning clubs that encourage criminal or
delinquent conduct, bigotry or sexual behavior, after the
Gay-Straight Alliance was formed at a Salt Lake City high school.
Eventually, the school board banished all non-academic clubs at all
of the city's high schools.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gilbert district officials downplayed concerns
about GLASS. They said they sought legal advice and held a couple
of meetings with Evans and his friends, but have concluded that the
club can continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the legal right to be there,'' Assistant
Superintendent Dave Allison said. ``We don't want it to be a
political action group. That would be true of any club.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Morrison, Gilbert School Board president, admitted there
is room for misunderstanding when folks hear about the club. But
every club will be given the same privileges as long as they abide
by the rules, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Gray still has problems with Gilbert High's GLASS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not like when kids are singled out and made fun of,'' she
said. But ``where does it (the club) meet academic standards?''
</P>
<P>
   Gray also took offense to club members trying to recruit
students during class time and telling each other they didn't have
to share with their parents that they were attending GLASS
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Evans said students and teachers have told him they respect
and admire his determination in forming the club. The straight
members of the club tell Evans they joined because they want to
support their gay friends and family members.
</P>
<P>
   Even the student council, which some said was against GLASS in
the beginning, is trying to find a happy medium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Evans said, he knows the future of GLASS is never a
given.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how life is going to be. It is a lot to handle,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Republic writers Melissa L. Jones and Hal Mattern contributed to
this article. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
