<HEADLINE>
DR. BENTON FINALLY GETS RESPECT ON `ER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Eriq LaSalle knew his time would come. Anthony
Edwards has had his episodes, same for Julianna Margulies. Of
course, we all know about George Clooney, whose departure from
``ER'' on the Feb. 18 episode is a milestone in the top-rated show.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Peter Benton never got his shot in the spotlight as the
sole focus of this ensemble hit.
</P>
<P>
   Why so long? ``I've been asking that for five years,'' LaSalle
said in a telephone interview last week. ``All the principals have
had not just one opportunity, but multiple opportunities. Finally,
this year Warner Brothers (the production studio) stepped in and
here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Benton stepped into the forefront in ``Middle of
Nowhere,'' the title of the episode where the young super surgeon
traveled to Mississippi on a special assignment he took for
much-needed cash. In the end he earned a lot more than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The episode itself, as I see it, is a metaphor about a man
going on a geographic journey, but more importantly ... an
emotional journey,'' LaSalle said. ``It allows him to get in touch
with himself with what is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps him to start diminishing his God complex. He
starts realizing he can't control everything. He can't control
people.''
</P>
<P>
   LaSalle said the most surprising thing about Benton's evolution
has been the audience's reaction. Originally, the acerbic doctor
was the character people loved to hate. After the third season he
became the character you hated to love. But through this process
viewers never became turned off to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more fun playing a three-dimensional character,'' LaSalle
said. ``You never know what you are going to get. He still has ego.
He can be cold and indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is human,'' LaSalle said. ``Sometimes you are going
to like him, sometimes you are not.''
</P>
<P>
   LaSalle said part of the appeal of Benton is that he can't be
pigeon-holed into the role of sinner or saint, hero or villain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times it is reverse racism, the `Noble Savage'
syndrome: we are either beasts or perfect,'' LaSalle said. ``No
race or people completely fits either one of those definitions.
This guy is flawed, but ultimately he has a good heart. But there
are times those flaws will overwhelm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously would like to see certain parts of Benton explored
more,'' LaSalle said. ``There are so many layers to this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clooney, LaSalle said his worth to the show went far
beyond what viewers saw on Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has been the center of the ensemble,'' LaSalle said.
``He is the big brother who took care of everybody. He helped keep
us a tight unit and I think that translates on film. He was the
peacekeeper, he was the clown, he was the adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   LaSalle was circumspect in discussing his own potential
departure from the show. ``My contract expires next year,'' LaSalle
said. ``I am on the show until my contract expires.''
</P>
<P>
   And after that? ``My contract expires next year,'' LaSalle
repeated. ``I am on the show until my contract expires.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
