<HEADLINE>
FANS KEEP OLD TV HEROES ALIVE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By IHOSVANI RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Mekka is still alive, and thank heavens for that.
</P>
<P>
   The poor dancing fool better known as Carmine Ragussa from
``Laverne and Shirley'' was rumored on the Internet to have been
polished off by some overzealous moose in North Dakota during a
hunting expedition several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unsubstantiated death accounts of long-forgotten entertainment
personalities are nothing new on the Web. Fortunately for Mekka,
fans determined to keep their idol's names alive have built sites
that have become staples of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Liz Clare's Internet tribute to Herman Wedemeyer.
Herman who? He's the chap who played Duke Lukela on ``Hawaii
Five-O.''
</P>
<P>
   From pictures of his football glory days, to his stint as a
state legislator in Hawaii, the site is Wedemeyer all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ``Hawaii Five-O'' sites are about Jack Lord, said
Clare, of Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about (Wedemeyer), and since I started
the site last June, I've learned so much about him,'' Clare said.
``I haven't heard from him, but I hear he's alive and well and
playing golf everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to another site, the name George Stanford Brown of the
1972-'76 police series ``The Rookies'' will no longer be a Trivial
Pursuit answer. A devoted fan of the star has ensured Brown's
perpetual presence on the Web. Like most typical fan pages, Brown's
includes a complete filmography, biography and photo gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is not totally relegated to television history. He
recently played a bit role on ``The X-Files.''
</P>
</TEXT>
