<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMATOES-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY WAY YOU SLICE IT, THE TOMATO IS PACKED WITH NUTRITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no escaping the tomato. And who would want to?
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes are used in everything from soup to salad. Texans, for
example, have long recognized the value of this fruit of the vine
(it's a vegetable only in the legal sense; the Supreme Court
declared it so in 1893 for trade purposes) and have used it
liberally in such regional staples as salsa, Spanish rice and pico
de gallo.
</P>
<P>
   It's also one of the few foods moms don't have to use a hard
sell to get their children to eat. A tomato's great flavor makes it
as appealing as its levels of vitamins and potassium.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that a tomato a day can reduce a person's risk of
developing prostate, colon, rectal and breast cancers, as well as
cut the risk of heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes contain a substance called lycopene, which has strong
cancer-fighting properties. Lycopene is an antioxidant in the
carotenoid family, the same group as beta carotene, and it is what
gives tomatoes their rich red color.
</P>
<P>
   Processed tomatoes are better than raw, said Dr. Venket Rao, a
professor in the University of Toronto's Department of Nutritional
Sciences, who has conducted independent studies of lycopene.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will increase the lycopene level, he explained, adding that
the level found in tomato paste is 2 1/2 times that of a raw
tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Rao's research also suggests that the body processes lycopene
more efficiently when it's taken with a small amount of oil or fat.
So any way you prepare or eat tomatoes _ even ketchup on a few
fries _ can be good for you.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Weir, a fourth-generation chef, found it easy to fill her
cookbook, ``You Say Tomato: Peel, Chop, Roast, Dry, Freeze,
Preserve, and Enjoy'' (Broadway Books, $15).
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other fruit or vegetable, the tomato has changed
the face of modern cuisine,'' Weir said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where we live, we look forward to growing our own
tomatoes or to buying them fresh at the farmers' market,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Weir is not one to let any part of the tomato go to waste. If a
recipe calls for peeling, she will save the skin, bake it and grind
it into what she calls tomato dust. The dust is a great flavor
enhancer in vinaigrettes, sauces and soups. It's also rich in
lycopene, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other red foods, such as watermelon and pink grapefruit, also
contain this cancer preventive, but studies have focused on
tomatoes, Rao said, because ``85 to 90 percent of lycopene in our
diet comes from tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't be fooled into thinking lycopene-rich tomatoes are the
only weapon in fighting cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a nutritionist, I must say there are no magic bullets,''
the Toronto researcher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1253EST &QL; 
