<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL609-ORDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL, PARTNER UPBEAT AS ORDERS FOR 609 CIVILIAN TILT-ROTOR COME IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ With 75 orders already in hand for their new 609
civilian tilt-rotor aircraft, Bell Helicopter Textron and its
Italian partner, Agusta, are feeling optimistic enough to nudge the
ante a bit higher.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 75 orders, which will be delivered through 2004,
buyers had to make an initial deposit of $100,000 toward the total
cost of about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But now the earnest money is rising to $150,000, Bell said this
week at the industry's annual Heli-Expo show in Dallas. And the
second round of buyers won't get their aircraft until at least
2005.
</P>
<P>
   The 609 is the civilian version of the V-22 Osprey, being built
for the U.S. Marines. The tilt-rotors are designed to hover like a
helicopter, or fly straight ahead at speeds up to 300 miles per
hour, double the speed of the fastest helicopters today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope that in the first decade of production, we could
sell about 1,200 609s,'' said James K. Rogers, a longtime Bell
executive who is managing director of the Bell/Agusta joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Early buyers who have made deposits include local luminaries
such as Ross Perot Jr. and Donald Carter, as well as billionaire
Wayne Huizenga of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and golfer Greg Norman.
Perot and Norman are longtime Bell customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is concentrating on the executive market, as well as
offshore energy and rescue industries.
</P>
<P>
   Bell intends to assemble 609s at its new Amarillo plant and also
at the Agusta helicopter plant in Vergiate, Italy, north of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The 609 will have a range of 750 miles, reach an altitude of
25,000 feet, and fly in all weather. Prototypes are scheduled to be
completed late next year. The first craft will probably not be
delivered to buyers until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The 609's current price of $10 million is $3 million to $5
million more than the cost of the twin-blade helicopters that the
609 will compete against. But the craft, which is powered by
turboprops, is considerably cheaper than corporate jets such as the
Gulfstream V, which can cost up to $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and Agusta announced their joint venture last year. The
venture will be based in Fort Worth but will have a separate
identity from Bell Helicopter Textron.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 Agusta engineers and marketing personnel have already
relocated from Italy to Bell's plant in far east Fort Worth.
Agusta's presence at Bell is headed by Antonio Giovannini, a
22-year veteran of the company who learned to fly helicopters in
the Italian Navy. Giovannini moved to Bedford this month.
</P>
<P>
   Giovannini professes to like Texas, even though he can't easily
indulge his passions for Italian soccer and skiing. But his highest
enthusiasm is reserved for the 609.
</P>
<P>
   ``This aircraft will revolutionize flight the way the helicopter
did in the early 1950s,'' Giovannini said.
</P>
<P>
   Agusta was a longtime fixed-wing aircraft builder until stripped
of that right after World War II. It switched to helicopters, and
Bell was the first American company to license its products with
Agusta in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really was the birth of the modern Agusta, and we have
had a good relationship with Bell ever since,'' Giovannini said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell has been betting heavily on tilt-rotors for the past two
decades. The fight to get the military to buy the Osprey was long
and torturous, including a cancellation by the Bush administration
in 1990. The Clinton Pentagon revived the Osprey, and the first
prototypes are going through land and sea trials now. Bell expects
to deliver the first full production V-22 to the Marines from
Amarillo this May.
</P>
<P>
   Military orders for the V-22 stand at 425 for the Marines, and
50 for the Air Force special forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Chairman Terry Stinson is optimistic that tilt-rotors will
also be sold to the Coast Guard for rescue work.
</P>
<P>
   The military is expected to play a major role in the shakeout of
tilt-rotor technology before the civilian market accepts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of questions about the tilt-rotor,
particularly its cost of maintenance, and how it will handle
turbulence and other problems,'' said Mike Harvey, vice president
of a Bellport, N.Y., helicopter reconditioning company, who stopped
by the 609 mockup for a peek at the Heli-Expo.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvey said the military will answer a lot of those
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody doubts the gee-whiz aspect of the tilt-rotor. But there
are still questions about the tilt-rotor's application in
nonmilitary fields.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, will corporate executives accustomed to jet power
give it up for a turboprop?
</P>
<P>
   The company is counting on it, citing the advantage that the 609
can land atop a building or on a flat parking lot, eliminating
drives through heavy traffic to distant airports.
</P>
<P>
   The acute shortage of full-service helicopter ``vertiports'' in
major U.S. cities is often a topic of discussion at meetings like
Heli-Expo.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers notes that the 609 is lighter than several other
civilian hover aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   It ``has been designed to land anywhere a conventional
helicopter can land,'' he said. ``That includes open fields.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
