<HEADLINE>
MEXICO TO IMPOSE FEE ON INLAND VISITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Mexico plans to charge tourists a $15 entry fee
beginning July 1, a move some business people say could harm
tourism, particularly among travelers of modest means.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Espinosa Villarreal, the tourism minister of Mexico,
announced the new fee this week during a visit to Texas, where he
is campaigning for foreign investment in his nation's visitor
industry. The fee is expected to generate about $150 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Espinosa said the fee would be collected from airline passengers
as well as from tourists arriving by auto or bus.
</P>
<P>
   For airline passengers, the fee will be added to the price of
tickets, he said. Auto and bus passengers will pay the fee at the
interior checkpoints of Mexico, usually located about 15 miles from
the border. Tourists traveling no further than border cities will
not have to pay the fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not complicate entry into Mexico,'' Espinosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, some 10 million people visited Mexico's interior _
including about 800,000 who arrived in autos and buses _ according
to the Mexican Government Tourism Office in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism representatives said the fee would not likely change the
plans of vacationers who fly into resort areas, but would hurt less
affluent people who go to Mexico to visit family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will definitely have an impact on tourism,'' said Max
Rosenstein, owner of the Sanborn's Mexican Insurance office in San
Antonio, which sells auto insurance for people driving into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not look on this favorably. Business is off already
because of bad publicity of incidents with tourists in Mexico. This
cannot help,'' said Floyd Woods, general manager of Travco Service
in McAllen, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists entering Mexico now receive a free visa good for six
months. Each time they leave and return to Mexico, they must get
another visa, even if an earlier one has not expired. After July 1,
each entry will require payment of the $15 fee, according to the
Mexican Government Tourism Office in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The fee will be in addition to the $18 per-passenger airport
departure tax, which is used to fund the nation's airport system.
</P>
<P>
   The revenues from the entry fee will go mainly to pump up
Mexico's budget to promote and advertise tourism, Espinosa said.
Other portions of the revenues will fund international networks of
consulate and tourism offices, the modernization of immigration
services plus tourist assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists to Mexico will be compensated,'' Espinosa said.
``This is a duty similar to that charged in many other countries
and it will, for the first time, allow us to plan our promotion
programs on a long-term basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinosa said his ministry had weighed the impact of the fee on
the country's growing visitor industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of international experience, we expect the
negative impact of this duty on tourist flows to be minimal, and we
are confident that the positive impact on our ability to promote
Mexico internationally will far outweigh it ... This is competitive
with the rest of the world. Mexico is not a high-taxation
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SISTER26-COX     02-25 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SISTER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luminous Lewis lifts uneven `Sister'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juliette Lewis' off-kilter, eccentric acting style makes her
performance in ``The Other Sister'' seem inevitable. As a mentally
challenged woman determined to live life on her own terms, she
brings focus and electricity to a gooey-glossy film that sometimes
plays like a lavish Movie of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Co-written and directed by Garry Marshall (``Pretty Woman''),
``Sister'' unfolds in a rarefied stratum of San Francisco, where
the Tate family awaits the arrival of Carla (Lewis). She's the
daughter of Elizabeth Tate (Diane Keaton), sent years ago to a
private boarding school for ``special'' students. It's a decision
Elizabeth still regrets. We know, because she tells her
long-suffering husband, Radley (Tom Skerritt), ``I'm gonna make it
up to that girl!''
</P>
<P>
   But mom can't distinguish loving from smothering. She frets when
Carla enrolls in the local poly tech, when Carla insists that she
wants her own apartment, and most of all when Carla falls for
another mentally challenged person, Danny (Giovanni Ribisi).
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds familiar, you might be remembering ``Like Normal
People,'' a 1979 TV movie that starred Linda Purl and Shaun Cassidy
as a similar young couple. ``The Other Sister'' does a big-bucks
variation on the theme, filling the screen with plush Bay Area
interiors and honey-gold cinematography from Dante Spinotti (``L.A.
Confidential'').
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of movie in which Radley blows off steam by
tinkering with his sailboat and Elizabeth says things like, ``You
remember the club, don't you, Carla dear?'' When mother and
daughter finally have their big emotional blowup, it happens on a
pristine golf course and the ladies are wearing formal gowns.
(Director Marshall makes sure we realize that this is a big, teary
moment by having the lawn sprinklers whirl on at the climax of
their argument.)
</P>
<P>
   These silver-spoon trappings are nice to look at, but they lower
the dramatic stakes. No matter what happens, you know that nobody's
in danger of losing much. The big issue is Carla's self-worth, not
where her next meal is coming from or how she would get by if all
she had to rely on was a welfare check. All the Tates love one
another, including Carla's smart, blond sisters. (One of these has
a lesbian lover whom Elizabeth refuses to meet, but the subplot
seems to be there for P.C. flavoring, because it sure doesn't add
any extra dramatic interest.)
</P>
<P>
   Keaton, that nimble comedian, seems uncomfortable playing a
fussy matron. Because Elizabeth is a control freak, we're
encouraged to dismiss her concerns out of hand. We never have to
face the reality that, whether Carla and Danny are in love or not,
Elizabeth has good reasons to be worried about their life together.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``The Other Sister'' is still surprisingly watchable.
Mainly that's due to Lewis' emotional translucence. She has moments
onscreen that are as breathtakingly truthful as the script is
dishonest. She also knows how to have naughty-girl fun as Carla,
reveling in the newfound pleasures of just sitting around in her
very own apartment, belching aloud because she can. Ribisi, who was
so good in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' holds his own with a
performance that's fearless, but respectful.
</P>
<P>
   You can't say as much for the script. It keeps manipulating us
by putting Carla and Danny through the same series of events. First
it shows them being cute, then it shows them being humiliated, then
it shows them crying. Carla's big dream is to be a veterinary
assistant, and that's no surprise: The movie treats her and Danny
like adorable puppies, always in danger of accidentally peeing on
the rug. Danny even has to wear a puppy costume at one point (Carla
gets a swan outfit), and the script turns their sexual stirrings
into the source of nudge-nudge comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most effective scene in ``The Other Sister'' is Lewis'
angry, tearful outburst when she thinks a roomful of people are
ridiculing her. You can understand her frustration, because of the
inconsistent way the movie treats its mentally challenged
characters. It wants us to laugh with them, but too often it's
laughing at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Juliette Lewis, Giovanni Ribisi and Diane Keaton. Rated
PG-13 for thematic elements involving sex-related material.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A couple of strong performances get undercut by
glitz, jokes and sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
