<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-8MM26-COX     02-25 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-8MM26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Eight Millimeter' exposes itself as sham
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest sample of Morbidity Chic from ``Seven'' scripter
Andrew Kevin Walker, ``Eight Millimeter'' is like a morally
bankrupt public health official: It warns you about the dangers of
an illegal substance by making you indulge in the stuff till you're
sick.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, we're talking pornography. Not the slick pages of
Playboy, but the seamy bazaars of the kinkiest skinflicks. That's
because private eye Tom Welles (Nicolas Cage) has been hired by a
rich widow (Myra Carter) to find out why her late husband had a
porn reel in his safe. And whether that movie is really what it
seems to be: a ``snuff'' flick, ending with the brutal slashing
death of a sad-eyed teenage girl.
</P>
<P>
   Tom's investigation takes him from his Pennsylvania home to
North Carolina, Los Angeles and Manhattan. Trying to track the
identity of the girl, and the movie's makers, he enlists the help
of an L.A. porn-store clerk, Max (Joaquin Phoenix, whose amusing,
street-smart performance is the best thing here).
</P>
<P>
   They find themselves in a murky world of filmmakers for hire,
willing to shoot anything for a price. Unfortunately, these guys
(played by the fine James Gandolfini and Peter Stormare) are as
two-dimensional as they are evil. As he uncovers ever worse ethical
squalor, Cage exhibits his moral outrage with a glum expression
that suggests the onset of a migraine. He's something I never
thought I'd say about him: boring. (Another casualty is the fine
actress Catherine Keener, reduced to a limited performance as
Cage's anxious wife.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with ``Eight Millimeter'' is the way it
turns us into voyeurs (like the rape-murder sequence in ``Strange
Days''), then gets self-righteous about what it's been showing us.
It's hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   When it came out in 1960, the British film ``Peeping Tom,''
about a photographer who takes pictures of women at the moment he
murders them, disgusted critics. And it ended director Michael
Powell's career. But it was trying to say something relevant about
the ways film can objectify reality and turn us all into voyeurs.
``Eight Millimeter'' has nothing on its mind but cheap sensation.
It pretends to explore moral ambiguity, then finds shortcuts so
that our man Tom can be both a hero and a vigilante whose actions
are as bloody as the porn sleazos'. More hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   But enough with the egghead analysis. Here's what you want to
know: This movie is also slow-going, punishingly grim and often
ugly to look at, in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a set designer for TV commercials, director Joel
Schumacher does his usual job of visual oversell. The widow's
mansion is so comic-book baronial that you expect Alfred from the
director's two ``Batman'' movies to drift through. Other houses
seem to be lit by a single fluorescent light that bleaches color
from everything. The porn kings cavort in junky-baroque sets that
look like a sci-fi hand-me-down from ``Dark City'' director Alex
Proyas.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is to remove the movie from its moorings in the real
world. It turns everyday evil into a comic book, something we can
easily dismiss. It says that bad guys are out there. But don't
worry _ bang! pow! _ they can be beaten. The movie comes close to
real complexity only once, when one of the murderous creeps turns
out to be a bespectacled, next-door-Joe kind of guy. He even lives
with his mother. But before the implications of this can sink in,
out come the knives and guns for another bloody burst of action.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, ``Eight Millimeter'' is sharply done. It's an
exploitation flick tricked out as art. The pluses include a score
from Mychael Danna (a longtime collaborator of director Atom
Egoyan). It's a terrific mix of hushed percussion and Middle
Eastern-sounding vocals. But after a while, you realize that even
this is a questionable choice. It implicitly equates the porn
underworld with our fears of ``alien'' cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody could probably make a great movie that explores the
strange, sorry world of pornography: a parallel studio system
breeding in the shadows cast by Hollywood's klieg lights. ``Boogie
Nights'' came close, but it lost sight of what it was trying to
say. ``Eight Millimeter'' isn't even in the ballpark. It just drags
you through the mud.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the deepest thing it has to say is, ``Mean people
suck.'' You can get that message off a bumper sticker, for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight Millimeter''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage and Joaquin Phoenix. Rated R for strong
language and for strong, perverse sexuality and violence. 2 hours,
</P>
<P>
   3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A depressing and unpleasant waste of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
