<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-CIGARETTES26-C     02-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CIGARETTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Cigarettes' misses the party, but brings hip cast, great music
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What little we know about Ellie midway through ``200
Cigarettes'' we really don't like: We've heard that she's a moody
performance artist who's chosen New Year's Eve, of all socially
stressful times, to dump her boyfriend, Kevin (Paul Rudd).
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop the audience at a recent Atlanta preview
from happily applauding Ellie's first onscreen appearance. ``That's
Janeane Garofalo!'' one woman whispered excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   And that pretty much seems to be the point of ``200
Cigarettes,'' a disjointed series of tales about more than a dozen
New Yorkers (with a few New Jerseyites and Long Islanders thrown in
for good measure) in 1981, all trying to get to the same New Year's
Eve party. From Courtney Love and Ben Affleck to Elvis Costello (!)
and Christina Ricci, the large ensemble cast is a would-be
hipster's dream, and it's that sense of shared coolness that the
filmmakers seem quite happy to substi-
</P>
<P>
   tute for any serious character development.
</P>
<P>
   Why else would they keep returning to Rudd and Love, a
thoroughly unlikable couple of platonic friends who set out to
attend the party together and proceed to whine their way through a
series of bars, diners and cab rides along the way?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just gonna go home and kill myself,'' Rudd declares in one
scene, for reasons we already don't care about.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Love earthily challenges him to have sex,
for reasons we already don't care about.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do we really care what happens to teenagers Val (the
ubiquitous Ricci) and Stephie (Gaby Hoffman). They can't remember
the address of the party they've sneaked in from Long Island to
attend (the duo's overly broad accents are more appropriate to
Staten Island, or maybe an early Bowery Boys movie), and they keep
running into a pair of punks (Casey Affleck and Guillermo Diaz) who
seem liable to hurt them whenever Val's not busy kissing them.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget (Nicole Parker) ditches Eric (Brian McCardie) when she
finds out that the party is being thrown by his ex-girlfriend
Monica (Martha Plimpton). Then Bridget scrounges the bars for
another date, while Eric demands that Monica tell him why he's a
loser with chicks.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, you'll be completely unsurprised to know by this
point, has to do with sex. In fact, everything in this movie has to
do with sex, which, truth be told, isn't interesting enough to
spend 90 minutes on. At least not in a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ``200 Cigarettes'' is recommended viewing, if only for
the way it faithfully re-creates that pre-Reaganomics period in the
very early 1980s when women willingly dressed like Madonna's
version of a virgin, stereo turntables were more commonplace than
condoms, and love and fun _ not career and money _ were what really
mattered. Indeed, in one of the movie's slyer moments, Ben Affleck
turns off women by revealing that he's a third-year law student
planning to make a lot of money in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   There also are several excellent performances turned in by the
cast's less hip names. As party hostess Monica, Plimpton, who was
one of the hottest young actresses a decade ago in ``The Mosquito
Coast'' and ``Running on Empty,'' gets funnier the later the
evening gets and, still, no guests have arrived. And in her film
debut as the recently deflowered virgin and colossal klutz Cindy,
Kate Hudson winningly combines Lucille Ball-like physical comedic
skills with just a touch of the screwball line readings of her
mother, Goldie Hawn. Similarly, Jay Mohr, as Cindy's initially
unknowing deflowerer, and Dave Chapelle, as a grooving,
philosophizing cabbie, also seem to understand how not to overplay
their characters' hands.
</P>
<P>
   But the real star of ``200 Cigarettes'' is the music. From
Blondie and Roxy Music to Joe Jackson, Costello and Nick Lowe, the
authentic period music never stops playing or surprising us anew
with its freshness and its enduring hipness.
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Affleck, Casey Affleck, Dave Chappelle, Guillermo
Diaz, Angela Featherstone, Janeane Garofalo, Gaby Hoffman, Kate
Hudson, Courtney Love, Jay Mohr, Martha Plimpton, Elvis Costello,
Christina Ricci and Paul Rudd. Rated R for language, sexual
situations and alcohol use. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Like most New Year's Eve parties, this one fails to
live up to expectations. But the music is great.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
