<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY PROVIDES FIRST AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ At the time, it must have seemed like an act
of appeasement, Jimy Williams's way of taking the sting away when
he told Mike Stanley that he would no longer be catching for the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a first baseman's glove, Williams asked in the
spring of 1997. If not, do you think you could get one? We'd like
you to take some ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Mo Vaughn the same day,'' Stanley said Wednesday,
``and he gave me a first baseman's glove, one with his name in it.
I still have that glove. It's the one I use in games.''
</P>
<P>
   That glove appears destined to show some worn leather this
spring. Stanley, his career redirected by Williams's suggestion, is
a candidate to log some serious time at first base for the Red Sox,
a role he hasn't known since he was in college at the University of
Florida 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long ago I can't remember it,'' said Stanley, who is
occupying Vaughn's locker, wearing his glove, and perhaps, taking
on some of his leadership qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sign that says you've got to go to the last
locker,'' Stanley said, alluding to the daily gathering of
reporters around Vaughn's locker.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 35, and with 13 seasons in the big leagues behind
him, Stanley ranks as the Sox' most experienced position player.
Only pitcher Bret Saberhagen, who broke into the big leagues in
1985, has been around longer than Stanley, whose debut with the
Texas Rangers came a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as vocal as Mo was,'' Stanley said. ``Mine is more a
by-example-type thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not afraid to say something when it's time to talk,
either. Not in a scolding manner, but as a guy who has been around
the league for awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley is in his second go-round with the Sox, who traded him
to the Yankees for prospects late in 1997, when the Yankees needed
a bat for the stretch drive, then recaquired him from Toronto last
July, when Boston had the same need for its run at a wild-card
spot. Stanley did not disappoint, batting .288 with seven home runs
and 32 RBIs in 47 games.
</P>
<P>
   With Vaughn gone, first base could end up being a shared
proposition, depending on how Williams intends to use newcomer Jose
Offerman. But with Stanley's 29 home runs last season making him
second only to Nomar Garciaparra among Red Sox returnees, it stands
to reason Williams will want Stanley in the lineup on close to an
everyday basis, either at first base or as the DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I get that sense? I get that hope,'' Stanley said. ``It's
out of my control, obviously. I just come with the thoughts of
that's the kind of goal you set for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, if we start the season  &UR; tomorrow &LR; ,
I've got to go see the lineup card to see who's in there. Nothing
is guaranteed at all. You just go with that hope and that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley played some first base for the Sox when Vaughn went down
with a knee injury in '97, then wound up there last spring in
Toronto, where the Blue Jays had signed him to be a
righthanded-hitting DH but were forced to use him at first when
young star Carlos Delgado was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really starting to enjoy my time over there,'' Stanley
said. ``I was kind of sad and reluctant to let it go. At first,
they said he wouldn't be back till the end of May. When he came
back after just two weeks in April, it was like, `Oh, man.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who had balked in the past at being used as the DH, went
along with Williams when he started Stanley a dozen times at first
base upon his return to Boston for last summer's stretch run.
Stanley didn't make an error for the Red Sox, and only made one in
22 games for the Blue Jays at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``From time to time, I had played first base in the minors, and
I also played there in winter ball in the Dominican,'' Stanley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't something that I had to go learn where to put my
feet on the bag, or do you hold a runner on or not. I've got some
instincts about playing the position.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part about playing first base for the Sox, Stanley
suggested, is learning how to handle the throws from shortstop
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got all types of different (arm) angles,'' Stanley said.
``His is not your true, over-the-top Alan Trammell throw. His throw
is sinking and it's hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the break is pretty consistent. But still, when he
makes that little running play he likes to do, where he throws off
one leg, that can handcuff me in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley doesn't believe the Red Sox are doomed by Vaughn's
departure, even though talking hitting with Vaughn was among the
most pleasurable aspects of the job for him. Neither should anyone
believe that the Yankees will match last year's 114-win regular
season, even if they have basically the same team, plus Roger
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was such a magical achievement,'' he said. ``To sit and
think they can repeat that because they have the same cast of
players is unfair and unrealistic. Sure, they're the favorites, but
it's unrealistic to think they'll do what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley accepts that the Sox could end up trading for another
first baseman. But in the meantime, there are some new first
baseman's mitts that need breaking in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
