<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MARRIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROBING POST-MORTEM OF A MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
The Story of One Marriage 
By John Taylor 
Random House, 240 pp. $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plane crashes have many causes _ metal fatigue, pilot error,
wind shear _ and so do failed marriages, including but not limited
to incompatibility, infidelity, and inertia.
</P>
<P>
   One difference, though, is that when an airliner goes down, an
investigation is usually launched and relevant information gets
passed along to the public. Not so with most marriages, which,
absent an equivalent black-box investigation, sink without a trace,
leaving behind a pool of bewildered survivors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the valuable services John Taylor renders in this
brooding, oddly affecting memoir is essentially a forensic one.
Taylor, a former staff writer for New York and Esquire magazines,
sets out to examine how and why his own 11-year marriage imploded.
He is hopeful that his inquest can enlighten others. He is not out
to settle scores with his ex _ how refreshing is that in this age
of literary payback? _ or to dish dirt on colleagues, but to
explain his observation that while it ``requires will to make a
marriage work, it also requires a horrifying act of will to make
one end.''
</P>
<P>
   Horrifying yes, but in its way admirable too. Taylor is too
gifted, too smart a writer to duck the tough questions or
romanticize his own pain. His foibles and failings _ the drinking
bouts and temper tantrums, the ways in which he rationalized his
extramarital affairs, the lies told his spouse and the trauma
inflicted on his daughter _ are recalledwith a conspicuous lack of
self-pity. He can be funny, as in describing the therapy sessions
to which he was dragged by one romantic partner or another. He can
be brutally candid, as in portraying his conflicting emotions about
leaving or staying, ending the marriage or extending it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure,'' he observes, ``can be gratifying, even liberating;
it relieves you of the need to aspire.'' He goes on to compare his
crippled marriage and its principals to ``animals in a drought''
who survive ``by keeping still and doing little.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Taylor pretends to be an unbiased witness. On the
contrary, it is his bias that gives his book its peculiar shape,
its gritty texture, its melancholy resonance. ``At what precise
point does the breakdown of a marriage become irretrievable?'' he
asks, and then makes you want to know the answer. Not The Truth,
necessarily, but his truth. Which is all one can ask for.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and his wife Maureen married in 1982, 18 months after
they met. He was 26 at the time, she a few years older. As their
romance flourished, so did Taylor's career. He cannot remember who
proposed marriage first, only that marriage and family life was
something to which he had always aspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' he writes, ``marriage was a way not of settling down
but of moving on'' from a life of chronic restlessness. Shortly
after marrying, though, Maureen was diagnosed with Parkinson's
disease. The couple moved from Boston to Brooklyn, and Maureen
stayed home when their baby was born. It was, Taylor acknowledges,
a ``power shift'' that bred resentment and caused the couple to
withdraw, emotionally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, he began an affair with a young married woman whom
he calls Alex. Their affair seemed ``rakish'' and ``glamorous''
initially, says Taylor. He even imagined himself alongside other
celebrity adulterers, from President Kennedy to Picasso. Meanwhile,
he scorned one neighbor of his who boasted of his own ``open
marriage,'' as if cheating in secret were a lesser matrimonial
crime than serial wife-swapping. He and Alex took a small apartment
together. Gradually she began seeing Taylor as the exit visa to her
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife's physical condition worsening and Alex pressuring
him to leave, Taylor found himself going through the motions in a
marriage that had lost its moorings. Ending the affair with Alex,
he confessed his infidelity to his wife while asking for a ``trial
separation,'' the first big step toward divorce. He moved out, they
agreed to see a marriage counselor, yet he also began another
affair. Four months later, Taylor went back to wife and daughter,
in what proved to be another futile stab at domestic tranquility.
This time around even their therapist diagnosed the couple as
depressingly ``low-energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The endgame would go on for two more ennervating years, Taylor's
career being about the only thing that was flying on all engines.
At home his goal was modest to a fault: to keep a low profile, to
avoid confrontation. One more affair, however, this time with a
woman firmly committed to her own marriage, was the last Mayday
before the plane went down. In the end, it was his wife who found
the courage to say, enough.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what Taylor's daughter will make of this memoir when
she is old enough to approach it with adult eyes. Perhaps she will
view it as an act of betrayal, perhaps an act of bravery. One thing
she will not have to ask is, ``What exactly happened between you
and Mommy?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
