<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-EQUITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR AND WOMEN PUSH FOR EQUAL PAY FOR EQUAL WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nobody says men and women shouldn't get equal pay
for doing the same job. But what's brewing now is a big push
nationally by the president, organized labor, and women's rights
groups to level the gender playing field on wages for different but
equivalent work.
</P>
<P>
   In a strategy session Thursday, Senator Tom Harkin, an Iowa
Democrat who has been the lonely champion of pay-equity legislation
since 1996, was to meet with John Podesta, the president's chief of
staff, and other officials on ways the White House can boost his
bill this year. Wednesday, the AFL-CIO launched a nationwide
campaign to pass comparable-worth bills in 24 states.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here? Trying to determine comparable salaries
for jobs traditionally held by men and women is an old idea,
discredited by some economists as unwieldly, if not downright dumb.
They wonder who can and will decide the economic value of a riveter
versus a nurse, the comparable pay for a probation officer and a
librarian, the equivalent salary for an auto mechanic and a
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Many see pay equity, even if it is difficult to enforce, as the
only remedy for wage discrimination, a problem that persists for
women, even as they have earned advanced degrees, climbed the
corporate ladder, and plopped their children in day care while
pursuing fulltime jobs in huge numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study released by the AFL-CIO Wednesday, the
average working family loses more than $4,000 each year to the
gender wage gap, which has narrowed very little in recent years.
Women still tend to be clustered in lower-paying, female-dominated
occupations and, on average each week, earn 74 percent of men's
wages, the report said. Minority women earn 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, working women have been seething while
politicians have remained silent,'' said Karen Nussbaum, director
of the AFL-CIO's Working Women's department. ``Pay equity can right
a longstanding wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, pollsters are telling politicians the wage gap is
starting to show up as a big issue for American families. It was no
accident that in his State of the Union message last month,
President Clinton asked Congress to ``make sure women and men get
equal pay by strengthening enforcement of equal pay laws.'' It was
one of the few declarations that got a standing ovation from both
Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also devoted his Jan. 30 radio address to the issue and
proposed a $14 million equal-pay initiative to help the Labor
Department break glass ceilings and end wage discrimination against
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay equity has gone from being a women's issue to a national
priority because there is enormous documentation _ from focus
groups to town hall meetings _ that unequal pay for women undercuts
family security in two-wage-earner families,'' said Anne Mosle, an
analyst at the Center for Policy Alternatives, a private,
nonpartisan group that studies women's economic issues. ``The more
wives work, the more husbands notice the gap, and they don't like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also getting major lobbying support from organized
labor, which advertises a narrower gender wage gap for union
members _ women in unions earn 84 percent of men's wages _ as a way
to recruit women. The AFL-CIO recently set up an equal-pay web site
that allows a woman to tap in her age, income, and education level
and _ ``if you're ready for some really bad news,'' it says _ click
to see how much more a man with the same data will earn in his
lifetime. (The website is http://www.aflcio.org/women/calculat.htm)
</P>
<P>
   Diana Furchtgott-Roth, a resident fellow at the American
Enterprise Institute, says there are plenty of reasons why men and
women earn different wages _ seniority, job risk, and market demand
for certain skills _ that have nothing to do with discrimination
and would not be erased by ``cockeyed'' pay-equity laws. She said
when you compare men and women with the same qualifications doing
the same jobs, women earn 95 percent of men's salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparable worth is certainly making a comeback,''
Furchtgott-Roth said, ``and I believe it's because feminists who
supported Clinton through the Lewinsky mess are demanding a
political payoff. I don't see any Republican support for these
proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Democratic equal-pay bills are expected to be introduced in
the GOP-controlled Congress next week. Harkin's Fair Pay Act would
provide equal pay for women in jobs of comparable skill, effort,
responsibility, and working conditions to low-skill jobs held by
men. The Paycheck Fairness Act, sponsored by Senate Minority Leader
Thomas Daschle of South Dakota, would strengthen penalties under
the 1963 Equal Pay Act, including awarding compensatory and
punitive damages to women who prove wage discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new momentum for the federal pay-equity bills, the
flurry of activity in state legislatures is perhaps more
significant because of the bubble-up effect. For example, 15 states
passed family and medical leave laws before it became a federal
priority and was enacted in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's pay-equity law, passed in 1982, stands as the
current model. Under it, cities, counties, and school districts in
the state must correct any sex-based inequities in salaries for
employees in equivalent jobs. A state bureaucracy helps evaluate
jobs based on what knowledge, skill, effort, and responsibility
they require. According to the National Committee on Pay Equity, a
private advocacy group, the wage gap between men and women in
Minnesota is 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, West Virginia, a state with a big gap in the median
salaries of men and women, passed a bill to protect state employees
from gender discrimination in wages paid for ``work of comparable
character.'' The legislation will not take effect until 2001 while
a state commission studies how to implement the law and handle
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Barring wage discrimination for ``work of comparable character''
is already on the books in Massachusetts, but state courts have
defined it so narrowly that state Representative Patricia Jehlen, a
Democrat of Somerville, recently introduced legislation to broaden
it to include jobs that require comparable skill, effort,
responsibility, and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The language of the bills is the easy part; it's the
implmentation that is a ``swamp,'' said Wendy Rose of the Maine
Centers for Women, Work, and Community, a nonprofit group in
Augusta. Maine has had the nation's most far-reaching
comparable-worth law on the books since 1965 _ it requires both
public and private employers to pay equal wages for similar jobs _
but only in the last year, when pressed by advocacy groups, has the
state's Labor Department begun to develop enforcement rules and
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1965 executive order, the US Labor Department is
required to audit federal contractors for wage discrimination. The
Clinton administration has recently stepped up enforcement; last
year the agency charged with contract compliance reviewed more pay
cases and got more settlements than ever in its history.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Texaco agreed to pay $3.1 million to women in
professional and executive positions after the Labor Department
cited the company for inconsistencies in its wage policies. It
included $2.2 million in back pay and interest and $900,000 in
raises.
</P>
<P>
   The government also got settlements in the last year from
CoreStates Financial, a Philadelphia-based bank, which paid $1.5
million in back pay and increased wages to 142 women and
minorities; Chicago publisher R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons, which paid 29
women and minorities $425,000 in lost wages; and US Airways, which
paid $400,000 to 30 women managers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
