<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9011 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     02-25 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIME AUTHOR SAYS ECONOMY WORKS BETTER WITH LESS PLANNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Progress can best be made by those not preoccupied with planning
the future.
</P>
<P>
   That's the counterintuitive message delivered in a new book from
first-time author Virginia Postrel, who argues that dynamic growth
in business and the economy is possible only when individuals are
free to experiment and react to market forces instead of slavishly
relying on blueprint models that may not reflect the desires and
demands of today's marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Future and Its Enemies: The Growing Conflict Over
Creativity Enterprise and Progress'' (The Free Press, $25, 265
pages), Postrel carefully constructs an argument suggesting that
the ``invisible hand'' driving economic movement is a much more
powerful and effective force than today's scientific approach to
``master planning.''
</P>
<P>
   By predeterming progress by plotting out future developments far
ahead of time, America's growing technocracy can stifle spontaneous
evolution in business rather than pave the way for further
industrial growth and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technocratic governance transfers to deliberate, centralized
authorities decisions that would otherwise be made nimbly, through
competition and feedback in dispersed, evolving markets but also
for ideas,'' Postrel writes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the author criticizes the meddling role of government
in business affairs, she is no advocate of conservative thinkers
who work to merely maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Calling these individuals ``reactionaries,'' Postrel contends
that such an outlook can be equally effective in pre-empting
progress that leads to economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an overarching fear of the future _ and the need to
either manage it or to keep it from evolving at all _ actually
casts ultraliberals and ultraconservatives in the same camp, she
writes.
</P>
<P>
   A growing group _ dubbed ``dynamists'' by the author _ is
beginning to embrace the future by rolling with the punches and
adapting to society and markets forces as they change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a party that has no true political or intellectual home
in America today, a party that barely recognizes itself as an
entity,'' Postrel writes. ``Its central value is learning, which
unlike stability or control is an open-ended process. Dynamists do
not expect, demand or desire a world that holds still.''
</P>
<P>
   Postrel sprinkles her work with effective examples of the way
the serendipity of market forces have created fundamental changes
more sweeping than anyone could have planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, for example, sprang from its roots as a
low-profile Defense Department project to emerge as a far-reaching
communications network that has become suitable for the mass
market.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the U.S. semiconductor industry _ considered to be a
weakling in need of government funding and protectionist trade
barriers as recently as the 1980s _ roared back to world dominance
this decade even though only modest government programs and plans
were ever enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The power of the marketplace, it seems, was enough to encourage
the innovation that helped U.S. semiconductor makers regain the
upper hand in their industry. Had the manufacturers been sheltered
by government, Postrel writes, the industry may not have felt the
pressure to innovate and very well still could be saddled with
old-style thinking that could have relegated the nation to
second-class status in the vital semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stodgy thinking even invades everyday businesses, such as
hairstyling. Postrel decibes a situation in New York where state
licensing exams test would-be hairstylists on outmoded hairstyling
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that prompts hair-styling schools to teach only
old styling techniques, so their students can pass their exam. As a
result, new techniques, such as African-style braiding of hair, are
never taught to students even though the demand for such styles is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   While many readers still may find comfort in the security that
comes from the planning process, Postrel provides some important
food for thought for those seeking to encourage creativity and
innovation in their workplace.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cover blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``Race for Success: The Ten Best Opportunities for Blacks in
America''
</P>
<P>
   By George C. Fraser
</P>
<P>
   Avon Books, $13.50
</P>
<P>
   Three years after his first book on economic opportunities for
African-Americans, author and speaker George Fraser has been
scouring the country for more material. He found it, and his new
book is full of interesting anecdotes about the economic viability
of the black community. After civil rights and affirmative action
programs, Fraser suggests that the next move for African-Americans
is in economic gains. His book could help his community further
this effort through inspiring tales of economic opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``How To 2000''
</P>
<P>
   By Raytheon E-Systems employees
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $69.99
</P>
<P>
   With 589 pages and a CD-ROM included, one would hope this book
would have the answer to anyone's Y2K problem. The authors are all
program managers, software engineers and systems engineers for
Raytheon E-Systems. The book is obviously technical in nature, but
appears to cover the waterfront on solving this computer problem,
for those who have procrastinated to this point.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful Business Networking''
</P>
<P>
   By Frank J. DeRaffele Jr. and Edward D. Hendricks
</P>
<P>
   Chandler House Press, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   Networking is one of the most powerful tools to any business or
career, yet one that is hardly mentioned in business schools.
Authors Frank DeRaffele Jr. and Edward Hendricks, both consultants,
speakers and trainers, have written a step-by-step process on
developing a network, with both hints and resources.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
