<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-JEHOVAS-BOS &LR;      02-25 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JEHOVAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS FREEDOM SEEN AT RISK IN RUSSIAN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Religious freedom is on trial in a stuffy Moscow
courtroom, where a judge is hearing a case on whether a sect can be
banned because its beliefs and practices are alien to Russian
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are Jehovah's Witnesses, who prosecutors say are
guilty of fomenting religious discord. So far, the prosecutor's
line of argument could be summed up: The authorities do not like
Jehovah's Witnesses, so they should be banned.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first legal test for a 1997 law that names four
traditional Russian religions _ Orthodox Christianity, Islam,
Judaism, and Buddhism _ and sets tough criteria for other faiths to
win legal recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates warn that a ruling against the Jehovah's
Witnesses could be used as a precedent to outlaw any religious
group that falls out of official favor.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors' evidence comes not from any specific allegations of
wrongdoing but from charges that the group's doctrine is that of a
totalitarian cult. For example, because Jehovah's Witnesses are
discouraged from having blood transfusions, prosecutors say they
refuse care to ill people and encourage suicide. Or, because
Jehovah's Witnesses proclaim their faith as the only legitimate
one, prosecutors say, they foment discord with other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Yelena Prokhorcheva has refused to accept such arguments,
saying that members of many faiths believe theirs to be the only
true one. The prosecutors see her reasoning as biased, and have
repeatedly asked the judge to excuse herself from the case. The
defendants say that the prosecutors' approach just shows they have
no case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to see evidence for the trial,'' said Vasily
Kalin, a Jehovah's Witnesses' lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   If Prokhorcheva finds against the defendants, the Jehovah's
Witnesses, who claim 10,000 members in Moscow and 250,000
nationwide, would be banned from worshiping in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   But the implications could be even greater.
</P>
<P>
   If the prosecution wins ``this case, they can easily use it as a
precedent to close down groups throughout Russia,'' said Diederik
Lohman, director of the Moscow office of the international
organization Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it does not win, the rules governing Russian legal
proceedings make it easy for the prosecution to drag out the case
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the prosecutor faxed a request for a recess 45
minutes after the proceedings were supposed to start. The case was
already postponed in November to allow the prosecution more time to
prepare its case. In the meantime, state-owned television has run
several reports critical of the Jehovah's Witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conecerned that this delay is just another excuse to
manufacture evidence through a smear campaign,'' Kalin, a lawyer
for the Jehovah's Witnesses, said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 law has been widely criticized as a vehicle for
Russia's Orthodox Church, which lobbied hard for its adoption, to
reestablish itself as the country's official state religion after
decades of Soviet repression.
</P>
<P>
   The church and state were closely linked until the 1917 Russian
Revolution that brought an atheist regime to power.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 law requires any religion deemed ``nontraditional'' to
wait 15 years before acquiring official status, and makes it hard
for believers to worship in the meantime. During this probation
period, so-called nontraditional religions cannot own property,
open a bank account, publish and spread literature, or invite
foreign preachers to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Jehovah's Witnesses were registered under a Soviet-era
religious law, but after the 1997 law was passed, they were told to
register again. In the fall their application was blocked by
Moscow's city prosecutor on the basis of charges lodged against
Jehovah's Witnesses by a youth group close to the Russian Orthodox
Church.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
