<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_DRUG RESISTANCE FOUND IN COMMON INFECTION  
 _DISPARITY EXAMINED IN HEART FAILURE DEATHS  
 _BIRTH TIMING, PLACE TIED TO SCHIZOPHRENIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 Drug resistance found in common infection
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Germs that cause garden-variety bladder infections in women are
increasingly resistant to the antibiotics that doctors commonly
prescribe to cure them.
</P>
<P>
   A study published Wednesday in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that resistance to
trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (brand names Bactrim and Septra)
doubled between 1992 and 1996 among 4,000 Seattle women with
bladder infections.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to these main-line drugs rose from 8 to 16 percent
during the five-year period. That is close to the 20 percent that
specialists say should signal doctors to stop using a particular
drug, for fear it will drive a community's resistance rates higher.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kalpana Gupta of the University of Washington and her
colleagues warn that Bactrim and Septra ``may not be acceptable
choices. . . for much longer.'' The study was paid for by the
National Institutes of Health and the drug manufacturer Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   One implication, Gupta said in an interview, is that a woman
should ask her doctor to ``culture'' her urine if she does not get
better on a first-line drug. Only then can the doctor know which
drug to try next.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs remain effective, Gupta said. One, nitrofurantoin,
may require seven days of therapy to cure the infections, compared
to only three days for the current front-line drugs. Another,
ciprofloxacin, is effective in short doses, but the researchers
warned that increased use will merely promote microbial resistance
to it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are part of a global problem. ``This is the decade
of multidrug resistance,'' Dr. Stuart B. Levy of Tufts University
School of Medicine warns in testimony to a US Senate committee.
``Resistant infections are four to 10 times as expensive to treat.
. . and US healthcare purchasers are paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Disparity examined in heart failure deaths
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans are twice as likely to die of heart failure as
whites, but researchers have long debated whether that reflects
differences in access to care, greater likelihood that blacks have
other complicating diseases, or some underlying racial
predisposition.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current New England Journal of Medicine points to
a racial disparity. Analyzing 2,600 patients who participated in a
federally funded study designed to prevent heart failure, plus
4,200 others in a sister study to treat the disease, researchers
found that blacks were 25 to 36 percent more likely to die after
all factors were accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel L. Dries of the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute and his colleagues call for more research on heart
failure in blacks to see if different treatments are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another new study in the same journal pins down a
different, and also much-debated, racial and sexual disparity in
heart disease treatment.
</P>
<P>
   To see if doctors are more inclined to diagnose and treat
suspected heart disease more aggressively in white men than others,
Dr. Kevin Schulman of Georgetown University and his colleagues
presented 720 physicians with videotaped interviews of actors
portraying patients of different ages, genders, and races _ but
with the same chest pain symptoms and risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were much less likely to order cardiac
catheterization, the definitive test for clogged coronary arteries,
for women and blacks. Black women were only 40 percent as likely to
be sent to the cath lab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Birth timing, place tied to schizophrenia
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having a mother, father, or sibling with schizophrenia raises
the likelihood that an individual will develop this common,
devastating mental illness. But so does being born in February or
March, or in an urban rather than rural area, according to a Danish
study of nearly 2,700 schizophrenia cases in the current New
England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The late-winter effect jibes with other studies suggesting that
flu virus infection during pregnancy may predispose a fetus to
schizophrenia later, said Dr. Francine Benes, a schizophrenia
researcher at McLean Hospital in Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   As for the urban factor, Benes said ``it raised the question in
my mind whether living in an urban center may be associated with
more stress. I'm convinced that part of what triggers this disease
in susceptible individuals is stress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
