<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-25 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING TABS ON THE NATION'S TOP PREDATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ First, this bit of rudeness in the toniest part
of Pacific Heights. On Wednesday morning fliers appeared saying,
``Neighborhood Alert! Sexual predator headed our way.''
</P>
<P>
   The fliers referred to President Clinton's appearance at Gordon
and Ann Getty's home for a fund-raiser Thursday night. There's no
escape for the guy.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't scrawled notes. They were designed and nicely
typeset. Folks can afford it in the Gettys' neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the flier advertised Wednesday's
``Dateline'' interview with Juanita Broaddrick, the woman whose
accusations against Clinton even feminists can't ignore.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the flier, in very small type, were the words:
``But he's so GOOD on women's issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in San Francisco, Superior Court Judge Ernest Goldsmith has
a strange formula for justice: He sentenced the three people who
attacked Mayor Will Brown with pies to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   That's extreme for an assault with tofu cream. I say that as a
columnist who condemned the attack as ugly and potentially
dangerous, and condemned the attackers for using the excuse that
they were doing it for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Six months? ``That's very harsh for that kind of a crime,'' said
Peter Keane, dean of the law school at Golden Gate University, and
a friend of Judge Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you or I got hit with a pie it would be considered
egregious if someone did a weekend in jail ... People have had
their noses broken and significant injuries, and people didn't do
anywhere near that.''
</P>
<P>
   This judge is either very crusty or very flaky.
</P>
<P>
   I did some research on newsworthy sentencings in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   A young man involved in the racially motivated gang beating of
two black couples and an infant in a San Francisco neighborhood got
a year in jail, of which he'd probably serve only six months
because of time served. And he used a chain, not a pie.
</P>
<P>
   Latrelle Sprewell got three months of home detention for
reckless driving on Interstate 680 when he swerved off an exit and
injured a couple in another car.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in Salinas, Calif., got six months in jail for running
up $8,000 worth of bills on other people's credit cards to buy
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, weird crimes make the news. Now we have the weirdest
crime and punishment of all time, six months of hard time for soft
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Goldsmith missed his chance to be the Solomon of
Sachertorte. Instead he created martyrs, and these people seemed to
want to be martyrs _ although perhaps not for six months.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect Solomonic sentence, of course, would have been six
months of community service baking pies for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Biotic Baking Brigade members showed no remorse,
there could have been an extra condition on the community service.
These vegetarians could have been ordered to bake the homeless meat
pies _ chicken pot pie, steak and kidney pie, shepherd's pie and
empanadas.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been more than just de(s)serts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weirdest press kit ever arrived from the Business Software
Alliance, a trade group that fights software piracy and runs a hot
line so you can turn in your company or the guy in the next cubicle
for using unauthorized copies of software.
</P>
<P>
   The press kit is a clear plastic kids' school backpack, and it
arrived just as the group announced that five California companies,
including the Los Angeles Unified School District, settled software
piracy claims for $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, L.A. schools had to hand over to BSA money that
could have been used on education, and the BSA mailed the little
backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   What is the message here? The backpacks, appropriately enough,
were filled with play money, protractors and notebooks _ the kind
of school supplies you use if you can't afford computers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A radio station in New Zealand has rented hotel rooms in early
April for 100 couples to see which can concoct the first baby of
the millennium. April 9 has been named National Bonk Day in
Britain. Don't ask me how you tell who wins the contest if all the
clocks fail because of the year 2000 computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
