A9022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-CHECKS-BO     02-25 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-CHECKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS CHECK POLICY LACKS SAFEGUARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Every year, the Commonwealth of Massachusetts issues
more than 1.5 million checks to pay for everything from salaries to
road salt to psychiatric drugs for state hospital patients.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, better than 98 percent of the checks are cashed. But
more than 12 years ago, to handle the several thousand that remain
outstanding at any given time, the state established an Unclaimed
Check Fund, an accounting device to create a cash reserve for
checks that might be cashed months late while moving them off other
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At times it has held $42 million or more, money that was
supposed to be regularly transferred to the treasurer's heavily
publicized ``unclaimed money list'' for rightful owners to learn
about it and try to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out the system has been grossly abused and ignored,
allowing a treasury employee to allegedly try to steal $6.5 million
from it and trade on insider information about the fund to reap
kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the system as designed had been honored, it appears
Massachusetts would have fallen well short of several other states
in trying to locate owners of uncashed state checks _ and keep
state funds from being stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that it took a criminal act to expose a
system that we now know needs significant overhaul,'' said Dwight
Robson, a spokesman for Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien. ``It is
apparent that a lot more work needs to be done before the technical
and managerial problems are fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   The main failing appears to be that under at least the last two
treasurers, Joseph D. Malone and Robert Q. Crane, the state never
widely publicized who held uncashed stae-issued checks. Also, since
1986 the treasury only sporadically _ and often with faulty
documentation _ transferred the money to the larger unclaimed money
list where its existence would become public. The unclaimed money
list normally accumulates $90 million annually from abandoned bank
and investment accounts and other private sources.
</P>
<P>
   Until last December, according to sources familiar with the
process, Malone's office would release a list of outstanding checks
worth only under $5,000 to bounty hunters commonly called ``heir
finders'' who requested it under the state's public records act.
(Heir finders make money by contacting the check owners and
offering to get them payment in exchange for keeping part of it as
a fee.)
</P>
<P>
   One heir finder who requested the list said Wednesday he was
told Malone's office did it that way because it was unsure of the
accuracy of the data, and ``if they're going to make a mistake,
they're going to make a mistake for less than $5,000.'' The Malone
aides involved were not available Wednesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, that policy _ which was not formally changed until Dec.
3 _ apparently allowed the official overseeing the fund, John
Trischitta, to tip off an heir-finder accomplice named Martin
Robbins about big checks outstanding, allegedly in exchange for
kickbacks, according to investigators probing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new policy, developed last May under pressure from at
least one heir finder who complained about the arbitrary manner in
which the fund approved and paid claims, the treasury began
releasing to people who requested it a complete list of checks
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It also attempted to put in safeguards on releasing the money,
requiring heir finders to provide a notarized power-of-attorney
form to prove they represented the individual or company who was
due the money. In addition, they had to show a photocopy of the
individual's driver's license or Social Security card, or for a
business, its letterhead and taxpayer identification number form.
</P>
<P>
   When an agency of state government needs to pay a check, it puts
in a request to the state comptroller through the Massachusetts
Management Accounting and Reporting System.
</P>
<P>
   This may be for a single big payment, or it could be an
aggregate amount covering a host of small checks going to, say,
injured employees receiving workers' compensation payments.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every workday, the comptroller combines the payment
requests on a computer tape and ships them to the state treasury,
which cuts the actual checks or authorizes wire transfers of money
from state accounts to individual or business bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Checks typically are paid from a ``pooled cash'' account held at
State Street Bank and Trust, Robson said. But each withdrawal is
attributed by the comptroller to the agency budget line item
covering the expense.
</P>
<P>
   For the huge amounts of money handled, the unclaimed check fund
seems to have had minimal oversight. Trischitta, the sole full-time
management employee overseeing the fund, apparently reported only
to Deputy Treasurer Robert E. Foley, and his assistant, Amelia
Viscomi, and was easily able to forge their signatures on paperwork
to release money.
</P>
<P>
   One question is why, if state checks are supposedly void unless
cashed within 90 days, the treasury even bothered to create the
fund. One approach the state could have taken would be simply to
refuse to pay checks cashed too late.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``If someone performs a service for us and the check
gets lost, our contracts don't say we're relieved of the legal
liability to pay you because you didn't cash the check in 90
days,'' said state comptroller Martin Beneson.
</P>
<P>
   It appears several states have stronger policies in place to
handle uncashed checks. For example, Missouri makes a list of all
unclaimed state-issued checks available to heir finders once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri state checks are void 12 months after the date they are
issued. But if someone presents a check from the ``outlawed list''
later with adequate documentation, the state will reprint a check
for the amount owed, according to Jay Moore, banking division
director for state treasurer Bob Holden.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, state comptroller H. Carl McCall Jr. four years ago
instituted an aggressive policy of sending as many as three letters
to owners of uncashed checks, starting 6 to 9 months after a check
was issued. The letters urge recipients to either redeem the checks
or ask his office for help getting a lost check replaced, said
spokeswoman Theresa Bourgeois.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state makes checks void after 180 days, and leaves
with the individual agency the responsibility for tracking down
people who failed to cash checks, treasury spokeswoman Donna
Lawrence-Kennedy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
