<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPOUTERS-ADOBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ADOBE PRODUCTS TAKE THE DRUDGERY OUT OF WEB IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, an old friend dropped me a note about my Web
page. He was amused by the relatively simple typography and the
gray background. ``Are you intentionally going for that retro
look,'' he asked, ``or have you simply not had the time to update
the page in the past four years?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, alas, is a little of both.
</P>
<P>
   Although I do take the time to update my Web page now and then,
Web technology is moving along at a much faster rate. Content was
king back when the Web was born, but these days style frequently
triumphs over substance. Perhaps its time for me to get with the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The key to making compelling Web pages is the combination of
cute little images and cleverly crafted JavaScript. Designers use
the images to display buttons or knobs or navigation bars.
JavaScript, meanwhile, is the tiny programming language that make
the buttons change when you roll over them with your mouse or click
on them.
</P>
<P>
   Most sophisticated Web designers that I know create their pages
with a fairly Spartan set of tools. They write their own HTML and
JavaScript using a basic text editor, they create their images with
Adobe PhotoShop ($600), and if they care about how long an image
takes to load they run a specialty program like Debabalizer to
super-compress the image without sacrificing too much in the way of
quality. The reason that my Web pages lag behind is that I never
had the time, or the desire, to master many of these tools.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Adobe Systems released two new image manipulation
programs that are designed to make it easier to put out
professional-looking Web pages: ImageStyler ($130) and ImageReady
($190). Both programs combine the look-and-feel of the popular
PhotoShop (and probably much of its technology as well) into
packages that are significantly easier to use, although
substantially more limited. Both products run on either Mac or PC
-- it's the same price for either version, but the programs come on
different CD-ROMs, so be sure to get the on you need.
</P>
<P>
   ImageStyler is a special-purpose tool for building banners,
buttons, navigation bars, complex image maps, or entire graphical
Web pages. What makes this program easy-to-use is the fact that it
is object-oriented. You start by creating a blank Web page and
adding images, text, and shapes. You can then modify the property
of each object, changing its color, typestyle, or special effects.
Finally, you can integrate this with JavaScript, so that images and
text change shape when you roll over them, click them, or release
the mouse. This is a lot easier than using Adobe PhotoShop because
it operates on images at the pixel level, it doesn't keep together
images that combine into a single Web page, and it doesn't know a
thing about JavaScript.
</P>
<P>
   When you are done designing your navigation bar or complex page,
ImageStyler exports it as an HTML file (complete with embedded
JavaScript) and a collection of images. Overall, the HTML is pretty
good -- it even has comments! You can then either insert this HTML
into your Web pages or include it automatically using HTML Frames.
</P>
<P>
   If you make a lot of Web pages that have buttons, ImageStyler
can save you a lot of work. But if you are just doing a few pages,
you might be better off with a more comprehensive product like
Adobe's PageMill. Finally, if you are cheap, take a look at
Microsoft's FrontPage Express, which comes for free with Internet
Explorer 4. You can use both PageMill and FrontPage to create many
(but not all) of the image maps and navigation bars that you can
with ImageStyler. The pages won't look as professional and whizzy,
but you'll save money. There are also a bunch of shareware programs
out there for making Web buttons. Unfortunately, most of these
programs require that you register them in order to use them
properly, and registration usually ends up costing half as much as
ImageStyler does -- for products that aren't nearly as functional.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe ImageReady is designed for the person who is cranking out
a lot of images for the Web and needs each one to be perfect. The
program lets you quickly touch up images, change the color balance,
crop, paint, compress them, and do other simple manipulations. Then
you can preview the result, finding out not only how it will look,
but how many seconds the image will take to download over a modem
of a given speed. You can also have ImageReady make a tiny scripted
application that will repeatedly apply your set of manipulations to
any file that is dragged on top of the application's icon.
</P>
<P>
   This is really handy if you have a few thousand images that need
to be shrunk, compressed, and color-balanced all in exactly the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   ImageReady allows you to work with multiple layers. You can pick
colors and area-fill. You can sharpen, blur, and stamp text -- even
text that is anti-aliased. And it can use any PhotoShop plug-in.
Indeed, ImageReady incorporates so many features from Adobe
PhotoShop that I would be hard-pressed at this point to recommend
the more expensive program for anyone who is not a graphic artist.
</P>
<P>
   What I like best about both ImageStyler and ImageReady is that
they fairly easy-to-use programs that do one job and do it well.
They are also extremely polished, thanks, to that common code that
they share with Adobe PhotoShop 5.0. With these programs, PageMill,
and Acrobat, Adobe continues to reinforce its dominance in the
graphics and multi-media authoring arena.
</P>
<P>
   The only product that's missing is a system for building Web
sites that integrate with database systems. Perhaps we'll see such
a program later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at
plugged-in(at)simson.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
