<HEADLINE>
`200 CIGARETTES' IS A BREATH OF FRESH AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ensemble cast united by a single event or place has long been
a mainstay in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Robert Altman and Alan Rudolph made the notion
commonplace in films such as ``Nashville'' and ``Welcome to L.A.,''
the concept dates as far back as 1932 with Edmund Goulding's
star-studded ``Grand Hotel.'' It's taken many turns since then _
from 1964's ``The Yellow Rolls Royce'' to just about every disaster
epic made in the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the indie film world has embraced the idea of a taxi cab
as the thread that links stories and characters together in such
offbeat fare as ``After Hours,'' ``Night On Earth'' and ``Chicago
Cab.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the idea has pretty much worn itself out, ``200
Cigarettes'' is, oddly enough, fresh air in a stale genre. It
features a top-notch cast of young talent and it actually recreates
with some success the arty allure of New York's trendy Lower East
Side.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1981 and New Year's Eve. A party is about to take place in
a downtown loft belonging to Monica (Martha Plimpton), who broke up
with artist boyfriend Eric (Brian McCardie) six months earlier. But
Brian isn't moping around. He's dating Bridget (Nicole Parker).
Bridget and her best friend Caitlyn (Angela Featherstone) have
agreed to attend the party with him, but Bridget's a little miffed
that Eric's just told her that Monica is his ex and she seizes the
opportunity to make the moves on the handsome bartender (Ben
Affleck) who is serving the trio some pre-function cocktails at a
downtown bar.
</P>
<P>
   Add two ``Jersey girls,'' underage friends Val (Christina Ricci)
and Stephie (Gaby Hoffmann), who are hoping to sneak into the bash,
as well as good pals Lucy (Courtney Love) and heartbroken Kevin
(Paul Rudd), woefully lamenting the demise of his relationship with
performance artist Ellie (Janeane Garofalo), and a new couple,
sweet, clumsy Cindy (Kate Hudson) and conceited Jack (Jay Mohr),
and the air is ripe with possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Blend in a jive-talking taxi driver, played by Dave Chapelle,
who drives the characters to their appointed destinies and anything
can _ and does _ happen.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun is discovering who will end up with whom by the
end of this goofy affair. And though there are several
all-too-familiar plot contrivances, first time feature film
director Risa Bramon Garcia manages to keep the action moving and
the silly lines light and appealing. She is aided immensely by the
charming Affleck, Plimpton and the scene-stealing Garofalo.
</P>
<P>
   Who could resist a come on as awful as Affleck's when he finally
realizes he's scored with two women at once: ``How do you like your
eggs in the morning? Scrambled or fertilized?'' The preview
audience howled at such dreadful stuff, but then no one ever said
the '80s were known for good taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' is energetic and nearly quaint despite its
eccentricity. Although it's essentially just a puff of smoke that
evaporates once we're out of the theater, it still engages and
entertains because of a terrific cast.
</P>
<P>
   200 Cigarettes. Directed by Risa Bramon Garcia. Written by Shana
Larsen. Cast: Ben Affleck, Dave Chapelle, Janeane Garofalo, Kate
Hudson, Courtney Love, Jay Mohr, Nicole Parker, Martha Plimpton,
Paul Rudd, Christina Ricci. Paramount Pictures. 96 minutes. Rated R
for language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
