r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-8MM-SPI &LR;      02-25 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-8MM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORDID `EIGHT MILLIMETER' APPEALS TO BASEST INSTINCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joel Schumacher's new mystery-thriller, ``Eight Millimeter,''
could well have the distinction of being the most thoroughly sordid
and depressing Hollywood big-studio film of the '90s. It gives a
whole new meaning to the word ``downer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the director's other work (``Lost Boys,'' ``The Client,''
the last two ``Batman'' movies), it's slick and fast-paced, with
the most expensive-looking production values Hollywood has to offer
and mostly competent performances.
</P>
<P>
   But also like those films, it's numbingly vacuous at its core,
and _ despite its sanctimonious tone and ``serious'' subject matter
_ it's basically an exploitation film that's out to shock,
titillate and appeal to the absolute worst in its audience.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about an upscale private-eye (Nicolas Cage) hired
by the widow of an industrial czar to track down the makers of an
8mm film she's found in her late husband's private safe showing a
teenage girl being savagely murdered for some sicko's viewing
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   It seems an impossible task, but in no time at all he's found
the victim's family, and cornered the committee of monsters who
created the ``snuff'' film, but not before he himself comes into
great peril _ both psychological and physical.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we're treated to a relentless journey into the
dark side of Schumacher's imagination: S&AMP;M bars, kiddy-porn
emporiums, numerous glimpses of movies that depict people being
bound and tortured, and young women butchered for a sexual kick.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Hardcore,'' ``Cruising'' and other big-budget studio
films that have dealt with the S&AMP;M world, the sensibility here is
highly conservative. Its message is that sex is evil, and the end
product of sexual freedom is not fulfillment but murder. Step out
of line and you become Ted Bundy.
</P>
<P>
   If you like that message, you may find the film a more profound
exploration of human nature than I did. But even if you do, you'll
still likely to find it amazingly hypocritical, and uncomfortably
designed not just to shock, but to excite.
</P>
<P>
   As a genre thriller, you're also likely to find it a fairly
incompetent exercise that constantly relies on a series of amazing
coincidences, that seems implausible every step of the way and
finally disintegrates into a bad horror movie, ``Friday the 13th,
Part X.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has been given the generic ``R'' rating by the MPAA,
which brings up a disturbing question: how could a movie that shows
frontal nudity, masturbation, oral sex, bondage and graphic S&AMP;M,
and refers to bestiality, child pornography and toilet sex,
possibly not earn an NC-17 rating?
</P>
<P>
   At the film's preview earlier this week, I actually saw several
families with pre-teen children happily watching this crash course
in abnormal sexuality. Why does Hollywood even bother to go through
the pretense of having a rating system if it has no intention of
using it?
</P>
<P>
   Eight Millimeter. Directed by Joel Schumacher. Written by Andrew
Kevin Walker. Cast: Nicolas Cage, Joaquin Phoenix, James
Gandolfini, Catherine Keener, Peter Stormare. Columbia. 123
minutes. Rated R for nudity, S&AMP;M sex scenes and extremely graphic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
