<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FINALLY TASTE A TOURNAMENT WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIRANDOLA, Italy _ The Revolution had to travel far from
Foxborough to win a tournament for the first time. Actually, the
Torneo Cesare Ragazzi should not be considered an event of great
significance, with three mini-games of 40 minutes each, but any
accomplishment will suffice for the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition included two teams from divisions even lower than
the Serie C teams the Revolution have been facing _ and will meet
Friday in Modena. Still, the Revolution edged Concordiese, 1-0, on
a 27th-minute free kick by Imad Baba, then played a 0-0 tie with
the home team, Mirandolese, to clinch first place. Concordiese
defeated Mirandolese, 2-1, in between.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zenga filled only the coach's role of his player-coach
duties and made key substitutions in the opening match. A starting
lineup of mostly reserve players began strong but soon faltered
against Concordiese. Baba, Mike Burns, Jair, Joe-Max Moore, and
Giovanni Savarese entered in the 25th minute and the Revolution
surrendered a shot off the side of the net seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwin Gorter moved from defense into midfield, and Baba
converted with an impressive free kick that swerved into the far
left side of the net from 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mirandolese was reinforced by retired Serie A midfielders
Giuseppe Accardi and Carlo Trevisanello. Though neither player had
been training, they displayed a savvy and touch that kept their
team in contention, even against a Revolution team that was
physically superior.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution needed at least a tie to clinch first place, and
the back four _ Burns, Dan Calichman, Richard Goulooze, and Ted
Chronopolous _ had a take-no-prisoners approach to the contest.
This game involved the prospective starting lineup for the
Revolution, which could also include John Harkes, after his loan to
Nottingham Forest expires next month. They performed like a team
that will think defense first and be difficult to maneuver against.
But the offense lacked a finishing touch. Baba drilled the
Revolution's best chance off the top of the bar in the eighth
minute, and No. 3 goalkeeper Anthony Latronica stopped
Mirandolese's best chance from Accardi in the 32d minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games do not mean too much,'' Zenga said. ``You can
sometimes win playing badly, or lose playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Revolution players felt a sense of accomplishment,
especially after last year's disastrous record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to win a tournament,'' defender Manny Motajo said.
``This is something we can build on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ian Feuer, starting goalkeeper for the Revolution last year, was
traded to Colorado for future considerations. Feuer expressed his
desire to leave the Revolution after Zenga announced he would be
playing this year and had been performing on loan in England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
