<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-TENTH-BOS &LR;      02-25 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-TENTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURE OF THE MOUNTAINS IS STILL STRONG FOR THE TENTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CONWAY, N.H. _ So much has been written about the 10th
Mountain Division ``Ski Troops'' of World War II that these white
cloaked soldiers on their white skis carrying white carbines have
become as romantic in lore as the elite air corps dogfighters of
the previous war.
</P>
<P>
   Many divisions in the Europe and Asian theaters fought longer,
under more prolonged battle conditions, and suffered more
casualties over time. Through the 54 years since the war ended,
many of those divisions have remained in touch, vowing not to let
the memories that bound their lives together, fade.
</P>
<P>
   But the 10th Mountain Division _ known simply as ``The Tenth'' _
has another dimmension binding them, one that will bring them
togehter yet again this weekend at Mt. Cranmore during the Hannes
Schneider Meister Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our love of the outdoors,'' says Newc Eldrege, an Enfield
New Hampshire native and veteran of the Tenth. ``We love to ski and
hike and climb in the mountains. Sure there was the crucible of
combat, but there was much more than that that has held us
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, says Eldrege who had just played tennis with
90-year-old Tenth vet John Hubner on Wednesday, ``guys from a lot
of other divisions that fought far longer than we did get ticked
off because we get so much publicity _ and I don't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995 when Eldrege and his friends climbed up Riva Ridge
in Italy in a 50th anniversary reenactment of the most famous Tenth
battle scene and there, on the summit, embraced their former
enemies, it was clear that the love of the mountains made a greater
bond than the combat that once enveloped them.
</P>
<P>
   The International Federation of Mountain Soldiers, says Eldrege,
who led a squad on the front lines the night the Tenth won the
battle of Riva Ridge, includes fighting units from Germany and
Austria as well as England, France, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So it is more than old war memories that keep veterans of the
Tenth coming back to events like the Meister Cup, which this year
coincides with the 60th anniversary of the Cranmore Mountain
resort. A lifelong devotion to skiing still keeps the now 70- and
80-year-olds coming back to race on the mountain whose history is
entwined with early years of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the ski area opened in the Mt. Washington Valley,
a young ski instructor from Austria _ Hannes Schneider _ who was
fleeing the Nazis, took a job as ski school instructor. With much
pomp and ceremony, Schneider and his 17-year-old son, Herbert,
arrived in North Conway by train, and were given a hero's welcome
at the station.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Schneider began a trend that found many European ski
instructors teaching the new sport that was catching on in this
country. His Arlberg training technique was the first uniform
method of ski instruction, and Schneider for all time will be
remembered as ``the father of modern skiing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the European expatriates who fought in the Tenth
founded ski areas and schools from New England to the Rockies
(Aspen and Vail) in a post-war decade that established skiing as a
broad middle-class sport in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our numbers are shrinking,'' says Eldrege, who will be racing
on one of three teams, each with five Tenth veterans to compete
this weekend. ``We used to get 300, and now we're down to about 100
at this reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who will race over the weekend, skiing is still a
serious pursuit. ``Most of us have kept at it because it's
something we love,'' says Eldrege, noting that the modernization of
equipment _ most notably shaped skis _ have made it easier for the
aging soldier/skiers to make their turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volante made a Tenth special edition shaped ski,'' he says,
``and they are wonderful. They carve well, and give great control.
They really make skiing easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``old soldiers' race'' is just one feature of the Meister
Cup, which also includes NASTAR handicapped speed competitions for
various age groups ranging from 13 to 80. Races, demonstrations,
special events, and a banquet are all part of the weekend in North
Conway.
</P>
<P>
   All proceeds raised will benefit the New England Ski Museum and
the Make-A-Wish Foundation of New Hampshire, which is devoted to
fulfilling wishes for children faced with life-threatening
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the draw for the Tenth veterans is simply the
opportunity to get together are reminisce. ``We don't bother too
much with the facts,'' says Eldrege, who remembers that several of
the veterans met in the spring of 1995 for the 50th anniversary
reenactment.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatched to Italy in the spring of 1945, the Tenth encountered
elite German mountain troops firmly anchored atop Riva Ridge on the
1,200-foot rock ledge of Mt. Belvedere that commanded the Po
Valley, a possible entrance point for an enemy advance. The nearly
vertical face of Belvedere was considered unclimbable.
</P>
<P>
   But on an April night, some 800 Tenth soldiers climbed Belvedere
and then even engineered a tram car on the mountain to evacuate
wounded. They engaged the surprised Germans, overunning one
stronghold after another until they had dirven the enemy so far
back the Allied troops were able to cross the Po River. On May 2,
the war in Italy ended with the German surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people tell this and make it sound like the Tenth
guys think they won the war,'' says Eldrege, ``and the publicity we
get outweighs what we did in comparison to some other divisions,
like the 5th and the British 8th.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the veterans did their reenactment climb in 1995,
and met with former enemy soldiers to admire the beauty of the
country they once fought over, their message was clear to all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germans, Swiss, US . . . we all worked to create a trail for
people who love to climb and hike in those mountains. Our mission
has been to make peace trails out of the battle mountains, and to
pass (the message) of peace and human rights onto future
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' says Eldrege, ``we're not going to be around a
hell of a lot longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
