<SLUG> BC-FILM-SISTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INOFFENSIVE `OTHER SISTER' IS PLEASANT ENOUGH DIVERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does this sound like a bad idea or what? A comedy-drama (with
the emphasis on comedy) about a family coping with the return of
their mentally handicapped daughter after (heh, heh) several years
in an institution, directed by low-humor specialist Garry Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   You can recall past Marshall epics and almost see the movie,
can't you? Perhaps an uneasy combination of the medical hijinks of
``Young Doctors in Love,'' the dysfunctional family fun of
``Nothing in Common,'' the sappiness of ``Beaches'' and the
wholesale false sincerity of ``Dear God.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. ``The Other Sister'' is no masterpiece and definitely has
its share of wincing moments, but it's an incorrigibly
sweet-spirited affair that gradually finds a pleasing middle ground
between an affliction-of-the-week weepie and a rollicking domestic
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about the Tate family: wealthy dentist father (Tom
Skerritt), meddling mother (Diane Keaton), and three grown
daughters, one of whom _ the 24-year-old Carla (Juliette Lewis) _
has just returned to the bosom of her family after a lengthy tenure
in a boarding school for the retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the already guilt-ridden mom is instantly
overprotective of Carla, and the film works off the tension that
arises in the family as she moves out from under that maternal
protection, finds an apartment of her own and falls in love with an
equally mentally handicapped young man (Giovanni Ribisi).
</P>
<P>
   With so much of the drama _ and humor _ of the piece designed to
come out of semi-slapsticky scenes in which Carla keeps doing
things that are horrendously embarrassing for the family, the whole
enterprise constantly totters on the edge of a descent into the
worst kind of bad-taste black comedy imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, it doesn't happen. And much of the credit for this
has to go to Lewis, who doesn't have to stretch her normal goofy
mannerisms very far to convince us she's authentically handicapped.
She creates a genuinely believable character (in the way Helena
Bonham Carter did not in her recent affliction role, ``The Theory
of Flight'').
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ensemble is almost as strong. Tom Skerritt has
rarely been so winning as he is playing an endlessly patient man
whose meekness masks a profound love for his disabled daughter; and
Diane Keaton is wonderfully exasperating as a mother struggling
between protecting and controlling an especially vulnerable child.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Marshall has admirably restrained his usual
penchant for broad comedy and crude sexual innuendo to let a more
subtle humor and groundswell of family affection emerge from his
characters and situations. ``The Other Sister'' is too long and
never quite comes together to be anything truly special, but it's
inoffensive, reasonably entertaining, very much its own thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Sister. Directed by Garry Marshall. Written by
Marshall and Bob Bruner. Cast: Juliette Lewis, Diane Keaton, Tom
Skerritt, Giovanni Ribisi, Poppy Montgomery, Hector Elizondo,
Joanna Going. Touchstone/Disney. 130 minutes. Rated PG-13 for some
sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
