<SLUG> BC-TV-ALICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S `ALICE IN WONDERLAND' IS A LOVING TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine Lewis Carroll pitching ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland'' to a network executive in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll: ``The main character is a little girl who can grow
smaller or bigger by munching mushrooms or drinking magic
elixirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive: ``So it's about the '60s drug culture? NBC just did a
whole miniseries on the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll: ``No. It's a fantastical tale with characters like
Tweedledum, Tweedledee and the Queen of Hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive: ``Oh, it's about Diana and the royal family? You're
about a year late, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll: ``No, no. It's a fictional story that pokes gentle fun
at adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive: ``A satire, huh? People don't get satire.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll: ``NO! It's just an illogical little yarn that doesn't
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive: ``Well, why didn't you say so? Give me 22, no, 44
episodes and we'll put it on right after `Two Guys, a Girl and a
Pizza Place.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is our good fortune that Carroll dealt not in the offices of
Hollywood high-rises but in the tall imaginations of children (and
adults reluctant to grow up).
</P>
<P>
   Not that the story defies translation to the screen. Millions
who were kids in the '80s remember Irwin Allen's four-hour,
two-night telefilm on CBS that probably holds the record for
celebrity bloat. The cast included Steve Allen, Ernest Borgnine,
Beau Bridges, Lloyd Bridges, Red Buttons, Sid Caesar, Carol
Channing, Imogene Coca, Sammy Davis Jr., Patrick Duffy, George
Gobel, Steve Lawrence, Eydie Gorme, Merv Griffin, Sherman Hemsley,
Ann Jillian, Arte Johnson, Harvey Korman, Karl Malden, Roddy
McDowall, Jayne Meadows, Donna Mills, Pat Morita, Robert Morley,
Anthony Newley, Louis Nye, Donald O'Connor, Martha Raye, Telly
Savalas (as the Cheshire Cat), Ringo Starr, Sally Struthers, Jack
Warden, Jonathan Winters and Shelley Winters.
</P>
<P>
   There have been at least 11 other film treatments, including
five more on television, dating all the way back to 1903, which was
only five years after Carroll's death. No question, the story of
Alice's adventure after she followed White Rabbit down that hole is
enduring and endearing.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Entertainment's three-hour film Sunday night on NBC is
no slouch, though in the celebrity department it's a featherweight
compared with Allen's.
</P>
<P>
   The scene stealers are Martin Short as a caffeinated Mad Hatter
and Miranda Richardson as Queen of Hearts, whose ear-splitting
rants are reminiscent of Judy Tenuta, sans accordion. It's a
wonderful encore for Short and Richardson, who stood out in Robert
Halmi Sr.'s Hallmark productin of ``Merlin'' last season.
</P>
<P>
   With Carroll's fabulous imagination and twice as many special
effects as were in ``Merlin,'' Halmi couldn't possibly go wrong,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much, except the first hour of ``Alice'' is a bit slow.
Tina Majorino ultimately makes it work, playing Alice with a mix of
bashfulness and bravado that's nearly as perfect as the sumptuous
visuals.
</P>
<P>
   For some children, ``Alice in Wonderland'' is more nightmare
than dream. But with warm lighting and no monstrous Jabberwock,
this one is as benign as they come. Alas, no Jabberwock means no
Jabberwocky. (Perhaps the network censors feared there's something
subversive in mysterious verse about ``slithy toves'' that ``gyre
and gimble in the wabe.'')
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's precious little of Carroll's nonsense language
in this ``Alice,'' and several familiar characters are also
missing. Nonetheless, it is a lavish, loving tribute, and if it
sends many kids and their parents in search of the unabridged
version, the Cheshire Cat's grin will last a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   Alice in Wonderland. Three-hour TV movie based on ``Alice's
Adventures in Wonderland'' and ``Through the Looking-Glass and What
Alice Found There,'' by Lewis Carroll. Starring Tina Majorino,
Robbie Coltrane, Whoopi Goldberg, Ben Kingsley, Christopher Lloyd,
Pete Postlethwaite, Miranda Richardson, Martin Short, Peter
Ustinov, George Wendt and Gene Wilder. Sunday on NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
