<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE DESERVES BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ Byron Dafoe wouldn't classify himself as a
statistics nut but he does peruse the sports pages to see where he
ranks among National Hockey League goalies.
</P>
<P>
   If, during training camp, you'd have told the Bruins netminder
that at this point in the season he'd have a 2.12 goals-against
average (sixth in the league) and a .924 save percentage, he'd have
been a happy man. But what doesn't add up about Dafoe's numbers is
his 18-19-7 record, a mark that belies his other stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite a funny stat,'' said Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is tied for second in shutouts (six) with some pretty good
company _ Philadelphia's John Vanbiesbrouck and Phoenix's Nikolai
Khabibulin _ and tied for fourth in save percentage with Carolina's
Arturs Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is discouraging,'' Dafoe said of his losing record. ``As
happy as I do feel about my goals against and save percentage, I'd
trade it in for where I was as far as wins last year. I'm ahead in
all categories from last year except for wins. Probably the most
frustrating thing is you can go out and feel you had a pretty good
game _ even Ottawa (a week ago when the Bruins lost, 2-0), you give
up two goals on 28 shots and that's generally a pretty good game _
but you walk away pretty disappointed because it's a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how well you played because if you don't
win, it's not satisfying. That's the reality. You'd think sooner or
later, it would turn if you could keep those numbers where they are
because in the last two games, we've scored 11 goals. If we can do
that some more, the wins are going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who was born in Great Britain but raised in Canada, said
it wasn't his lower number of wins that kept him off the World
All-Star team. At the time the roster was filled out, he had more
wins than Irbe. Dafoe said it was his understanding that he never
was considered at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard through the grapevine that they didn't even consider
me because I'm not truly European,'' said Dafoe. ``We're marketing
this game as World players against North Americans and you don't
fit so let's go with Irbe. That's what I heard. To be honest (that
explanation) makes sense because the numbers didn't make sense.
That disappoints me. Then put me on the North American ballot. As
long as next year it's cleared up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
