<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE THE NEW GUY A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ It's not his fault.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans are going to have to remind themselves that Jose
Offerman did not ask to become The Man Who Replaced Mo Vaughn. He
did not hold a gun to the head of Red Sox general manager Dan
Duquette and demand a four-year, $26 million contract. He did not
ask to take Mo's place at first base. And it's not Offerman's fault
that the Sox failed in their bids to acquire Bernie Williams,
Albert Belle, and other high-profile free agents this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Offerman Era began Wednesday, and it's important to remember
all of the above. Let's resist our primal instincts and give the
guy a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   Jose made his first appearance at Red Sox camp at 9:27 a.m.,
walking into the Sox minor league complex with a Kansas City Royals
equipment bag slung over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman walked up behind Boston manager Jimy Williams and said
hello. Williams, who had been talking with a Boston radio producer,
turned around and said, ``We were just talking about you, Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of folks in the Sox camp have been talking about Offerman.
They talk about where he'll play _ first base, second base, or
designated hitter? They talk about him replacing Vaughn's ``on-base
capability.'' They talk about difficulties he had with former
Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda. They talk about how the pressure of
following Mo might get to the 30-year-old Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman won't have any of the Vaughn comparisons. Nor should
he.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people don't see me that way,'' he said. ``That wasn't
the situation. They don't got me because Mo leave the team. They
got me because they was looking for me. It's a lot different
between me and Mo, and I hope people don't compare me with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman is not going to hit home runs. He's hit 22 homers in
his career (including one off Dennis Martinez in his first big
league at-bat), never more than seven in a season. Last year he hit
.315 with a league-leading 13 triples and 45 stolen bases. He
played 152 games at second base and committed 19 errors. He's a
leadoff man who strikes out more than he walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what people expect from me,'' said the
switch-hitter. ``I just want to do my job. The only thing I can
bring is a guy that likes to play every day and do everything I can
do to help the team, and that's what I'm here for.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman gets on base and manufactures runs. Will that be enough
to satisfy bloodthirsty Boston fans?
</P>
<P>
   It might be rough. Stan Papi never got a fair shot in Boston
because he was traded for popular Bill Lee. Matt Young was hooted
out of town because fans felt he was overpaid and couldn't pitch
under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman already has been stung by Boston columnists and talk
show hosts. Movie star Samuel L. Jackson took a shot at him during
the ESPY Awards on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is Offerman's reputation as a player who
doesn't like playing in big-market towns. He was more comfortable
in Kansas City than he was in Los Angeles. So how is he going to
handle the darts and arrows that find all athletes who play in
Boston?
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through that before,'' he said. ``I played in LA and it
was that way. Right now I'm in a better position because I'm older
and I can handle it a lot better than what I used to do before. It
would be a lot easier than last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Jose. How do we tell him that nothing in his professional
baseball life has prepared him for the months and years ahead in
Boston? He hasn't played a game yet, but already he's a marked man
because of the contract and his status as The Man Who Followed Mo.
If he's anything less than Maury Wills, he's going to get roasted
in the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   Already there is controversy regarding where he'll play.
Offerman isn't going to remind anyone of Bill Mazeroski, but
Duquette makes it clear that he wants Offerman to play second base.
Williams loves Jeff Frye and doesn't feel Frye should lose his job
just because he blew out his knee last year. Offerman broke in as a
shortstop, but that won't be an option here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm willing to wait for them to put me in the
position they want me to play,'' he said. ``I'll just be ready for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing first, naturally, would only add to the pressure of
following Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want nobody to compare me with him,'' he said. ``I'm
too far away from him. I just try to do my job. The only difference
is if I have to play first. I don't try to do what he do, and
people have to understand that. I will try to do the best I can. It
is hard to say what I'm going to do, but I will try to do my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman is from the Dominican Republic. His English is good,
but not as good as Pedro Martinez's. He will wear No. 30. He is 6
feet tall, weighs 190 pounds, and is married with two children.
</P>
<P>
   He is not Mo Vaughn, but that is not his fault. He is Jose
Offerman. Give the guy a chance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
