<HEADLINE>
WHEN IN DOUBT, THROW IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After 13 years, my husband still swears I was
trying to collect on his life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   I had roasted a pair of cornish game hens. Mine was fine, his,
though delicious, harbored some relentless bacteria that keep him
praising the porcelain god for days.
</P>
<P>
   I should have used a meat thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the woman who refrigerated vegetable soup in the
stockpot overnight and reheated it the next evening. Before she
realized the soup had taken on a life of its own, her daughter had
eaten a bowl and gone off to soccer practice. They carried the
child off the field to an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   She should have placed the soup in glass or plastic containers
before refrigerating it.
</P>
<P>
   And there are questions I am frequently asked: ``Can I still use
this case of canned tomatoes I bought three years ago?'' ``Is this
pasta salad leftover from the church luncheon safe to eat?''
``Can't you just tell a turkey is done by wiggling the leg?'' I
usually answer a question with a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the $12 you're saving by not replacing those tomatoes worth
a bout of food poisoning?'' Or, ``Is wasting a bowl of pasta salad
so bad you'll risk a case of salmonella?'' Or, ``So, how big is the
insurance policy on your spouse?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-25 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE THE RECKLESS AN ENDANGERED SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago we visited the family of Gren Anderson who began
skiing a year ago and is well on his way to being a solid
intermediate. We let pass without comment a story Anderson told me,
which should not have passed.
</P>
<P>
   While he was taking a lesson, a snowboarder ran into him,
knocking him down, causing some pain, and giving him plenty to
worry about the next time he ventured out onto a trial. During his
next lesson, his instructor skied on Anderson's uphill side to
protect him from any other unguided missile that might be headed
his way.
</P>
<P>
   With our story a couple of weeks ago focusing on Anderson's
delight with his new sport, we unfortunately let slide the outrage
that he was blindsided by an out-of-control boarder.
</P>
<P>
   I could fill this space and much more with letters of horror,
hate, stupidity, and slope rage from people with tales similar to
Anderson's. Anecdotal though it may be, it does seem that such
incidences are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Reenforced by news accounts from throughout ski country, the
evidence is pretty clear that some skiers and boarders are not only
out of control but that they are a danger to others on the slopes.
Lest you think the complaints apply only to snowboarders, read from
a letter by Joan Hatch of Andover, Mass.:
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened on one of those what I call classic ski days.
Perfect snow, blue sky, bright sun. We were skiing at (name held
because the area needn't be singled out; it happens everywhere)
down a main intermediate slope. My husband and I were stopped at
the side of a trail looking at a trail map when four teenage boys
came flying around a corner on skis, racing each other. It was
obvious that they couldn't ski very well, but that wasn't about to
slow them down. As they tried to cut the corner where we stood,
three of the boys went in front of us, and you can guess where the
fourth one tried to go _ between us and the woods behind us about 2
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, he didn't make it, but was going too fast to
stop, and careened into my husband, knocking him into me. All three
of us went down. My husband broke two ribs, I had two bad bruises,
and the young man was also injured so badly he also had to be taken
down in a first-aid sled. Many things were said, you may be sure,
but the one I remember best was the young man saying to us, `You
were right in my way! I didn't have anywhere to go. This wasn't my
fault.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This may be the most flagrant case, but it is only one of many.
It could have been far worse for the Hatches than bruises and
broken ribs.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Frew, president of Colorado Ski Country, the
reports of ``road rage'' on the slopes is rising throughout the
Rockies, and a number of deaths can be attributed to such
recklessness. Frew spoke on the very day a snowboarder was killed
by a skier who ran into him, airborne, at an Oregon ski area.
</P>
<P>
   In response to this alarming trend, Vail _ one of the busiest
resorts in the country _ has gone beyond the incessant analyses of
safety figures. Over February vacation week, it took a simple but
effective action to at least give the perception that it gives a
damn: It deputized safety patrols.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not new and has been tried in various forms. Many
years ago, the late King Ridge in New Hampshire had ``courtesy
patrols'' _ regular skiers at the area who were empowered to ask
skiers to slow down, stay in control, and to report violators to
the ski patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds kind of nerdy, you say? What's the alternative? The
patrol staff is simply not large to do the job, areas acknowledge,
and for the cost of a free lift ticket, the ski area at least has a
deputy patrol person to keep an eye out.
</P>
<P>
   Most areas put up ``SLOW'' signs in areas of heavy traffic,
especially where mixed abilities come together in a runout to a
lift. But how many areas put a ski patroller around the ``SLOW''
sign to see how many youngsters use it as a slalom gate?
</P>
<P>
   At Aspen's Snowmass Village _ another very busy resort _
residents of the area became so incensed after a hit-and-run
accident that they have set up a $1,000 reward for information
leading to rogue skiers who flaunt safety on their slopes. The
bounty, according to a spokesman for the residents, turns everyone
into a patrolman. ``And they don't have to arrest anyone,'' he
said, ``just blow the whistle on some of the jerks out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
