<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYNT RETURNS WITH PG MUCKRAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember a few weeks back when Hustler's Larry Flynt was the
most feared publisher in America after forcing the resignation of
House Speaker-elect Bob Livingston amid allegations of marital
infidelity? After a failed attempt to inflict similar damage on GOP
Congressman Bob Barr, Flynt vanished along with his threat to
expose the sexual misdeeds of other leading Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, fans of the porn king's style of Scarlet A journalism will
be able to plunk down $4.99 to purchase The Flynt Report, an
84-page magazine (with no advertising) that should arrive on your
newsstand in early April. Hustler editor Allan MacDonnell won't
reveal its contents, other than to say ``it's not going to be a
Hustler thing. It's going to be PG-rated'' and to mention several
other top Republicans (whose names we'll omit out of abiding
respect for the libel laws) who are ``gonna be very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his attorney, Alan Isaacman, Flynt took a break
from his public sexual sleuthing after the Barr episode because the
impeachment trial ended and because of difficult negotiations with
sources trying to claim his reward of up to $1 million. ``They
valued the information more than we did,'' says Isaacman.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacman would not say how much Flynt paid in his effort to
embarrass Republicans. But counting snitches and investigators,
MacDonnell put the figure at between $3 and $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the impending arrival of a new editor, one of journalism's
most reliably left-wing voices may soon be singing a different
tune. Roger Cohn, the former executive editor of Audubon magazine
and longtime environmental reporter at The Philadelphia Inquirer,
says it'll be reporting over ideology when he takes the reins of
Mother Jones in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the magazine has . . . leaned too heavily toward
commentary,'' says Cohn. ``To me, it's important that the magazine
take a hard look at the sacred cows of the left, to challenge the
readers' own assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   With a larger circulation (130,000) than either The New Republic
or the Nation, the 23-year-old Mother Jones is a standard-bearer
for liberal journalism, eagerly attacking such conservative icons
as Rupert Murdoch, Rush Limbaugh, and Newt Gingrich and accusing a
center-seeking Bill Clinton of being a ``good Republican
president.'' (To get a sense of its readership, 67 percent of the
respondents to an on-line poll on its Web site favored legalizing
drugs.)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine has done its share of hard-hitting reporting in
following the trail of filthy lucre: In his final column, outgoing
editor Jeffrey Klein characterized ``the money behind politics'' as
the dominant story of his tenure. But Cohn is not satisfied with
the staus quo, saying ``I really would like to improve the quality
of the writing . . . the direction I want to take the magazine in
is very journalistic, not ideological.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is one time the overworked David-versus-Goliath analogy
fits. When the Duxbury, Mass. (population 14,800) proved unable to
support three weeklies, it was the big kid on the block who took
the fall. The Duxbury Mariner _ one of 117 papers owned by mutual
fund giant Fidelity's Community Newspaper Co. (CNC) _ is shutting
down after failing to compete with the independent Duxbury Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching only about 1,200 paying subscribers at its height, the
Mariner was purchased by CNC in 1995 and converted from a shopper
into a broadsheet, to no avail. ``There is no question there is no
need in Duxbury for a third weekly paper,'' said CNC president Kirk
Davis, explaining the decision to fold the tent.
</P>
<P>
   Still left standing is the Duxbury Reporter, a free weekly
mailed to almost 2,900 homes. But the real victor is The Duxbury
Clipper, an old-fashioned community weekly with 4,000 paid
subscribers that belongs in a Norman Rockwell painting.
</P>
<P>
   It's a real hometown paper,'' says editor Josh Cutler. ``When
they're born, their name is in the paper. When they go off to
school, their name is in the paper.'' Cutler is one of three
full-time staffers on the Clipper. But more important, he is the
scion of the Cutler publishing dynasty. His father, David, is the
Clipper's publisher and his grandparents, John and Roberta, founded
the paper in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see the little guy win one,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1980s officially ended on Nov. 21, 1990, when junk-bond king
Michael Milken was sentenced for violating securities laws. After
years of image rehab, Milken is now someone held in even lower
esteem than an ex-con. A journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Through his nonprofit economic think tank, the Milken Institute,
Milken has published the first issue of The Milken Institute
Review, a quarterly journal of economic policy that will initially
have a controlled circulation of about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to find a happy niche between the popular business
and economic journals and academic journals,'' says Peter Passell,
the former New York Times staffer who is editor.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-page debut issue features everything from a Mark Alan
Stamaty cartoon ``Ekinomix'' to a quiz page (Did you know that
Massachusetts and California soak up 50 percent of new venture
capital?) to a piece on ``capital mobility.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly easy reading, even Milken's ``From The
Chairman'' message with its sentimental recollection of how his
father taught him to analyze corporate finances at age 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
