<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GRAMMY-SHOW-BOS &LR;      02-25 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GRAMMY-SHOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSIE O'DONNELL FRONTS A LARGELY GLITCH-FREE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell presided over the 41st Grammy ceremony like an
old pro. She just showed up and did her Rosie thing, by turns
goofy, brash, and sly, but generally comfortable and always _
always! _ hammy. She put last year's pop-illiterate Grammy host,
Kelsey Grammer, quickly to shame, turning the 1999 event into three
hours of knowing goofs on the music world and Rosie-ized versions
of the hits (``Near, far, the Cross Your Heart bra,'' she sang).
She was everyone's greatest fan, the high-school funny girl, the
lovable misfit talking to the junior-class pretty girl from the
stage: ``Hi, Shania. You look nice.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the event seemed to be more about Rosie's routines than
the Grammys and their winners. But the West Coast gala was such a
remarkably smooth ride this year, it depended on O'Donnell's
attention-getting stunts and shtick for any hint of peppiness. No
one else was going to let go and make the Jerry Falwell Tinky Winky
joke, or mimic Latin pop performance winner Ricky Martin's ``hip
thing,'' or scream-sing a Steven Tyler song. The night contained a
painful shortage of glitches, botches, insults, controversial
political statements, and emotional moments _ the sort of
spontaneous bits that give these award telecasts their color. At
least O'Donnell filled in the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there weren't grace notes along the way. Lauryn Hill
accepted her award for new artist by reading a Psalm, and later
delivered a sweet version of her song to her son, ``Zion,'' with
Carlos Santana on hand to play his licks from her album. No longer
angry, Alanis Morissette delivered a poised version of
``Uninvited,'' which won rock song and female rock vocal awards,
and Will Smith warmly accepted for best rap solo by admitting that
he had just learned his son's ``rhyming skills are down'' in
school. It was all sedate and, at points, sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Only one or two pop in-jokes had slightly racy overtones. First,
a pair of sushi chefs on stage after Madonna's Asian-themed opener
revealed the words ``Soy'' and ``Bomb'' on their chests. They were
there as reminders of last year, when a crazed performance artist
surprised Bob Dylan during his heartfelt rendition of ``Love Sick''
by convulsing with those words written on his bare torso. Then
Jerry Seinfeld alluded to one of the more controversial episodes of
``Seinfeld'' as he presented an award with Jennifer Lopez. ``I'm
Jewish, and you are . . .?'' he said. After Lopez replied, ``100
percent Puerto Rican,'' Seinfeld archly waved a miniature Puerto
Rican flag and said, ``Viva Puerto Rico.'' Last year, Hispanic
leaders denounced a plot that had Kramer setting the Puerto Rican
flag on fire and stomping it out.
</P>
<P>
   With one or two exceptions, the fashions were tame. The spy vs.
spy award went to Shania Twain: Early in the evening, both in the
red carpet interviews and in her Shrine Auditorium seat, she was
regal and noble in a bright, sparkly, Audrey Hepburn-necked gown.
The subliminal message was ``white sugar.'' But when she came
onstage to sing ``Man, I Feel Like a Woman,'' Twain had become the
ultimate bad girl, stuffed into a very short, tight, silky black
dress, with tall black boots and long black gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But the boldest fashion statement goes to Madonna. Some 15 years
after she broke onto the pop scene, she is still the Sybil of
style, and she kicked off the gala by leaving yet another indelible
image on our eyeballs. This time she was a red-hot groovin' geisha
(or ``the little geisha that could,'' as O'Donnell said), singing a
full-voiced version of ``Nothing Really Matters'' and swinging her
shiny and profoundly straight black hair. Somehow, she managed to
dance in a pair of cartoonishly arched clogs.
</P>
<P>
   The red carpet action also rated notably low on the garishness
meter. Usually, watching the celebrities trip on their tacky gowns
as they wander into the auditorium, making awkward small talk with
cable TV anchors like Melissa ``How Cool Was That'' Rivers,
provides a special kind of cheap, jittery, aniticipatory high. But
the preshow specials on E! and MTV were quiet, with lots of premade
filler in between the on-site interviews. Morissette, tastefully
dressed and with unstringy hair, confessed, ``I love singing,'' and
Elvis Costello shamelessly plugged ``200 Cigarettes,'' the
forthcoming movie that includes his songs and a cameo. Steven Tyler
sang a ditty to MTV's Serena Altschul, and Brandy and Monica, whose
rift is tired old news indeed, held hands as they talked to E!'s
David Adelson. ``People, we're friends,'' Brandy said. ``Get over
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
