<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA:PRESIDENT-L     02-25 2019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA:PRESIDENT-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S REVOLUTIONARY HURRICANE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By RAYMOND COLITT 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CARACAS, Venezuela _ When Hugo Rafael Chavez Frias was
officially declared president-elect of Venezuela last December,
``El Comandante,'' as he is known to his supporters, cited the
words of the 19th century independence fighter and national hero
Simon Bolivar, ``all I am is a frail straw being dragged along in a
revolutionary hurricane.''
 &HT;    As candidate and perhaps even president-elect being a ``frail
straw'' is fine, but President Chavez, who started a five-year term
last month, must now gain his bearings fast. The economy is
plunging into recession. The budget is flying out of control.
Nothing has been secured _ economic policy reforms, investor
confidence and popular demands for a better standard of living are
blowing in the wind.
 &HT;    Indeed, Venezuela in 1999 faces one of the greatest challenges
in its modern history. Chavez's landslide victory over the
traditional political parties and the dramatic price decline of its
principal commodity, oil, last year marked the collapse of the
economic and political models that dominated the country for the
past 40 years. The task of reconstruction now falls into the hands
of Chavez, a 44-year-old, former paratrooper who led a failed coup
attempt in 1992.
 &HT;    ``There is no room for mistakes,'' says Luis Henrique Ball, head
of the industry association, Confederacion Venezolana de
Industriales (Conindustria).
 &HT;    Record low prices for oil have decimated petroleum revenue,
which accounts for as much as 70 percent of the country's exports
and half of the government's revenue. Oil export earnings plunged
some US$7 billion to about $11 billion in 1998, forcing dramatic
cuts in expenditures by state-run oil company Petroleos de
Venezuela (PDVSA) and the government alike. Nonetheless, the public
deficit finished last year at an estimated 9 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP).
 &HT;    Hundreds of sub-contractors and suppliers to the oil industry
have shut down; unemployment has jumped from 11 percent to as much
as 20 percent, according to industry sources. The economy
contracted by an estimated 1 percent last year and, according to
many estimates, is expected to shrink at least another 2 percent in
1999.
 &HT;    Chavez himself rose to power on a wave of popular discontent
with the deterioration of real incomes and basic public services
such as health, education, and justice. Real incomes per capita
have fallen by two-thirds over the past two decades and, although
Venezuela is one of the oil-richest countries in the world, an
estimated 70 percent of the country's 23 million people live in
poverty.
 &HT;    Since his election, however, Chavez has moderated his populist
rhetoric and anti-establishment platform. ``We certainly do not
want a communist economic model but we also reject the savage
neo-liberal model,'' Chavez says.
 &HT;    He has shelved his trademark military-style red beret and taken
to wearing a business suit. Instead of speaking about revising
privatization contracts, halting foreign debt payments, and
shutting down Congress, he now talks of strict fiscal discipline,
endorsing foreign investment, and negotiating with Congress. In a
show of continuity, he even retained Finance Minister Maritza
Izaguirre, who was appointed under the Caldera Administration.
 &HT;    Venezuela's new president, for example, aims to cut public
spending by reducing the number of government ministries, slashing
the public sector payroll, and restructuring the profile of foreign
debt payments. He hopes to increase revenue with better tax
collection _ with the very optimistic goal of an additional $5
billion annually _ and a crackdown on corruption in customs.
 &HT;    The government's success in maintaining fiscal discipline and
boosting the autonomy of the Central Bank, as announced, will
largely determine its success in bringing down a stubborn inflation
rate of near 30 percent in 1998, still one of Latin America's
highest. The Central Bank currently lacks sufficient financial
instruments to practice an adequate monetary policy.
 &HT;    Yet some analysts say the government will not be able to bring
its accounts in order without raising funds on international
capital markets and reaching an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund. ``We are going to need a Brazilian-style package and
international help to refinance our foreign debt obligations,''
says Conindustria's Ball.
 &HT;    Others are concerned the Chavez government may excessively tap
the coffers of PDVSA to subsidize agricultural activities and fund
social programs. Chavez has been critical of PDVSA's management,
saying the company is run as ``a state within a state.'' He has
promised to eliminate fringe benefits including ``the fleets of
private aircraft, overseas travel and credit cards without limit.''
 &HT;    The government has also pledged to respect contracts signed with
domestic and foreign oil companies in recent years to develop vast
oil fields. The private sector has announced investments worth an
estimated $7.2 billion in 1999, more than twice the $2.5 billion
spent in 1998. That comes on top of PDVSA's $3.8 billion in capital
investment in 1999. This could have an important ripple effect in
the economy, kick-starting many service and supply companies.
 &HT;    Some of these oil projects are already being delayed and many
experts say the picture could get worse as oil prices are expected
to remain low for some years to come.
 &HT;    Facing such a scenario, the Chavez government has revived the
country's long-held goal of diversifying the economy, developing
agriculture, tourism and other non-oil sectors.
 &HT;    The public/private investment promotion agency Consejo Nacional
de Promocion de Inversiones (Conapri) says it has identified some
$32 billion in potential investment over the 5-year government term
(1999-2004). Heading the list are infrastructure projects that will
require some $6 billion, followed by mining with $4.3 billion, iron
and steel with $3.2 billion, and petrochemicals with $3 billion.
``Provided the government implements a program towards
macroeconomic stabilization, we could see such investment in coming
years,'' says Luis Soto, head of Conapri.
 &HT;    With immense diversity and unique tourist attractions,
Venezuela's tourism potential is large, industry experts say, and
much of the necessary infrastructure is already in place. New
hotels and international air links have been inaugurated recently.
``What we are looking for primarily from the government is targeted
promotion abroad,'' says Francisco Crededio, a Caracas-based
tourism consultant. Tourism operators are also calling on the
government to further professional education so as to staff hotels
and airlines with trained personnel.
 &HT;    ``I'm very optimistic. For the first time a new government is
appointing experienced professionals and not political supporters
to the government tourism agency,'' says Crededio. Previously, he
says, government officials charged with inspecting hotels ``had no
idea at all'' about the industry. Crededio says Venezuela could
boost the number of visitors from currently 700,000 per year to
around 3 million within five years.
 &HT;    Privatization could also bring in big investments, but the
Chavez government's commitment to the concept is unclear. Officials
have said that they do not oppose privatization, except for the
sale of PDVSA's domestic operations and those of hydroelectric
power company Edelca, which generates some 70 percent of the
country's electricity. His advisors say they are reviewing PDVSA's
foreign assets (except for the U.S. company Citgo) for possible
sale.
 &HT;    However, shortly after Chavez's election last December, the
Venezuelan government postponed the bidding for an electricity
distribution company in order ``to review the terms of the sale.''
Just how long the process remains suspended may be indicative of
the government's resolve.
 &HT;    The country's largely state-run power sector is dramatically
undercapitalized, plagued by red tape, corruption, and
inefficiency. Power shortages are common and extremely costly to
business and industry. According to one estimate, the industry
requires as much as $20 billion in capital investment over coming
years.
 &HT;    Even with the potentially important revenues from the sale of
oil and power assets, Chavez will have to create a positive
investment climate, particularly by setting clear rules of the
game, slashing red tape, and tackling corruption in the judiciary.
In a recent paper on economic guidelines for the new government,
the influential employers trade group, Federacion Venezolana de
Camaras y Asociaciones de Comercio y Produccion (Fedecamaras),
said, ``If the bureaucracy, which stimulates corruption, is cut
back to a minimum, and we have a state that facilitates instead of
complicates business, certainly the private sector will respond
with new initiatives creating jobs and wealth.''
 &HT;    Yet the plan to form a constituent assembly to rewrite the
Constitution raises the prospects of a prolonged period of
uncertainty. With a new Carta Magna, companies could face new rules
of the game. ``Until there is a new order, a new state, uncertainty
will be present in Venezuelan society,'' says retired general
Alberto Muller, Chavez's former campaign manager. In addition, it
will be difficult for the government to implement unpopular
austerity measures and sweeping market-oriented reform before the
new Constitution is approved.
 &HT;    As a result, private capital investment could remain on the
sidelines for some time to come. ``I don't expect private
investment to recover until at least the third or fourth quarter of
this year'', says one prominent economist in Caracas, who forecast
a decline of between 2 percent and 3 percent in gross domestic
product next year. ``Of course it could be much longer,'' he adds.
 &HT;    Few Venezuelan manufacturers anticipate significant economic
recovery in the near future. ``There won't be any expansion before
the year 2000. We will be happy to survive,'' says Henry Gomez,
head of the industry chamber, Federacion de Micros, Pequenos, y
Medianos Industriales de Venezuela (Fedeindustria).
 &HT;    The automobile industry expects sales of no more than 100,000
units this year, compared to the estimated 180,000 for 1998. ``It
is going to be a year of belt-tightening,'' says Alfredo Behrens,
head of Toyota de Venezuela.
 &HT;    Sacrificing 1999 may be worth it, if President Chavez can lay
the groundwork for a sustained recovery thereafter. In the past,
governments, such as that of former President Rafael Caldera, have
started out with a series of short-term policies that provide for
an initial boom, followed by a bust. Industry association head Ball
thinks Chavez is off to a good start. He says,'' If Chavez
continues along these lines, he could do things that president
Rafael Caldera could not.''
 &HT;    Others are less optimistic. ``It's not going to work. It's not
just the budget, it's a matter of philosophy. He is going to take
us back to a 1930s-style paternalist, populist government,'' says
Robert Bottome, head of Veneconomy consultancy.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
