<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     02-25 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Congress tries to buy enlistments
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not surprising that the Congress last week quickly and
overwhelmingly passed a healthy pay and benefits increase for our
people in the Armed Forces. Statistics showed that enlistments and
re-enlistments in the military were woefully low.
</P>
<P>
   It is reported that the branches of our military will need about
200,000 new enlistments this year alone _ and the chances of
achieving that are not good.
</P>
<P>
   But any thought that a slightly larger paycheck is going to get
a person to join, or one to re-up, is to miss the real point of why
so many are declining to remain: Someone could get killed out
there.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has become unbridled in its use of U.S. troops around
the world. After frosty experiences in Bosnia, our young men and
women in uniform now face the possibility of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we remain pitiably exposed in the Middle East,
exposed to germ warfare, missiles and terrorism. The Iraq situation
involves actual combat as well as jeopardy on a daily basis
</P>
<P>
   Being in the Army or the Navy isn't exactly as it is depicted in
those TV ads during football games. Indeed, you do see the world
and you can get a college education, but lately Army life has been
in full battle gear rather than on a day's leave or in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to detract from the fact that our military was
in need of, and had earned, those increased paychecks and benefits
from the government. With all those billions and billions of
dollars being devoted to pork, waste and mismanagement, what's
wrong with throwing a few billion into the hands of soldiers,
sailors, Marines and airmen?
</P>
<P>
   Our worldwide adventures in the guise of stopping communism,
dictators, drug dealers and warlords have exposed U.S. troops to
previously uncharted territories, and it has not always been
supported by the U.S. people.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers have little choice; they are sent.
</P>
<P>
   What choice they do have is to decide whether to re-enlist. As
President Clinton, without benefit of congressional approval, moves
his soldiers around the globe to put out what he considers to be
critical fires, the chances of major losses loom.
</P>
<P>
   Military spokesmen claim young men and women no longer think of
the military when planning careers, but let's be realistic: For a
great number of America's youth, joining the military is a way out
of a hard civilian life. Not all of us can become rocket
scientists, lawyers or presidents. So many join up. Or, rather,
many did join up.
</P>
<P>
   But with the authority of presidents to commit troops to foreign
conflicts, even over the protests of usually opposition-party
congressmen and women, the element of physical danger increases
dramatically. Eighteen-year-old kids do not savor the idea of
signing up to make themselves available for dangerous duty in a
desert half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   So intense was the Congress to pass this legislation that it
broke down all political and budgetary barriers. The few who
questioned the move did not do so in opposition to military pay
raises but did by questioning where the money was coming from.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about it, the protagonists insisted, we'll get it.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm certain they will, just as Ronald Reagan got all that
money to build up our military nearly two decades ago _ from a
money-printing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Money is not going to bloat our military ranks. What we really
need to question is why we need such a large military complement.
When do we stop being the world's policemen? What is the threat to
the U.S. by civil war action in Yugoslavia between ethnic Serbs and
Albanians?
</P>
<P>
   When youngsters join the service, they rarely think they are
going to be killed, yet when they step across the line at the
recruitment station, their lives do belong to someone else.
Soldiers should not be surprised, or disillusioned, if they are
sent off to war; that's why they're there in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   But what needs to be examined, also, is why we go off to so many
murky wars, so many that are not our wars. If we're really trying
to find out why enlistment and re-enlistment is down, the answer is
not in a paycheck; it's in our policy.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
