<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN SIDE OF HISTORIC HUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Feb. 15, 1851, Shadrach Minkins, an escaped slave new to
Boston, was waiting tables at a downtown coffeehouse when federal
marshals arrested him under the Fugitive Slave Act. He had fled
Norfolk, Va., about a year earlier, but a bounty hunter employed by
slaveholders had tracked him to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Later, while a large angry crowd of about 200 blacks gathered
outside the Custom House, then Boston's federal courthouse, a
smaller group of about 20 stormed the courtroom where Minkins was
being arraigned, overwhelmed two constables, and hustled him out of
the courtroom and eventually out of town to safety.
</P>
<P>
   While the Custom House survives _ as a timeshare resort _ you
won't find any mention of this dramatic piece of Boston history on
or near the building.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would anyone strolling past the Starbucks coffee shop on the
edge of City Hall Plaza, Boston's unintended monument to
brickmasons, have reason to suspect that they are on the site where
William Lloyd Garrison published The Abolitionist, the newspaper
that played a key role in rousing antislavery sentiments before the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of the Black Heritage Trail on Beacon Hill
_ a collection of 14 historic sites, almost all from the
abolitionist period _ Boston's critical role in the history of
black America has been, in many cases, little noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Even the honored history leaves something to be desired. The
Black Heritage Trail lacks any visible signage _ in stark contrast
to the Freedom Trail, whose signature bright red stripe can
scarcely be avoided by anyone walking downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Even less visible than sites on the Black Heritage Trail is
black history from the period after the Civil War. While Boston is
a city sometimes obsessed with its history, much history of black
Boston is a story that remains largely invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of the city's sense of history is shaped by its
role as the birthplace of the American Revolution, its preserved
past is heavily dominated by sites from the Colonial and
Revolutionary period.
</P>
<P>
   That has been a source of pain, and complaint, for many of the
groups that have arrived in the city since, or whose early
contributions often went unacknowledged: African-Americans, after
all, trace their history in Boston back to the 1630s.
</P>
<P>
   The missing pieces range from such sites as the Abolitionist
office to the site that housed Columbus Avenue AME Church on
Columbus Avenue, to many sites in lower Roxbury that formed the
epicenter of black community life as blacks migrated from Beacon
Hill to the South End to lower Roxbury around the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   The truncated preservation of black history owes something to a
debate that occurred when the Black Heritage Trail was being
established in 1976: whether to attempt to commemorate sites that
no longer exist in their original form, or to limit the trail to
sites that people could actually visit.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when much history is absorbed via loudspeakers on tour
buses, it was no contest. Only places that still existed in
historically recognizable form made the list, and only sites from
the period when the black community lived on Beacon Hill _ even
though most black families were priced out of there after the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, at least two important efforts are now underway to
promote more recent history of Boston's people of color.
</P>
<P>
   The most original and interesting of those is MYTOWN
(Multicultural Youth Tour of What's Now). That group trains
minority high school students to conduct walking tours of the South
End and lower Roxbury for tourists, introducing them to the history
of their people in Boston and promoting, its organizers hope, a
greater sense of belonging.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Boston History Collaborative, which recently
inaugurated a successful Literary Trail of Greater Boston, is also
planning an ``Abolition to Civil Rights'' project that would
encompass the history of black Bostonians after the period focused
on by the Heritage Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Both those efforts can only be an asset in encouraging
Bostonians of all backgrounds to embrace the full scope of the
city's history. Boston's history, after all, did not end with the
Revolution or the Civil War. It is only stubborn habit that leads
us to treat it as if it did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
