<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-25 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAT RATE PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are fast approaching flat-rate telephone service. To some
extent, we're already there; MCI-WorldCom offers 5-cent Sundays,
AT&AMP;T offers ``one rate'' service, Sprint spins its famous dime. For
the moment, these offers are about minutes. In the near future,
they will be about months.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Three major forces are at work. The first is technology.
Not so long ago, there was only one way to make a local or long
distance phone call. For simplicity's sake, call it the Bell
Telephone method. In the near future, there will be as many as five
other ways to make that same phone call; over the Internet, over
cable television lines, over electricity lines and across two
already extant wireless systems (cellular and digital).
</P>
<P>
   The technology exists to make all these alternatives available
in less than five years. And major telecommunications corporations
are gearing up to do just that. AT&AMP;T bought TCI (the cable
television behemoth) for this reason (among others). AOL acquired
Teleport in anticipation of Internet telephony. US West acquired
Continental Cablevision and formed Mediaone, which is rolling out
local telephone service in Massachusetts this year. Bell Atlantic
will soon buy more cellular and digital telephone networks for its
system. The list goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   These corporate conglomerations are made possible by
deregulation, which is the second reason that the cost of phone
service will soon be packaged into a flat-rate fee. Deregulation of
telecommunications services ensures that competition for your
business will escalate as more and more providers enter the market.
</P>
<P>
   Different companies approach the deregulated marketplace in
different ways. AT&AMP;T dreams of the day when you will use its
products seamlessly. You will use AT&AMP;T World Net for Internet
access, you will use AT&AMP;T for long distance and local telephone
service, you will use AT&AMP;T wireless service for mobile and you will
use AT&AMP;T paging and messaging services just to be safe. In
addition, AT&AMP;T will likely offer GPS positioning technology, so
that you will be able to know where your kids are, exactly, at any
given moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has a slightly different game plan, as does WorldCom MCI,
as do the Regional Bell Operating Companies. Bell Atlantic
desperately wants to break into the Northeast corridor long
distance market, so that it can offer its ``local'' customers a
full array of telecommunications services. SBC Corp. last year
acquired Ameritech (having gobbled up Pacific Telesis before that)
in a bid to become, essentially, Ma Bell with a few regions of the
country missing.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation has transformed telephony from a regulated utility
business into a commodity business. In the not so distant future,
supply of telecommunications services will outstrip demand, causing
the price of the commodity to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the third and perhaps most important reason
that telephone service will soon be a flat-rate product: Wall
Street. Wall Street is wildly enthusiastic about the future of
telecommunications and more than willing to overlook short-term
problems (like lower revenues from reduced phone bills). Wall
Street, in fact, encourages telecommunications executives to cut
prices for its services, on the theory that the service itself is a
kind of loss-leader. The real money to be made is in the customer
data-base.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T has 60 million customers using the full range of its
telecommunications services, then it has a database whose value far
exceeds the value of the actual service it provides. And if AT&AMP;T
offers what Wall Street calls ``discounts for data,'' the value of
that database increases exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discounts for data'' is a simple trade between you and your
telecommunications provider. In return for flat-rate service (say,
$40 for all local and long distance, or $55 for all Internet,
local, long distance and paging), you fill out a detailed
questionnaire revealing your basic demographic information as well
as your interests, preferences, habits and the like. This data can
then be sold to companies who have products that may be useful to
you.
</P>
<P>
   This basic trade already happens on the Internet. Yahoo and
Excite offer free e-mail in exchange for the data they glean about
you from how you use their sites. Now that technology has
commoditized the phone business, ``discounts for data'' deals will
soon be a standard feature of telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   How low can the cost of telephone service go? There are many
people in the high-tech world who believe that it will drop to
zero; the ultimate loss-leader. That probably won't occur, but it's
not out of the question. Whatever happens, it is certain that the
``one rate'' plans of the future will be calculated not in minutes,
but in months and years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
