<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-25 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM IMPERFECT KITTENS TO WHEN TO MENTION SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time, this column answers selected readers'
questions. Please send yours to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; fax 617-929-2813 or e-mail
meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our cat had a litter of kittens, including one born with
clubfoot. No one will adopt it. Since this kitten is not really
sick but has a deformity that keeps it from walking, my instinct is
to put it to sleep. But how do I tell that to my kids, 10 and 8?
Should we keep it, even though that doesn't seem like a good
solution for the kitten? I want my children to be sensitive but not
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   A. You're right to sense this is a tricky issue; whatever you do
sends a message to your children about how much you, and by
extension society, value living things when they are less than
perfect. But there are more options available than you may realize,
according to educator Judith A. Skretny of Life Transitions Center
in Buffalo, N.Y. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   --Surgery. Although costly, surgical repair has been known to be
successful for cats with clubfoot.
</P>
<P>
   --Adaption. A kitten may need help getting around, but grown
cats are often able to lead active lives with just three legs by
learning to compensate for the disability.
</P>
<P>
   --Adoption. Skretny suggests trying to find an adoptive family
by working through your vet or a local animal rescue league. ``Many
people will take a disabled pet,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, include your children in conversation about the
choices, although don't leave the ultimate decision to them.
``That's too much responsibility for children of any age,
especially if you are considering euthanasia,'' says Skretny, who
lectures nationally on death and dying with the American Academy of
Bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   Because children have great affinity to animals, they may opt to
keep it without realizing the effort that entails. Include a visit
and discussion with the vet with the kids and the kitten before you
finalize a decision. If they want surgery, for instance, the vet
can give you an idea of the cost and recovery. Then a discussion
for your family may include ways in which the children can earn
money to help pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are so many options for this kitten, Skretny does
not advocate killing it. ``Do you euthanize something just because
it's imperfect?'' she asks. She notes this is very different from a
decision a family must make when an older, sick or infirm, and much
beloved pet needs to be put down. (Look for a fuller discussion of
this in a future Child Caring column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We found your recent column against spanking (Feb. 4) very
helpful, especially what you said about matching expectations to a
child's temperament and stage of development. Can you give us ideas
about how to keep our Mother's Day celebration from turning into a
disaster? My mother-in-law is coming from Michigan. We want to take
her someplace special but our son, who is 5, doesn't do well in
restaurants (he's very physical and active) and we usually end up
angry and exasperated. We've spanked once, and it was over his
behavior in a public place.
</P>
<P>
   A. Matching expectations to temperament and development means
not expecting more from a child than he is capable of, so you're
right to worry that a meal in a fancy restaurant might be a
disaster with a 5-year-old who has a hard time sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you can't do it, though. By feeding into his
strengths, you might be able to take preventive measures to make
this meal _ or any similar situation _ work, says Roni Leiderman, a
psychologist in Fort Lauderdale and director of the Family Center
at Nova Southeastern University there.
</P>
<P>
   It will take effort, however. A few days beforehand, talk about
the event and give him some idea of what to expect: ``Since Grandma
is coming all the way from Michigan, we want to do something
special for Mother's Day. We're thinking about taking her to a
fancy restaurant.'' Describe in detail what makes this restaurant
different from others he's been to: ``It's very quiet in this
restaurant, not like McDonald's where you can talk loudly.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, show him that you understand what makes him
tick and that you're going to help him manage: ``We know how hard
it is for a boy your age to sit still for a long time, so we'll
bring some surprise activities that will be fun for you to do right
there at the restaurant table.'' Does your child have some
interests that hold his attention? Dinosaurs? Pirates? Find a new
book, bring along markers and paper and other activities. The more
options you have, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, pay close attention. ``Heading off a meltdown
depends on reading cues before he falls apart, so he never gets to
the end of his rope,'' says Leiderman. Sometimes that means leaving
the restaurant altogether but it can also mean providing a break in
the activity when he first gets antsy. Take him outside for a walk
around the block or something else physical. Make a game of it;
this shouldn't be punitive.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, says Leiderman, be sure to reinforce good behavior:
``What a good job you're doing of sitting still at the table!'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 10-year-old son is not showing any interest in things
sexual but many of his friends are. Should I wait for him to bring
up the subject of sex before I give him some books about it? What
books would you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   A. Absolutely don't wait for him to bring it up, says Debra
Haffner, president of SIECUS (Sexuality, Information and Education
Council of the U.S.). You could wait forever, because so many kids
are too embarrassed or intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for the teachable moment,'' says Haffner. It could be
anything, from lyrics to a song on the radio _ ``What do you think
about what that song says about girls?'' _ to seeing a pregnant
woman in the store: ``Seeing that woman makes me think you're old
enough to wonder about these things. Do you have any questions
about how a woman gets pregnant?'' Conversations don't need to be
long or involved, shouldn't be lectures, but should offer
opportunity for your child to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   Three books Haffner recommends:
</P>
<P>
   --``It's Perfectly Normal: Changing Bodies, Sex and Sexual
Health,'' by Robie H. Harris (1994, Penguin).
</P>
<P>
   --``The `What's Happening to My Body?' for Girls/for Boys,'' by
Lynda Madaras (l993) Newmarket Press.
</P>
<P>
   Preface giving a book by saying, ``I notice some of your friends
are going through puberty and you will, too, soon. I hope you look
at these books when you have some questions, and that you'll feel
free to ask me any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Haffner reminds that sex education happens little by little.
``It's not a conversation you only have once,'' she says. SIECUS
has a Web site (www.siecus.org) where parents can pose questions
that will be answered by professionals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your article on disappointment (Feb. 11) hit home big time
for us. Our child is applying to private school (third grade) for
the first time. What advice do you have about preparing her for the
potential disappointment of not getting in?
</P>
<P>
   A. How disappointed she will or won't be depends largely on you,
says educator Janine Bempechat of Harvard Graduate School of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Before you hear from the school, ``Keep your own anxiety in
check,'' she says. Talk about it as an interesting option you may
or may not want to do even if she gets accepted: ``They get to
decide if they have enough room for you to go, and we get to decide
if that's what we want.'' Keep comparisons of her present school to
a minimum: ``Just because we're applying doesn't mean we don't like
your school now. We do; each school has advantages. Mostly, we like
the idea of having choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't over-talk about it. ``At this age,'' Bempechat says,
``there's no reason to get into the concept that selections are
based on how smart a child is. Even if a third-grader senses that's
part of it, they don't know it in the same way an older child does,
and they certainly don't attach any significance to it, in terms of
the future.'' If she doesn't get in, Bempechat urges a
matter-of-fact approach: ``There wasn't enough room this year. If
you really liked it, we can try again next year, if you want.''
</P>
<P>
   For older kids, it's harder. ``By sixth grade, they know it's
based on qualifications,'' says Bempechat, who is author of
``Against All Odds: How `At-Risk' Students Exceed Expectations''
(Jossey-Bass). For their parents, her advice is to downplay the
smartness factor: `` `You throw your hat into the ring and it
depends on who else is applying at the same time. If you don't get
in, it's not necessarily that you weren't smart enough, but that
other kids were just as smart and the school values something they
have that you don't, like a musical talent.'''
</P>
<P>
   With a disappointment like this, Bempechat urges talking about
the life lesson to be learned: Wherever you are in life, there are
people who do better than you and some who do worse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ In response to the recent column on spanking,
Parents Anonymous of Massachusetts writes: ``We're here for parents
who feel isolated, overwhelmed or afraid of the anger they feel
toward a child.'' For information about PA's network of support
groups, call 800-882-1250. For the 24-hour parental stress line,
call 800-632-8188.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores.)
</P>
