<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DESIGNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHEER DELIGHT OF BEING FABRIC ARTIST PETER FASANO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. _ Designer Peter Fasano, his
paint-smeared sweatshirt a Niagara of colors, walks a bolt of sheer
linen fabric over to a glass door. He unfurls an armful of the
material till the sunlight plays through it, leaving the design _
an opulent arabesque of leaves _ in silhouette. Then he &UR;  &LR; walks the
linen back to a long worktable and spreads it out. What was sheer
in the design is now opaque. What was airy is now static. What had
flirted with the outdoors will seal it off. Fasano strokes the
pattern flat so it reveals bits of gold paint riding the curves.
This same bolt of linen is now the stuff of formal interiors, a bit
dulled under artificial light, mannerly but not heavy. Fasano
grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheers,'' he says, ``are always changing with the light.'' The
grin becomes a laugh. ``Sheers are the chameleons of curtains.''
</P>
<P>
   Fasano designs wallpapers and material for curtains. Leading
decorators seek him out for their hush-hush clients _ a CEO in Napa
Valley, a country club in Kentucky Bluegrass Country, tax exiles in
Florida. With a small crew, Fasano produces all he designs, mostly
by the silk-screen process. But what he likes doing best is to
paint directly on fabric. An hour in his company is to know the
delights of the unexpected. He loves telling about the happy
accident. He's got tales about the suggestion someone else made,
which made his design that much better. He adds motifs: Monkeys
acquire palm trees. He subtracts: Lose the flower but keep the
plaid. He inserts: Rivers of color flow between columns of black
knots. He borrows: That grid of little white dots ought to remind
you of the penny candy you peel from shiny paper. That's where he
got the idea. The difference: ``No paper in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started in New York City in 1972, where Fasano moved
after his Vietnam service. The GI Bill had paid his tuition at
Parsons School of Design, but life wasn't all window treatments and
shag carpeting. With Kent State and Vietnam on their minds, a lot
of young people like Fasano were caught up in various movements to
cure society's ills. ``We were very environmentally conscious at
Parsons, especially David Easton, who was an interior designer for
Parrish/Hadley,'' Fasano recalled in an interview the other day.
The idea was to see if changing bad environments through good
design would help. ``I worked on designing prisons and mental
hospitals. I wanted to see if good three-dimensional design would
lower the rate of recidivism.'' But the difference between a
well-presented student thesis and testable results is money.
``There was just never any money around to see if we were right,''
Fasano says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He had to support himself, and a Parsons degree was entree to
the likes of decorator Dorothy Draper. But after a year-and-a-half
of cosseting her clients, Fasano found out interior design wasn't
for him. He still had a few dollars left from the GI Bill, so he
went to the Art Students League in New York. He'd always known he
liked working on surfaces. Now he tacked a canvas square, 6 feet by
6, to the floor of his Manhattan loft and let the paint talk. ``I
loved this more than life itself,'' he says. Patterns were his
thing. ``I was a pattern painter before the word existed.'' His
timing was good. Minimalism was just coming in. The buzz names were
Agnes Martin and Eva Hesse. Abstract Expressionism also grabbed
Fasano. He had a new war to fight, pitting the spatter curves of
Jackson Pollock against the straight edges of Kenneth Nolan. What
was happening in the art galleries was not lost on a decorator like
Albert Hadley. He began using painted fabrics for interiors, some
designed by Fasano, and Fasano's future was secure.
</P>
<P>
   He was lucky. His talent for pattern might have doomed him to a
career in fashion designing scarves. But he saw that as a dead end.
``Fashion changes every two months. They want it `Monday,' and they
want it in thousands of yards. Then you've got to top that. Fabric
designed for interiors has a much longer life. You can design from
a point of view. Your ideas can evolve.''
</P>
<P>
   So Fasano spent a couple of very happy years living in a cheap
uptown loft in the Carnegie Hill section of Manhattan painting in
the mornings and designing in the afternoons. About this time,
Elizabeth Hamilton, the woman who would become his wife, was
walking her blonde good looks through Grand Central Station and a
spy from Glamour asked if she'd like to model for the magazine. So
she did that till she fell in love with word processing. She was so
good at teaching herself she went into a career teaching others.
``She'd much rather read a computer manual than see herself in a
magazine,'' says her husband fondly. In 1982, when the stock market
began going up, Fasano laid down his paintbrushes and went full
time into fabric painting. He worked at home on an 18-yard table of
his own design. The stuff was free form _ silk-screening would come
later _ and he would turn out 5,000 to 8,000 yards a year. The
actress Dina Merrill loved one particular spatter print so much
that 15 years later when it began to look a little tired she asked
Fasano to duplicate it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a master plan,'' says Fasano, ``and I still
don't. We operate by controlled anarchy.'' You wouldn't guess that
from the tranquil order of his studio workshop just south of the
Great Barrington fairgrounds, where on a half-mile track slow
horses will always beat slower horses and the old town, despite the
gentrification of the main drag, delights Fasano for its ``perfect
mix of blue collar and white collar.'' He and Hamilton moved here
in June 1990 with their son, Nicolas, now 12. ``We thought it would
be fun to live in the country,'' Fasano says. They had known the
Connecticut foothills of the Berkshires from visits to friends.
Moving from Manhattan was ``not the culture shock you might
expect,'' Hamilton says. She had grown up in Milton and Orleans.
``We're New Englanders at heart,'' says her husband.
</P>
<P>
   And with Great Barrington came the discovery of golf. It's
Fasano's other passion. Also a sudden reminder of his own
mortality. He drops the name of Tiger Woods, actually Woods's
decorator ``who's a good friend,'' and then says: ``I'm probably 30
years older than Tiger Woods and for the first time in my life I
realize I'm not going to see his entire career. I'll be dead not
knowing the end of his story.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first six years in Great Barrington, Fasano worked at
home. More studio than house, he suggests. Then an old mill
building right on Route 7 became available. Fasano built onto the
footprint and could finally move his four 32-yard-long worktables
into an evironmentally friendly shop. Other designers tease him it
doesn't stink like a print works. In part, he says, because the
acrylics in those hundreds of mustard-squeeze bottles they use to
paint with is all water-based.
</P>
<P>
   One day a month Fasano is on the road visiting one of the 15
decorator showrooms that ``rep'' (represent) him by carrying his
fabrics and wallpapers for the delectation of interior designers.
At the Boston Design Center, it's David Webster of Webster &AMP; Co.
Ltd. Fasano's sheers retail for about $40 a yard, printed canvas
about $80, and painted tafetta about $90. Wallpapers are about $65
a roll. Webster likes Fasano for his colors and textures, his
patterns (checkerboards, stripes, grids), and his ``creative funky
look.'' One popular print even dares to co-opt that awesome symbol
of atomic power, a nucleus with orbiting electrons, and by
miniaturizing it makes you smile. There's no one Fasano customer,
Webster insists. ``Well, his stuff does go very well with painted
furniture, with things that are not terribly serious.''
</P>
<P>
   But most days, Fasano is to be found on the floor of his shop
and Hamilton in the little corner office seeing to the business
end. Their old dog, a black Lab/coon hound mix named Calvin, lies
in the doorway. Fasano does of course have a business strategy and
that is to stay flexible. He can turn out goods by the hundreds of
yards. But he's also one of the few who can, and will gladly, fill
an order for a minimum of 10 yards. And, yes, like the fashion
industry, they do want it ``Monday.'' Fasano relishes telling about
a recent order that reached him on a Tuesday, was designed and
faxed the next day, produced on Thursday, and samples shipped FedEx
before Friday noon. Sprints like these keep Fasano and his crew on
their toes. He thinks variety makes for a happy shop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning, two men walked a paint trough slowly over a
table-length of raw silk from China, coloring it a warm beige
called Wedgwood Drab. A few years ago, Fasano could silk-screen his
popular monkey print called Coconut Grove right on this drab. Then
the silk started arriving lighter in shade. Did the silkworm diet
change? Fasano doesn't know. Another shop might choose to dye the
fabric. Fasano always prefers paint. Paint, he says, sits on the
surface, plays with light, sets the picture off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coconut Grove is a huge seller for us. Very popular in Florida
but not in Hawaii where they don't seem to like monkeys.'' The
print is appealing, the monkeys sweet without being cartoonish.
``If you can get people to smile, you've won them over,'' says
Fasano. It takes four separate screenings to bring Coconut Grove to
life. Most people will see only the little brown monkeys and their
perky palm trees. But Fasano also screens on other bits of flora
and fauna, red here, yellow there. If they register at all on the
customer it will be for their throwaway whimsy. But the designer
knows they serve a more serious purpose, and that is to make the
pattern dance. The last step requires the business end of a
squeegee dipped in brown paint. Daub-daub, goes the squeegee.
Daub-daub-daub. From each of the palm trees now hang two or three
hand-painted coconuts. If silk-screened, these would lie flat. But
the paint has set up another, competing rhythm _ ``real'' fruit in
an imaginary jungle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
