<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSPEAKING WORDS OF WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston broadcaster David Brudnoy notwithstanding, it's always
Celtic with a soft C, says Charles Harrington Elster. On this side
of the Atlantic it's never Keltic, unless it's spelled that way, as
in Keltic Krust bakery (in Newton, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   Brudnoy enjoys twitting sports fans with the hard C version of
Celtics. According to Elster, this makes the talk show host
something of a quodlibetarian, ``a pedantic blowhard who engages in
elaborate arguments about theoretical fine points.'' Elster should
know. He says he's a quodlibetarian himself.
</P>
<P>
   Elster's new book, ``The Beastly Big Book of
Mispronunciations,'' sheds light upon the American pronunciation of
hundreds of words. It's not meant to be read straight through,
Elster said from his home in San Diego, but used as a reference and
argument-settler _ or argument-starter. His opinions about the word
``aunt'' are fighting words in this part of the world. He says the
only proper pronunciation is ``ant.'' Obviously he doesn't know
everything.
</P>
<P>
   His book, however, is engaging enough to invite front-to-back
reading because Elster is such a captivating writer, armed with a
seemingly endless store of language-related trivia and a host of
violent opinions. His fulminations are marvelous. For instance he
writes that the pervasive mispronunciation of the word bulimia
(correctly ``byoo-LIM-ee-uh'') ``proves yet again that human
stupidity is rampant at all levels of speech, from the most
ignorant, beastly mispronouncer to the most erudite, self-important
egghead. What is wrong with everybody, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   On the phone Elster seems less fierce than he does on the page,
even willing to concede that in certain cases, popular usage has
superseded correct pronunciation. Take the word grimace, for
example. ``I am probably the only person in America who pronounces
it gri-MACE,'' he said. ``The MACE should rhyme with place.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimace is one of several words Elster says he's just about
given up on. Bulimia is another. Loath _ rhymes with both _ is a
problem too because so many people confuse its meaning (unwilling)
and pronunciation with loathe (to hate). Lingerie, he says, is a
lost cause. ``When I pronounce it correctly, lan-zhe-REE, people
don't know what I'm talking about. So now I say `women's
underwear.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Elster's book is instructive, unless you're an omnierudite
pedant. I stand corrected about any number of words. Mauve, for
example. It's always been ``mahwv'' to me, but the correct
pronunciation rhymes with stove. That's a fairly common mistake,
Elster said, because people assume mauve and suave should sound
alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Book of Beastly Mispronunciations'' includes plenty of
examples of why it should be a required reference for anyone who
speaks before the public. Elster monitors radio and television for
beastly mispronunciations by those who should know better. He's
rounded up some humdingers. Dan Rather incorrectly stressing
``spy'' in respiratory (correctly ``RES-pur-uh-TOR-ee''). Sister
Wendy, ``public TV's winsome, wimpled art critic,'' wrongly
stressing the second syllable of Medici, instead of the first
(correctly ``MED-i-chee''). A number of public figures saying
``nucular'' instead of nuclear, or in President Carter's case,
``noo-kee-ur.'' Former congressman William Dannemeyer's pronouncing
``anal'' as if it rhymes with channel. Elster even catches The New
York Times language expert William Safire stumbling, pronouncing
chimera as ``shimmera.'' (it's ``ky-MEER-uh'' or ``ki-MEER-uh''.)
</P>
<P>
   Elster and Richard Lederer, author of ``Crazy English'' and
other popular books about language, cohost a call-in program, ``A
Way With Words,'' on the San Diego public radio station. Elster
says they have hopes of syndication, someday, maybe someday soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
