<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY OF WAXING AND WANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been trying to wax my kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   I know that millions of women accomplish this task every day
without trauma. It doesn't take extraordinary intelligence, or
unusual persistence, or superhuman strength. It's a simple act of
physical labor.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   I started yesterday. I actually had my cleaning lady wash the
floor so I had only to finish what she started. All I had to do was
spread the wax on the cork tiles with a sponge. Right? Not miss any
spots. OK, I can do that. Keep the dog from stepping on the floor
while it was wet. Duh.
</P>
<P>
   How hard could it be?
</P>
<P>
   I lifted up the throw rugs I had secured to the floor with
double-sided tape. What a mess! It was sticky and yucky, spatula-
and Brillo-resistant. No cleaning product I had made even a dent.
After my efforts, the glue was also hairy and caked with foam. I
headed out to the hardware store to get advice. Because I'm trying
to be well-organized, before I went I checked to see that I had a
decent mop and a can of liquid wax. Stupidly, I congratulated
myself on my ability to think ahead. I came back from the store
with a bottle of Goo Gone and after 30 minutes of pouring, waiting,
and scrubbing, the floor was smooth and clean.
</P>
<P>
   I squirted wax on the floor, noticing for the first time that
the can was only one-third full. Oh-oh, I'd have to get more. I
mopped with the waxer, noticing for the first time that one of the
screws was loose, making the sponge wiggle out of alignment. Oh-oh,
I'd have to fix that.
</P>
<P>
   I went to my husband's workroom, looking for a nut that would
fit on a plastic protuberance. Three coffee cans of screws and nuts
and bolts later, I acknowledged it was hopeless. I'd have to run
out to the store again, but my pocketbook was on the window seat
and yes, I'd waxed the floor in front of it. Five long minutes
later, I set off into the night.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware store was closed.
</P>
<P>
   I began again the next morning, having purchased adequate tools.
The first coat was beautiful, but halfway through the second coat,
the wax looked milky in spots. Reading the label, I realized I'd
shaken the new can when the instructions said, ``For the smoothest
shine and best results, do not shake.'' I reeled with the thought
that I might have to spend the rest of the day removing the wax I'd
just applied. All I could do was hope the cloudiness would
disappear when the wax dried. I waited on the unwaxed portion of
the kitchen floor, my fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Then I noticed tiny spots of paint the grandkids had gotten on
the lower kitchen cabinets. The upper ones weren't that spotless,
either. How come I hadn't seen the cobwebs behind the chest in the
corner? When did that grime on the radiators arrive? I saw a light
smudge on one painted wall. I observed the scuff marks under the
window seat. I got down on my hands and knees and at floor level
peered in all four directions.
</P>
<P>
   I got up, wishing I hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   I could feel the compulsion to make everything perfect coming
on, the way it always does when I start to clean. Suddenly my brain
awakens and I'm no longer blind to the chaos engulfing me. I knew
if I opened the refrigerator and looked in, my eyes would be
offended. I knew if I opened my silverware drawer, my stomach would
turn. I wanted to scrub the tile behind the stove with a
toothbrush, pull out a can of paint and freshen the woodwork, run
outside and wash my windows.
</P>
<P>
   I was, of course, also afraid I'd do what I usually do when I'm
overwhelmed by housework _ go upstairs and read a book.
</P>
<P>
   I looked down at the floor. The wax had dried to a clear glossy
finish. I wanted to shout with joy. I wanted to kiss the dog, who
was outside whining pitifully, having been put on her run for a
crime she hadn't yet committed. No matter. The floor was gleaming.
I had rubber mats to slip under the rugs. For the next two hours, I
scrubbed and wiped and polished and organized until the kitchen
looked passable, even to me.
</P>
<P>
   By the time my husband came home, I had no energy left to make
dinner. Jack volunteered to make lamb chops, but as he lifted them
out of the oven, the practical joker who sneers at all my attempts
to create order in my life, knocked the sizzling broiler pan out of
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   On. To. My. Newly. Waxed. Floor.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. I'll. Do. It. Again. Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
