<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-IRISES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISES ARE AS SUBLIME AS THEY ARE TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irises are elegance. Their swordlike leaves serve as season-long
architectural elements in the border. Their relatively short-lived
flowers are sublime.
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly why I grow some. (Also, they are named for
Iris, the goddess of the rainbow, as is my mom.) Another reason I
grow them is that their 200 species include some of the easiest to
grow perennials, especially the Siberians. These are beardless,
which means their falls are not well-fuzzed or furry. The falls are
the three sepals, petal-like structures, which tend to droop. The
standards are the three petals, which are upright.
</P>
<P>
   Before buying my first Siberian iris, I consulted Wyman's
Gardening Encyclopedia, whose iris entry was written by Beatrice
Clark Warburton, the noted iris authority and hybridizer. She
wrote: ``The Siberian group of garden iris is the most dependable
of all iris types. They will grow whereever any iris may be grown,
without any particular care, and offer a choice of plants with
robust manners or with more delicate ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Schafer of Carlisle, Mass. also consulted ``Bee''
Warburton, but he did it directly and came away with the stock with
which he began an ambitious Siberian iris breeding program.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer got into gardening in 1980 when, while ``courting my
girl,'' he and she were given a box of vegetable and flower seeds
by one of her roommates, who happened to be a seed salesman. (More
proof that life is a mysterious circle.) The seeds were old, so
mainly flowers came up. ``We became hooked on flowers'' and, later,
irises in particular, he told me recently. Today, Schafer and the
woman he courted, Jan Sacks, grow flowers for the wholesale
cut-flower market and hybridize Siberian irises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something about irises that really excited me,''
especially Siberians, Schafer explained. ``They're very adapted to
New England. They're tough, and they don't rot. They go dormant in
winter, which most bearded irises don't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Siberians will take a bit of shade and withstand some drought,
which is what won me over. Well, maybe it was the new pastels,
outstanding flowers, on the market now. Growing next to
tradescantia and Campanula carpatica I have `Orville Fay' (blue,
darker veins), `Lavender Bounty' (lavender falls, lighter
standards, early), and `Butter &AMP; Sugar' (butter yellow, white
standards).
</P>
<P>
   Schafer and Sacks have gone far beyond those and, so far,
through their Joe Pye Weed's Garden, have introduced 26 Siberian
hybrids to the market. They introduced one a year for the first
four years, then two a year for a while, and last year 10. ``I had
a really good year in 1992,'' Schafer said. ``We planted out 8,000
seedlings.''
</P>
<P>
   Schafer does the pollinating, Sacks does the photography, and
they share the other duties. Pollinating is done in June, and seeds
are collected, labeled, and dried in August. The seeds are planted
in October and early November, and they germinate the following
April or early May. About 10 percent flower the first year.
Hybridizing is a long-term affair.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer is pursuing five goals, three color-related: true blues,
true yellows, and combinations known as overlays. He has been using
yellow ``as a tool to pry new things out of the old colors.'' The
pigments are different substances in different areas of the plant,
so they don't mix like paints but are, rather, more like the
separate tiny dots of color in pointillist paintings, such as those
by Seurat. In fact, Schafer said, under a microscope, iris tissues
appear to have small bodies of color suspended in white, but in
normal view, the dots merge into solid color.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer's fourth goal is fragrance. Irises are not known for
fragrance, but there is some, here and there, and Schafer is trying
to develop that, to strengthen it. What do his fragrant Siberians
smell like? Oranges, he said, and while they may never fill a room
with scent the way jasmines do, his hybrids may someday reward us
garden browsers who tend to shove our snouts into such beautiful
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Schafer is intrigued by the iris styles, which are the
stalks arising from the ovaries and holding the stigmas. Schafer
has been breeding them to be more petal-like, smooth, colorful,
pretty in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pye Weed's Garden is 2 1/2 acres, 1 acre of field-grown
plants, ``and otherwise there's just gardens everywhere.'' (It is
not a nursery open to the public; plants are sold by mail order
from a catalog, available for $2, 337 Acton St., Carlisle, MA
01741.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real neat place we have,'' Schafer said, with lots of
``wonderful rocks here, lichen-encrusted rocks, the bones of New
England sticking up all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Schafer, who is finishing a term as president of the Iris
Society of Massachusetts, clearly recognizes beauty, but then, he
is from a musical family, and his training is in dance and theater.
In his breeding program, he follows his instincts and the plants
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interaction between the plant and the hybridizer,'' he
said. ``It's just amazing where the flowers will lead you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
