<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL REPORT &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SOUP-KITCHENS-I (Peekskill, N.Y.) _ A stream of low-wage
workers, retirees and refugees from public-assistance are swelling
the lines at soup kitchens and food pantries across America. Some
are the welfare-to-work versions of an old phenomenon: the working
poor caught in the middle _ too well off for public assistance but
not well enough off to make it on their own. Some are immigrants
who are here legally but were cut off from food stamps under new
federal welfare laws. Some are following a path of least
resistance: rather than jump through hoops designed to tarnish the
appeal of public aid, they are turning to private charities.
Together, they are changing the face of food lines long occupied by
the addicted, the disabled, the generally down-and-out. And they
may help explain a puzzle confronting poverty analysts: Why have
the lines kept growing when unemployment is at its lowest level in
a generation and the economy has remained healthy for years? By
Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (3000 words with an abridged version of about 1500 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (First of two articles. The second looks at the supply side and
the increasing difficulty churches and other groups have in reeling
in the grocery industry's castoffs.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-TAPES (Washington) _ The last of the ``abuse of power''
tapes from the Nixon White House _ 124 conversations previously
classified on national-security grounds _ are made public, after 25
years of lawsuits by Nixon and his estate. They include
conversations about the CIA, the Bay of Pigs debacle, the
assassination of South Vietnam's President Diem, the 1971
India-Pakistan war, the ``Huston plan'' for spying on Americans and
many other nuggets from the Nixon era. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-RECONCILE (Washington) _ Two senators _ Brownback and
Lieberman _ scheduled a reconciliation meeting at which they hoped,
with the help of rabbis, chaplains and a choir, to get beyond the
divisions and differences between the parties. Unfortunately, only
six senators showed up. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Tucson, Ariz.) _ President Clinton speaks on Social
Security, Medicare. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-HEALTH-WORKERS (Los Angeles ) _ In the biggest single
unionization vote since workers at Ford's River Rouge plant joined
the UAW in 1941, 75,000 home health-care workers are voting today
on whether to join the Service Employees International Union. The
organizing drive reflects labor's new emphasis on low wage,
minority workers. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISESHIP-DUMPING (Undated) _ A federal grand jury in Los
Angeles has indicted Royal Caribbean for at-sea dumping from 1994.
By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EXTRADITE (Jerusalem) _ Ruling in a case that has
strained U.S.-Israeli relations, Israel's Supreme Court today
blocked the extradition to the United States of Samuel Sheinbein,
an 18-year-old wanted on murder charges in Maryland. Sheinbein will
instead face a murder trial in Israel. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-PHONES (Miami) _ For political reasons, Cuba cut off phone
service from the U.S. mainland today. Phone companies are now
rerouting calls through other countries.
</P>
