<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-NIEDECKEN-BOS &LR;      02-25 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-NIEDECKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNER NIEDECKEN SHARES THE PEDESTAL WITH WRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone's heard of Frank Lloyd Wright, the greatest of American
architects, as much a legend for his epic ego as for his
revolutionary designs.
</P>
<P>
   But George Mann Niedecken? The name is likely to generate a
response of ``Who?'' among all but connoisseurs of what went inside
Wright's Prairie Style houses.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Robertson aims to fix that. She's raising the profile of
Niedecken, a muralist, interior decorator, and designer of
furniture, lighting fixtures, and carpets, through a new exhibition
she's organized, ``Designing in the Wright Style: Furniture and
Interiors by Frank Lloyd Wright and George Mann Niedecken,'' at the
Museum of Our National Heritage. She's uniquely qualified to act as
Niedecken's champion. He was born in Milwaukee in 1878, died there
in 1945, and based his business there; she, until her 1996 move to
Lexington, was a curator at the Milwaukee Art Museum, where, while
riffling through the archives, she discovered the Niedecken
documents that eventually led to her 1981 retrospective of his work
at that institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intent is not to knock Wright off his pedestal,'' she says
in the fine catalog of her show, ``but rather to include others,
Niedecken as well as (Wright affiliate) Marion Mahony among them,
on it or close by.''
</P>
<P>
   Her show gets at the heart of collaboration in architecture,
which is a collaborative art no matter how hard a Wright tries to
take credit for everything down to the doorknobs. (Wright tried to
downplay Niedecken's contribution in a 1931 Princeton University
lecture in which he proclaimed that decoration ``must be part of
the architect's design in both concept and execution . . . Let
decoration, therefore, die for architecture, and the decorator
become an architect, but not an `interior architect,' '' which was
what Niedecken called himself.)
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also hits at the notion that, as she puts it,
``influence was a one-way affair from Wright to `lesser'
designers.'' She points out that Niedecken spent considerable time
in Europe, in direct contact with the Art Nouveau movement that
influenced Wright, years before Wright went there himself. Wright
knew the work of the Viennese Secessionists and other
forward-thinking artists and architects through publications;
Niedecken, who studied with Art Nouveau designer Alphonse Mucha in
Paris, knew it first-hand _ and brought it back to the American
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robertson can't resist hanging plant drawings by Wright and
Niedecken side by side in her show: Gazing at the slightly clumsy
Wright and the exquisitely sure Niedecken, she asks, with a note of
triumph, ``Now which of the two was the better draftsman?''
</P>
<P>
   She clearly gets a kick out of this, not only because Niedecken
is unsung and not only because he was extremely talented, but also
because he was apparently a really nice guy, gentle, and easygoing,
``which is why he could work with Wright,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   Their personalities were opposites; their design styles, while
distinct, harmonized. Robertson opens with rooms that explain those
styles, showing what the two men were up to before they first
worked together in the early years of this century. Wright's room
comes first, with a model of the 1902 Ward Willits house that
epitomizes the Prairie Style. A building that spreads in all four
directions, capped by a sheltering roof, it was ``the beginning of
ranch houses,'' the curator notes, as well as a signal of the
preeminence of the horizontal line meant to echo that of the
Midwestern plains. Then comes a lineup of Wright's iconic chairs,
heavy and severe, the flickering grain of the oak their sole
ornament, one permitted only because it was internal rather than
superimposed. Wright's most famous chair, the extremely tall one
meant for dining, was not meant for comfort. It demanded perfect
posture, and the height of its seat meant maybe your feet wouldn't
hit the floor. ``Who the hell wants to sit in it?'' Robertson asks.
</P>
<P>
   In the next room, the arms of a Niedecken chair curve in a
welcoming embrace. A cabinet from the Adam Mayer house that
Niedecken decorated between 1904 and 1907 is downright delicate in
proportion, filled with Gruby pottery in that calm, pond-green
color that was the Gruby firm's signature. The bed Niedecken
designed for the Emma Demmer house, which, like Mayer's, was in
Milwaukee, is a room-within-a-room, its massiveness relieved by
long-stemmed flowers cut out of the head- and footboards and a
pattern of squares on the sides. In the Mayer and Demmer houses,
Niedecken designed the stained-glass windows and doors, the carpets
and lamps, even the embroidery details on the upholstery and
curtain fabrics. He achieved the kind of integrated interior, the
merger of architecture, fine and decorative arts, that was an ideal
common to the Secessionist Gesamtkunstwerk, Whistler's Peacock
Room, Frederic Edwin Church's house, Olana _ and Wright.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of the showrooms Niedecken remodeled in the F.H.
Bresler Co., an art gallery, shows his willingness not to dictate
every detail in every situation, though, his willingness to
acknowledge that people use rooms, they have their own stuff they
want around them, and their homes and businesses aren't merely the
fulfillment of a design theory. Niedecken's sleekly curving
cabinets in the Bresler gallery are topped by accessories in
varying styles, and traditional paintings hang on the walls.
Wright, such a control freak that he made his furniture so heavy
that it would be difficult for clients to move it around after he
left the scene, would have tossed it all out. Bresler was evidently
pleased: He became a silent partner in the decorating firm
Niedecken formed in 1907 with his businessman brother-in-law, John
Walbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Niedecken and Wright shared a passion for the deliberate
flatness and calm of Japanese prints, which both collected, and
which influenced the murals Niedecken did for Wright and led him to
put stylized pine cones on draperies in one Wright house. Botanical
imagery played an important part in the nature-inspired design of
Art Nouveau, Arts and Crafts, and the Prairie Style, but it was
nature ``conventionalized,'' as artists of the era put it. Botany
played a part in the first documented collaboration between Wright
and Niedecken, the Susan Dana house in Springfield, Ill., where, in
1904, Niedecken designed and painted a gorgeous dining-room frieze,
with stylized sumac, goldenrod, and purple asters, ``what you'd see
on a Midwestern roadside in autumn,'' Robertson says. In the
evening, Wright's art glass fixtures cast shadows in the shapes of
flickering butterflies on Niedecken's fresco.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration continued in projects including the May and
Robie houses, with Niedecken designing dining chairs for the May
house that were tall but also tapered, graceful as opposed to the
assertiveness of a Wright design. The harmony and warmth of the May
dining room make it one of the collaborators' greatest moments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After finishing only a preliminary design for the Irving house
in Decatur, Ill., Wright bolted to Europe with his mistress, the
wife of a former client, leaving associates in charge of his
practice _ and Niedecken in charge of the Irving interiors.
Niedecken's combination couch, table, and desk _ one of the oddest
objects in Robertson's show _ is also one of the most massive. With
its shifting horizontal planes, it looks like a Wright house, the
embodiment of Wright's principle that furniture be architecture. It
is more monumental and architectural than any furniture Wright
himself would turn out until the 1930s, though. And, says
Robertson, ``It comes apart. It's a prototype of sectional
furniture, an idea not developed until much later.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wright returned from Europe, he ignored most of his former
associates. Niedecken was an exception. Together, they worked
during World War I on the Bogk and Allen houses, their last
collaborations, and ones where Niedecken's refinements included
beveled edges and cross-grained veneers, hardly Wright-like
touches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1918, they parted ways, Neidecken to focus on elegant
interpretations of the past, Wright to look to the future. The
architect who had depended on a host of other artists eliminated
Neidecken and his painstakingly painted murals and costly custom
furnishings. Wright went on to design affordable ``Usonian''
houses, where the furniture was supposed to be do-it-yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(``Designing in the Wright Style: Furniture and Interiors by Frank
Lloyd Wright and George Mann Niedecken'' is on view at the Museum
of Our National Heritage, 33 Marrett Road, Lexington, Mass.,
through Sept. 6. Hours are Monday-Saturday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., and
Sunday, noon to 5 p.m. Admission is free.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
