<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIE-SENTENCES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE GET SIX MONTHS FOR TOSSING PIES AT MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three people convicted of hurtling pies into the
face of Mayor Willie Brown got what prosecutors believe to be their
just desserts: six months in jail, the maximum possible punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're insane, your honor,'' defendant Gerard Livernois, 34,
of San Francisco barked after Superior Court Judge Ernest Goldsmith
issued the sentence Wednesday. Defense lawyers said they would
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vermeulen, Livernois' court-appointed lawyer, said the
decision was another example of how the three members of the
loosely organized Biotic Baking Brigade have been unfairly targeted
by the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's indicative of the political pressures felt in this
case,'' Vermeulen said.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants were eligible for reduced jail time if they
had accepted probation. But all three declined that option, saying
their political activism could require them to commit other acts of
civil disobedience, which would violate the terms of their
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Reg Smith, spokesman for District Attorney Terence Hallinan,
said, ``Mr. Hallinan is disappointed the defendants declined
probation. In our system ... that means the sentence is up to the
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, flanked by extra police protection in his first public
appearance after the decision, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith said he had no choice but to render the maximum
sentence because the defendants offered no remorse for their action
and refused probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail is just a waste of time,'' said Livernois, whose sentence
was delayed two weeks so he can seek medical treatment for a benign
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Also sentenced to jail were Rahula Janowski, 27, of San
Francisco, and Justin Gross, 27, of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeulen and defense lawyer Katya Komisaruk have said Brown's
pride and his friendship with Hallinan have obscured justice from
the start of the case.
</P>
<P>
   They said the mayor and the district attorney conspired to
prevent a plea bargain and instead made examples of them. Brown
testified Jan. 13 that he believed all ``criminals,'' the
defendants included, should be used as ``learning tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Komisaruk, who has been arrested 31 times for civil
disobedience, said the case should really have been seen only as
``an act of political theater.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant District Attorney Maria Bee insisted throughout
the three-day trial that the case wasn't about free speech or
protests, but about Brown's right to personal safety. She argued
that the three carried out a brutal Nov. 7 attack on Brown that
left him dazed, confused and fearing for his life.
</P>
<P>
   All three were convicted Jan. 19 of battery, but acquitted of
the more serious charge of assault on a public official. They all
testified that their point in the attack on Brown was to use humor
to draw attention to what they said was his failure to help
homeless people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
