<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-RAYCHARLES28-CO     02-25 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RAYCHARLES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ray Charles followed his instincts to produce music beloved by
mainstream audiences, paving the way for Civil Rights.
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Charles has been a part of the nation's culture for so long
that it's easy to take him for granted. He seems to have been
around forever, an ageless Muppet seated on a piano stool, rocking
back and forth in a mask of black sunglasses and carefree grin,
belting out his raspy blues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after more than four decades as a hitmaker, it's surprising
how little most people really know about the 69-year-old man behind
those shades. Where did he come from? How did he lose his sight?
And is he really the smiling, ``uh-huh'' hep cat seen in soft drink
commercials and on TV? In this ambitious biography, music
journalist Michael Lydon has rummaged through Charles' mysterious
past as if he were going through the singer's coat pockets, and
what he has discovered is a stunning story of poverty, racism,
greed, sex, wealth, opportunity and power.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Ray Charles the superstar was never supposed to
happen. Born in 1930 into barefoot poverty in the North Florida
town of Greenville, he was raised in a ``colored'' neighborhood
called Jellyroll, where women washed white people's clothes and men
were largely absent. His mother, Retha, was 16, an orphan taken in
by a local couple. His father was Retha's married guardian. Though
not technically incest, the relationship was scandalous. On top of
it all, Ray was handicapped, losing his sight at age 6 to
congenital glaucoma.
</P>
<P>
   Although neighbors dismissed him to a future ``with a tin cup in
his hand,'' headstrong Charles had different ideas. After leaving
the Florida School for the Deaf and Blind, where he learned to read
music in Braille and bang out tunes on an upright piano,
18-year-old Ray bought a one-way ticket to Seattle on a Trailways
bus. In the Pacific Northwest, the young man found jazz music,
racial tolerance and heroin.
</P>
<P>
   It was Charles' 16-year addiction to the seductive drug that
shaped much of his musical style. Without inhibitions, he ran his
long fingers over the keyboard night after night, fusing the smooth
jazz of the day with the blues, gospel and country of his
childhood. That is the signature sound fans would later hear on the
radio, an absolutely fresh approach in which Charles would take
standard pop melodies such as ``Georgia on My Mind'' or ``America
the Beautiful'' or country tunes like the Don Gibson classic ``I
Can't Stop Loving You'' and wrap them up in blues for a white
audience. In Seattle, Charles also met 15-year-old Quincy Jones,
who would become one of pop music's biggest producers and a
lifelong friend.
</P>
<P>
   Lydon sets the stage for Charles' unlikely ascension to pop
stardom by reminding us how very segregated the music world was in
the late 1940s and early '50s. Routinely, Charles and his bandmates
encountered Jim Crow on the road, in the form of racist cops and
restaurants that had no ``colored'' seating. Record companies
signed artists along racial lines, and radio was split into two
distinct camps: white and black.
</P>
<P>
   The chapters dealing with Charles' professional breakthrough and
rise to fame _ through songs such as ``Hit the Road, Jack'' and
``What'd I Say'' _ are the most compelling. In meticulous detail,
Lydon, a founding editor of Rolling Stone magazine and a musician,
describes how Atlantic Records founders Ahmet Ertegun and Jerry
Wexler encouraged Charles to drop his guard and sing with his
initial abandon. In fact, the breakthrough happened when Charles
recorded the sassy smash hit ``I Got a Woman'' at Atlanta's WGST
studios in November 1954. Lydon writes:
</P>
<P>
   `` `I Got a Woman' '' had hit written all over it. . . . The
record blended elements like a hybrid flower. It had a dancing beat
like a jump blues, but it was built on gospel's `rise to glory'
chords, and the cheerful lyric, infectiously delivered by Ray, gave
that mix a pop music gloss. As a bonus, Ray repeated the title so
often that `I got a woman, way over town' might become a sing-along
line people would plug nickels into the jukeboxes to hear over and
over again. `I Got a Woman' was a record for every happy couple in
America, black, white and in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   That tune became the first of a string of hot sellers for
Charles, who developed a rather hedonistic and self-centered
response to success. Though he made millions, the singer was
incredibly cheap, requiring band members to pay their own room and
board on the road. As soon as he became a star, Charles dumped
Ertegun, Wexler and Atlantic for a contract with the milquetoast
ABC Records. That's when strings began appearing on his songs, as
well as those insipid, white-sounding backup singers (remember the
chorus of ``Georgia on My Mind''?).
</P>
<P>
   Charles also is portrayed as a major misogynist, cultivating a
musical harem of women who fell in love with him but never seemed
to crack his heart. Hardly a chapter goes by in which the singer
hasn't fathered an illegitimate child, picked up a woman or dropped
another one cold. An inside joke in the Charles entourage, which
included female backup singers known as the Raelets, was that ``to
be a Raelet, you have to let Ray.'' Meanwhile, Della, the woman who
would be his wife for 21 years, stayed quietly at home in Los
Angeles, raising three kids and cooking Charles an occasional
Southern meal.
</P>
<P>
   With this quirky private life as a background, Lydon excavates
Charles' musical growth and contribution as thoroughly as an
archaeologist. Every recording session is described in minute
detail, which may become tedious for all but the most hard-core
fan. (Readers might want to consider purchasing the Ray Charles
boxed CD set to use as a tool while reading the book.)
</P>
<P>
   Charles didn't self-destruct like Marvin Gaye did, or take
Elvis' route and become a bloated parody of himself. Rather, now
gray-headed and slightly stooped, the Rock and Roll Hall of Famer
has become a required prop for sweeping moments, growling out
``America'' under a giant flag at presidential inaugurations, or
singing a chill-bump-raising ``Georgia'' at the 1996 Summer Olympic
Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Lydon points out, however, that Charles' contribution to our
culture goes way beyond the hit parade. He didn't march on
Washington or boycott buses, but years before the civil rights
movement, Charles was performing to integrated audiences. The
singer was one of the first to leap from ``race'' radio to the
turntables of affluent whites, not by becoming a clone of
mainstream vocalists (as did Nat ``King'' Cole), but by sticking to
soul. With a smile, he paved the way for people to clap, sing,
celebrate and shout ``hallelujah'' no matter the color of their
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Charles: Man and Music. By Michael Lydon. Riverhead. $27.95.
429 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A thorough unmasking of a music icon.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino covers radio, country music and pop culture for
the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1434EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SMILEY28     02-25 1981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SMILEY28 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A willing vessel: Smiley gives words free rein
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look for Jane Smiley in her novels or short stories.
Unlike many fiction writers, she draws little from her life
experiences, family lore or innermost feelings. There are no clues
to her psyche in ``A Thousand Acres,'' her Pulitzer Prize-winning
tragedy about an Iowa farm family, or in ``Moo,'' a wicked satire
set on a Midwestern college campus, or in her latest book, ``The
All-True Travels and Adventures of Lidie Newton,'' a romance
adventure set in 19th-century Kansas that's just out in paperback,
or even in ``Horse Heaven,'' the novel she's working on now about
the wild world of Thoroughbred horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pure Midwestern sensibility that prompts Smiley to avoid
looking inward for inspiration. Mining the outer world, after all,
provides endless possibilities, long after the personal well runs
dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing fiction is a mentally complex thing, which means
anybody can do it,'' Smiley says. ``It's the things that are not
complex _ shooting a ball through a hoop, running . . . _ that you
either have a talent for or you don't. . . . But any mental
activity _ even math _ people can learn. Writing is a skill, not a
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley spent a recent balmy winter day at Wesleyan College, a
liberal arts college for women in Macon, delivering the 1999
Katharine Payne Carnes Lecture, and then working her way through a
series of smaller, more intimate exchanges with students and
enthralled community members.
</P>
<P>
   She is a comfortable, if not flashy, speaker _ more interested
in making a point than in impressing anyone or making friends. And
when she talks about her craft, writing fiction becomes a cosmic
event, an inexplicable collaboration between writer and story,
between words and a willing vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word knows where it wants to go,'' Smiley tells slightly
mystified students, some of whom aspire to be writers and some of
whom dream of nothing more this particular day than earning extra
credit in English. ``The way you learn to write is you learn not to
not write. It's a matter of getting out of the way. I have to learn
anew every day to sit and quit wasting time and to be there for the
story to come, the characters to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In Smiley's parlance, characters walk on and off the page at
will, speaking in dialogue that surprises even her. (In ``Moo,''
for instance, she swears she didn't know Chairman X's first name
until his wife used it on the very last page.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep yourself open for anything to come,'' Smiley says.
``Whatever comes, use it. Dickens, Trollope, George Eliot . . .
their greatest talent was that they could be there when the story
came to them,'' she adds. ``They gloried in it but also disappeared
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing 6-foot-2 in flat shoes, Smiley is imposing in her
invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jane always had a tremendous kind of confidence, even when we
were all beginners and struggling,'' recalls North Carolina
novelist Allan Gurganus (``Plays Well With Others,'' ``Oldest
Living Confederate Widow Tells All''), a classmate of Smiley's at
the prestigious Iowa Writers' Workshop in 1974-76. ``She papered
one whole room of her house with rejection slips. But none of us
ever doubted that she was going to be a major voice. She's
immensely intelligent, very talented and serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she's complicated, to say the least,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   While at the workshop, Smiley lived in a ``very lively, crazy,
wonderful old Victorian farmhouse, full of books and
conversations,'' Gurganus recalls. ``And she grew corn right
outside the kitchen. . . . I tend to look back very tenderly on
those times.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other members of the class _ T. Coraghessen Boyle, Ron
Hansen and Richard Wiley _ have remained close friends over the
ensuing decades. When asked about Smiley's ongoing role in the
group, Gurganus demurs, lamenting the ``competitive nature'' of
some writers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Smiley doesn't mince words when talking about the
priority of writing in her life. ``My writing just goes on,'' she
recently told an interviewer for The Atlantic. ``It wasn't affected
by children, it wasn't affected by marriage, it wasn't affected by
teaching, it wasn't affected by quitting teaching. It's never been
affected by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions thoughtfully and concisely, wasting few
words, gestures or even pleasantries, Smiley is a professor by
nature if no longer by vocation. In 1996 Smiley left Iowa State
University, where she taught for 15 years, and moved to a 3-acre
spread dubbed ``the Do-Re-Mi ranchette'' in northern California.
She relocated to indulge her latest, lingering interest _ and the
subject of her novel in progress _ raising thoroughbred horses. She
now owns 12, with three more on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses were a passion when I was a child,'' Smiley says with a
slow smile. ``I gave it up when I went to college, and then resumed
it about 5 1/2 years ago, since my parents can no longer rein in my
passions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since settling in California, Smiley says she doesn't miss the
academic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I still teach,'' she says. ``I just teach horses
instead of people. I put up my hand and say, `Ho!' That's still
teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago Smiley set a goal befitting her relentless genius _
to write each one of the four major narrative forms: epic (``The
Greenlanders''), tragedy (``A Thousand Acres''), comedy (``Moo'')
and romance (``Lidie Newton''). With that heady project completed,
Smiley was anxious to begin working on ``Horse Heaven.'' In true
Smiley style, she's trying something a little offbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the characters are horses,'' she says. ``Each one kind
of passes through the network of thoroughbred racing, so they all
have human associates. But some of the characters are horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley has to be ``fairly obsessed'' with a subject before she
undertakes writing about it, and what she reads depends on what
she's writing at the time. For her current project, she's reading
publications such as the Thoroughbred Times, learning all she can
about horse breeding and genetics. To ensure her accuracy, she
solicits regular input from a horse breeder and a veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of learning is very deep in her,'' says Neil
Nakadate, a neighbor and a fellow professor at Iowa State for 15
years. His book ``Understanding Jane Smiley'' will be published in
May by the University of South Carolina Press. ``She likes to do
research, reading in and around a subject. . . . That very serious
research component is so important to her work as a creative
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's constantly looking for a new challenge, some new project
that makes her have to do something differently,'' Nakadate says.
``And she's willing to take risks. If people don't like it, well,
it was still worth trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley's claim to literary fame is a ceaseless attention to
detail _ whether in the farming methods of the 1970s or the social
structure of 14th-century Greenland _ and an astonishing range of
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accuracy is very important to me,'' she says. ``I try never to
take poetic license, because real events are always so much more
interesting than anything you could make up. Of course, there are
always places where nobody knows what really happened. Then I
extrapolate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lidie Newton'' is a case study of how a writer's obsession
takes hold. Smiley was on a book tour in Washington, D.C., in 1995
when she heard about the bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City. She telephoned a friend and told him she wanted to
write about ``the intersection of ideology and violence in American
life.'' Without hesitation he suggested that she consider Kansas in
1850.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a researcher's dream,'' Smiley says. ``It was an
election year, so there was a media storm, which meant there are
articles and memoirs and polemics _ an incredible amount of primary
source material. It was also a novelist's dream because it was not
a well-worn path.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she delved into the history of that turning point in
American history _ the tumultuous battleground between slavery and
abolition _ she was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Critical reaction to the book, published in hardback last
spring, was mostly positive, but sales were disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a controversial take on a controversial issue,'' she
says with a shrug. ``So everybody's going to have more of an
opinion on it than they're going to have on farming or Greenland .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley first learned the depth of modern-day opinions on slavery
in 1996, when she wrote an essay for Harper's magazine titled ``Say
It Ain't So, Huck,'' essentially debunking Mark Twain's most famous
work as the quintessential American novel. It's a firestorm she
still doesn't understand, even as she stands by her critique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always kind of astonished me that anyone would care that I
don't really like Huck Finn, especially in the context of Twain's
sinking of the reputation of James Fenimore Cooper. Twain hated
Cooper, and he tried to make sure Cooper was never read again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twain would certainly honor my right to say whatever I thought
about any author, even if it was him, because he did that himself.
. . . One good thing that came out of that is that more people
said, `Maybe I should read ``Uncle Tom's Cabin.'' ' It's a
wonderful book and deserves to come back into the mainstream of
American fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley's not shy about challenging any writer's work, including
her own. Last year, she wrote an essay for The Washington Post's
Book World repudiating her most successful work, ``A Thousand
Acres.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a writer, you are constantly confronted by what you put on
paper 20 years ago, in all its naivete and rigidness,'' she says.
``You may no longer believe any of that stuff. Some of it may
actually offend you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Hardy and William Butler Yeats spent their later years
rewriting their earlier work. Every writer wants to bring their
work up to date. Do you want a record of your progressive
ignorance? Or do you want everything to look good in the end?''
</P>
<P>
   For ``an ever-renewing source of inspiration'' in her writing
life, Smiley relies heavily on her favorite author, Charles
Dickens: ``His style is wonderful and he's always just beyond
comprehension.'' Early next year, Viking is publishing a short
biography of Dickens penned by Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Smiley plans to keep doing what comes
naturally, writing two or three hours every morning, tending to
horses every afternoon and occasionally lecturing and teaching
humans. When asked by a Wesleyan student whether she would like to
see any more films made of her work, as in 1997's ``A Thousand
Acres,'' Smiley takes a long pause before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' she says finally. ``Hollywood is a large
shallow pond where nothing really interesting is going on. . . .
They always tempt you to have hopes and then they dash your hopes.
What they came up with for ``A Thousand Acres'' was earnest but not
very inspiring. So who cares?''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Midwestern sensibility is clear: An author's success
isn't measured in movies, or even in dollar figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep at it and develop your standards of writing, you
will be published,'' Smiley says. ``But the word `successful' is so
subjective. I once heard Amy Tan describe me as being more
successful than her, and I almost fell out of my chair, because she
had much more money than me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to: Do you like sitting down and doing your work
every day? If you do, you're a success. If you don't, you're not.
It doesn't really matter how anybody else defines it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
