<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS28-COX     02-25 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gloriously gloomy: `Archangel' is true to spy-novel heritage
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Archangel. By Robert Harris. Random House. $24.95. 416 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The espionage novel wouldn't be what it is without a certain
gloom. The detective story develops toward a point of sudden
menace, but the low-level tension of the spy novel is altogether
different. Pervasive and vaguely ominous, it is the air that colors
character and detail. Where the murder mystery can be written in
the pastels of Southern California or South Florida _ not that most
are, but Raymond Chandler and John D. MacDonald wrought darkness
from the sunshine _ the thriller thrives in gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pious Friday evening in May and a fine river mist lying in
the market square.'' So begins John le Carre's ``A Small Town in
Germany.'' It is 10 minutes before midnight and the leather coats
of policemen ``glistened in the lamplight,'' and soon a single
church bell began ``its monotonous chime, a dirge for Christian
virtue in an empty city.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harris, English like le Carre, has learned the technique
as well as anyone in contemporary fiction. ``Thick cloud had
pressed down on Berlin all night,'' his haunting first novel,
``Fatherland,'' began, and on the western horizon ``plumes of rain
drifted across the surface of Lake Havel like smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War of le Carre's fiction evoked damp nights and heavy
cloud cover even if day-to-day reality was otherwise. But Nazi
Germany, the setting of ``Fatherland,'' could only be imagined in
the grainy shades of old film footage. It was more than
atmospherics. Of all forms of fiction, the spy novel draws most on
sensory response. In ``Archangel,'' Harris immerses us in the
torpor and heaviness of Moscow and the forested expanses of
Siberia. Not only that, but he reacquaints us with Joseph Stalin
and Lavrenty Beria, head of the secret police under Uncle Joe.
</P>
<P>
   They are only background characters, but their presence anchors
everything. If the characters in the foreground are somewhat less
compelling, it only suggests the difficulty of forcing the template
of the thriller onto the less pliable past. Fluke Kelso, once a
promising historian at Oxford University, is in Moscow to attend a
symposium on newly opened Soviet archives. He is in his hotel room
one night when a man named Papu Rapava knocks on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Rapava, it seems, had been Beria's bodyguard and had spent time
in Siberia. After Stalin died of a stroke in 1953, the Kremlin went
into one of its periodic purges. Beria was executed and Rapava was
sentenced to 15 years' hard labor. He is old now, gruff and soaked
in vodka, but he carries with him a secret. It happens that on the
night Stalin suffered his stroke, Rapava was at the dictator's
dacha with Beria.
</P>
<P>
   As rigor mortis set in, Beria hurriedly took into his possession
some private papers no one knew existed. But Beria himself would
soon be dead, a victim of the same ruthlessness he had helped
Stalin carry out, and now they were in the hands of this boorish
old man who addresses the middle-aged Kelso as ``boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Rapava should have chosen to intimate his secret to
Kelso, an academic has-been, is less than clear. But what ensues is
a chase through the forests to the Arctic port city of Archangel.
Along the way, a couple of other characters come onto the scene _
Vladimir Mamantov, a political extremist who would strike Americans
as a madman, and R.J. O'Brian, an unscrupulous Western journalist.
</P>
<P>
   For Kelso and O'Brian, the truth of what Stalin left behind
means different things _ for the one a last chance at scholarly
recognition, for the other a journalistic coup. It would be giving
too much away to suggest the nature of that truth, but as Kelso and
O'Brian are drawn to a remote frozen city on the White Sea,
Stalin's malevolence almost rises from the grave like a putrid gas.
</P>
<P>
   From book to book, the stock devices of the spy novel _ the
stranger with a secret, the Westerner in unfamiliar surroundings,
the dance of hunter and hunted, the obsession that drives the story
_ are like interchangeable parts. What distinguishes one novel from
another is the darkness of the obsession and the dread that attends
it. Stripped to its component parts, ``Archangel'' is well-paced,
garden-variety espionage, but Harris is a master of storytelling
with the patina of reportage:
</P>
<P>
   ``It never seemed to get properly light, even two hours after
dawn. It was as if the day had given up on itself before it even
started. The sky stayed gray, and the long concrete ribbon of road
that ran straight ahead of them dwindled into a damp murk. On
either side of the highway lay a wrinkled dead land of rust-colored
swamps and sickly yellowish plains _ the sub-Arctic tundra _ that
turned in the middle distance to dense, dark green forests of pine
and fir.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the end of that road, at the end of this skillfully
written novel, lies the stale breath of an awful past. Oxidized
anew, it has the frightful stench _ and the plausibility _ of
something buried but not fully decomposed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
