   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JASPERDEATH-TRIAL _ JASPER, Tex. _ Closing arguments and
possible punishment verdict in the dragging death trial. (Gamino,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-DEFENSE-FUND _ AUSTIN _ Texas contributors to the Bill
Clinton legal defense fund range from the famous to the obscure.
They include former U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright, who gave $100,
to hundreds of retired teachers and current college professors, to
one Grand Prairie man who gave $1.69. We talk to some folks about
why they gave and what they think now. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DRIVERLICENSE-PICS _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A report on Thursday
night's public meeting on the controversial sale of driver's
license photos to a New Hampshire data company. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LYONS _ LARGO, Fla. _ Jurors could begin deliberating as soon as
Thursday afternoon the case against the National Baptist Convention
USA president and his co-defendant after hearing more than five
weeks of testimony. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES _ Gas prices fell to their lowest point in history
this month, according to industry analyst Trilby Lundberg, who
produces the respected Lundberg Survey. The report, which checks
10,000 gas stations nationwide, found the average price of gas was
99.8 cents a gallon in mid-February. The cost of a gallon of gas in
1949 _ about 27 cents _ equals $1.86 in 1999 dollars when adjusted
for inflation, according to the U.S. Energy Information
Administration. The government began recording average gas consumer
prices in 1949. But drivers should enjoy the cheap fuel while it
lasts. Some fear that after a year of plunging, gas prices have
reached the floor. (Banstetter, Palm Beach Post). 12. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PEACECORP _ The Peace Corps is preparing to recruit more
volunteers this year than at any time in the past 25 years but
won't meet President Clinton's goal of 10,000 by the turn of the
century. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-COIN _ English kicked the Spaniards out of Georgia.
Archaeologists and coin experts say the coin is ``an incredible
find'' that may help them pinpoint the site of a Spanish mission
that existed on the island for much of the 17th century. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-INSURANCE _ AUSTIN _ We talk to some Austin area
families about the juggling act they must perform when it comes to
paying the doctor vs. paying the household bills. Hundreds of
thousands of Texas families are watching the Capitol for a decision
on a state insurance program that would cover families too wealthy
for Medicaid but too poor for private insurance. (Greenberger,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-PRAYER _ AUSTIN _ A report on the Texas Prayer
Breakfast for legislators. Denny Pearce, the Houston businessman
who helps put on the breakfast, says it's an all-inclusive event
for everybody of every faith. ``I want to emphasize this is not a
Christian event,'' Pearce says. It focuses on one religious figure,
he adds. ``The only common demoninator is Jesus of Nazaraeth and
everybody can identify with Jesus.'' Hey, what about the Jews?
``Jesus was aJ ew,'' Pearce replies. We'll see how some
non-Christian legislators feel about it. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPORT _ AUSTIN _ Capitol report. News briefs,
bright moments and other tidbits from the Texas Legislature.
(Staff, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
