<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR &LR;      02-25 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAS `PEOPLE'S BUSINESS' TO DO  
 (ADV: THIS ARTICLE APPEARED IN THE FEB. 25 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Dear Mr. President:
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy your visit.
</P>
<P>
   No offense, sir, but don't you have more important things to do
than glad-hand with a large crowd of friendlies, including some of
those who helped put you over the top in Arizona during the last
presidential election?
</P>
<P>
   Not that we blame you for wanting to get out of Washington. You
know better than most how downright unfriendly a place it can be.
Just remember, you don't have much more time there. (We're counting
the days.)
</P>
<P>
   We know it's important for you to meet with the people, to
assure them that you truly are capable of acting presidential,
despite those painfully true things the House managers said during
the impeachment hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But we would thrill more to the sight of you and Congress
actually working together, putting your partisan shoulders to the
wheel to do the people's business.
</P>
<P>
   At least while you're here, you'll talk up pressing national
matters: Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   There are few issues more important to more Americans _ young,
old, rich, poor and all along the political spectrum _ than
figuring out what to do about programs so tightly woven into the
American social fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, with its concentration of retirees and its steady
influx of upwardly mobile and anxious young workers, needs signs
that national leadership is capable of righting the listing ship
called Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   We'd love for you to choose Tucson as the place to be forthright
about the so-called budget surplus that you propose to use to save
Social Security. Tell us true. It's really not a surplus, is it?
Oh, by Beltway standards it is, but if the rest of us did the books
like you folks in Washington, we'd be in bankruptcy _ or jail.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can you pay operating expenses by borrowing from a
fund meant to pay retirees, count those dollars as revenue and then
tout budget surpluses?
</P>
<P>
   Using Social Security funds to report a balanced budget is a
little like a working couple figuring in their projected pension
benefits to balance the checkbook. It's a neat trick, but the banks
and creditors wouldn't be amused.
</P>
<P>
   We know fixing the system is going to require some bold strokes
of leadership. But are you really serious about investing the
nation's projected budget surplus _ your word, not ours _ in the
stock market?
</P>
<P>
   You actually want the government to invest Social Security funds
in the stock market and become a shareholder in major corporations?
What was that Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said about
your stock market plan? Oh, yes, it has ``very far-reaching
potential dangers for a free American economy and a free American
society.''
</P>
<P>
   We agree that some aspect of privatization of Social Security
will be necessary to give American workers a healthy retirement
income. But it makes more sense for these investments to occur
among individuals in private accounts, not with government holding
shares in private businesses.
</P>
<P>
   You've got an idea to pay down the national debt and earmark the
savings for Social Security. Go with that. That sells well in a
state whose people generally want as much financial freedom as
government will allow them. Give hope to those many Arizonans who
view debt as a plague on society and taxes a bitter medicine for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy Arizona. We do.
</P>
<P>
   But please do hurry back to Washington. You've work to do. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
