<SLUG> BC-PALM-ORGANIZER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PALM PILOT IS A STEP ABOVE ITS PREDECESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You can't be too skinny, too bright or too
connected. Especially when it comes to a hand-held organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com Corp. has embraced this high-society truism with the
latest in its popular line of personal information managers, the
Palm V, which appeared on store shelves Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The original Palm Pilot, which debuted in early 1996, was an
instant hit in a languishing market filled with some clunky,
calculator-like devices that made a simple paper planner seem high
tech.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 3Com's organizers hold a 70 percent share of the
hand-held computer market, according to IDC, a marketing firm based
in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The field is becoming more crowded. Using the Microsoft CE
operating system based on the Windows operating system, most of the
major computer manufacturers, including Hewlett-Packard and the
Compaq Computer Corp., are producing hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, IDC estimated that 2.5 million hand-held computers had
been sold in the United States. That market is expected to increase
to 3.4 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm has got the incumbency,'' said Chris Stix, an analyst at
SG Cowen &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``They just dominate now.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Diana Hwang, a research manager specializing in hand-held
computing devices at IDC: ``3Com simply has the larger installed
base, and we expect the Palm V to solidify that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Palm Pilot was capable of holding 500 names and a
year's worth of to-do items. It featured a small screen for
scribbling data using a handwriting software package called
Graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   But it was dull gray and had some sharp edges. It also didn't
have an integrated cover, and the delicate screen could easily be
scratched.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm III solved those problems. It eliminated some of the
sharper corners and came with an attached flip-up cover. But there
was still that dull, gray plastic, which was starting to look
decidedly down market in a field of blossoming competitors like the
Philips Nino, which sported a polished aluminum skin.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm V is a vast design improvement over its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The new Palm sports a slim anodized metal casing that's half the
thickness of the Palm III. The murky monochrome screen, which had
always been a weakness in previous Palms, has been replaced by a
crisper, sharper liquid-crystal display. The screen is just a tad
smaller than the Palm III, but the sharper image makes up for size.
</P>
<P>
   Some other good changes in the Palm V:
</P>
<P>
   _ The contrast button, which was a hard-to-use wheel on the
older Palms, is now an on-screen feature activated by a recessed
push switch.
</P>
<P>
   _ The desktop cradle now has a built-in charger that replenishes
the Palm V's built-in lithium batteries. No hunting around for
AAAs, and no more draining the batteries when the device is being
used while parked in the cradle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Palm V contains 2 megabytes of memory, which means it can
store the names, addresses and phone numbers of 6,000 people, as
well as five years of appointments, 1,500 to-do items and 1,500
memos.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers at 3Com, based in Santa Clara, Calif., have come up
with an ingenious solution to the screen cover problem: There are
channels carved into both sides of the device, made to fit either
the included weighted stylus or the edge of a leather and rubber
cover pad. Users can decide whether they want the elegant cover pad
to open on the left or right. A small detail, but nice.
</P>
<P>
   An optional 33-bits-per-second modem is available in case users
want to access e-mail on the road. 3Com plans to release the Palm
VII this spring, which will feature a built-in wireless modem. The
price is expected to be about $700.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm V's synchronization software, which allows duplication
of data on a desktop computer, now includes a ``conduit'' that is
compatible with the ubiquitous Microsoft Outlook data manager.
</P>
<P>
   At $499, the Palm V isn't cheap. However, buyers can save
themselves $100 and get the $399 Palm IIIx, which has a slightly
larger, sharper screen than the Palm III, and sports 4 megabytes of
RAM.
</P>
</TEXT>
