<HEADLINE>
REMOVE BAY LEAVES BEFORE SERVING DISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STEVENS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Why do recipes that call for bay leaves always say to remove
them before serving the food?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bay leaf's edges are very sharp and have been know to
perforate people's intestines, so be sure to remove the herb after
cooking, Tufts University recommends in its ``Tufts University
Guide to Total Nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I like to keep a variety of gourmet coffee beans on hand for
when friends drop by. What's the best way to store the coffee?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're smart to buy the whole bean coffee to preserve its
freshness. Ground coffee loses its flavor more rapidly than whole
bean because it presents more surface area and smaller particles to
the air that accelerate the loss of the coffee's characteristic
oils. Store the coffee in an airtight container. The best
containers are glass ones with a rubber ring sealing lid since
these will not alter the taste or characteristics of your coffee.
Don't store your coffee in the refrigerator because this introduces
extra moisture and unwanted flavors into the coffee. You can freeze
it to maintain the freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Whole beans freeze better than ground coffee. You'll want to
take the coffee out of the bag you bought it in and freeze it in an
airtight container. And remember, don't keep coffee frozen longer
than three months.
</P>
</TEXT>
