<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 10 years, DePreist back to conduct ASO
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James DePreist, music director of the Oregon Symphony
in Portland and the Monte Carlo Philharmonic, will conduct the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   DePreist, 62, last conducted the ASO 10 years ago. He is the
nephew of the great American contralto Marian Anderson. He will
lead the ASO in a program that features the Symphony in F sharp by
Erich Korngold (1897-1957), one of Europe's most impressive talents
until he was forced into exile from Austria by the Nazis in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   He resettled in Hollywood, where his film scores included the
Errol Flynn pirate epic ``Captain Blood'' and the Oscar-winning
``Anthony Adverse'' and ``The Adventures of Robin Hood.'' Of
Korngold, DePreist says: ``There's movie music, and there's movie
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Guest artist Leila Josefowicz, 21, will play the violin concerto
of Felix Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Era Dance,'' which opens the program, is by Aaron Jay
Kernis, 39, who won a Pulitzer Prize in music last year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Orchestra with James DePreist, conductor; Leila
Josefowicz, violin. 8 tonight-Saturday; 2 p.m. Saturday (casual
concert). $19-$48. Symphony Hall, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280
Peachtree St. N.E. , Atlanta 404-733-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
