A9217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKI-CANADA1stT     02-25 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-CANADA1stTAKE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skiing is just the beginning of the snow-season pleasures that
await in crystal-blue Banff
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANFF, Alberta _ You should be as lucky as me right now: I am
stamping my Australian wool-lined sheepskin boots on a glittering
frozen pond in the middle of western Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It is New Year's Eve, not many minutes before midnight. But it
could be almost any winter night of the year here. My right hand is
wrapped around a steaming, very strong Irish coffee; my left is
deep inside the pocket of my ski parka. It's cold: minus-something
Celsius, which translates into plus-something Fahrenheit, though
not plus-something much. But I'm dressed for it, and the sky is the
clearest, darkest black you've ever seen, and the Big Dipper is
turned upside down and spilling stars all over the place while the
man in the full Canadian moon is grinning a big, goofy, McKenzie
brothers smile.
</P>
<P>
   That bright grin lights up everything: three soaring peaks of
Canadian Rockies that run along the frozen river behind me; the
castlelike Banff Springs Hotel (circa 1888) that rises on the steep
hill to my right; the snow-bloated pines that scent the air
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   My teenage son is somewhere on top of that hill in front of me,
with a herd of other kids, streaming on a toboggan down the packed,
moonlit snow. Every other trip he hits a bump and sails through the
frosty air for long, suspended moments, as if frozen there,
stop-frame, cartoonlike, before finally landing with a thud.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Ann, is here, too: She's the one taking her sweet time
skating at the other end of the pond, mixing with a couple dozen
locals. Some of them are playing hockey; one is slashing back and
forth with a shovel in his hands, clearing snow so there's even
more room to skate; another is pulling his swaddled, gurgling baby
behind him in a sled, with a string of kids on skates holding on
from behind and laughing as they're slung along.
</P>
<P>
   Some couples are skating around the pond in slow, lazy circles,
hand in hand. I did that with my wife earlier, before I chucked my
skates, my legs mushy from the day's dawn-to-dusk skiing between
the towering glaciers over at Lake Louise _ which, by the way, is
unreal, and which I'll get to in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But first you need to see this stuff. What's happening here
tonight could be almost any winter night in this part of the world:
The skiing here is great, but the being here is something else.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fire blazing on the other side of that thigh-high
snowdrift. I'm headed there in a minute, to huddle next to families
huddled on benches around it, talking about mutual friends and
their kids' teachers and how the elk are always mating on the golf
course during warm weather while you're trying to hit a 5-iron
(``There was this male just surrounded by females. He should be on
`Jerry Springer' ''). I'm headed there right after I trudge up the
hill for one more Irish coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's really almost midnight: I'm next to the fire and a guy
on a cell phone has signaled everybody to start counting down the
New Year _ ten! nine! eight! _ the shouted numbers hanging white in
the air like living ice sculptures, clanging into each other as
more are let loose _ five! four! _ a dozen kids and adults
sprinting back up the hill with their toboggans and sleds and
saucers and plastic sheets _ anything! _ to slide down in one last
ring-in-the-New-Year scramble.
</P>
<P>
   And then the countdown ends and champagne bottles are uncorked
and skaters hug each other and there's a crazy pile of people at
the bottom of the toboggan run and I kiss my wife's frozen lips and
my son's frozen head and throw back the last of my Irish coffee.
</P>
<P>
   And I ask myself: Who does winter better than Canada?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Quirky, cosmopolitan
</P>
<P>
   You come here in the winter to ski. There are three resorts
within Banff National Park, two of them _ Lake Louise and Sunshine
Village _ considered among the best in North America.
</P>
<P>
   But Banff is more than a skier's paradise during the snow
season, which bleeds into early May. That New Year's Eve moment is
the kind of thing that runs through this place like a dry-ice
charge. A quaintly overgrown mountain town (population: 7,500),
Banff is where The United Colors of Benetton meets ``Northern
Exposure.'' Hip and quirky, it's an international magnet that draws
Americans and Japanese and Brits and Germans with its memorable
skiing, wry Canadian cheerfulness and generous exchange rate (it
currently adds about 50 cents to every U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
   The pretty little downtown, with a main street bookended by
mountains, is crammed with more than 80 restaurants of all stripes
(Canadian, Korean, Japanese, Greek, Mexican). Souvenir shops range
from Canadian Mountie tacky to indigenous peoples artful. There are
ski shops, bars, a bowling alley, a movie theater _ and, yes, a
United Colors of Benetton and a Hard Rock Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet whatever ski-culture flash Banff possesses (and it ain't
much) is tempered mightily by the playful earthiness you'd expect
in a huge, hugely popular national park, located about an hour and
a half west of Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where elk are spotted sidling down the middle of
Banff Avenue (``Zey look friendly like aye pet, but eet eez just a
front,'' a French-Canadian bus driver warned us of the area's
ubiquitous elk, who are not to be messed with).
</P>
<P>
   A handmade sign warns inside a Banff hospital emergency room:
ABSOLUTELY NO SKI BOOTS BEYOND THIS POINT! As if. (One doctor said
the hospital averages 40 skiers a day, while a nurse said she
relishes the hour respite between when the last skiers leave and
the first drunks arrive.)
</P>
<P>
   The park radio station provides a daily avalanche bulletin and
airs stories of National Public Radio quality on topics that range
from ``Tales of the Canadian Rockies'' to wildlife inbreeding to
Hudson Bay rum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1523EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKI-CANADA2ndT     02-25 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-CANADA2ndTAKE28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   BANFF, Alberta: Hudson Bay Rum.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the skiing. Oh, man. I'm a piker on skis, and
my son was a first-timer, and my wife is a somewhat reluctant
veteran of slopes around the world (she has teared up at the summit
of lifts from Innsbruck to Squaw Valley). So as a family, we run
what you'd call the gamut.
</P>
<P>
   And we all had a ball.
</P>
<P>
   There's a startling, almost vertiginous feeling here of skiing
on top of the world (``Do you think that's the top?'' my wife asked
as we drove through the canyon winding to Sunshine Village,
pointing to a towering peak that disappeared into a cloud). The
snow here is plentiful and powdery, and the views never end,
especially those at Lake Louise, about 35 miles from Banff.
</P>
<P>
   A beginner's green trail runs from every lift there. That allows
absolutely anybody a look at the heart-stopping scenery that
includes above-cloud vistas of a frozen Lake Louise and a bulging
Victoria Glacier and a string of ice-capped Rockies that run and
run until they disappear into a mist you suspect stops somewhere
just short of the North Pole. (From certain angles you look toward
the nearby Icefields Parkway, a northbound, glacier-lined route
considered one of the world's most scenic.)
</P>
<P>
   Standing on skis at the summit of the aptly named ``Top of the
World'' chairlift, for instance, you get a sense that the hand of
God could reach right down at any moment and, with a forefinger or
a pinky, just flick you a million miles away. When he doesn't, you
ski on down. Trails run all over and behind the mountains, with
lodges tucked away so that many runs become their own destination.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine Village, about 15 miles west of Banff, is most famous
for its snow _ averaging more than 30 feet a season, it doesn't use
snow-making machines. A dizzying, mountain-scaling, 25-minute
gondola ride is required to get to the main ski area (expert skiers
often unload a little earlier, at Goat's Eye Mountain, which offers
some of Sunshine's most challenging runs). It's best to get to the
gondola before 9 a.m. to avoid long lines.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the resort, you're in the middle of it all; skiing is
almost 360 degrees around you. There's a rustic lodge and
restaurant, along with a newer set of shops _ but no cars within
sight. Families with young children like to stay at the few
accommodations available here _ the ski-in, ski-out Sunshine
Village Inn and some condos _ for that reason. Chairs take you from
sweeping beginner runs to a trail that literally spans the
Continental Divide, allowing you to cross from Alberta into British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The only way out of Sunshine Village is the gondola _ or the
miles-long, beginners-can-do-it, ski-out run that weaves below the
gondola much of the way. It was one of the highlights of our trip.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't make it to Mount Norquay, 10 minutes from Banff. Its
reputation is of a lower-altitude, family-friendly resort. It's a
great place to go if you only want to ski half a day, then do
something else. Like head back into Banff for shopping. Or take a
dip in the areas's year-round hot springs. Or drive the scenic,
30-minute route along the Bow Valley Parkway to Johnston Canyon,
where snow-packed hiking trails snake past two frozen waterfalls
(ice climbers often scale the largest of them).
</P>
<P>
   Or . . . you can wait for night, to skate or toboggan or just
bask in the glow of that bright, grinning Canadian moon.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Reserve by Monday to take advantage of a sale
to Calgary _ $375 round trip for midweek travel through June 14
(with 14-day advance purchase) _ on Delta, United, American,
Northwest, Continental and Air Canada. After Monday, the fare jumps
to $555.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations: Some suggested midprice hotels: Inns of Banff,
a pleasantly convenient, few-frills spot (1-800-661-1272); and the
slightly more atmospheric Banff Caribou Lodge (1-800-563-8764).
More luxurious digs: Banff Springs Hotel (1-800-441-1414); Chateau
Lake Louise (1-800-441-1414); Post Hotel, in Lake Louise, whose
Dining Room is one of the area's best restaurants (1-800-661-1586).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat: Among midprice favorites: Earl's, 229 Banff
Ave., an easy (if often crowded) respite that has something
(Canadian, Mexican, Cajun, Asian) for just about everyone's taste;
the Grizzly House, 207 Banff Ave., a Canadian-appointed fondue
restaurant that has a vibrating lounge chair in the waiting lobby
to shake out the day's soreness before you eat; and Joe Btfsplk's,
a vowel-less, '50s-style diner that's great for a sit-down
cheeseburger and fries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to wash it down: The relatively new St. James Gate, 205
Wolf St., an Irish pub with a wide selection of beers on tap and 50
brands of single-malt scotch. Other standbys: the Rose &AMP; Crown, 202
Banff Ave.; Wild Bill's Legendary Saloon, 201 Banff Ave.; and the
Barbary Coast, upstairs at 119 Banff Ave.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When you're not skiing: Pamper yourself at the luxurious Upper
Hot Springs Spa (403-760-2500) or the Solace spa at Banff Springs
Hotel (403-762-1772). Take a heart-arresting ride on a bobsled or
luge at Canada Olympic Park in Calgary, home of the '88 Winter
Olympics (403-247-5452). Take a snowy, heart-easing sleigh ride:
Holiday on Horseback in Banff (403-762-4551) and Brewster Lake
Louise Sleighrides (403-762-5454). Or take a dog sled ride. Many
outfits to choose from, including Mountain Mushers Dog Sled Tours
(403-762-3647). Take a nature tour in Banff at the Cave and Basin
National Historic Site (403-762-4335).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Booking a trip: Several travel agencies specialize in ski
vacations. One we found particularly helpful in booking our entire
Banff trip (plane, hotel, rental car and lift tickets): Aspen Ski
Tours, 1-800-525-2052.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Banff/Lake Louise Tourism Bureau, 403-762-8421,
or on the Web at http://www.skibanfflakelouise.com.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
