<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-NGEORGIA26-CO     02-25 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-NGEORGIA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New lodge 5-mile walk from Amicalola park
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About two miles into the five-mile hike the chill drizzle became
a downpour, the sort that rips leaves off the trees. My son Taylor
walked ahead of me, wearing an oversized yellow rain slicker over
his day pack. In what could only be the result of free association
by a 7-year-old, he began singing above the roar of the rain:
``Somewhere over the rainbow, bluebirds fly . . .'' The entire
score of ``The Wizard of Oz'' followed.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, did I want to go back to the car.
</P>
<P>
   But I slogged on, led through the woods by the improbable
offspring of Judy Garland and Quasimodo. What kept me going was the
knowledge that at the end of the trek I would be dry and warm and
well-fed. Instead of pitching a tent on soggy ground in a driving
rain, I would be taking a hot shower.
</P>
<P>
   Crummy weather sharpens your appreciation for the special
qualities of the Len Foote Hike Inn at Amicalola Falls State Park.
The rustic 20-room lodge, named for the naturalist who was the
inspiration for the comic strip series Mark Trail, was designed to
provide an experience somewhere between a tent and a Holiday Inn.
Although it has been open for less than four months, it has become
quite popular: Every Saturday night through April is booked.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge, which spreads over 5,750 square feet, was designed
and built to have minimal impact on the wooded, mountaintop site.
The four buildings that make up the lodge were built on stilts to
minimize grading. Composting toilets are used because building a
septic tank leech field would have meant cutting down more trees,
said Garland Reynolds, the Gainesville architect who designed the
lodge.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the lodge was inspired by traditional Japanese inns.
The broad eaves of the steeply pitched roofs provide continuous
cover as you move from the bunkhouse to the bathhouse to the mess
hall and on to the Sunrise Room, where built-in seating surrounds a
wood stove. The Sunrise Room serves as the primary social and
entertainment center of the lodge. It is well-stocked with books
and board games; Taylor was kept amused through a rainy afternoon
and evening.
</P>
<P>
   There are other gathering spots at the inn. The lobby of the
bunkhouse where guests check in after making it up the trail is
furnished with mission style furniture that looks like it could
have been ordered from L.L. Bean. Guests gather around the wood
stove here too, chatting while their boots and socks dry by the
stove.
</P>
<P>
   Other guests can be found in the mess hall, playing backgammon
and sipping coffee, hot cocoa or fruit punch that is available
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond fellowship, it is the wood stoves that bring people to
these places.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms aren't heated.
</P>
<P>
   They are truly spartan, little more than an 8-by-10-foot wood
box. There is a ceiling light and an electric fan for warm summer
nights, but no electrical outlets. The bunk beds are comfortable,
but there is no other furniture. As you lay in bed at night you can
hear the rain on the roof and the snoring of the guy next door.
</P>
<P>
   The bathhouse offers two showers for each sex. The sink counter
has electrical outlets, which made Jill Smith's decision to pack a
blow dryer a wise one. The Marietta (Ga.) woman took some ribbing
for hauling a hair dryer to the woods, but many other women took
advantage of it after spending most of the day walking in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   After a hot shower, it is soon time for supper, served after a
ringing of the dinner bell at 6:30. Meals are served family-style,
with heaping platters of meat and vegetables set on the table.
Guests mix at tables of four or six, passing dishes and swapping
stories. The menu on our visit included grilled chicken, pot roast,
salad, succotash and killer biscuits about the size of a 45 rpm
record.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is served at 8 a.m. Coffee, cocoa and other hot drinks
are available for early risers who wander into the Sunrise Room to
watch the sun come up. Again, the meal is tasty and hearty: eggs,
bacon, sausage and apple corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, some visitors take off on day hikes. Springer
Mountain, starting point of the Appalachain Trail, is about three
miles away. Most guests, however, find the hike to the lodge and
back exercise enough and spend the morning relaxing in one of the
many Adirondack chairs scattered about the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a challenging, but not brutal, hike with hot meals
and a hot shower at the end of the trail appeals to tenderfoots and
hard-core hikers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a safe adventure,'' said Jill Smith,
the hiker with the hair dryer.
</P>
<P>
   The hike to the inn was the first lengthy walk in the woods with
her husband, Brian, who admitted, ``I came under duress.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience was worth it, Smith said, adding that he
particularly liked hearing the stories of people like Bob and
Barbara Stephens. The mostly retired couple from Evans, near
Augusta (Ga.), has covered a lot of ground in the past 15 years,
including treks through the Grand Canyon. The inn, they said,
provided all the necessary comforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take the pit toilets,'' Barbara said, ``if you can
have hot showers.''
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, the boy and I explore the grounds of the inn,
including Starbase, a sort of solar calendar that architect
Reynolds designed and built just for fun with the help of John
Burgess, an astronomer at the Fernbank Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   It's sunny and warm as we begin our hike back to the car. We
take an alternate return route that follows the approach trail to
the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we find some bear scat in the trail and study it
a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, today we saw something amazing,'' Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the trail, Taylor asks if we can come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``And can we bring Mom when we come back?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Mom can come.
</P>
<P>
   After all, there is an outlet for her hair dryer in the
bathhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Amicalola Falls State Park is 15 miles
northwest of Dawsonville (Ga.). Take Ga. 53 west out of
Dawsonville, then Ga. 183 north to Ga. 52 east. Check in at the
visitors center at the entrance of the park to pay a $2 parking fee
and to get directions to the parking lot for the Hike Inn
trailhead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hike: Be sure to check out the view from the top of
Amicalola Falls, the highest waterfall in the state. There is a
short trail from the trailhead parking lot to the top of the falls.
The hike to the inn is just under five miles, with a total
elevation gain of about 500 feet. The longest uphill pull begins
after the second stream crossing. Plan on a two- to three-hour
hike, depending on your level of fitness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rates: The rate is $55 per person double occupancy, $75 single
occupancy. Children are slightly less. A family of three can sleep
in one room, with the child getting a pad on the floor. The rate
includes dinner and breakfast. Trail lunches and snacks are
available for an extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to bring: Despite the accommodations, you must be
prepared for a day in the woods. Bring toiletries, flashlight,
first aid kit, extra clothes, water, insect repellent. Wear
comfortable hiking boots or walking shoes and be prepared for a
change in the weather. In cold weather, bring a stocking cap. The
bunks have plenty of blankets, but whatever sticks out from beneath
the covers may get cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reservations: In metro Atlanta, call 770-389-7275. Outside
metro Atlanta, call 1-800-864-7275.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
