<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park City mining outpost-turned-hip hangout
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Staff photographer David Tulis, an avid skier,
is drawn to the collision of past and present in this mining
outpost-turned-hip hangout.
</P>
<P>
   Some ski towns are modern inventions, with a history shorter
than your average beginner's run. Not so Park City, where silver
mining dates to the 1860s and where vestiges of a frontier past
stand strong and proud amid a ski resort with up-to-the-minute
amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the town's ultimate time warp: Catalog entrepreneur and
sometime movie star Robert Redford, artistic director of the
Sundance Film Festival, held here every January, owns a trendy
restaurant in what was once the Union Pacific train depot. It's the
same place that was regularly robbed by the real Sundance Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Why, they oughta make a movie. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
