<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take your pick: Indian fair or island nature
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Heard Museum in Phoenix _ internationally known for its
collections of Native American artifacts and fine art _ unveils its
$18 million expansion today.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion, the fourth in the museum's 70-year history,
doubles the size of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights include three new galleries, bringing the total to
13; a 400-seat auditorium; a fully equipped artists' studio; an
education center; a cafe; and an expanded museum shop and
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Grand opening festivities culminate next weekend with the 41st
annual Heard Museum Guild Indian Fair and Market. On March 20-21,
the museum will host the ninth annual World Championship Hoop Dance
Contest.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 602-252-8840.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sugar in the morning: The sap is rising in Massachusetts, and
visitors through early April can watch farmers performing the art
of maple sugaring.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts legend has it that after Iroquois Chief Woksis
threw his tomahawk into a maple tree one winter evening in 1609 and
returned to retrieve it the next day, sap began flowing from the
hole left by the tomahawk. The tribe used the sap to boil meat,
then discovered the taste was wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Popular souvenirs among tourists are the pure maple products
created at sugarhouses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to traditional pancake syrup, the sap can yield
maple candy; ``soft sugar'' or ``maple cream,'' a soft table
spread; and ``sugar on snow,'' a taffy-like treat made by
thickening syrup on a stove and then immediately pouring it over a
pan of clean snow.
</P>
<P>
   For information on maple sugaring and sugarhouses, visit the
Massachusetts Maple Producers' Web site, which can be found at
(http://www.massmaple.org) or call the Massachusetts Maple Phone
(413-628-3912).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calling Mother Nature: Amelia Island Plantation is offering a
nature lover's weekend package April 22-25.
</P>
<P>
   Keep busy with bird watching, sessions with a staff naturalist,
kayaking, hiking, bicycling, nature photography, marsh walks, fly
fishing, a painted bunting encounter and stargazing. Rates begin at
$129 per person per night based on four people in a two-bedroom
villa. All nature activities are included. Information:
1-800-874-6878.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
