<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-WRINKLES28-COX     02-25 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-WRINKLES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mirror, mirror, on the wall: Can I buy a younger face after all?
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most women don't mind acting their age. They just
don't want their face to make a formal announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Although baby boomers are richer, fitter and more
technologically advanced than their parents were, they are no
closer to discovering the fountain of youth than the generation
before them. But that hasn't stopped them from looking for hope in
a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-aging skin care products are one of the fastest-growing
segments of the cosmetics industry. Consumers spent $3 billion on
facial treatments in 1998, according to Kline &AMP; Co., a cosmetics
research firm in Little Falls, N.J. In 1997, skin care accounted
for $1.5 billion in sales in better department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the skin care business, including anti-aging products,
has grown 6 percent a year for the past five years, said Lenka
Contreras, project manager at Kline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot given that the industry as a whole is only growing
by 2 percent to 3 percent a year,'' she said. ``It's just the aging
population and new product formulations that offer different types
of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are the main customers. As long as Hollywood and Madison
Avenue define beauty by how youthful a woman looks, products that
claim to remove wrinkles, firm sagging skin and eliminate dark
pigmentation spots are likely to be in demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, I do it all,'' said Debbie Webb as she shopped for
cosmetics recently at Nordstrom at Perimeter Mall. Webb, 47, of
Peachtree City estimates that she spends more than $1,500 a year on
products to make her skin look younger. And that doesn't include
the monthly pumpkin facials, a treatment rich in exfoliating fruit
acids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're not going to turn the clock back,'' Webb
admits, ``but they're going to make the changes less drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Skin care experts say that over-the-counter anti-aging
treatments are more hype than hope. They make you feel as if you're
doing something good for your skin, but dermatologists say they
won't reverse wrinkles, eliminate lines or tighten skin.
</P>
<P>
   What the products can do, according to dermatologists, is
exfoliate surface layers of dead skin, leaving your facing looking
polished and smooth. Commercial treatments also can hydrate the
skin to help it look less sullen. Other products can lighten dark
spots that women get from the sun and when their hormones change
during menopause.
</P>
<P>
   Perception is everything; the results, only temporary. ``If you
think you'll put it on and your husband will say, `My God, you look
five years younger,' that's not going to happen,'' warned David
Steinberg, a cosmetics consultant and professor of cosmetic
chemistry at Fairleigh Dickinson University in Teaneck, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Dermatologists say the best way to protect skin and prevent
premature aging is to avoid going out into the sun without wearing
sunscreen. The practice should start in the cradle.
</P>
<P>
   When dark spots and age lines start to appear, experts say, the
most effective treatments contain alpha hydroxy acids, particularly
glycolic and lactic acids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the kind of thing that's going to be the
eternal fountain of youth,'' said Dr. Daniel Zivony, a
dermatologist at Emory Clinic North (Emory University, Atlanta).
``But it's reasonable for women to expect fresher feeling skin.''
</P>
<P>
   But finding cosmetics that contain alpha hydroxy ingredients can
be tricky. Cosmetic manufacturers are required by law to limit the
concentration of glycolic acids in commercial skin care products.
Dosages high enough to minimize or camouflage signs of aging must
be prescribed by a dermatologist or other licensed practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be effective, you need a glycolic acid of between
35 and 75 percent,'' Zivony said. ``They can't sell high
concentrations of glycolic acid like that over the counter.''
</P>
<P>
   Many brands don't indicate on the label what, if any, percent of
glycolic acid is inside. Sales clerks often don't know, either.
</P>
<P>
   Although some products made by companies such as Mary Kay, Avon
and L'Oreal list alpha hydroxy among their ingredients, many other
popular lines don't. For example, Estee Lauder's new Resilience
Lift, a face and throat cream with SPF 15, doesn't state that
glycolic acid is one of its active agents, nor do Clarins
extra-firming face creams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have alpha hydroxy acid products,'' said Clinique
spokesperson Shannon Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   Clinique this month came out with a product called Stop Signs,
an anti-aging serum that sells for $32.50 an ounce. It promises to
smooth, firm and tone. But even Cooney acknowledges, ``Clinique
doesn't really say we're going to turn back the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Dermatologists and other licensed practitioners dispense higher,
more effective levels of glycolic and lactic acids in chemical
peels and moisturizing creams sold by prescription. The products
work best when used with Retin-A, a vitamin A derivative frequently
prescribed for acne. They help exfoliate age spots, replenish the
skin and gently fill in the appearance of fine lines. But they
don't perform miracles.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean women should give up the good fight and simply
grow old gracefully. Experts advise that if a particular skin
treatment makes you feel good about yourself and improves your
skin's appearance, buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Makeup as well as skin care is an emotional purchase,'' said
Sam Fine, a New York-based celebrity makeup artist. ``If nothing
else, they help the mind. It says you care about your skin instead
of just waiting until your 40s and saying you're aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Zinn-Moore can attest to that. As senior vice president
of cosmetics and fragrance for Macy's East, she has seen wrinkle
creams take up more and more space on cosmetics counters. Cosmetics
manufacturers know that boomers want to defy the inevitable, so
they're giving them plenty to chose from.
</P>
<P>
   ``All women want to look young, and all women don't want surgery
or can't afford it,'' Zinn-Moore said. ``So they will try the
newest product on the market. I know I do.''
</P>
<P>
   HOLDING THE LINE ON AGING
</P>
<P>
   Want to slow down the signs of aging? Here's what experts
recommend to minimize fine lines, sagging skin and wrinkles:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Always use a sunscreen when in the sun, regardless of skin
color or ethnicity. Wear a hat and sunglasses to avoid direct
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start at an early age to keep your skin clean.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Give skin a rest by not sleeping in makeup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In your 20s, start wearing a moisturizer with an SPF to keep
skin soft and supple. Choose the right formula for your skin type.
For example, oily skin doesn't need an oil-based moisturizer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By the early 40s, you might need a foundation to even your
skin tone. Look for one that will moisturize.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Moisturizers are critical for women in their 50s, as skin
starts to thin. Be prepared to change products for aging skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hypo-allergenic products are good for sensitive skin. Be
prepared to change products if skin becomes irritated after a
second or third use.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chemical peels, Retin-A and products containing alpha hydroxy
acids that are prescribed by a dermatologist or other licensed
practitioner are more effective than over-the-counter products.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask to try a sample before making a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When purchasing anti-aging products over the counter, look for
ones with glycolic acid or lactic acid. Even though they do not
work as aggressively as prescribed formulas, dermatologists say
they help the face look rejuvenated by exfoliating dead skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Follow instructions. If it says use twice a day, don't use it
more often. There's a valid reason why it shouldn't be used, say,
six times a day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
