<HEADLINE>
THERE'LL BE LOTS OF FLAGS AT NEW CEMETERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to donate a flag for the Avenue of Flags at
the Dallas-Fort Worth National Cemetery?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the Texas National Cemetery Foundation, 928 Murl
Drive, Irving, TX 75062.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-Fort Worth National Cemetery is scheduled to open in
October, ``but it may be later than that,'' foundation Chairman
Cloyde Pinson said.
</P>
<P>
   When it opens, the avenue will be lined with 80 U.S. flags, five
service flags and ``the main 90-footer,'' Pinson said. The avenue
will be extended as the cemetery is expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery, southwest of downtown Dallas near Mountain Creek
Lake, will initially have 14,600 grave sites.
</P>
<P>
   For information regarding eligibility to be buried there, call
(800) 827-1000 or visit the World Wide Web site at www.cem.va.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find the fish symbol that says ``Darwin'' on it
and has feet?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.P., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: One retailer that sells the Darwin fish is Ring of Fire, a
California mail-order company. Car plaques sell for $7, and the
company also has coffee mugs, T-shirts, and several other fish
symbols.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 676-1445 or write to Ring of Fire
Enterprises, Box 3793-W, Santa Cruz, CA 95063-3793.
</P>
<P>
   The Darwin fish was created by Chris Gilman and trademarked by
Evolution Design in 1997. Ring of Fire has a World Wide Web site at
www.rof.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to ``Buddy Faro''? Tell me there is hope
someone influential also liked the show and will bring it back.
</P>
<P>
   _ B.B., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: CBS announced that the series was ``on hiatus'' in
mid-December, and there has been nothing since then to indicate
that it might return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magnificent Seven'' took over the show's Friday night time
slot Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
