<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKET-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAST-TALKING SCALPER MAKES A PITCH FOR LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Just the Ticket,'' Andy Garcia has one of the flashier
roles of his career as Gary Starke, a hyperkinetic, motormouthed
scalper who dashes frantically around New York importuning busloads
of Asian tourists to purchase tickets to events from basketball
games to museum exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   When it is announced that Pope John Paul II will visit the city
and conduct an Easter Mass at Yankee Stadium, Gary sees an
opportunity to make a big score, set his chaotic live in order and
win back the woman he loves, Linda Paliski (Andie MacDowell), an
aspiring chef. Come the big day, he arrives at the stadium
disguised as a nun.
</P>
<P>
   But a flashy leading role does not insure a credible or coherent
movie. As hard as Garcia works to spit out his best Al Pacino
imitation, the film, which aims toward a John Cassavetesesque
spontaneity and grittiness, is a mawkish, incoherent mess.
</P>
<P>
   Although shot on the streets of Manhattan, it fails to capture
the jostling, hard-edged texture of street life, and Gary's
personal and business relationships ring false. Ms. MacDowell, her
Southern accent more pronounced than usual, is miscast as a young
woman from the outer boroughs making her way in big, bad Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's shabby circle of acquaintances who work as short-order
cooks and parking lot attendants look and act like leftover Damon
Runyon characters. The movie even throws in a forlorn pregnant
junkie (Laura Harris), who exists solely to show what a kindhearted
guy Gary is.
</P>
<P>
   But the most hopelessly sentimentalized character is Gary's
mentor, Benny Moran (Richard Bradford), whose one claim to fame,
which no one believes, is his friendship with the former
heavyweight boxing champion Joe Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   The story focuses on Gary's simultaneous efforts to win back
Linda, who has given up on him after eight years, and to carry off
his last big score while evading the police and the wrath of a
ruthless West Indian operator (Andre Blake) who is putting Gary out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, ``Just the Ticket,'' written and directed by
Richard Wenk, gives Garcia, who is the film's co-producer, some
chances to chew the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, he visits a store where Linda works as a clerk
selling appliances, and improvises a maniacal pitch that convinces
a customer to buy a 60-inch television set.
</P>
<P>
   In another, he persuades Linda to trash the kitchen of a wealthy
catering client (Irene Worth), who is portrayed as the world's
stingiest, most mean-spirited hostess. Their crowning touch is to
roll the roast about to be served in kitty litter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the Ticket'' is rated R (Under 17 requires parent or
adult guardian). It has some strong language. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUST THE TICKET
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Richard Wenk; director of photography,
Ellen Kuras; edited by Christopher Cibelli; music by Rick Marotta;
production designer, Franckie Diago; produced by Gary Lucchesi and
Andy Garcia; released by MGM. Running time: 115 minutes. This film
is rated R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Andy Garcia (Gary Starke), Andie MacDowell (Linda
Paliski), Richard Bradford (Benny Moran), Elizabeth Ashley (Mrs.
Paliski), Andre Blake (Casino), Ronald Guttman (Gerrard), Laura
Harris (Cyclops), Chris Lemmon (Alex), Louis Mustillo (Harry the
Head), Don Novello (Tony), Fred Asparagus (Zeus), Patrick Breen
(San Diego Vinnie), Donna Hanover (Realtor), Bill Irwin (Ray
Charles), Ron Leibman (Barry the Book), Paunita Nichols (Rhonda),
Abe Vigoda (Arty), Irene Worth (Mrs. Haywood) and Joe Frazier
(himself).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
