<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-FOR-YOUNG-PEOPLE     02-25 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-FOR-YOUNG-PEOPLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ JAMS FOR THE NINTENDO SET: A FATHER PASSES THE TORCH SONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 Samuel G. Freedman, a professor of journalism at Columbia
University, is the author most recently of ``The Inheritance.''  
 By SAMUEL G. FREEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 25 years as a jazz fan, I long ago learned to
savor the virtues of an 11 o'clock set, that crossroads of languid
ballads and fiery bop. But until I walked into Alice Tully Hall
last December, I had never been to one that sold Raisinets
alongside Cognac and had the occasional tangerine tumbling out of a
backpack and down the aisle. This concert was starting at 11  &UR; in
the morning &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Beside me sat my son, Aaron, notebook and pen at the ready. At 6
he was naive enough to want to be like his father, and I dreaded
the day he would awake to my failings. Because I wrote books, he
wrote books, and he had already filled half a shelf with tales of
sorcerers and gods. Lately, he'd been asking me, dead-serious, why
his works weren't available on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I hoped, I could pass along another passion of mine, jazz.
When Aaron was an infant, I had dandled him to the polyrhythms of
Milton Nascimento, but as he grew older I felt somehow timid about
pressing on him a music as intricate and demanding as jazz. It took
enough paternal vigilance just to steer him clear of Raffi.
</P>
<P>
   Though more of a Bonnie Raitt fan herself, my wife, Cynthia,
encouraged me to subscribe to the Jazz for Young People series,
produced by Lincoln Center and presided over by the trumpeter and
composer Wynton Marsalis. From my mouth, the notion of spending a
few Saturdays at jazz shows would have dripped of self-interest;
from hers, it soared on wings of arts education. Given the opening,
I snatched it.
</P>
<P>
   So here Aaron and I sat amid a sold-out crowd, half of it
ranging from toddler to teen and the other half graying like me.
The audience was as casually integrated by race as any I remembered
from the club scene, even if it produced some sounds I never heard
at the Village Vanguard _ sniffles, whimpers, juice boxes being
sucked dry.
</P>
<P>
   We parents had lived long enough to see jazz finally win
acceptance as an American art form. The jazz program at Lincoln
Center enjoys the same institutional status there as the
Metropolitan Opera. And the seven-year-old series of children's
concerts, which continues Saturday with a program about Duke
Ellington, consciously models itself on Leonard Bernstein's
classical Young People's Concerts presented from 1958 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   My jazz education had been of the informal and nocturnal sort.
It began at college in Wisconsin with an older friend on the campus
newspaper. He was listening to Sinatra when I was listening to
Jethro Tull, and at the time I thought him hopeless. But
occasionally late at night, driving back to the dorms from the
print shop, he would tune his car radio to catch ``The Best of All
Possible Worlds,'' Harry Abraham's jazz show out of Rochester, and
I understood some powerful disclosure was being made.
</P>
<P>
   When I moved to the New York area a few years later, I sought
out the sound. I flopped over the floor pillows in the Jazzmania
Society's loft as Cecil Bridgewater played, embarrassed and nearly
impoverished myself by showing up to hear Marian McPartland at the
Carlyle with a flannel shirt on my back and a small-town reporter's
salary in my pocket. I would shamble to bed at 3 or 4 a.m. and wake
the next afternoon to buy records.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the toddler next to us gummed a bagel, Aaron and I
watched Marsalis stride across the stage, Italian-cut suit draped
elegantly on his frame, trumpet and plunger in hand. Seven side
men, all turned out in similarly immaculate style, awaited him. And
on a music stand, instead of a fake book, rested a script from
which Marsalis, in true jazz fashion, would freely improvise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today,'' he explained, ``we're going to find out what makes a
jazz singer.'' As the pianist Renee Rosnes underscored him, he went
on, ``Singing jazz means improvising, singing blues, swinging,
playing with words _'' he paused to inspect his dapper self ``_ and
looking good doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the laughter died down, he guided the band into a New
Orleans syncopation of the spiritual ``Just a Closer Walk With
Thee.'' Aaron perched forward in his seat, then turned to me.
``It's the horns,'' he said excitedly. ``The horns make it a good
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to agree. In all the years I had listened to Marsalis, I
had admired his music more than I had viscerally responded to it.
The one exception was ``Fathers and Sons,'' a record on which
Marsalis played with his mentor, his father Ellis, a pianist. On
that release, so joyous, so effervescent, Wynton Marsalis had laid
down the burden of being a prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   The same easy delight came through in his teaching. In his years
running the Jazz for Young People program, Marsalis has played
kazoo, cracked toothpaste jokes and dribbled a basketball to make
rhythm visible. On this morning, he demonstrated vibrato by shaking
his body along with his voice. Looking at his inspired looseness, I
remembered the time Bernstein used one of his televised concerts to
extol the Beatles' chord structure in ``Norwegian Wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Marsalis led the band through Scott Joplin's
``Maple Leaf Rag,'' I spotted Aaron playing imaginary piano keys.
When Wycliffe Gordon put down his trombone to growl through the
Count Basie standard ``Goin' to Chicago Blues,'' I noticed Aaron
miming the bassist plucking away, then writing the name of the song
in his notebook.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The auditorium went dark as Marsalis introduced a film clip of
Louis Armstrong. Aaron asked me if I knew who he was. I started to
tell him about a poster of Armstrong I had at home, part of a
promotional campaign for a radio station that no longer exists, but
then I realized there was a much more personal story, and I
whispered a shorthand version of it beneath the soundtrack of
Armstrong doing ``Dinah.''
</P>
<P>
   My parents went for years to the same internist, Dr. Gary
Zucker, who treated Armstrong. In the waiting room one day, my
mother saw him emerge from an appointment, grabbed an envelope from
the receptionist and had the trumpeter autograph it for me. I was
perhaps 10 then, years away from even the Jethro Tull stage of my
listening life and, as far as I knew, my mother's taste ran to
classical music and flamenco guitar. Only after she died and I
found an orange crate of her Glenn Miller and Billy Eckstine
records in the basement did I understand why she had leaped to get
a jazzman's signature.
</P>
<P>
   On the Lincoln Center screen, Armstrong gave way to Billie
Holiday and then Ella Fitzgerald as Marsalis explained phrasing and
scatting. Milt Grayson, a guest vocalist with the band, turned his
oaken bass voice to a languorous version of ``Do Nothin' Till You
Hear From Me.'' I thought of a weekend 15 years earlier when I had
sat at the Blue Note bar two nights in a row to hear Johnny
Hartman. Now, in my concert seat, noon felt like midnight, sultry,
melancholy midnight.
</P>
<P>
   All the balladry, though, was taxing Aaron. He slumped down in
his seat, crossed his arms. There is a certain experience of love
and loss at the heart of any torch song that eludes a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting bored,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   The words chilled me. I'd heard them for one football season
after another in my futile effort to turn Aaron into a Giants fan.
His 4-year-old sister already showed more potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few more songs,'' I pleaded, consulting the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to eat lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stay, we can have pancakes after.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then the tempo picked up, with some television clips of
Jimmy Rushing shouting the blues song ``Take Me Back, Baby.'' When
the guest vocalist, Sister Mekea Keith, dug into the bop
composition ``In Walked Bud,'' Aaron waved his tissue in time. We
left the auditorium after the chanting the ``doo-wah, doo-wah''
chorus of the final song, ``It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got
That Swing).''
</P>
<P>
   ``The concert was fun,'' Aaron announced over the promised
pancakes at a West Side diner. ``I decided I like jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home late that afternoon, I put on a Joe Williams CD so
Aaron could again hear the ``Goin' to Chicago Blues.'' Then I went
to my desk, opened a drawer of keepsakes and withdrew a yellowing
envelope inscribed with the autograph of Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Performance Information
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz For Young People series continues Saturday at 11 a.m.
and 1 p.m. with a program titled ``Happy Birthday to Duke.'' As
part of the centennial of Duke Ellington's birth, Wynton Marsalis
will lead a big band through a program including such classic
compositions as ``C-Jam Blues,'' ``The Mooche'' and ``Harlem Air
Shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   A jazz ensemble will appear with Marsalis in ``What Is Hot?,''
the last concert in the series, on May 22 at 11 a.m. and 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's shows are sold out but returned tickets may be
purchased an hour before each performance at the box office of
Alice Tully Hall. Tickets are $15 for adults and $10 for those
under 18. Information: (212) 875-5599. Tickets: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
