<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLESH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCHOOL OF FLESH': SHE LOVES HIM, BUT HE LOVES OTHERS, INCLUDING
MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The School of Flesh,'' that wonderfully complicated French
actress Isabelle Huppert demonstrates an uncanny ability to weep
buckets while remaining poker-faced, her tears appearing to emanate
from a realm somewhere beyond feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between Ms. Huppert's copious tears and her
apparent calm makes watching the movie, filmed by Benoit Jacquot,
the acclaimed French director of ``A Single Girl'' and ``Seventh
Heaven,'' a little confusing. For ``The School of Flesh'' is about
the greedy, unfettered carnal passion of two people and the
desperate power games it leads them to play.
</P>
<P>
   But because there are so few signs of genuine passion between
the lovers, the movie often seems like a terrific idea that fell
into the wrong hands. Watching this handsomely filmed, deftly
edited but rather dry movie, you keep imagining the juice that a
director like Pedro Almodovar could have squeezed out of the same
story.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a novel by Yukio Mishima, ``The School of Flesh''
explores the relationship of a well-to-do Parisian woman in the
fashion business who falls madly in love with a much younger,
working-class boxer and bisexual hustler.
</P>
<P>
   Her lover, Quentin (Vincent Martinez), whom she picks up in a
gay bar after some heated eye contact, is a wiry, glowering young
stud who resembles a tougher, surlier Joaquin Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Their power struggle begins on their very first date, at an
arcade where Quentin, who loves video games, becomes so absorbed he
barely notices her. Dominique walks away in disappointment, then
suddenly changes her mind and returns.
</P>
<P>
   She is already hooked. Although she has been planning to pay for
his sexual services, during their first night together the
chemistry is so hot that in the morning he refuses to take her
money. Dominique impulsively decides to keep her new boyfriend. And
after consultations with Chris (Vincent Lindon), an employee in the
nightclub where Quentin works as a bartender, she secretly pays off
Quentin's debts and later comes to an arrangement in which she
gives him an allowance but permits him certain freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, who himself used to keep Quentin and who may also have
pimped for him, is one of the more unbelievable gay characters to
appear in a recent movie. A burly hirsute man who wears earrings
and eye shadow and walks with a flounce but still dresses like a
man, he suggests a garish ``La Cage Aux Folles''-inspired fantasy
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Chris is given to tossing off shrill declarations like ``I am 
girl'' that sound at once false and dated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The School of Flesh'' is the rare movie in which there isn't
enough sex. And the lovemaking that's shown is so tepid and
mechanically detached that the lovers' physical bond is never
discernible. All it would have taken to set this film's thermostat
at an appropriately high temperature is one brief scene like the
lovers' first encounter in Brigitte Rouan's 1998 film ``Post
Coitum, Animal Triste,'' a movie that deals with many of the same
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique and Quentin have the usual troubles that such
arrangements bring. Despite her better instincts, Dominique becomes
prying and possessive. She goes through Quentin's belongings and
interviews a prominent lawyer who once kept him.
</P>
<P>
   When Quentin disappears, she tracks him down to a remote street
corner where he is busily selling his body to male clients.
Everyone Dominique meets, however, assures her that Quentin really
prefers women. Eventually, she finds herself competing for
Quentin's affections with the teen-age daughter of one of her
closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lot happens, by the end of the film we know very
little more about what makes its characters tick than we knew at
the beginning. The emotions the movie deals with _ intense sexual
passion, jealousy, possessiveness and insecurity compounded by
differences of age and class _ are incendiary.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The School of Flesh'' insists on holding them at arm's
length, as though they are too hot to handle.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE SCHOOL OF FLESH
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Benoit Jacquot; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Jacques Fieschi, based on the novel ``Nikutai no
Gakko'' by Yukio Mishima; director of photography, Caroline
Champetier; edited by Luc Barnier; production designer, Katia
Wyszkop; produced by Fabienne Vonier; released by Stratosphere
Entertainment. Running time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Isabelle Huppert (Dominique), Vincent Martinez (Quentin),
Vincent Lindon (Chris), Marthe Keller (Madame Thorpe) and Francois
Berleand (Soukaz).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
