<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGARETTES-FILM-REVIE     02-25 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`200 CIGARETTES': SO, HOW WAS YOUR NEW YEAR'S EVE? SMOKIN'! 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Risa Bramon Garcia is a well-known casting director, and she
directs her first feature by doing what she does best: cast. The
MTV-produced ``200 Cigarettes'' gathers a partyful of young players
and barely gives them enough of a story line to puff on, but it
gets by on personality anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   It's no ``Smoke,'' but this loosely interwoven set of sketches,
breezily derivative of ``American Graffiti,'' does throw its
characters together in a New York setting on a conveniently fateful
night in each of their lives. The year is 1981, and all you need to
know about the story is that each reveler eventually finds a new
mate on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' is a chain-smoking shambles, but an enjoyable
one. It not only has nicotine poisoning but also 49 party songs on
its soundtrack, including a raga surf selection that's a hoot in
its own right. Its East Village setting is given a cool, zany look
that's fun even when a few of the characters become unduly grating.
</P>
<P>
   As two would-be groupies from Ronkonkoma, N.Y., Christina Ricci
and Gaby Hoffmann inflict braying accents that stop being funny
fast, and Jay Mohr is stuck with the one-note role of a vain
ladykiller. Kate Hudson, who is Goldie Hawn's daughter and has her
mother's grin and giggle, makes her feature debut adorably despite
being asked to spend part of the movie with dog excrement on her
coat.
</P>
<P>
   The funniest performances here come from Martha Plimpton as a
nervous wreck of a hostess, Dave Chappelle as the driver of a
tiger-upholstered disco taxi, Paul Rudd as a roguishly charming
birthday celebrant and Janeane Garofalo as his bad-tempered ex.
(Ms. Garofalo's entrance is the best moment in the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the story's amusing, unlikely swains are Casey Affleck as
a nice-guy punk, Brian McCardie as a Scotsman mocked as a lousy
lover and even Elvis Costello.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's Kevin spends the evening drifting around town with his
best friend, Lucy; though as played by Courtney Love, Lucy doesn't
much seem like anybody's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy and Kevin might start a halfhearted affair if she weren't
so busy bagging a smug, handsome bartender (Ben Affleck) who has a
few memorable pickup lines of his own. Like: ``My clothes and those
clothes would look good on my floor.'' And: ``By the way, how do
you like your eggs in the morning? Scrambled or fertilized?''
</P>
<P>
   Lurking behind the studied debauchery in a film (written by
Shana Larsen) that really boils down to smoking, drinking and
finding one-night stands, is an affecting sense that this
particular party is about to be over.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS and yuppiehood are just beyond the horizon, as witnessed by
the way Ben Affleck's character voices a secret yen to get into
real estate law. ``Punk was dying, and people were looking for
something to believe in,'' McCardie has said about the film's 1981
ethos. ``They chose Jane Fonda's workout video.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual references, mild
profanity and heavy emphasis on smoking and drinking throughout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
