<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKS-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-25 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREAKS UNCENSORED!': AND HERE, A CHILD SOLD BY A DISGUSTED MOTHER
AND FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those drawn to the world of circuses, sideshows, amusement
parks and carnivals, ``Freaks Uncensored!'' possesses the appeal of
a well-stuffed scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping archives and private collections, this documentary,
opening Friday for a run through Sunday at Anthology Film Archives
in Manhattan, sprints through the history and lore of the unusual
people who have been gaped and gawked at by everyone from royalty
and scientists to so-called ordinary people and their offspring
strolling a midway while a barker beckons.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who steps right up to ``Freaks Uncensored,'' directed and
edited by Ari Roussimoff and produced by Vivian Forlander, will see
plenty of odd and malformed humanity, from so-called giants, whose
height was usually exaggerated, to bearded ladies, dwarfs and
midgets, armless and legless men and women, four-legged people,
conjoined twins, human pincushions and other sideshow attractions.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the film sheds historical light on people like
Jo-Jo the Russian Dog-Faced Man and some of the actors like the
Hilton twins, Johnny Eck, Zip and Pip and Schlitzie, who appeared
in Tod Browning's 1932 classic, ``Freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkable film clips show a splendid German tenor whose height
of four feet denied him a career in opera, and the armless Carl
Unthan, whose dexterous feet enabled him to play the trumpet, deal
cards, remove the cork from a bottle and pour drinks into tiny
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   But for its commentary and narrative, ``Freaks Uncensored!''
relies too heavily on people already involved in the sideshow
milieu or attracted to it, like the young bearded lady Madame
Xenobia (Jennifer Miller); James Taylor, the author and publisher
of the sideshow periodical Shocked and Amazed; David F. Friedman, a
carnival entrepreneur and exploitation film producer, and Jack
Dracula, the tattooed wonder.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know 42nd Street and Times Square only in its
Disneyfied renaissance, Jack Dracula proves an instructive guide as
scenes of the old Hubert's Flea Circus premises unreel.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Freaks Uncensored!'' makes clear that the
malformations and anomalies it shows are largely of a nature now
well understood by medicine and science, the film would be improved
by the presence of a few dispassionate expert voices to discuss
these conditions and the psychological impact of sideshow life on
individuals sometimes abandoned or sold by their parents as well as
to analyze and assess the impulses that continue to draw audiences
to these exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   When the film wanders off for a while into Hitler's
extermination of the abnormal and Jesus' kindness to lepers, there
is an inescapable feeling that ``Freaks Uncensored!,'' though
compassionate, is weighted heavily toward the curiosity component
of sideshow life and has ventured into depths it is ill-equipped to
deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the historical value of its content, ``Freaks
Uncensored!'' offers a lively and eclectic score by John Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest wisdom imparted by this film comes from the
malformed Jeanie Tomaini, billed as the last living circus
half-lady, who says she has yet to meet a normal person.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FREAKS UNCENSORED! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Human Sideshow
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by Ari Roussimoff; written by Roussimoff and
Vivian Forlander; music by John Watts; produced by Ms. Forlander;
released by Bohemia Productions. At the Anthology Film Archives, 32
Second Avenue at Second Street, East Village. Running time: 100
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jeanie Tomaini, the half-lady; Jack Dracula, the tattooed
man; Jennifer Miller, the bearded female performance artist; James
Taylor, author of the periodical Shocked and Amazed; Joe Petro III,
collector; David F. Friedman, carnival entrepreneur, and Ari
Roussimoff (the Jester).
</P>
</TEXT>
