<SLUG> BC-GOP-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LINES DRAWN OVER CALIFORNIA GOP LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The nuns and priests who read the San
Francisco Faith newsletter may have found mild interest in an
interview last month with John McGraw, the self-described Irish
Catholic vice chairman of the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But McGraw's comment that ``killing our babies ... is the issue
of the century'' was immediately pounced upon by an abortion-rights
faction of the Republican Party, opening a nasty debate just as the
GOP is attempting to repair its damaged image.
</P>
<P>
   Possible Republican presidential candidates, including Elizabeth
Dole, former Vice President Dan Quayle and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, arrive here this weekend for the state GOP convention. But
the candidates' beauty pageant threatens to be overshadowed by
McGraw's interview with the obscure Catholic newsletter and the
turmoil it created.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect this would trigger a civil war in the
California GOP,'' said San Francisco Faith editor George Neumayr,
who interviewed McGraw only because he thought it was interesting
that a ``traditional'' Catholic would rise so high in the party.
``I certainly wasn't trying to stir up trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGraw, 37, opened his mouth. Although none of his comments
should surprise anyone familiar with devout Catholics or
conservative Republicans, they have forced McGraw to defend himself
and have jeopardized his once-certain chance to become state party
chairman this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy highlights the Republican Party's continuing
struggle to define itself with voters more interested in
kitchen-table issues such as health reform and education than
abortion or gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to reach out to minority communities and women,
and his comments were not in good judgment,'' said Nicholas Bavaro,
who is challenging McGraw for the state party's top post. ``The
California Republican Party needs to elect a chairman, not a
pope.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of state Republicans is attempting to remove a portion
of the GOP platform that opposes abortion. Another faction wants
the platform left alone and GOP campaign money withheld from
politicians who don't support a ban on late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, McGraw said bishops should withhold communion
from Catholic politicians who support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can they go out and actively lobby for something that is
fundamentally opposed to one of the basic teachings of our
church?'' he told the Faith.
</P>
<P>
   But McGraw gave the pro-choice Republican camp its greatest
weapon when he told the Faith, ``The most important issue by far is
the abortion issue. I don't care what anybody says ... Killing our
babies ... is the issue of the century ... Compared to that,
cutting taxes or any other issue pales in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the centrist image the Republican Party wants to
project, particularly after the November elections. The party's
anti-abortion gubernatorial candidate, Dan Lungren, lost by a wide
margin. Dave Stirling, the anti-abortion candidate for attorney
general, lost to a Democrat by 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats gained a large majority in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party has an identity crisis and we allowed
Democrats to take our issues. They killed us,'' said Bavaro, 46, a
self-described ``blue-collar'' Republican from Modesto who
announced four weeks ago that he was challenging McGraw for the
chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Mr. McGraw's points of view, but the interview (with
the Faith) was not conducted with him as a person; it was about him
being the next chairman of the Republican Party,'' Bavaro said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGraw has avoided talking to the news media. He recently issued
a statement saying the interview with the Faith ``reflects my
personal moral priorities'' and contended the party represents a
``diverse and broad spectrum of members who come together behind
certain core beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that one should be able to discuss his or her moral
priorities as a Catholic without having them confused with the
priorities of the California Republican Party,'' McGraw said in the
statement. ``I regret if there has been any confusion on this
point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
