</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLIND FAITH': TRAGEDY AT HOME AND IN THE COURTROOM FOR A BLACK
YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The courtroom drama ``Blind Faith,'' directed with conviction
and restraint by Ernest Dickerson, describes a hate crime and the
miscarriage of justice that it engenders.
</P>
<P>
   With a first-rate performance by Courtney B. Vance as an
embattled defense attorney, it manages to explore more kinds of
prejudice than might be expected. Receiving a theatrical release a
year after it aired on Showtime, it looks all too timely today.
</P>
<P>
   Set mostly in 1957 with a quick opening reference to the 1989
murder of Yusuf Hawkins by a mob of white youths in Bensonhurst,
the story revolves around three black brothers. John ( Vance) is
the decent lawyer trying to get a career started. Eddie (Kadeem
Harrison) is the reefer-smoking, jazz-playing brother regarded as a
ne'er-do-well by Charles (Charles S. Dutton), a stern police
officer with rigid ideas about how his relatives ought to behave.
</P>
<P>
   It is Charles' son, Charlie (Garland Witt), who is seen first as
a nice boy hoping to take art lessons and, next thing the audience
knows, is being held on a murder charge. He is accused of having
strangled a white boy. And the only known witnesses to the crime
are the white boy's white friends.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie has already signed a confession, which makes John's
legal maneuvering even trickier than it would otherwise be. But
John eventually discovers, in a well-delineated if overly tidy way,
that the events surrounding the murder are not what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   And he realizes that Charlie faces an even tougher battle at
home than he does in the courtroom. A sharply manipulative turn
late in the story makes Charlie's plight even more tragic than it
first seemed, and ultimately sends the viewer home with a lesson to
be learned.
</P>
<P>
   What gives ``Blind Faith'' its forceful tone is the actors'
intense interaction, especially in scenes between Dutton and Vance.
It's also notable here that in a cast that also includes Lonette
McKee (as Charles' wife and Charlie's mother), strong language is
used sparingly and with care.
</P>
<P>
   Though the case itself is an obscenity and could well prompt
obscene talk, the film (written by Frank Military) saves its
harshest language for a scene in which Charles finally explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from so stern a character, these words really mean
something, and get right to the reason why ``Blind Faith'' is a
father-son tragedy in the end.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   BLIND FAITH
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ernest Dickerson; written by Frank Military;
director of photography, Rodney Charters; edited by Stephen
Lovejoy; music by Ron Carter; production designer, Jeff Ginn;
produced by Nick Grillo; released by Roxie Releasing. Running time:
118 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Charles S. Dutton (Charles Williams), Courtney B. Vance
(John Williams), Kadeem Hardison (Eddie Williams), Lonette McKee
(Carol Williams) and Garland Whitt (Charles Williams Jr.).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-8MM-REVIEW-LADN     02-25 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-8MM-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`8MM' WALLOWS IN THE SLEAZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients  on Friday, Feb. 26 or
thereafter ) 
OUR RATING: 2 STAR S 
By  BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the thoroughly unpleasant ``8mm,'' Nicolas
Cage does a 180 from his performance in his last intolerable
thriller, ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous film boasted an eye-popping, over-the-top attempt
to distract us from its nonsensical cluelessness; in this one, Cage
plays it so grave and depressive that our attention repeatedly
drifts away from him. We end up wallowing in ``8mm's'' deviant,
clammy atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It's not anything you want to be exposed to for extended lengths
of time.
</P>
<P>
   Cage plays Tom Welles, a working-class guy whose impressive
self-control and discretion has lifted him up to the status of
Pennsylvania high society's favorite private eye. Married to a
well-bred writer (Catherine Keener) and the father of a baby
daughter, Welles lives in a picturesque little house beside a
pleasant, woodsy creek.
</P>
<P>
   That he doesn't seem to mind spending much of his time away on
business and gets a kind of perverse pleasure out of lying to his
wife about quitting smoking would perhaps indicate some dark
resentment roiling beneath Welles' buttoned-down veneer.
</P>
<P>
   But nah, the script does take Welles on a nightmare journey in
which his assumptions about himself are confronted and tested, but
what's revealed is a pretty simple, standard bent for
self-righteous vigilantism. Writer Andrew Kevin Walker doesn't
bring out the complexities of motivation he got at in his superior
script for ``Seven,'' let alone the kind of character
contradictions initially hinted at here.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Welles is hired by a super-wealthy widow to quietly
investigate a reel of film depicting a teen-age girl apparently
being murdered _ the proverbial snuff film _ that was found in her
late husband's private safe. She wants reassurance that the sick
production was staged, that the unknown girl is still alive. Money,
of course, is no obstacle, so the case becomes Welles' quest.
</P>
<P>
   An extended stretch of detective grunt work leads Welles to a
tentative identification of the victim, then to the film's best
scenes: meetings with the long-missing girl's sad, lonely mother,
magnificently played by Amy Morton as a woman whose hopelessness
gives her a strange kind of sustenance. The trail then meanders to
Hollywood's porno underworld, where Welles descends deeper and
deeper into the purgatory of extra-legal fetish stuff: hard-core
domination, kiddie porn, fake snuff.
</P>
<P>
   His guide through these circles of desire is Max Hollywood
(Joaquin Phoenix), an aspiring musician and adult-bookstore clerk
who proves a resourceful, goofy font of hidden knowledge. Welles
eventually locates a sleazy, X-video producer (James Gandolfini,
overdoing the ooze) and a New York director of bizarre
``specialty'' films (Peter Stormare, overdoing everything). From
there, things get bloody, obsessive, demented ... but not
necessarily any better than the low-key passages that dragged on
before.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Joel Schumacher, best-known for his ``Batman''
sequels and John Grisham potboilers. He is obviously reaching for
something deeper and more stirring with ``8mm,'' but the execution
is too often superficial and confused. A film with this kind of
degraded subject matter has to be sharply insightful and resonate
deeply, like a ``Boogie Nights'' did, to justify itself. Otherwise,
it just comes off as exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   You can see Schumacher trying to get at something serious
throughout ``8mm,'' but he's overwhelmed by the film's tawdry
elements. When you roll around in this stuff, it's hard to not look
dirty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SISTER-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-25 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``THE OTHER SISTER'': THE GODS MAY BE LONG, BUT YOU CAN BET ON
LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A beautifully acted love story about two mentally challenged
young people struggling for independence and self-respect, ``The
Other Sister'' is a movie that's so eager to please it includes not
just one but two triumphal wedding scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Those two scenes give this lumbering, overlong movie successive
endings that feel clumsily tacked together, not to mention
manipulative. At one of the ceremonies, the participants re-enact a
variation of the wedding at the end of ``The Graduate,'' a film to
which ``The Other Sister'' alludes so frequently and shamelessly
that the references smack of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the song ``Mrs. Robinson'' (performed by the
Lemonheads) is even recycled for strained dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   The need for all this candy-coating and referential weight is
understandable, given the movie's subject. For ``The Other Sister''
focuses so intensely on the problems facing Carla (Juliette Lewis),
24, a spunky mentally retarded woman trying to make her way in the
world after being discharged from a special school, that while
watching the film you often share the frustration of her
overprotective, high-powered mother, Elizabeth (Diane Keaton).
</P>
<P>
   When Carla falls in love with Danny (Giovanni Ribisi), a young
man whose mental impairment is a bit more severe than hers, the
scenes of the two making elaborate plans to have sex press
uncomfortable emotional buttons. The movie dares you to feel a
derisive superiority.
</P>
<P>
   What redeems the film, directed by Garry Marshall, who gave us
``Pretty Woman,'' are its three outstanding performances. The
gawky, shining-eyed, stubbornly willful Carla is played by Ms.
Lewis with enormous heart and sensitivity, and with body language
so precise that you soon forget it is a performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keaton's finely nuanced portrait of a kind of maternal
perfectionist and overachieving Martha Stewart type we all know
finds her character's soul beneath her irritatingly high-strung
surface. The boldest performance of all is Ribisi's Danny, a mostly
endearing character who at moments can seem repulsive, even a
little monstrous.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins with Carla's return from the school to the
bosom of her well-to-do family. Once Carla is home, Elizabeth
expects her daughter to study art, learn to play tennis and conform
as much as possible to the image of a genteel West Coast woman of
means. She had always assumed that Carla would remain a child
requiring parental supervision and protection.
</P>
<P>
   But Carla doesn't like to play tennis, isn't interested in art
and is probably incapable of cultivating her mother's refined
manners. Utterly guileless and bluntly candid about her feelings,
she speaks with a loud, unguarded naivete that Elizabeth can barely
tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   While at school, she learned that people ``do it.'' And she is
pleased as punch to discuss her knowledge of human biology at the
dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for independence, Carla persuades her mother to let
her attend a Bay Area technical school and begins taking a computer
class. When this works out, Carla announces that she wants to live
on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by her father, Radley (Tom Skerritt), and her sisters
Caroline (Poppy Montgomery) and Heather (Sarah Paulson), she
persuades an extremely reluctant Elizabeth to let her live in her
own apartment in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest of all for Elizabeth to accept is Carla's relationship
with Danny, a good-natured fellow student and fanatical devotee of
marching bands who shares Carla's mental incapacity.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the movie's best scenes show Carla and Danny
successfully, if precariously, making their way in the world,
learning to communicate and falling in love. As they achieve one
small victory after another, you can almost feel the movie cheering
them on.
</P>
<P>
   But each new step toward autonomy presents a new crisis. While
the movie doesn't show the daily humiliations Carla and Danny
endure, their fragile self-esteem is evidence enough of what they
have suffered. Both are inclined to fall to pieces whenever they
think they are being laughed at.
</P>
<P>
   The movie awkwardly shoehorns in other lessons in tolerance. One
of Carla's sisters is a lesbian whose lover Elizabeth refuses to
acknowledge. A nasty marital spat between Elizabeth and Radley
reveals him to be a recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Because these additional elements of the family dynamic remain
undeveloped, they only add clutter. But for all its
disease-of-the-week television movie inclinations, ``The Other
Sister'' has a core of integrity. Beneath their spiffy wedding
outfits are characters you can believe in.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER SISTER
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Garry Marshall; written by Marshall and Bob Brunner,
based on a story by Alexandra Rose, Blair Richwood, Marshall and
Brunner; director of photography, Dante Spinotti; edited by Bruce
Green; music by Rachel Portman; production designer, Stephen J.
Lineweaver; produced by Mario Iscovich and Ms. Rose; released by
Touchstone Pictures. Running time: 131 minutes. This film is rated
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Juliette Lewis (Carla), Diane Keaton (Elizabeth), Tom
Skerritt (Radley), Giovanni Ribisi (Danny), Poppy Montgomery
(Caroline), Sarah Paulson (Heather) and Linda Thorson (Drew). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-GUERRILLAS27-     02-25 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-GUERRILLAS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI SOLDIERS AND HEZBOLLAH GUERILLAS A WORLD APART
 &HT;    Advance for use on or after Saturday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    EDS: For those who did not use it, this is an updated version of
a story that moved recently. It includes events this past week.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASHEET, Lebanon _ Images of bloodied young soldiers this week
sent Israelis into another anguishing round of outrage and mourning
over their seemingly endless war in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, three Israeli paratroopers were killed and five
wounded. They were walking to set an ambush for Hezbollah
guerrillas in south Lebanon, but guerrillas got the jump on them in
a fierce 15-minute fire fight.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first Israeli casualties this year in a
17-year-old war that has killed 897 Israelis, about 1,400 Hezbollah
fighters and more than 10,000 Lebanese civilians. The war, in which
Israel occupies a nine-mile wide swath of Lebanese territory, is
often called Israel's Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Though Israeli jets responded Thursday, killing four guerrillas,
stunned Israeli citizens were still analyzing the fatal night-time
gun battle. They noted that Hezbollah has steadily improved its
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But, tactics offer only an abstract view of the war. For a
personal view, you have to look under the scrub brush on Lebanon's
rocky hills, where Israelis and Hezbollah fighters act out roles
cast by two very different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Cox Newspapers interviewed two Hezbollah fighters and
two Israeli paratroopers, all of whom regularly set ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   They are emblematic of a war that pits east against west and
matches middle-aged Lebanese seeking Islamic martyrdom against
young Israelis fulfilling their rites of passage into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   About the only sentiment they hold in common is the anxiety of
waiting in ambush for days and nights at a time, eating little and
speaking in whispers.
</P>
<P>
   They all volunteered for the combat duty, but the two Hezbollah
guerrillas interviewed say they literally pray that they will die
fighting for their homeland. The Israelis, by contrast, say they
know they are just holding ground until there is a negotiated end
to the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are born here. We are religious and we love our land,''
says guerrilla Ahmad Sayeed, a 30-year-old house builder who leaves
his family many nights to fight in Hezbollah, the Party of God.
``We are all asking to be martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayeed and fellow fighter, Khalil Musa, 29, spoke in their
farming village of Brasheet. Israeli artillery shells often land
nearby and many guerrillas and civilians have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   With his flannel shirt and well-trimmed reddish beard, Sayeed
could pass for a middle class American contractor. Musa, with a
small black beard and steely eyes, is an electrician who wires
buildings by day and Hezbollah bombs at night.
</P>
<P>
   Musa says his ambushes have killed four Israelis. Asked if he's
ever sorry for the fallen Israelis, he shakes his head with
certainty: ``Never . . . the behavior of the Israelis makes us
carry our weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls Israeli soldiers ``cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis, meanwhile, are well aware of Hezbollah's
determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the big advantage for them. For us, it's not even
worth getting wounded,'' says paratrooper Moti Rubin, 20, speaking
at an army base near his home city, Jerusalem, between stints in
Lebanon. ``In truth, I don't care about the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has a crooked smile and curly hair that his commanding
officer repeatedly tells him to cut. He chose duty in the elite
paratroopers for the personal challenge it poses. Eventually, he'll
head to business school in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he knows the rules of the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the guerrillas) believe they are going to heaven if they
die killing you, then you don't just wound them, you have to kill
them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When you see someone walking at night in the Lebanese mountains,
he says, you shoot him. ``It's for sure he's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Itamar Haviv, another 20-year-old paratrooper, sees fighting as
part of a patriotic duty to protect northern Israel, just as his
own father did when he fought in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   When Haviv is done, he wants to be a tour guide. He's single
now, but hopes his children will not have to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's Musa is not so optimistic, as he looks over his
village toward the Israeli fort on a nearby hill and discusses his
10-year-old, Issa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will follow in my way,'' he says. ``We want to be martyrs
so, if he is killed, I am not afraid of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
