<P>
   SOUP-KITCHENS-I (Peekskill, N.Y.) _ A stream of low-wage
workers, retirees and refugees from public-assistance are swelling
the lines at soup kitchens and food pantries across America. Some
are the welfare-to-work versions of an old phenomenon: the working
poor caught in the middle _ too well off for public assistance but
not well enough off to make it on their own. Some are immigrants
who are here legally but were cut off from food stamps under new
federal welfare laws. Some are following a path of least
resistance: rather than jump through hoops designed to tarnish the
appeal of public aid, they are turning to private charities.
Together, they are changing the face of food lines long occupied by
the addicted, the disabled, the generally down-and-out. And they
may help explain a puzzle confronting poverty analysts: Why have
the lines kept growing when unemployment is at its lowest level in
a generation and the economy has remained healthy for years? By
Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (3000 words with an abridged version of about 1500 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (First of two articles. The second looks at the supply side and
the increasing difficulty churches and other groups have in reeling
in the grocery industry's castoffs.)
</P>
