<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     02-25 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: HAROLD RAMIS, JULIETTE LEWIS, GUY RITCHIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychotherapy He Can't Refuse
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Harold Ramis, the director of ``Groundhog Day'' and
``Caddyshack,'' is a deep believer in psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lifetime interest in psychotherapy,'' said Ramis, 54,
the writer and comedian who appeared in ``Stripes'' and the
``Ghostbusters'' films. ``I know a great number of therapists. I've
relied heavily on psychotherapy during every crisis of my life.
I've done therapy with my wives, my children, my brother, my
parents. We've all been in sessions together.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with his commitment to psychotherapy, Ramis also has a
fascination for the Mafia. ``I'm a sucker for gangster mythology,
just like everyone else in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So it was perhaps inevitable that Ramis would merge these
interests into a comedy, ``Analyze This,'' with an unlikely plot: A
big-time New York gangster (Robert De Niro), about to assume his
role as leader of his crime family, is stricken with anxiety and
panic attacks that worry his loyal henchmen. How does the gangster
deal with his crisis? He consults a suburban New York
psychotherapist (Billy Crystal) who has plenty of problems of his
own. The film opens March 5.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was not especially easy to lift off the ground. It
went through numerous writers and, more important, the two stars
were nervous about their roles. De Niro initially wanted his
longtime collaborator, Martin Scorsese, to make the film. When
Scorsese turned it down, De Niro and Crystal seriously considered
directing the film together, which probably would have been a
formula for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And both stars, at least at the outset, were nervous about
acting with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was afraid Billy would turn it into a sentimental farce, a
sitcom; he was afraid it would be too pat, too unrealistic,'' said
Ramis, ultimately the film's director and one of its writers. ``And
Billy was afraid it would turn into `Goodfellas': too violent, too
mean spirited. I came in sort of to reconcile these points of view.
I reassured Billy the film would be funny. And I told Bob this
wouldn't be a sendup of `The Godfather.' I said, `Imagine you're
watching `Goodfellas,' and Woody Allen enters.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the two stars not only enjoyed making the
movie but overcame their initial hesitancy about working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we all were a little intimidated about working with
De Niro,'' Ramis said. ``But I try to approach things in a Zen-like
way. I don't deal with images, I deal with people. And De Niro is
virtually image free. He's totally about work. He's not
pretentious. He's totally focused on the task and what should be
done at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramis, who lives in Chicago, said he was not especially
concerned about the new and successful Home Box Office series ``The
Sopranos,'' which includes a Mafia leader who visits a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll be hurt,'' Ramis said. ``You remember the
movie `Big.' It was practically the fourth movie to come out that
year where an adolescent was transformed into an adult. The others
pretty much went away.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors' Challenge
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Juliette Lewis has a reputation for sometimes startling
performances in a career that has already swerved up and down. Her
films have veered from Martin Scorsese's ``Cape Fear,'' for which
she was nominated for an Academy Award for supporting actress;
Woody Allen's ``Husband's and Wives,'' and Lasse Hallstrom's
``What's Eating Gilbert Grape,'' to mishaps like ``Kalifornia,''
``Natural Born Killers'' and ``Romeo is Bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year hiatus _ ``I sort of eliminated the enemy from
within by doing good things for myself'' _ Ms. Lewis has returned
in her most challenging and high-profile role. She plays Carla, a
somewhat retarded young woman who wants to make a life for herself,
in the bittersweet romantic comedy ``The Other Sister.'' The film
is directed by Garry Marshall, who wrote the screenplay with Bob
Brunner.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opens Friday, also stars Giovanni Ribisi as Ms.
Lewis' boyfriend, a character who is also struggling to forge an
independent life despite his retardation, and Diane Keaton as Ms.
Lewis' overprotective mother.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based loosely on the memories of Alexandra Rose, one
of the producers, who had a friendship with a mentally disabled
woman. In the film the two main characters are functioning and
productive people, seeking to earn their own livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, whose biggest hit as a director was ``Pretty Woman,''
said he fought hard to get Ms. Lewis the role despite concerns by
executives at Walt Disney Co., which made the film. Among other
issues, executives doubted that the actress could play a romantic
and gentle role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed someone with power and determination,'' Marshall
said. ``She's probably the most powerful young actress since Jodie
Foster came along. But I knew she wasn't a laugh riot. We talked,
and she read for the part. I asked her if she had anything against
comedy. She said, `No one ever asked me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis and Ribisi, who played the doomed medic in ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' spent time with mentally disabled children and
teen-agers at two Los Angeles schools, the McBride Special
Education Center and the Exceptional Children's Foundation, as well
as with older people who were able to live alone and work despite
their retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Ribisi said, ``What struck me was how happy they were to be
working, to have a real job, their own apartments _ the
self-respect they had.'' Some of the students at the schools became
extras on the film.
</P>
<P>
   For both actors the challenge was to play the characters
honestly. It would have been easy, and embarrassing, they said, to
overact and unwittingly make the characters targets of comic
derision.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis said it took her a while to find the right tone for
the part. She found herself imitating the expressions and
intonations of her 2-year-old niece. She listened to countless
tapes of mentally disabled people having conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to invent this character and make it truthful,''
she said. ``High functional mentally handicapped people are as
varied as the colors of the rainbow. It was so scary because it was
so easy to do poorly. Unlike any other role, this one could have
been so self-conscious, so over the top. Once I found her voice, I
depended on Garry. I was always safe in his hands, which you don't
always find with directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said Ms. Lewis was a bit too hard on herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets insecure,'' he said. ``She kept asking: `Was I
honest? Was this right?' After a while she lightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ms. Keaton, an old friend, was an ally, especially
as the younger actors struggled with their roles. At one point,
before a big scene, Marshall decided to use a New Age strategy,
asking the cast to join him and hold hands. The younger actors
adored it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it thrilled Diane,'' said Marshall, laughing.
`` `Do I have to do it?' she asked. Diane was not big on holding
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said Ms. Keaton was also cast in an uncharacteristic
role for her, a wealthy suburban woman who wears designer clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised Diane good clothing; she got to wear great
outfits,'' Marshall said. ``I said. `I'll give you the clothes.'
She took the part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   One Tough Cast
</P>
<P>
   Guy Ritchie, who a few years ago was making commercials for
British television, has been absorbed with movies since childhood
and had an idea to make one in the East End of London. With a bow
to Quentin Tarantino, the idea was simple: A group of friends
bankroll a card shark for the biggest game in town. But the game is
a setup. He loses. And the friends must pay off a vicious
underworld boss a fortune _ or else.
</P>
<P>
   The caper, ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' is already a
big hit in Britain and opens in some cities in the United States
next Friday. What makes the film different from similar tough-guy
movies is its humor, its energy and, equally important, Ritchie's
decision to cast some ex-convicts and underworld figures he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to British gangster films, and the nuances of
accent and class structure, there's no way around it: you've got to
cast villains if you want bad guys,'' said Ritchie. ``Villains are,
generally speaking, good actors. They've been sharpening their
skills on policemen and judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, 30, said numerous members of the supporting cast had
been in prison. ``I couldn't work with a more polite, disciplined
and hard-working group of individuals,'' said Ritchie, who has
become a hot ticket in Hollywood and has been signed by a top
agent, Robert Newman of International Creative Management.
</P>
<P>
   There were other advantages of working with the unusual
supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually on a film like ours you need security guards to stop
things from being stolen,'' Ritchie said. ``We had none. There was
no thievery on the set. Everyone backed off once they knew who was
in the cast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
