<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN27-COX     02-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chimes, gongs stir symphony for the soul
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Saturday, Feb.27.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The sound garden is growing by bongs and chimes.
</P>
<P>
   When I first started planting in Atlanta 10 years ago, I put in
bamboo and ornamental grasses to add whispers and rustles to my
space _ a space already alive with the rat-a-tat-tat of acorns from
the pre-Civil War oak next door, the sighs and crackle of falling
leaves brushing stone and branch.
</P>
<P>
   The more, the mellower; a gardener benefits from sounds as
surely as from sights, smells and touches. Happily, the dancing
leaves of grass and the swaying bamboo canes entertained and
intrigued from the first, their sounds rising and falling with the
wind's intensity. Thin and reedy in soft breezes. Heavier, thicker
in strong gusts.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, I added a brass disk, hanging it on the
brick wall out back. The plate, about 18 inches wide, was
discovered when we had to pare down the household of Lyn's mother
and move her to a care home; Alzheimer's had gotten her.
</P>
<P>
   That disk remains as mysterious as its markings, as mysterious
as the disease that has robbed her and us of her memories. We
believe the once-shiny plate came from one of the many countries
Lyn's mother visited, but which one? When she visits us, she
listens as the plate catches a light breeze and gongs, softly,
listens in high winds as it gongs and bongs harder, longer, more
persistently. Maybe those sounds almost recall once-vivid
experiences . . . someplace.
</P>
<P>
   The disk, the bamboo and the grasses got company a few years ago
when I brought back from Savannah (Ga.) several bamboo chimes and
hung them on the porches _ front, side and back. Made from five
sections of various lengths, 10 to 15 inches long, the chimes twack
and thock in the winds, bringing to the garden that evocative sound
so reminiscent of the primeval clacking of canes in bamboo forests.
I love it.
</P>
<P>
   Lately I've been worrying about myself. Just as I recognized
obsession in my planting when my car no longer could pass a nursery
without wheeling in, I now fear I cannot resist anything that
brings sound to the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Others apparently recognize it, too. Our daughter and son-in-law
in Massachusetts gave us a bell for Christmas; it hangs high in the
saucer magnolia. It's a beautiful bell _ about 8 inches tall,
wearing a blue-green patina and a copper sail that catches breezes
and pulls the attached striker that makes the amazingly big sound
that recalls much bigger bells from little towns in exotic places.
</P>
<P>
   So many sounds in such a small space might be enough for the
unobsessed. But not for me. Recently I bought a metal chime. Like
the bamboo, it has five tubes of varying lengths. Its coppery sheen
caught my eye, as it now catches the sun's afternoon rays from its
porch perch.
</P>
<P>
   This newest chime plays a five-note pattern ``made famous by
blues artists in the 1920s,'' says its tag. ``The boogie-woogie
style.'' Well.
</P>
<P>
   Now when the wind picks up, I hear a symphony. A boogie-woogie
symphony? Out front the wind whistles through leaves of bamboo and
grass while metal and bamboo chimes chime in, providing pansies
some music to dance by. Out back, the plate and bell and the bamboo
chime play percussion for blowing reeds.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds are soothing as long as the breezes don't kick too
high. But with March winds on the way and my obsession at full
tilt, that symphony could segue into cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
