<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VULCAN28-COX     02-25 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VULCAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vulcan, the colossal iron statue that stands as the symbol of
Birmingham, stands in need of colossal repairs
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ From the ground, he still looks like a Roman god.
Vulcan, billed as the world's largest cast-iron statue, ripples
with bronzed metallic muscles as he looms atop Red Mountain with
his anvil and hammer, overlooking the city whose steelmaking
heritage he embodies.
</P>
<P>
   But if you climb his 123-foot pedestal and stand in the pigeon
poop around his sandaled feet, it's obvious that the man of iron
isn't in peak condition these days. His ankles are rusting. Lime
leaches down his calves. Water drips embarrassingly from his
crotch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vulcan is like a lot of people you meet in bars: better
looking from a distance,'' says Guy ``Beaner'' Patton, who co-hosts
the ``Beaner and Ken'' morning radio show on WRAX-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Patton had occasion to take an up-close look recently, because
Vulcan is in the news again. An engineer has warned that the statue
is deteriorating. Such warnings are nothing new; reports of the big
fellow's decay date back at least a decade. But this time there's
something more alarming: Vulcan, the very symbol of Birmingham, is
threatening to become a public safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davis, a structural engineer hired by the city to inspect
the statue, found cracks in its iron skin. He says that chunks of
metal as heavy as 250 pounds could fall, endangering the 110,000
people a year who visit the park and observation deck. At first,
Davis thought the cracks were narrow enough that he could place
ultrasound sensors to measure whether they were widening. But the
gaps were already too large, the damage too advanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could slip my ruler in some of the openings,'' says Davis,
who used to inspect nuclear power plants. ``The worst part is just
above his butt, where the apron covers his hips.''
</P>
<P>
   At 95, Vulcan isn't just some stiff-backed geezer showing his
age. He's a beloved civic mascot who's been around almost as long
as the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham was barely three decades old when it commissioned the
statue, to promote its burgeoning steel industry at the 1904
Louisiana Purchase Exposition in St. Louis. Since then, the city
has been transformed; the blast furnaces that once blackened its
sky have closed, and medicine has replaced metals as its defining
trade. Yet Birmingham remains emotionally attached to its old
identity as ``the Pittsburgh of the South,'' with Vulcan, the god
of iron and fire, as its monument.
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham telephone book lists 46 businesses with
``Vulcan'' in the name. Generations have taken dates to the park,
with some couples getting married there. Preachers sit on benches
writing sermons under the pagan deity. Motorists know that the
torch in Vulcan's right hand _ everyone says it looks like a
push-up Popsicle _ burns green unless someone has died in a traffic
accident. Then the police flip a switch and the light turns red, as
if Vulcan himself were mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy was a trucker, and it always pleased him to see that
the light was red when he left on one of his runs. He figured the
odds were with him then,'' remembers Atlanta writer Paul Hemphill,
who grew up in Vulcan's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham has even managed to work up a fondness for the iron
man's most curious feature: his bottom. Sculptor Giuseppe Moretti
boldly left the buttocks bare on his 56-foot-tall creation. Today,
one of the most popular souvenirs at the gift shop is a T-shirt
praising Vulcan's ``Buns of Iron.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popular affection for Vulcan, the city, which owns
the statue, has no immediate plans to overhaul it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any money earmarked for major repairs,'' Mayor
Richard Arrington announced after the cracks were discovered. He
promised that the city would patch the statue and make it safe for
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The job could have been finished by now. In 1994, a citizens'
task force led by the director of the Birmingham Historical Society
recommended a full reconditioning, like the one given the Statue of
Liberty in the 1980s. Vulcan would have been dismantled, recast
where needed and reassembled around a new steel skeleton. The cost
was estimated at $8 million, most of which the task force offered
to raise in private funds.
</P>
<P>
   But the city administration, busy with preparations for
Birmingham's bit part in the 1996 Olympic Games, didn't follow up
on the proposition. After the Games, the city placed its hopes for
repairing Vulcan on a bond referendum that went before voters last
year. It failed because the centerpiece, a new football stadium,
proved unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   So now the city is back at square one. While it weighs its
options, Davis, the engineering consultant, has placed audio
sensors on the statue to detect any movement in the cracks. If the
sensors pick up anything, an alarm sounds and the site is supposed
to be cleared.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't good enough for Vulcan's many fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are outraged that they're putting sensors on it so they
can listen while it falls apart,'' says Marjorie White, director of
the historical society. ``We need to take him down and repair him
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do something,'' The Birmingham News editorialized,
``and soon, before a big chunk of Birmingham's heritage and pride
comes crashing down Red Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses are offering to help. People are sending money to the
Chamber of Commerce. Television and radio stations are planning
fund-raisers, such as the save-Vulcan concert that WRAX wants to
stage at the statue. The only thing missing is a plan from Vulcan's
landlord, the city.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time he's needed help.
</P>
<P>
   After the statue returned from the fair in 1904, Birmingham
planned to erect it in a park but decided not to when neighbors
protested that its nekkid bum would offend the ladies. The statue
sat in pieces in a rail yard for two years. Then it was reassembled
(with its right hand put on backwards) at the state fairgrounds,
where it remained for the better part of 30 years. It was often
used as an advertising medium. Instead of a spear, Vulcan at times
held a giant ice cream cone or a Coca-Cola bottle; once he donned a
very large pair of Liberty overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan wasn't rescued from commercial indignities until 1936,
when the Works Progress Administration started building him a new
home atop Red Mountain, a ridge named for its vein of iron ore. In
his moment of glory, though, the seeds of his present dilemma were
sown.
</P>
<P>
   To stabilize the statue in high winds, workers filled Vulcan up
to his armpits with tons of concrete. The problem is that concrete
expands much faster than iron, meaning that the statue's innards
have been pressing against its skin for decades, cracking the
1-to-2-inch metal plating. To make matters worse, Vulcan has a big
hole in his head. It allows maintenance workers access to the
statue but also lets rainwater seep into the concrete, further
eroding the structure's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Crick has disappeared into that hole on many occasions.
Several times a month, the wiry sign company owner climbs the rungs
sunk into Vulcan's chest and inches out onto the arm to change some
of the 32 lights in the torch. He first noticed the cracks in
Vulcan's hip about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're getting worse,'' Crick says, as he puts on his
harness to brave another climb. ``We better take him down and fix
him before he kills somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Achmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
