<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNITTING-HOSPICE27-CO     02-25 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNITTING-HOSPICE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day after day, a Douglasville, Ga. woman crochets afghans that
provide warmth and comfort to AIDS or hospice patients
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Saturday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ellie Handsel is a woman on a mission. She sits alone,
focused on her work, quietly crocheting. Nine hours after
beginning, Handsel is finished, a beautiful lap robe complete,
ready to be sent off to a terminally ill patient or a person living
with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The next day she will start again. Nine hours of effort. Another
blanket. It's a daily routine she's followed for 10 years, creating
more than 3,500 lap robes.
</P>
<P>
   The blankets, typically placed over the lap and knees for
warmth, are given to clients of Project Open Hand, a meal delivery
service for people with AIDS, and to patients at various Atlanta
area hospices.
</P>
<P>
   Each blanket carries with it a brief note: ``This was made
especially for you with love, hope and care. Sincerely, Ellie.''
</P>
<P>
   The gesture is simple. The impact is huge. Recipients have been
buried with their blankets. Others have become cherished family
heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, it's the last gift and last note they will
ever receive,'' says Handsel, 61.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, a network of volunteers from across the country has
taken up Handsel's mission, providing nearly 1,000 lap robes a
year. The nonprofit enterprise has become known as ``Smoking
Needle,'' a nickname Handsel earned years ago for her quick
needlework.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-plus volunteers, called Ellie's Angels, work at their
own pace _ some take six months to do what Handsel does each day _
and range in age from 7-year-old Scouts to senior citizens in their
90s. Most out-of-state volunteers send their blankets to Atlanta;
some give them away close to home. And Handsel occasionally sends
blankets to organizations across the country that request them.
</P>
<P>
   One Atlanta volunteer, the late Elizabeth Copeland, understood
the power of the robes. ``Ellie's blankets are the hugs some of
these people never got,'' Copeland was fond of saying.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Phillips received such a gift six years ago, five years
after he was diagnosed with AIDS, three years after he was told he
would be dead. ``It's my prize possession,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, 39, also cherishes the lap robe of his longtime
partner, John Maben, who died last September. ``It's like having
him around,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta resident, now a volunteer with Project Open Hand,
delivers blankets Handsel has made for new clients. ``I've seen
grown men and women, rich and poor, break down and cry over them,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Handsel traces her desire to help the terminally ill to her
childhood in North Carolina, where she spent seven years in a
boarding school outside of Asheville. ``That's how I learned the
compassion that comes from loneliness,'' she says. ``And death is
the loneliest trip we will ever make.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Hammett, an epidemiologist with the Division of HIV/AIDS
Prevention at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
became a volunteer with Handsel to put a face to the numbers she
compiled on the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these (recipients) had been rejected by their families
and felt very alone,'' says Hammett. ``You should have seen their
faces, the tears in their eyes, when they found out someone who was
not even part of the family would take the time to knit a blanket
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Castor, 44, of Missoula, Mont., has knitted more than 100
blankets for Handsel. ``Just the satisfaction of helping someone
else is why I do it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Rolen, 43, a chaplain with SunAlliance Hospice in Dunwoody
(Ga.), calls Handsel's work a ``true random act of kindness.''
Rolen, who has delivered her lap robes to many patients, says,
``They add a lot of warmth to some pretty austere settings.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Handsel's life is pretty austere as well. Twice
divorced, she lives in a room in a friend's house in Douglasville
(Ga.). Her only source of income is the occasional signature afghan
and baby blanket she sells. Friends help to supply her food and
yarn.
</P>
<P>
   A painfully self-conscious woman, she spends most of the day
crocheting while listening to music (big-band jazz is a favorite),
watching television (especially PBS dramas) and talking on the
phone with her volunteers _ most of whom she has never met.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a recluse, but I am crazy about people,'' she says, then
jokingly adds, ``The only thing I can't do while I crochet is
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for Smoking Needle came in 1989 when her life was at
a crossroads. After a series of short-lived professional ventures _
from troubleshooting for a developer to operating a Atlanta art
gallery _ Handsel received an invitation from an interior designer
to make an afghan for the living room of Jerusalem House, a
residence in Atlanta for people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over to deliver it and found a patient who was
unconscious,'' Handsel says. ``I held his hands and talked to him.
His hands were freezing. They told me he had no friends and no
relatives. So I thought, why don't I make everyone here a lap robe?
And that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Handsel had found her mission, her reason for being.
</P>
<P>
   She begins crocheting shortly after waking each day and often
works late into the night. She refuses to take even a day off. If
she were offered a vacation, her needles would have to come along,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her singleness of purpose can be overbearing,'' says good
friend Richard Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   But such zeal does not go unnoticed or unappreciated. ``She's
just a good, good woman,'' says Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Handsel remains steadfast, focused, always thinking about the
next lap robe to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never stop,'' she says. ``This is my mission, this is
what I am convinced God put me on Earth to do, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
