<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANTS-HEAT27-COX     02-25 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANTS-HEAT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garden centers to tag plants according to tolerance for a
region's high-temperature extremes
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Saturday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some plants _ like some gardeners _ can't take the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some nurseries still sell them, and some gardeners still
buy them. Call it greed, call it ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change. Growers have begun using a new tool
aimed at helping consumers determine which plants can tolerate an
area's high temperatures. The plant heat-zone map, developed by the
American Horticultural Society, charts 12 color-coded regions of
the United States according to the annual average number of days an
area experiences ``heat days'' _ extremes during which temperatures
reach 86 degrees or higher and plants begin to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale nurseries gradually are adopting the map, developed
about a year ago, to indicate heat zones on tags of more than
20,000 different types of annuals, perennials and woody plants that
they sell to garden centers. That means that beginning this spring,
shoppers will be able to tell whether a plant is suitable for their
garden. A tag in a potted daisy identified as ``Z-8'' means that
plant should thrive in Zone 8, metro Atlanta, where the city
experiences heat days an average 90 to 120 days per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A garden happens when the right plants are in the right
place,'' said Marc Cathey, a horticultural scientist who spent 14
years developing the map. ``We're always asking ourselves if a
flower or plant will make it in our gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathey, the horticultural society's president emeritus, has
spent the past year traveling the country to raise awareness about
heat-zone gardening, and last week he had a captive audience at
Atlanta's Southeastern Flower Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking us, `Why didn't you do this years ago?' ''
he said. ``How many times have you bought a plant at a garden
center and said to yourself later, `Didn't they know you can't grow
that here?' Of course they knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The map, which Cathey helped develop using daily highs recorded
at nearly 5,000 U.S. weather stations between 1974 and 1995, is an
important breakthrough, given global warming worries. It's also
been hailed as the overdue equivalent of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Hardi-
</P>
<P>
   ness Zone Map, long used by growers to indicate a plant's
tolerance for cold.
</P>
<P>
   The horticultural society's goal is to get growers to indicate
both heat zones as well as hardiness zones in their catalog
listings and on their plant tags. So far, six catalogs carry the
desig-
</P>
<P>
   nations, and two California-based growers _ Monrovia and Paul
Ecke Ranch _ are marking their labels accordingly. In addition,
about a dozen gardening books and plant guides now list heat zones
with their plant descriptions. The latest resource is the
pocket-size AHS Great Plant Guide Featuring Over 2,000 Plants (DK
Publishing, $16.95), released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 zones range from seven months of heat days at the
southernmost tip of Florida to no heat days at elevations such as
Grandfather Mountain in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The designations are given in ranges _ ``Z 6-8'' for cold
hardiness zones, for example, and ``8-6'' for heat tolerance zones.
(The cold range is always given in increasing numbers; the heat one
in decreasing order.)
</P>
<P>
   Cathey expects that with Monrovia, one of the nation's largest
wholesalers, leading the way, most growers will follow suit and
that by next year heat-zone-tagged plants will be common.
</P>
<P>
   For plant retailers, that won't be a day too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heat has always been a troubling question _ something people
always wonder about,'' said Rick Berry, co-owner of Goodness Grows
nursery in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the information began to surface more than 15 years
ago, he said, as more consumers began to experi-
</P>
<P>
   ment in their gardens with perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Cathey also hopes the map will encourage gardeners to experiment
with underused plants rather than relying on old standards simply
``because they can take the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of the same old humdrum, the ironclad choices, in
everyone's yard,'' Cathey said. ``There's nothing wrong with
junipers, but why not try something else occa-
</P>
<P>
   sionally?''
</P>
<P>
   For Martha Wills, who has watched her share of misplaced plants
wither in her yard, the coding can't happen soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Macon, and the heat there is just terrible for our
yards,'' she said after hearing Cathey's presentation. ``I think
it's going to be the best thing since sliced bread.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Copies of the plant heat-zone map are available for $14.95
from the American Horticulture Society. Call 1-800-777-7931. Check
the Web site at http://www.ahs.org.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
