<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-ENGLISH27-COX     02-25 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-ENGLISH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singer Michael English returns to the 'Gospel' road
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Saturday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael English wants to be known as more than the
Christian singer who sinned.
</P>
<P>
   His singing career peaked and crashed during a two-day period
five years ago. After winning six Dove Awards _ the Christian music
industry's equivalent of the Grammy _ he admitted to having an
affair with another Christian singer.
</P>
<P>
   He returned the awards. His marriage ended. He quit performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize every night for what I've done,'' English now
says. ``My heart is just broken for the people who believed in me
and supported me.''
</P>
<P>
   But English never lost his love for gospel music. He began
performing gospel again about two years ago and will be in concert
in Atlanta at 7 p.m. Sunday at the First Baptist Church in Avondale
Estates.
</P>
<P>
   The concert is part of English's attempt to carve out a new
identity that's not linked with his infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait until the day when the headline will just read,
`Michael English in concert,''' he said. ``It's always something
like, `Singer, fallen from grace.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who want me to stay out of it, but that's not
what I'm going to do,'' English said. ``It's hard to forgive and
forget. They don't want to. That's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including several pastors and Christian musicians, have
offered encouragement. And recently the Christian music industry
seems to have softened its stand toward English.
</P>
<P>
   CCM Magazine, which covers contemporary Christian music, raved
about his latest album, ``Gospel,'' noting that his voice now has
``a rich, melancholy timbre'' and ``plaintive urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   English has also been invited to sing with the Gaither Vocal
Band and on the Trinity Broadcasting Network.
</P>
<P>
   Such acceptance is comforting, but English still sounded
melancholy at times during a recent phone conversation. He said his
``self-esteem was shot'' after his divorce and he's still adjusting
to being the single parent of a 14-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   But his mood brightens when he talks about performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a part of my soul, of my life. I ran from God after
all this happened and I did things I'm not proud of,'' English
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But God was telling me you've run long enough. It's time to
get back to where you started.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
