A9364 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-NYT &LR;      02-25 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 2903 Thu., Feb. 25: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY LAWYERS? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two attorneys went into a diner and ordered two drinks. Then
they produced sandwiches from their briefcases and started to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The owner became quite concerned and marched over and told them,
`You can't eat your own sandwiches in here!`
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys looked at each other, shrugged their shoulders and
then exchanged sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU DONT HAVE TO BE JEWISH &LR;  ...
</P>
<P>
   A funeral service is being held in a synagogue for a woman who
has just passed away. At the end of the service the pallbearers are
carrying the casket out, when they accidentally bump into a wall
jarring the casket.
</P>
<P>
   They hear a faint moan. They open the casket and find that the
woman is actually alive.
</P>
<P>
   She lives for ten more years and then dies. A ceremony is again
held at the same synagogue and at the end of the ceremony the
pallbearers are again carrying out the casket.
</P>
<P>
   As they are walking the husband cries out, `Watch out for the
wall!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are finding more asteroids falling toward Earth.
Would it help if the outfielders now in spring training had bigger
gloves?
</P>
<P>
   If Kosovo itself gets stretched out as long as the peace talks
about it, it may end up as Kosovovovovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be a country where we all serve together,'' says
Mr. Clinton. Is he proposing concurrent sentences?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. could be debt free in 19 years, Mr. Clinton says, ``if
future Congresses have the discipline to stay on this track.''
Nineteen years of Congressional discipline? He must have started
inhaling now.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders met with the president this week and
everyone promised to work together. Darn. We were hoping they'd
work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with the aging of America,'' Mr. Clinton says.
What's his proposal? Give everyone over 50 an intern to date?
</P>
<P>
   For Chelsea Clinton's upcoming 19th birthday, the First Family
plans to go skiing in Utah. Hasn't the president lately been on
enough slippery slopes?
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monument, though still surrounded by scaffolding
for repairs, is open to the public again. The drawback is that the
view from the top of it is, well, of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan says all Americans should ``feel proud'' of the
economy. We'd like to but we're just too busy working.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it knocked the wind out of you, too, but let's all try
to recover from the news that Pete Wilson won't be running for
president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan says money left in the bank on New Year's Eve
1999 will be safe. Well, safer there than hanging around bars that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy,'' says Greenspan, ``appears stretched in a number
of dimensions.'' Which means the economy resembles many of us
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton's legal defense fund raised $4.5 million last year,
it's reported. Which works out to about a dime per denial.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over the law creating the Office of Independent Council
shows that once we fix problems we spend most of our time fixing
the solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Al and Tipper Gore say they will become grandparents this
summer. It must be a relief when politicians know babies they
really want to kiss.
</P>
<P>
   A new ranking of the most important stories of the 20th century
shows the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal came in just 53rd. If that one
is so low, imagine how far down the Clinton-Jones scandal is. Or
Clinton-Flowers. Or Clinton. . .
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan may run for president again. Why not? Loud,
annoying people deserve representation, too.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP moderate replacing Newt Gingrich in Congress says he's
for ``consensus and not divisiveness.'' Gee, one election and a
guy's whole legacy is shot.
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Daley will serve a third full term as Chicago's
mayor. If his father were alive, he'd, uh, say something
embarrassingly stupid.
</P>
<P>
   A new report says lots of foreign countries may have Y2K
problems. This will surprise people who didn't know other countries
also will enter 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
