<HEADLINE>
FAN PENS BIO OF KEITH MOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients   )  
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Tony Fletcher was 14, he attended an exhibit
of Who memorabilia curated by the group's fans.
</P>
<P>
   While studying a life-size hologram of the band's Keith Moon at
the drums, the boy turned to find the real thing standing next to
him. Pulling from his bag a copy of the fanzine he produced for his
schoolmates, Fletcher asked Moon to autograph it.
</P>
<P>
   After a short conversation with the teen, Moon gave Fletcher his
address and said to drop by sometime. A week or so later, Fletcher
went to the posh London apartment, but there was no answer.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of weeks later, Moon was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher tells that story as an epilogue in ``Moon: The Life and
Death of a Rock Legend'' (Spike Books; $30), his wonderful
biography of the manic, full-throttle hedonist and drummer whose
life was a nonstop out-of-control party.
</P>
<P>
   Music journalist Fletcher spent more than three years
researching Moon's life and interviewed dozens of the flamboyant
musician's friends, colleagues and associates. As for the surviving
members of the Who, only bassist John Entwistle participated; Pete
Townshend explained he no longer had anything good to say about his
former drummer, and Roger Daltrey felt the biography would conflict
with a proposed film project.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it's hard to imagine that this highly readable
unvarnished 600-page life story could be much more complete.
</P>
<P>
   Moon lived in Los Angeles for several years and even bought a
ramshackle house on Knobhill Drive in Sherman Oaks for less than
$50,000 in the mid-'70s. Of course, the TV ended up in the pool
right off the bat, and the slowly simmering neighbors eventually
exacted their revenge with a foghorn at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moon'' is full of hilarious stories but never ignores the fact
that Moon's energetic drumming is what made the Who so distinctive.
Fletcher does a good job making this musical trailblazing easily
understandable even to nonmusicians.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who previously penned books on R.E.M. and '80s band
Echo and the Bunnymen, also remains fixed on the troubled man at
the center of the maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame ``Moon'' has to end so sadly. But at the very least
you'll want to blast your Who albums. At most, you'll wreck a hotel
room in Moon's honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Keith Moon had been more than just a world-famous rock
star, more than simply a brilliant drummer, more even than the most
irrepressible and carefree character of rock 'n' roll's last 15
years,'' Fletcher sums up. ``He had been a human being, an
approachable, affable man who had never forgotten what it was like
to be a fan or a dreamer. More than that, for those few minutes
that August (at the exhibit), he had been as a friend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
