<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 KISS AND MAKE UP?
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Successful political leaders can never have friends
and never have enemies. They can only have interests.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that eternal truth is being ignored as President Clinton and
Republican congressional leaders struggle to pick up where they
left off in the business of governing before the ridiculous
impeachment show. They are so hung up on their distrust of each
other that it is difficult for them even to speak with civility.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that the confrontation was so hideously personal
it will require exceptional diplomatic tact to overcome the deep
animosities ground into our national being. But we did not elect
these bozos to indulge their innermost emotions. We elected them to
run the country. And if they can't remember that, we ought to
replace them.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders emerged in a sulky mood this
week from their chilly first post-impeachment meeting with the
president. Insider accounts indicate the session was unpleasant.
Afterward, the GOP spokesmen stubbornly refused to answer repeated
questions from reporters asking whether they trusted the president.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott had already declared in the
wake of Clinton's acquittal on charges of perjury and obstruction
of justice that he could no longer trust the president's word.
Actually, there is no evidence that he ever did trust Clinton since
Republicans have a long list of complaints about being misled in
past policy negotiations with the president.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, who unlike Lott has no past
experience of working directly with the president, said merely that
the meeting was a ``good first start.'' But Hastert's press
spokesman noted that the parties still needed to ``deal with the
trust deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton didn't display acres of trusting affection
toward the other side either. He implied the GOP leaders are
political cowards. Patronizingly, he observed they probably ducked
the questions because ``any answer they give makes it more
difficult for them, potentially at least, within their caucus or
within the country ...''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats and Republicans are having their own problems
with the impeachment hangover. Party leaders have scheduled a
retreat in March that is supposed to encourage members to become
bipartisan buddies. But many on both sides are scornfully resisting
attending it, and the affair is shaping up as a public relations
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   It is too much to expect that trust between the two sides _ that
is, total confidence in each other's word _ will suddenly blossom
in the Capitol corridors. The Republicans tried to take away the
president's job. That's not something one forgets. The president
made the GOP look mean-spirited and foolish. That's not easily
forgotten either.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally the political climate would improve if more Democrats
and Republicans actually liked each other. But it is not essential,
and neither is trust. The real test is whether they can
pragmatically put aside their personal feelings to work together in
their mutual self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Both the president and the GOP congressional leaders suggest
they understand this imperative, but they sound as though they are
mouthing what they think they ought to say, not what they really
mean to do. If they had boldly repeated Ronald Reagan's immortal
philosophy of how to conduct arms negotiations with the Soviet
Union _ ``trust but verify'' _ we might be getting somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It is clearly in the political interest of Republicans, burdened
with public disapproval over their handling of the impeachment
charade, to demonstrate that as the congressional majority they can
govern. It is just as clearly in Clinton's interest to demonstrate
that he is not a useless lame duck so burdened with scandal that
his party does not deserve to win elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP has only 11 more votes in the House than the Democrats,
a margin so narrow that unless the majority miraculously congeals
into a solid bloc, it cannot deliver anything without Democratic
help. The GOP has a similar margin of 10 votes in the Senate, too
slim to prevent a Democratic filibuster of any overtly partisan
legislation. The president is not always in step with his
congressional party, but the two are more in tune in
post-impeachment days than they have been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to bipartisan teamwork here is chaos. It is time
for strange bedfellows to plop themselves down on the mattress.
</P>
<P>
   History is replete with stories of politicians who distrust each
other overcoming their suspicions to accomplish what they both need
and want. And history applauds the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   A classic example is that of President Johnson and Robert F.
Kennedy, who despised each other. In 1964 the then-popular Johnson
campaigned for Kennedy in his New York Senate race despite their
barely-concealed mutual dislike. By embracing Johnson, Kennedy was
able to rescue a seat he had seemed about to lose. And by embracing
Kennedy, Johnson got an additional Democratic vote in the Senate
and temporarily muted the Kennedy family's resentment of him.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial question is whether a majority on both sides is able
to focus on the ultimate prize rather than the other guy's kickable
shins. That is not a matter of trust or of the heart. It is a
matter of a hard political head.
</P>
</TEXT>
