<HEADLINE>
`20 DATES': 'HI THERE, BABE, WANNA BE IN MY MOVIE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Myles Berkowitz, the man who is behind ``20 Dates'' and front
and center during most of it, is proud to make himself a nuisance.
Having come up with a saleable gimmick for a film about meeting
women in Los Angeles and having absorbed enough of Jerry Seinfeld
and Garry Shandling to take on a diffident, nit-picking persona, he
sets a task for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The game: to go out with 20 different women, film the dates by
any means necessary and fall in love with one of them before the
stunt is over. ``This is a documentary,'' Berkowitz keeps
insisting. ``This is real.''
</P>
<P>
   So off he goes to make dupes of new acquaintances and embarrass
as many of them as possible. What seems to make this a funny idea,
at least by Berkowitz's thinking, is that he's also so eager to
embarrass himself.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes the sole true focus of any scene, whether he's bungee
jumping or cruising for girlfriends in a supermarket. And he
chooses to hog the limelight even when revealing that cheese makes
him constipated or other such news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying this is about single women in Los Angeles when
really, Myles, this is all about you,'' a woman tells him. And
she's just Date No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It must be said that Berkowitz's shamelessness and persistence
aren't inevitably irresistible. He can sound wryly
self-deprecating, Woody Allenish, in a way that's bound to wear
viewers down. (``Given that my ex-wife was engaged and pregnant, it
was probably over between us anyway.'')
</P>
<P>
   And he concocts a long array of gambits, from not having enough
money to cover an expensive dinner to getting himself booted out of
Spago for bringing a camera crew. He crashes a wedding. He stakes
out an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting. He visits a fetish club. He
trawls wherever he can.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever ``20 Dates'' begins to establish a playful mood,
it's liable to do something to make you squirm. It's fair game for
him to include the screaming telephone voice of his crass financial
backer, who demands that Tia Carrere be in the film for supposed
marquee value.
</P>
<P>
   It's another to watch him grimace when a woman he dates doesn't
look enough like Jessica Rabbit. And there are a couple of
genuinely nasty episodes in which the candid camera turns cruel.
(Two of the 20 women have brought suit against Berkowitz, he
cavalierly explains.)
</P>
<P>
   Even when Ms. Right appears in the form of a beautiful
saleswoman named Elisabeth, she is made to squirm while Berkowitz
confronts her with the other women he's still dating. Incidentally,
his violations of privacy do not extend into spying on sexual
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``20 Dates'' prompts thoughts of Albert Brooks, who can turn
mock-verite into such a treat. It has also prompted at least one
other filmmaker to phone his lawyer. Stephen M. Manin's Cinemax
film ``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Saskatchewan,'' which also
observes courtship on camera, shares some strong similarities with
``20 Dates.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``20 Dates'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes mild profanity and implicit sexual
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Myles Berkowitz; director of
photography, Adam Biggs; edited by Michael Elliot and Lisa Cheek;
music by Steve Tyrell and Bob Mann; produced by Elie Samah, Mark
McGarry and Jason Villard; released by Fox Searchlight Pictures.
Running time: 88 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Myles Berkowitz, Elisabeth Wagner, Richard Arlook, Richard
McKee and Tia Carrere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
