<HEADLINE>
BARRYMORE'S OWN CINDERELLA STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Fairy tales do come true/It can happen to you ...
</P>
<P>
   For Drew Barrymore, who first made a splash as an urchin in
Steven Spielberg's 1982 hit ``E.T.,'' it's been a long and rocky
road. While it was clear early on that she had an abundance of
talent, her bouts with drugs and alcoholism starting at the
incredibly young age of 9 took their toll on her and her career.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the scion of the famed acting family has
straightened out her life but has had few chances in high-profile
films in which to showcase her acting abilities. (She was little
more than an ornament in 1995's ``Batman Forever,'' and was
dispatched early, and in quite a grisly fashion, in the 1996
chiller ``Scream.'' She was in the wildly successful ``The Wedding
Singer.'' But let's face it, no one's really taking your acting
seriously in an Adam Sandler comedy.)
</P>
<P>
   That's why her star turn last in last summer's box-office
success ``Ever After: A Cinderella Story,'' out on video Tuesday,
was a welcome chance to see a mature Barrymore (she turns 24 this
month) in action.
</P>
<P>
   And action is a key component in ``Ever After,'' which is a
reinterpretation of the Cinderella story. The story set in the 16th
century begins when an aristocratic French lady (the regal Jeanne
Moreau) calls in the Brothers Grimm to tell them the truth about
the Cinderella story:
</P>
<P>
   A young Danielle (played by Anna Maguire) is orphan at an early
age, just after her widowed father (Jeroen Krabbe) had remarried.
She then becomes, in essence, a servant in her father's house,
taking care of her stepmother Rodmilla (Anjelica Huston) and her
stepsisters, the pretty but shrewish Marguerite (Megan Dodds) and
docile and dumpy Jacqueline (Melanie Lynskey), while they squander
the family fortune.
</P>
<P>
   She grows up (now played by Barrymore), educating herself and
becoming quite self-assured despite her lowly status. Though
victimized and suffering repeated taunts by her stepfamily, she's
hardly a victim. Danielle is a woman of action, able to wield a
sword as well as a pen.
</P>
<P>
   When Prince Charming comes along _ actually Prince Henry
(Dougray Scott) _ she rescues him from a band of rogues by slinging
him over her shoulder. When Rodmilla schemes to marry Marguerite
off to the prince, it is not a fairy godmother who comes to
Danielle's rescue. Instead, it is the man who epitomizes the
Renaissance itself, Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick Godfrey), who
outfits her in a gossamer-winged gown and exquisite slippers.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ever After'' is no simple fairy tale. Much of the credit
should be given to director and co-screenwriter Andy Tennant, who
was smart enough to reinvent the Cinderella story with a modern
sensibility while not robbing it of its romantic essence and for
casting Barrymore, who brings these dual qualities to her
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Too often in the past, Barrymore has played tarted-up roles
(think ``Poison Ivy,'' where her character seduces her best
friend's father). In ``Ever After,'' she brings a solidness and
grace to her feisty character, a delicate balance that few young
actresses could pull off. Hopefully, this fairy tale part of her
career will continue.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the ``f word'' that earned ``Ever After'' a PG-13
rating has been deleted from the video, making it PG; it still can
be heard on the DVD, however. Nevertheless, it's excellent family
entertainment _ especially for girls, though there is plenty of
action for the boys.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who are fans of ``Doctor Who,'' the BBC is
releasing two more vintage episodes next week _ ``The Ark'' and
``Horror of Fang Rock'' _ priced at $19.95 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
