</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING DIGRESSIONS OF LIFE IN INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first of these three wonderfully observed short novels,
the uncle of 10-year old Sandeep remarks: ``When we were young, the
world was made of small islands of consciousness. Miles separated
one village, sometimes one house, from another. Letter-writing was
the only means of communication _ there were no telephones. A
mountain or a river formed the border to our world. Our world was
small, and things loomed large and astonishing for us: you wouldn't
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sandeep does understand, and so does his creator, Amit
Chaudhuri, a gifted young writer who has created an indelible
portrait of India in this volume while at the same time leaving us
with a Proustian tapestry of quotidian moments recaptured and
remade as they loom large and astonishing in his characters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Not a whole lot happens in these novels. The first, ``A Strange
and Sublime Address,'' concerns two visits Sandeep makes as a boy
to his uncle's house in Calcutta; the second, ``Afternoon Raag,''
concerns the arrival of a young man at Oxford University and his
memories of his childhood in India; the third and most
conventionally plotted, ``Freedom Song,'' concerns the
lackadaisical life of a young man in Calcutta, his dabbling in
Communist politics and his eventual decision to marry.
</P>
<P>
   As Chaudhuri himself puts it at one point, the writer is so
``caught up in jotting down the irrelevances and digressions that
make up lives, and the life of a city, rather than a good story''
that the reader might well cry out, ``Come to the point!''
</P>
<P>
   In fact there is no point beyond the capture of those
privileged, vanished moments that have lodged in the narrator's
imagination: the glimpse, down the street, of a young neighborhood
girl ``memorizing the rules of grammar, the old man in the easy
chair fanning himself, and the house with the small, empty porch
that was crowded'' with possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   From such small, bright Polaroids of ordinary life Chaudhuri
conjures a web of relationships among family members, neighbors,
friends and acquaintances, spinning their banal squabbles, gossip
and daily routines, ``the minute frustrations and satisfactions of
their lives,'' into a subtle musical pattern. He preserves for us
the mood of a particular day: its heat, its light, its emotional
weather. He gives us the busy rhythms of a morning in Calcutta, the
langour of a summer afternoon, that surreal nighttime moment, after
a power failure when the lights are restored, like the candles on a
birthday cake magically being relit.
</P>
<P>
   Though his writing on the surface may seem casual, even artless,
there is a hidden subtlety to Chaudhuri's work. While he appears
simply to be setting down random incidents _ the family automobile
breaking down, a tiff among the servants, a luxurious Sunday
morning shave _ such elliptical scenes are animated by an
underlying tension between tradition and modernity, continuity and
change, as well as the tension between the past and its remembered,
virtual re-creation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the reader is continually made aware in the
luminous first novel, ``A Strange and Sublime Address,'' of the
story's dual perspective. On one hand, there's the point of view of
10-year-old Sandeep, an aspiring writer mesmerized by his father's
tales of business dealings and the antics of the gods and goddesses
of his aunt's religion; on the other, there's the point of view of
the older narrator (presumably Sandeep, himself a kind of stand-in
for the author), trying to recapture his childhood through the
magic of simile and metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter two stories, a similar sense of time and flux is
created by the juxtaposition of the younger characters' lives with
those of their parents and grandparents. In ``Afternoon Raag,'' the
narrator's unhappy, desultory affairs with two women at Oxford are
thrown into relief by his portrait of his parents' long, enduring
marriage. In ``Freedom Song,'' set in 1993, a Calcutta family's
fortunes _ its losses, triumphs, misfortunes and anxieties _ are
chronicled against the backdrop of rising tensions between Hindus
and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Change is the dominant melody running through these novels.
There are the momentous changes older characters remember, like the
partition of India and the splitting of the provinces of Bengal and
the Punjab; and there are the smaller, domestic changes that ripple
through all their lives, disrupting their weekday rituals and
jarring their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths, marriages, births, the loss of a job or the acquisition
of a new car, all are woven effortlessly by Chaudhuri into a
seamless piece of music, not one of those ``straight, angular''
compositions of the West, carefully rendered like ``print upon a
page,'' but something closer to the curving lines from an Indian
raag that read like ``longhand writing drawn upon the air.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:`FREEDOM SONG'
</P>
<P>
   By Amit Chaudhuri
</P>
<P>
   434 Pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
