<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITH AND MEISSNER COOPERATE ON BORDER PATROL FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   380&AMP;add
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW MOLLISON
</P>
<P>
   C.1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two weeks after threatening to request the
resignation of Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner
Doris Meissner, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, promised Thursday to
push for an additional 1,000 agents for her agency's border patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Smith's threat, Meissner had dropped
consideration of a controversial proposal to deal with overcrowded
INS detention facilities by releasing some of the nonviolent
offenders who must be detained under the 1996 law. The Clinton
administration also is preparing a request for $80 million in
emergency funds to build more detention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   While chairing Thursday's hearing of his immigration
subcommittee, Smith showed that Meissner's response had satisfied
him. He and Meissner united in making a case for stationing more
agents than President Clinton had suggested along the
2,000-mile-long land portion of the border between the United
States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of the illegal drugs entering the United
States come across our Southwestern border,'' Smith said. ``Yet the
administration requested not one additional Border Patrol agent in
its proposed budget for Fiscal Year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress in 1996 authorized an additional 1,000 agents a year
through 2001. Clinton last year proposed adding only 500 in this
fiscal year, but Congress boosted that to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's failure to call for another 1,000 agents for next year
was condemned by Rep. Silvestre Reyes, R-Texas, a retired border
control chief now in Congress. He testified via satellite TV from
El Paso, where he was attending an international meeting on global
migration.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on a survey by his staff of the six border control
chiefs for Texas, Reyes said, ``Each and every one of them said
they desperately need more agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the bureaucrat's dream of testifying before
legislators who insisted that her kingdom should grow, Meissner
offered a tepid defense of Clinton's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have exceeded the president's goal of 7,000 agents by
2000,'' she said, recalling Clinton's pledge from his 1992
campaign. But she added, ``We need more agents and we will continue
to advocate for more agents.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   The INS had fewer than 4,000 agents on border duty just five
years ago. That will be up to nearly 9,000 after it meets its goal
of a net increase of 1,000 during this fiscal year, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   In what Smith described as the most well-documented report ever
submitted to his subcommittee, Frank D. Bean and two other
migration researchers from the University of Texas at Austin
concluded that effective control of the U.S.-Mexico land border
using current technology would require 16,000 border control
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Successful border control would then force illegal immigrants to
use other methods, such as overstaying their tourist visas, Bean
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said Clinton's budget includes money to make agents
more effective by erecting 200 tall poles with motion-triggered
video cameras and lights along the border and building 20 new
facilities to provide work space for the greatly expanded patrol.
Texas and California, where key subcommittee members live, would
get 17 of the new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Clinton asked for an 8 percent budget increase next
year for the INS _ far more than the 1.7 percent average for the
rest of the Department of Justice or the standpat budgets proposed
for many other departments.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes said that informants within the border patrol told him
that hiring and training for new agents is so far behind schedule
that the INS can't meet its goal of adding 1,000 new agents by
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we have had some difficulties with recruiting,''
due to increased competition for job-seekers, Meissner
acknowledged. But, she added, ``We absolutely will add 1,000 border
patrol agents. We will be training many more than that, to allow
for attrition as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hearing room, civil rights advocate Joel Najar of
the National Council of La Raza said he was afraid that the influx
of so many young agents would contribute to ``incidents of abuse
and violence at the border.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meissner said, ``We are getting a very high quality border
patrol officer. Over half have gone to college.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
