<SLUG> BC-EPIDEMIC-EXHIBIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUPERB EXHIBITION ON INFECTIOUS DISEASES, THEIR CAUSES AND
VECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's something about deadly epidemics that both
terrifies and fascinates people, drawing viewers not only to
science fiction movies but also to museums. One of the
best-attended exhibitions ever mounted by the American Museum of
Natural History was a six-week show in 1908 that drew nearly 1
million people to learn about tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   After a long absence, germs are back at the museum. Saturday a
new exhibition will open in which dozens of infectious-disease
organisms will strut their stuff as computer animations,
eye-catching models, photomicrographs, dioramas and even real (but
dead) disease microorganisms. It is called ``Epidemic! The World of
Infectious Disease,'' and in this viewer's estimation, it is the
most impressive and informative exhibition the museum has mounted
in years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Dr. Rob DeSalle, associate curator of the
museum's entomology department, and David Harvey, vice president
for exhibitions, modelers and craftsmen have assembled a tour
through both the microscopic and human-scale habitats of dozens of
disease organisms, underscoring the vulnerability of all the
world's peoples to epidemics.
</P>
<P>
   In his story ``The Masque of the Red Death,'' Edgar Allan Poe
described the nightmarish futility of trying to wall oneself off
from an epidemic-ravaged world. The museum's exhibition drives home
that theme with a vengeance. As the show demonstrates, the vectors
that spread epidemics take countless forms. A vector may be a deer
mouse carrying the deadly hantavirus. It may be a mosquito
transferring malarial parasites from its gut to the blood cells and
liver of a human victim.
</P>
<P>
   In at least one case, the vector of a disease outbreak was a
Komodo dragon that licked the bars of its cage. Children visiting
the zoo touched the cage bars, licked their fingers, and were thus
infected by Salmonella bacteria from the big lizard.
</P>
<P>
   No one is immune to every disease organism to which he or she
may be exposed, and human beings have had to learn to live with
their microbial tormenters and invaders. The result is a
never-ending battle between disease organisms seeking to penetrate
and overwhelm their prey, and the immune system, which must
constantly adapt itself to meet new threats.
</P>
<P>
   The adaptations themselves can have bad side effects. In Africa,
sickle cell anemia evolved as a ``scorched earth'' strategy by the
body for thwarting malaria parasites. A genetic tendency that
evolved over many centuries by which red blood cells are deformed
into sickle shapes reduces their ability to metabolize nutrients.
But it also deprives malarial parasites of a hospitable habitat,
thereby resisting invasion by the parasites. Unfortunately, sickle
cell anemia, common among African-Americans, is itself a
debilitating disease that renders a person vulnerable to infection.
</P>
<P>
   Among many gadgets devised for the show is the shadow outline of
a human being lying on the floor. By stepping on any part of the
shadow, a viewer can call up a display showing the disease
organisms that may inhabit the corresponding part of the body.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the many interactive computer demonstrations created
for this exhibition, two players, one representing the immune
system and the other playing the role of a pathogen, try to outwit
each other, mimicking the complex and ever-changing strategies
played by real immune systems and microbes like the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal of the show is to enhance public health, and
its major focus is sexually transmitted diseases, especially AIDS.
But the exhibition is also a compact introductory course in
microbiology and epidemiology, with something of interest for both
a young child and a mature college graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is organized to represent both the passage of
time and the chains of causal links that spread disease.
</P>
<P>
   After watching a video introduction, the visitor walks through
sections representing successive stages of various diseases:
exposure, infection, outbreak, epidemic and finally pandemic, the
global spread of an epidemic. The specific diseases viewers can
follow through the exhibition include hantavirus, malaria,
influenza, tuberculosis, AIDS, a disease-causing version of the
ubiquitous E. coli bacterium and Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors learn the distinguishing features of five groups of
notorious pathogens: viruses, bacteria, protists, fungi (including
yeasts), and helminths (parasitic worms). The recent outbreak of
Ebola in Africa is briefly described, and several exhibits recall
the devastating influenza epidemic of 1918.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the show are models made by the museum staff. One
of the most impressive is a complex model, 2 million times as large
as life and some six feet high, of a human T-cell, a component of
the immune system. The model depicts an attack by spherical
molecules of the HIV organism. The intricacy of the details of the
huge sculpture make it a masterpiece of the modeler's art.
</P>
<P>
   Another spectacular model represents the lining of a human
stomach invaded by a strain of E. coli bacteria that has absorbed
genes from shigella, an organism that causes dysentery. In
adjoining sections, this huge model (which viewers are invited to
touch) depicts the stomach's production of mucous to ward off the
E. coli bacteria, the bacteria's eventual victory and the bloody
destruction of the stomach lining.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most finely detailed of the models is that of a
paramecium, a harmless protozoan that inhabits stagnant ponds. The
museum modeler who built it, Vivian Stillwell, included not only
the organism's internal parts but some 2,000 hairlike cilia, the
external fibers paramecia use to propel themselves in quest of
food.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biology presented in this show may baffle some
visitors. A few of the display labels seem to assume a basic
knowledge of the nature and structure of proteins, for example.
Unfamiliar terms like macrophage, T-cytotoxic cells, the CD-4
molecule and reverse transcriptase are loosely defined but not
thoroughly explained, and casual viewers may sometimes feel adrift
in technical jargon.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it is probably too much to expect that an ordinary
museum visitor would emerge from the show as an expert in
immunology, microbiology and epidemiology. The excellence of the
models, the arresting lighting and the animations make up for the
brevity (and perhaps oversimplification) of some of the labels. All
who visit the show except professional experts are certain to
enlarge their knowledge of infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   While emphasizing the global need to check the course of
epidemic diseases, the exhibition makes the point that
technological progress is not necessarily benign. The ancient
Romans, by building reservoirs, inadvertently created new niches in
Europe for malarial mosquitoes, for example, and by building
irrigation networks to draw water from the Nile, ancient Egyptians
opened pathways for the spread of schistosomiasis (snail fever
caused by blood flukes) throughout the Nile Delta.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Global warming, whether caused by human activity or natural
agencies, presents another disease threat, the exhibition shows.
When temperate regions warm up, they offer new habitats for
malarial mosquitoes and the insects that transmit Chagas disease
and other pandemic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Clever dioramas built for the exhibition represent some of the
best-known epidemics; two brown rats climbing down a ship's hawser
suggest the arrival of plague in 14th-century Venice, for example,
and a truck unloading produce represents an outbreak of salmonella
food poisoning. A hand pump symbolizes the discovery in 1854 by
John Snow that water from a pump had infected an entire English
community with cholera.
</P>
<P>
   History has been punctuated and molded by epidemics for at least
as long as human beings have left records, and for every old
scourge brought under control _ smallpox, for example _ some
vicious newcomer seems to crop up. The museum's epidemic exhibition
may not offer sweeping solutions, but it can help a new generation
of would-be microbe hunters learn the basics of their challenging
craft in an entertaining way.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Lecture Schedule
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Epidemic! The World of Infectious Disease'' opens
Saturday and runs through Sept. 6 at the American Museum of Natural
History, Central Park West at 79th Street. The exhibition's
principal sponsor is Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microbes in the Movies,'' a special series of screenings of
documentaries and fiction films and videos as well as discussions
with film makers and health professionals, will run from March 5
through March 25; tickets to each screening program are $8, $7 for
members, students and the elderly; a series ticket is $63, $54 for
members, students and the elderly. Screenings during museum hours
require museum admission: $8, $6 for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   A lecture series and a conference in conjunction with the
exhibition are also planned. All lectures take place at 7 p.m. and
cost $12 for a single lecture, $10 for museum members, students and
the elderly; there is also a series ticket for $30, $27 for
members, students and the elderly. Museum hours: Sunday through
Thursday, 10 a.m to 5:45 p.m.; Fridays and Saturdays, 10 a.m. to
8:45 p.m. Information: (212) 769-5100.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a schedule of the lectures and the conference:
