<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ANTIQUES: 20th-CENTURY FURNITURE BARGAINS  
 (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared with the $8.3 million that an American 18th-century
Newport highboy recently fetched at Sotheby's, the prices paid for
20th-century American antiques seem like yard-sale numbers. If you
pay attention to the pre-sale estimates, some of the best bargains
in 20th-century American furniture may be at Skinner, the Boston
auction house.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, Skinner will conduct a ``20th-Century Furniture and
Decorative Arts'' sale, with 584 lots of art glass and pottery,
Arts and Crafts Movement furniture, Art Deco pieces and Modern
furnishings. (Information: 617-350-5400.) There are nearly enough
Stickley pieces in the sale to furnish a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stickley antiques went way up in price years ago, and stayed
up,'' said John Stewart, a New York art adviser who sometimes buys
antiques for his clients. ``The commonplace Arts and Crafts pieces,
the mass-produced ones, plateaued in value ages ago. It's only the
rare pieces that go for a lot now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although mass-produced, some pieces in the Skinner sale were
designed by Gustav Stickley (1858-1942), an American furniture
maker, businessman and publisher who was probably the greatest
influence on the American Arts and Crafts Movement. (His brothers'
mass-produced pieces, from the L. &AMP; J.G. Stickley firm, seem less
sought after.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, Gustav Stickley started United Crafts, a company of his
own in Eastwood, N.Y., near Syracuse. In 1901, he founded The
Craftsman, a magazine that extolled the virtues of sturdy, honest,
plain furniture.
</P>
<P>
   For Stickley, ornament was unnecessary. He wanted to design
affordable furniture of solid construction and good craftsmanship.
Even though it was factory produced, much of the furniture was made
of oak and purposely showed off the dowels and joints.
</P>
<P>
   In 1906, he moved to New York City. There, he overextended
himself. He went bankrupt in 1915. The Craftsman closed the
following year. ``He was a basically a synthesizer of others' ideas
and an entrepreneur,'' said Alexandra Anderson-Spivy, the editor of
an eight-disk digital replica of 183 issues of Stickley's magazine,
``The Craftsman on CD-ROM.'' The disks, published by Interactive
Bureau, are revolutionizing the study of the movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Gustav Stickley pieces in the Skinner sale include a
two-door, glass-fronted bookcase made between 1904-12 (estimate
$6,000 to $8,000); an oak side chair with three vertical back slats
over a rush seat ($200 to $300); an oak footstool, circa 1912, with
its original leather ($400 to $600); a single-drawer writing desk,
circa 1912-16 ($1,000 to $1,500), and a round occasional table,
circa 1907-12 ($1,200 to $1,800). The Skinner sale also includes
pieces made by his brothers' company and other contemporary firms.
</P>
<P>
   The 1930s are represented by a pair of classic lamps designed by
the renowned French designer Jean-Michel Frank in 1935. The
15-inch-tall table lamps are each in the form of a letter ``U''
with small shades. They are cream-colored and very handsome
(estimate $2,000 to $3,000).
</P>
<P>
   The sale's modern furniture from the 1950s includes some
examples by the American furniture designer Paul McCobb
(1917-1969).
</P>
<P>
   The '50s, of course, are hot. ``Prices have exploded: they have
gone up at least 100 percent in the last two years for anything of
decent quality,'' said Stewart, who recently furnished the
apartment of a Whitney Museum trustee with 1950s pieces. ``The
trend for '50s furniture has brought in a secondary market. You are
beyond the bargain hunters who are decorating their first house or
an apartment in the East Village. The '50s are now an accepted
collecting area and an accepted fashion statement. So you have lots
of people with real money chasing it. That means that condition and
rarity are now much more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCobb is not on the super-hot decorators' list, so the
major 1950s antiques galleries in New York, like Modernica, 41,
1950 and New World Furniture, don't tend to carry his designs.
Nonetheless, many people are looking for pieces by McCobb, a
painter, decorator and display designer, who created several lines
for different furniture companies. In 1949, for example, he
designed a successful low-cost modular line called the Planner
Group for the Winchedon Furniture Company in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   McCobb's work, which is illustrated in ``Fifties Furniture'' by
Leslie Pina (Schiffer Publishing, 1996), is not too dissimilar from
Charles and Ray Eames' designs of the time. Planner Group pieces in
the Skinner sale include a long, low, six-drawer maple bureau
(estimate $400 to $600); a two-foot-wide, three-drawer maple bureau
with tall, spindly tapered wooden legs ($300-$500); a matching
two-drawer night stand ($250 to $350) and a bookcase with two open
shelves, supported on a platform stand with short tapered legs
($300 to $500).
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s lots at Skinner include a walnut sideboard with three
sliding doors made by George Nakashima (1905-90), one of America's
legendary craftsmen whose work is very much in demand at the
moment. There were Nakashima pieces in Thursday's 20th-century
auction at Tepper in New York, and David Rago of New Hope, Pa.,
plans to include several in his sale in May.
</P>
<P>
   Nakashima, born in Washington state, studied art in France,
architecture at MIT and Japanese carpentry techniques in Japan. In
1943, he set up his own woodworker's shop in New Hope, where he
assembled extraordinary slabs of untrimmed old black walnut and
redwood trees. These thick pieces of wood, often marked by huge
knots, inspired benches, coffee tables and other pieces of fine art
furniture. Clients included Nelson Rockefeller and Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   Nakashima won the American Institute of Architects' Gold Medal
for craftsmanship in 1952 and was made a Fellow of the American
Craft Council in 1979. His daughter, Mira Yarnall-Nakashima,
continues the workshop today, and it is very active. The Nakashima
style has been rediscovered by a new generation of young
architects, like David Ling and Michael Gabellini, who commission
site-specific works for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their raw and unadulterated edges, these pieces of
furniture have the primitive power of their original state yet they
are handcrafted,'' Ling said. ``Nakashima had a talent in choosing
woods and editing them in a beautiful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan DeLorenzo, as assistant to the director of the gallery
1950, noted that prices for Nakashima pieces had skyrocketed in
recent years, but added: ``They are timeless.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimate for the Skinner sideboard is $4,000 to $6,000,
which is less than the estimates for the Nakashimas in Sotheby's
sale of 20th-century works of art on March 12. That sale has a 1967
cherry extension dining table ($10,000 to $12,000), a two-door
cherry cabinet ($5,000 to $8,000) and a pedestal desk with chair
($6,000 to $9,000). As Cara Greenberg, author of ``Midcentury
Modern'' (Random House), said, ``George Nakashima is in a category
all by himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
