<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT`S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With no major new titles to rush off for this week, maybe it's
time to relax and wet a line with John Lurie in ``Fishing With
John,'' a set of three cassettes released on Tuesday by Home
Vision.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, a composer of movie scores and leader of the jazz group
the Lounge Lizards, wouldn't go fishing for the life of him unless
there was a television show to be made out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A while ago he made six half-hour shows with five friends: the
director Jim Jarmusch, the actor and singer Tom Waits and the
actors Matt Dillon, Willem Dafoe and Dennis Hopper. Last year they
were shown on Bravo and the Independent Film Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect savvy fishing talk and perfect casts that land a
plug right by the bass snout. These shows are more about nothing in
particular than they are about fishing. ``Why am I here?'' asks
Jarmusch while fishing for sharks with Lurie.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the series there is no real answer to that question,
other than the fact that Lurie found some production money in Japan
and asked these people to go fishing with him.
</P>
<P>
   He fishes with Jarmusch off Long Island. Waits' episode is in
Jamaica, Dillon's in Costa Rica, Dafoe's in Maine and Hopper's in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie and Jarmusch actually catch a shark, a thrashing
10-footer; otherwise the action is light. ``There are fish in the
water, but when they aren't hungry there is no way to catch them,''
Waits says.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the series has two things in common: They fished a
little when they were boys, and they used cheese as bait. ``How
often do fish get a chance at the finer cheeses?'' Waits asks.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, much of this makes passable entertainment.
Fishless for hours, some participants appear to come unhinged.
Under a hot sun in Thailand, Hopper suddenly announces that if you
watch his film ``Easy Rider'' very closely, you will notice that
the character he portrays doesn't necessarily die at the end. That,
he says, opens the door for a sequel. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``French films basically have low budgets and really low
budgets,'' said Donna Sayada, ``so what Americans would consider A
and B movies just get lumped together into French cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   With her husband Ms. Sayada runs Video France in Bethesda, Md.,
a distributor of older French films on video. American attitudes
about newer ones don't help. ``Americans try to judge French movies
by American standards,'' she said. ``Production and budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, Video France issued two French films that
should transcend those standards: ``La Bandera'' (``Escape From
Yesterday''), about a wanted man who joins the Foreign Legion, and
``La Horse,'' about a farmer who defends his place against heroin
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Both films star the legendary Jean Gabin. ``La Bandera'' came in
1935 near the start of his career; ``La Horse'' was made in 1970,
near the end. Information: (800) 835-7537; www.francevision.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neil LaBute's film exudes the same cool sexual fury as his ``In
the Company of Men,'' so the effect is by now familiar. There is
nothing in any way relieving to report about any of the three male
characters, who have little on their minds beyond an obsession with
sexual performance. Cary (Jason Patric, left), a macho
gynecologist, berates a conquest for bloodying his sheets. Jerry
(Ben Stiller) believes that sex is all that matters while Barry
(Aaron Eckhardt), a middle-aged husband, is impotent.
</P>
<P>
   As examples of LaBute's idea of self-annihilating manhood, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``they're hard to watch and
even harder to forget.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $106.99. 99 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As an 8-year-old, Lara (Tatjana Trieb) is an adept surrogate for
her deaf parents (Howie Seago and Emmanuelle Laborit), speaking
both German and sign language, taking their phone calls and even
acting as the ears in parent-teacher conferences.
</P>
<P>
   But the accommodation becomes uncomfortable when Lara discovers
she is musically gifted and wants a concert career. By the time she
is a young woman, in fact, Lara (now played by Sylvie Testud) has
become edgy and introverted and eventually leaves to enroll in a
Berlin conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Though Caroline Link's film loses focus before finally turning
warm and fuzzy, ``its hardheaded performances tug against the
sentimentality'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 109 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age horror films may finally wear out their welcome, but
not this time. Mixing familiar young television stars (Alicia Witt,
Jared Leto, Joshua Jackson) with familiar older cult figures
(Robert Englund, of Freddie Krueger fame, and John Neville), an old
story stays surprisingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Again there's a killer loose on campus; this one hangs people
and cooks pets in the microwave. Audiences may guess who the killer
is, but Jamie Blanks' first feature film has ``an edgy sense of
humor, a tricky plot and characters too genre-savvy for their own
good'' (Anita Gates). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.77. 100 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a futuristic stew of a world, an aging soldier warrior named
Todd (Kurt Russell) with his name tattooed on one cheek and his
combat record inscribed on his bicep is shown the door after
society comes up with a genetically enhanced breed of soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Dumped on a planet reserved for refuse, he is nurtured by a
colony of peace-loving pioneers who are also stranded there. Soon
Todd is back in fighting form and ready to take on his tormentors
in a high-testosterone but predictable fantasy ``that is much
better at the wind-up than at the pitch'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $107.37. 98 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: March 2.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWSROOM. A scathingly riotous Canadian television series
depicts the behind-the-scenes machinations at a ratings-obsessed
Toronto news show. Meet George Findlay, the insecure and
politically incorrect director.
</P>
<P>
   With an important position to be filled, watch George choose
between the attractive ski bunny and the African-Canadian lesbian.
With a nuclear accident only hours away, watch George whip up a
station promo combining the O.J. Simpson trial, Hiroshima,
Einstein, the Sistine Chapel, a dog-catching frisbee and, to serve
as anchor, an actress who looks like Jane Fonda in ``The China
Syndrome.'' 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Acorn Media. Four cassettes with 13 episodes. $59.95 for the set
or $19.95 each. 325 minutes total. Information: (800) 999-0212.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT VICTORY. Combining British Army and German film, Roy
Boulting's documentary records the Allied victory over Field
Marshal Erwin Rommel in North Africa. Included is the 15-minute
short ``Cameramen at War,'' made by the British Ministry of
Information. 1943. Kino. $19.95. 62 minutes. Information: (800)
562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   THE DISENCHANTED. A warm, vibrant Paris almost beats like a
heart in Benoit Jacquot's richly lyrical film, which relates the
involvements of a beautiful 17-year-old (Judith Godreche) with
several males: her arrogant boyfriend, a Chinese fellow student, an
older writer she happens to meet and a retired doctor referred to
as ``the uncle.'' 1990. First Run Features. $79.95. 80 minutes.
French with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1738EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
