u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIATHLON-HNS &LR;      02-25 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIATHLON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE ISN'T EASY FOR AMERICAN BIATHLON TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Kristina Viljanen Sabasteanski once ate
nothing but jam sandwiches on wheat bread for more than a week,
because she spent her last $20 on small-bore rifle ammunition she
needed for practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Teela bought his first pair of nordic skis from a friend
at his high school, only to meet a girl who competed in his
school's cross-country club. Three years later, he was competing at
the international level.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Salmela racked up a $700 phone bill one month calling her
husband, because the two are forced to spend so much time apart. In
1998, she spent less than three months at home, she estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The unique stories of sacrifice and adversity go on and on. Such
is life for the U.S. Biathlon Team, which is hosting a World Cup
event this weekend at the Mount VanHoevenberg Olympic Sports
Complex in Lake Placid. The competition continues through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time a World Cup event has been held on American
soil, and the first significant international biathlon event in the
United States since 1987, when Josh Thompson shocked the world by
claiming the silver medal at the world championships on this same
Lake Placid loop.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights for the team members have been few and far
between since. They toil in anonymity, despite the fact they are
among the best in the world at their sport. They get virtually no
attention, little corporate financial support, and train year-round
knowing that a great finish often means one that winds up nowhere
near the medal podium.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they carry on, striving and striving, pursuing their labor
of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just optimistic it can become more popular here,
someday,'' said Jay Hakkinen, 21, who won the sprint competition at
the World Junior Championships in 1997, flashing a beacon that the
U.S. program may soon be ready to lose its perennial underdog tag.
``We have all the elements of a great story. We're getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Biathlon's identity crisis, first of all, starts with the
popular misnomer that it is a cousin of the triathlon and is
composed of some combination of running, swimming and cycling. What
the sport actually is a combination of nordic skiing and precision
rifle shooting, where competitors carry lightweight .22-caliber
rifles on their back while skiing and stop to shoot from both
standing and prone positions.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the sport ranks as high as winter standards like ice
hockey and ski jumping, but in America, it's almost something
people discover by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Teela and Salmela both were fine amateur swimmers before
discovering nordic skiing. Salmela was nearly 18 before she ever
skied; Teela, of Anchorage, Alaska, also didn't pick up skiing
until his late teens.
</P>
<P>
   Another top American woman, 21-year-old Rachel Steer, won two
medals at the 1997 World University Games, is another late bloomer
to the sport. Like Teela, she grew up in Alaska, where she dabbled
in sailing, kayaking, golf, triathlon, fishing and hunting moose
and caribou.
</P>
<P>
   The top European programs, like the ones in Germany and Russia,
have developmental programs where youngsters begin competing in
biathlons by the time they reach the age of 10. Among the
Americans, Hakkinen started competing at the youngest age, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Missing all the early development programs under the watchful
eye of national-level coaches automatically puts the Americans at a
distinct disadvantage compared to the Europeans, but the focus here
is beginning to shift toward building a strong feeder program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started in juniors (in 1994), the plan was to
medal in the Olympics in 2002,'' Hakkinen said. ``It was an
eight-year plan, almost like it was made for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is experience and confidence,'' Salmela said.
``We're waiting for someone to break through, to be able to say
that if he can do it, I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   They are looking for a breakthrough in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Biathlon program generates virtually no revenue
whatsoever. There are no American corporations that are significant
sponsors of the team, and without the aid of the military, there
would likely be no national program at all.
</P>
<P>
   Salmela, Teela and Sabasteanski are among the U.S. team members
that are subsidized by the National Guard, U.S. Army, or both.
Without that help, all three soldiers say they would be unable to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come here, I'm put on temporary duty orders, so I'm
paid like a regular National Guard soldier,'' Salmela said. ``The
National Guard has a great program for support, and the Army also
has a World Class Athlete program, where two or three years before
the Olympics they put you on full-time active duty and you
basically train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just always wanted to go to the Olympics and show the
world that I can get there,'' Teela said. ``Without (the military
assistance), I wouldn't be able to compete, not at this level
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain luster about competing in Lake Placid,
particularly for Sabasteanski, who lived in the village from 1991
through 1994.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Castleton (Vt.) State College in 1991, and
after spending five weeks backpacking through Europe, she tied her
mattress to the top of her beat-up Chevrolet Citation and drove to
Lake Placid, arriving at 8 o'clock one night.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she phoned someone she heard was looking for a roommate,
moving in that night with a perfect stranger. She talked her way
into a nighttime job waiting tables at a hotel, worked until
midnight on a regular basis, explaining her penchant for arriving
at morning training sessions late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was, 20 pounds overweight, hobbling because I broke my
kneecap, and showing up here saying `I want to make the Olympic
team,''' Sabasteanski said. ``It was interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plan always was to make the Olympic team and have a top-10
finish in an international event. Both dreams came true last year,
as she competed in Nagano at the Olympics and placed ninth in a
World Cup event.
</P>
<P>
   But she's still here, and that epitomizes the mind-set of the
entire U.S. contingent. There are rays of hope now, with the chance
that maybe, just maybe, with the world watching in Salt Lake City
three years from now, biathlon will finally have its day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going year to year now,'' Sabasteanski said. ``But there's
always that hope of having the perfect race.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dream the five men and four women who will don the red,
white and blue this weekend all share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, this was like a club where you went to
Europe,'' Hakkinen said. ``Now, it's time to actually start getting
results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
