<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER SAYS MRS. CLINTON `AT THE BEGINNING' OF SENATE DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said Thursday that
First Lady Hillary Clinton should take her time in deciding whether
to run for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is ``at the beginning'' _ rather than at the end _ of
the decision-making process on whether to seek the seat being
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who met privately at the White House with Clinton on
Wednesday, said he advised her to take her time about deciding
whether to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two weeks after the impeachment. She hasn't even come
back to the ground yet on that issue. She needs space. She needs
time,'' said Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be bad for her, bad for New York, bad for America to
make a decision, whichever way it came out, in the next couple of
weeks,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her take some time, think it through thoroughly,''
Schumer told reporters. He said he spent nearly five months making
his decision to run for the Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can put a timetable or deadline on this at
this point,'' said Schumer, New York's junior senator.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was requested by Clinton, said Schumer, who steered
clear of detailing the specifics of the 90-minute session. He
described their meeting as ``a pretty heart-felt conversation about
all sorts of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made no secret about her interest in running for the
Senate. She recently met with Moynihan to discuss her prospects.
</P>
<P>
   She also has consulted with Harold Ickes, the former White House
deputy chief of staff and veteran New York political figure, and
with New York Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, the state
legislature's top Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation over Clinton's candidacy also is being fueled by
statements from her husband, the president.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers are supportive of her undeclared candidacy. In a
statewide poll from Quinnipiac College's Polling Institute released
Tuesday, Clinton was favored over New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani in a possible Senate race by 54 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier Quinnipiac poll, conducted Jan. 26-Feb. 1, Clinton
led Giuliani 51 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani hasn't declared his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Schumer, a former congressman for 18 years, on
Thursday introduced his first legislation as a senator, sponsoring
bills that would:
</P>
<P>
   - forgive all student loans for teachers who spend five years
teaching at public or private schools;
</P>
<P>
   - spur airline competition by requiring New York's LaGuardia and
JFK airports to give landing and take-off rights to airlines that
would serve smaller communities within 500 miles of New York;
</P>
<P>
   - increase fines and penalties for criminally negligent
polluters;
</P>
<P>
   - and offer $2,000 tax credits for first-time home buyers in
impoverished regions.
</P>
<P>
   His most costly proposal would make all college tuition tax
deductible for families with annual income under $140,000. The plan
would cost $30 billion and Schumer would finance it out of the
federal government's budget surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
