<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three Abstract Expressionist paintings from the
Museum of Modern Art's permanent's collection will soon be on view
at the Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg. It will be the first
time that paintings by Willem de Kooning, Franz Kline and Robert
Motherwell will have been shown in Russia, said Mikhail Piotrovsky,
director of the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship with Moma has reached a new stage,'' he said.
``We have little contemporary art, and the museum can't afford to
buy any. So we plan to put the paintings in a special room we are
calling `Moma's Room.' This will be the first of many loans of
modern and contemporary art from Moma and will give the Russian
people an opportunity to see postwar American art.''
</P>
<P>
   The paintings _ de Kooning's ``Tree in Naples'' (1960), Kline's
``White Forms'' (1955) and Motherwell's ``Elegy to the Spanish
Republic, 54'' (1957-1961) _ will be on view from March 23 to Aug.
15.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern and the Hermitage have been working together for more
than 20 years. Since 1977 the Hermitage has lent the Modern
paintings, including some for ``Cezanne: The Late Years,'' ``Henri
Matisse: A Retrospective'' and ``Picasso and Portraiture.''
</P>
<P>
   While the loans have nothing to do with the Modern's plans to
close some of its galleries when its major expansion gets under way
in 2001, Glenn D. Lowry, the director, said the museum would
probably begin circulating parts of its collection both nationally
and internationally. ``We lent works in 1984 when we went through
that expansion,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Piotrovsky said the Hermitage was also hoping to borrow
paintings from the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum and put together a
special Guggenheim room. The Hermitage is also planning a Rothko
exhibition with help from the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, but that show has not yet found a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Menil Collection in Houston is experiencing
growing pains as it evolves from a family-run museum headed by its
founder, Dominique de Menil.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mrs. de Menil's death last year board members have been
striving to make the institution more professional. But the process
has brought a shake-up. Two weeks ago the board asked for the
resignation of Miles Glaser, 73, its chief financial officer and a
board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the financial office was not as well organized as it
should be during this time of transition,'' said Louisa Sarofim,
president of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser's lawyer, David Berg, said that his client was
``terminated in an unconscionable way after being at the Menil for
30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members say they want a more professional operation. But
Berg said, ``That was not the real motivation. They really want a
new and younger CFO, and they ought to have just said it, rather
than humiliate him in front of the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Winkler, the Menil's director and also a board member,
resigned in protest, as did another board member, Susan O'Conner.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler had run the Menil since 1991 and, like Glaser, has also
left the board of the Menil Foundation, the museum's supporting
institution. Winkler did not return several calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Now trustees are forming a search committee to replace Glaser
and Winkler. ``It's a difficult but exciting moment,'' Ms. Sarofim
said. ``We're trying to make the museum grow up without losing
Dominique de Menil's vision and spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Another institution in Houston, the Museum of Fine Arts, has
just received a bonanza. Audrey Jones Beck, a lifetime trustee
whose collection of Impressionist and post-Impressionist paintings
has been on loan to the museum since 1974, has given it 47
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The gift represents the balance of the John A. and Audrey Jones
Beck Collection, bringing the total number of works given to the
museum to 70. Experts say the collection is worth more than $150
million.
</P>
<P>
   While the paintings have been on the museum's walls for 25
years, said its director, Peter C. Marzio, ``every museum in the
world was after them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on all our audience research this is far and away the
most popular part of the collection,'' he added. Included are ``The
Orange Trees'' (1878) by Caillebotte, ``Bottom of the Ravine''
(circa 1879) by Cezanne and ``Russian Dancers (circa 1899) by
Degas.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   After a four-month renovation, the third floor of the Hirshhorn
Museum in Washington has reopened, in time for the museum's 25th
anniversary year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more wall space, new carpets, platforms for
sculpture and improved lighting, all the art has been reinstalled.
The museum's collection of modern art, which occupies these
galleries, begins with Thomas Eakins and continues through Pop Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the collection has been refined, the level of quality has
gotten higher,'' said Neal Benezra, the assistant director who
oversaw the reinstallation. ``We've tried not to necessarily
present a textbook history but to put together interesting
combinations that question conventional wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Benezra has aimed to give visitors unusual pairings. Wayne
Thiebaud's ``Girls With Ice Cream Cone,'' (1963), a Pop painting of
a girl in a one-piece bathing suit with her legs splayed, now hangs
next to Sigmar Polke's ``Bunnies'' (1966), a deeply ironic painting
based on a photograph of Playboy bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both images of women,'' he said, ``one by a California
Pop artist and one by a German commenting on American Pop and media
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's second-floor galleries are also being renovated.
More of the Hirshhorn's contemporary collection will be reinstalled
there. They are to open in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
