<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S LOCAL ELECTIONS WILL MEASURE MODERATES' STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Friday's local elections in Iran are shaping up
as an important test of strength between moderates and the
conservatives who remain the dominant political force.
</P>
<P>
   The elections will be the first local contests since the Islamic
revolution of 1979 ushered in an era in which conservative clerics
have held sway. More than 300,000 candidates are seeking posts,
including women, secularists and others wholly unconnected to the
mullahs who hold most central authority.
</P>
<P>
   A screening panel aligned with the conservatives has
disqualified a number of well-known moderates, a tactic used in
past elections to limit choices. But in a reflection of internal
rivalries, the Interior Ministry has rejected those
disqualifications, leaving open the question of who might be
permitted to hold office.
</P>
<P>
   The outcomes could provide an important gauge of the ability of
President Mohammed Khatami, whose election in 1997 opened a fissure
in the conservatives' grip on power, to maneuver around obstacles
planted by his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling indicator is most likely to be the fate of one
of his closest advisers, Abdollah Nouri. The conservative-dominated
Parliament ousted Nouri as interior minister last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri is seeking election to a local council, and his candidacy
has been the source of the sharpest contention between the
supervisory council, which is aligned with Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
the hard-line conservative who is the supreme leader of Iran, and
the Interior Ministry, which reports to Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the supervisory council rejected the candidacy of Nouri
and 50 other prominent moderates because their loyalty to Khamenei
had been questioned or because they were seen as having ``suspect
records from the past,'' according to the official Islamic Republic
New Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry overruled that finding, meaning that the
candidates' names will probably appear on the ballots. But in a
sign of the seriousness of the struggle, the supervisory council
has threatened to nullify the election results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, his deputy or his interior minister _ none of
them can have a say in the decision of the council,'' said the head
of the panel, Ali Movahedi Savoji.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone interviews from Tehran, Western diplomats and
Iranian political analysts said the lines had been sharply drawn.
``Both sides are digging in their heels,'' one diplomat based in
Tehran said.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear sign of the tensions, a gunman opened fire Wednesday
on the election headquarters of a moderate party in Tehran. No one
was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, authority across Iran, a nation of more than 60
million people, has remained within the closely circumscribed
central hierarchy, which has appointed governors, mayors and
religious leaders. But the election of the local councils, with
200,000 seats, has the potential to begin to shift the balance,
putting at least some power in the hands of vast numbers of
ordinary people. Khatami has promoted the elections as an important
step in developing Iranian democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In percentage terms, the candidates whom the supervisory boards
rejected are a tiny fraction of the candidates. The sheer number of
nonclerics who are seeking office appears to have overwhelmed the
screening panels, who passed on candidates whose campaign posters
leave little doubt as to their secular orientation.
</P>
<P>
   With a brazenness that would have been unimaginable just six
months ago, some men have posed for campaign photographs wearing
neckties and some women have worn lipstick, attire derided by
conservatives as anti-Islamic. That alone is a measure of Khatami's
success in instilling increased tolerance. Even the Freedom
Movement of Iran, banned by the revolutionary leader Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, has been allowed to field four candidates on a
slate of 11 for the Tehran City Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
