 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, February 26, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ASA-AIRTRAN _ Before ASA accepted a buyout offer from longtime
partner Delta, its board weighed options that included buying
AirTran Airways, SEC filings indicate. An acquisition of
``Asteroid,'' _ a code name for AirTran _ is listed as one of the
strategies ASA might have pursued had it spurned the Delta bid. The
filings also show how Delta leaned on ASA to sell out by
threatening to cut the amount of revenue it gets from jointly
booked passengers. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAY-LOANS _ AUSTIN, Texas _Cash-strapped Texans are paying
rates as high as 800 percent on an annual basis for small consumer
loans to hold them over to the next payday, the Southwest Regional
Office of Consumers Union said Thursday. The transactions are
disguised to looking like they are not loans and thus not subject
to Texas' ban on usurious or exorbitant interest rates, according
to the Consumers Union and the AARP. The payday loan practitioners
often use justices of the peace to pursue or threaten to pursue hot
check collection against the borrowers who are victims to begin
with. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ BellSouth's annual proxy statement is out; how much
did the hardest-working bunch of guys in telecom take home in
salaries and bonuses, etc. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLS-WEBCALLS _ Federal regulators approved a plan that will
change the way phone calls to the Internet are regulated, a move
that could save the large regional Bell phone companies hundreds of
millions of dollars each year. But will it cool or even kill the
Net's phenomonal growth? What will it mean for your average Net
surfer? (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FANNIEMAE _ Last year, 44 percent of the mortgages Fannie Mae
underwrote nationwide went to low- and moderate-income buyers.
Moreover, 26 percent of those borrowers were located in so-called
underserved areas of the nation. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Developments at the Microsoft trial,
with the final witnesses facing cross-examination on their direct
testimony as a weekend deadline looms to begin a six-week recess.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAYLOANS _ Cash-strapped Texans are paying rates as high as
800 percent on an annual basis for small consumer loans to hold
them over to the next payday, the Southwest Regional Office of
Consumers Union said Thursday. The transactions are disguised to
looking like they are not loans and thus not subject to Texas' ban
on usurious or exorbitant interest rates, according to the
Consumers Union and the AARP. The payday loan practitioners often
use justices of the peace to pursue or threaten to pursue hot check
collection against the borrowers who are victims to begin with.
(Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FCC _ Federal regulators approved a plan that will change the
way phone calls to the Internet are regulated, a move that could
save the large regional Bell phone companies hundreds of millions
of dollars each year. The U.S. Federal Communications Commission
voted to classify calls to the Internet as long-distance instead of
local. That distinction will change the way local phone companies
pay one another for connecting each other's phone calls. But will
it cool or even kill the Net's phenomonal growth? What will it mean
for your average Net surfer? (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
