<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORCORAN-ART-REVIEW-N     02-25 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORCORAN-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPE FOR THE PAINTING: LANDSCAPES IN 2 BRITISH COLONIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia )   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the early 19th century, Australia and the United
States had a fair amount in common. Although immigration to
Australia started nearly 200 years later than in this country, both
nations began as British colonies. Both had indigenous,
pre-European populations. Almost equal in land mass, the two also
had vast expanses of virgin territory, rife with unexploited
scenery made for the painter's brush.
</P>
<P>
   These similarities _ and many differences _ play into ``New
Worlds From Old: 19th-Century Australian and American Landscapes''
at the Corcoran Gallery of Art, which runs through April 19 here. A
big, solidly packed survey of the century when landscape painting
peaked in both countries, the show was organized by the Wadsworth
Atheneum in Hartford and the National Gallery of Australia in
Canberra. It is not only the first time that Australian and
American landscapes from this era have been shown together, it is
also the first exhibition of such a large group of historical
Australian landscapes outside that country.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, more than 100 works are on view, by artists ranging
from Thomas Cole and Albert Bierstadt to Winslow Homer and William
Merritt Chase on the American front; from John Glover and Eugene
von Guerard to Tom Roberts and Arthur Streeton on the Australian
side. The paintings are grouped in five categories, starting with
wilderness images and ending with the bustle of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking differences between Australia and the
United States is the terrain. Australia is essentially a flat, arid
country with few river systems whose highest peak, Mount Kosciusko,
rises only 7,328 feet. Its flora and fauna are spectacular, but the
landscape is short on set pieces like the Rocky Mountains, Niagara
Falls and Kentucky's Mammoth Cave.
</P>
<P>
   So, in terms of imagery at least, American painters had a big
advantage. It would be hard for an Australian artist to compete
with the immense visual power of Frederic E. Church's ``Niagara
Falls'' (1857), a close-up rendering of the mighty waters that
reflects the energy and optimism of a dynamic country. Or Albert
Bierstadt's ``Mount Corcoran'' (1875-77), a grandiose rendition of
snow-clad peaks in the Sierra Nevada that climb more than 14,000
feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Australians brought talent and vigor to their own subject
matter. The Bierstadt of Australia, von Guerard (1811-1901) _
European-born and German-trained, like Bierstadt _ was attracted to
mountains, too, and painted them with feeling. His ``Mount William
From Mount Dryden, Victoria'' (1857), the highest peak of the
Grampian Ranges, takes a view over a long patch of scrub to show
the mountain almost floating in the distance like a ship, topped by
a crown of clouds. Although less majestic than Bierstadt's Mount
Corcoran, (which is actually a composite of several peaks), it is
still a magnificent specimen of mountainhood, a symbol of power and
potency that made other landscape events look puny.
</P>
<P>
   Australian and American artists did not, of course, escape
European traditions. Their work was fed _ particularly in the case
of Americans, who were more apt to measure their work against Old
World achievements _ by notions of the sublime, regarded as the
revelation of God's presence in the grandeur of nature. But they
were also engaged by the picturesque, or a pleasing irregularity in
the arrangement of forms, a concept derived from the 17th-century
landscape painting of Nicolas Poussin and Claude Lorrain.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 19th century, however, painting in the two
countries took very different approaches. Whereas Americans once
had feared the wilderness, they began to celebrate its freshness
and novelty, associating it with a political order free from the
immoralities of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's ``Clove, Catskills'' (1826) is a case in point. It
proclaims the glories of a scenic notch between peaks of the
Catskill Mountains, its rocky slopes covered with trees and scrub
in autumnal colors. Storm clouds overhead and bare branches in the
foreground illustrate the power of nature over civilization and the
passage of time, both elements of the sublime. A cliched Indian
stands dramatically poised on a rock in the picture's middle as if
hailing the splendor of the scene. (Since Indians had all but
disappeared from the region by this time, the figure is pure
allegory.) The painting is a celebration of America and its natural
wonders, with a shiver of premonition that they might not last.
</P>
<P>
   A later example of the sublime in painting was Church's
``Natural Bridge, Virginia'' (1852). The bridge, an arch of rock
over Cedar Creek in the Shenandoah Valley, was once owned by Thomas
Jefferson, who bought it from King George III in 1774.
</P>
<P>
   Thought to have been created through a cataclysmic event, the
expanse of rock inspired awe in both settlers and Indians, who
called it the ``Bridge of God.'' In Church's painting, a black
guide at the bottom thought to be one of Jefferson's slaves
explains the bridge to a rapt white tourist.
</P>
<P>
   Australians, whose settlement began as a penal colony in 1788,
held for some time a perception of their land as unwelcoming and
unappealing, even though they appreciated the exoticism of its
flora and fauna. A humorous look at the forbidding country is
Augustus Earle's ``A Bivouac of Travelers in Australia in a Cabbage
Tree Forest, Daybreak'' circa 1838. The scene is the Illawarra
region of New South Wales, densely forested with jungly vegetation.
A group of travelers guided by Aborigines and bivouacked overnight
yawn and stretch before an open fire, inflecting the spooky
landscape with their cheerful human presence.
</P>
<P>
   An important theme in the show is the depiction of native people
by white artists. The treatment could be ethnographic, as in
Glover's lively ``Corrobery of Natives in Mills Plains'' (1832),
which depicts Tasmanian Aborigines dancing around a fire at sunset
under a snaky tree, their movements echoed by the tree's sinuously
curving branches.
</P>
<P>
   Or the approach could be highly romantic, as in Cole's
theatrical extravaganza ``Scene from `The Last of the Mohicans,'
Cora Kneeling at the Feet of Tamenund'' (1827). Depicting an
episode from the 1826 novel by James Fenimore Cooper, the painting
shows a mesa-like outcropping of rock on which a large circle of
Indians surrounds Tamenund, the Delaware chieftain, as he hears a
plea by a mixed-race heroine for her white half-sister's life.
True, it is hard to see the Indians for the spectacular surrounding
peaks, based on Mount Chocorua in New Hampshire's White Mountains
rather than Cooper's setting of Lake George in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   But Cole's concentration on Chocorua, named for a Sokosis Indian
chief who supposedly died on the mountain at the hands of settlers,
forecasts the dispersal of the Indians and the defeat of their
claim to the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The civilized landscapes of cities and settlements play an
important part in the show, too, starting with the neat, precise
``Houses and Shop of Elijah Boardman (Houses Fronting New Milford
Green)'' (1795-96) by Ralph Earl, one of the first American artists
to paint local scenery. Later, John Mix Stanley's ``Oregon City on
the Willamette River'' (1850-52) paid homage to a prosperous
American lumber town of orderly streets, houses, stores, a sawmill
and a church. In the foreground are two Indians, who turn their
backs on the scene as if to renounce land seized from them.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, Glover and Knut Bull each painted a placid view of
Hobart, the capital of Tasmania (then called Van Diemen's Land);
Glover in 1832, Bull in 1855. In the foreground of Glover's
``Hobart Town, Taken From the Garden Where I Lived,'' a closeup of
his handsome house and the flowers he grew overlooks a panorama of
the city and its splendid harbor. Bull's ``View of Hobart Town,''
23 years later, from a farm on the outskirts, shows a much more
built-up metropolis, also lying peacefully under a mellow sky.
</P>
<P>
   In the last part of the century, as the United States became
increasingly industrial, and Australia headed toward the 1901
Federation of its separate colonies, landscapes in the two
countries became less empty, more defined by figures, as seen in
the show's final section. But this is the weakest part.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian canvases by Tom Roberts, Arthur Streeton,
Frederick McCubbin and Clara Southern (the only woman whose work is
in the exhibit) lack the brio of the more or less familiar American
works by William Merritt Chase, Winslow Homer and Childe Hassam.
</P>
<P>
   We get a much better sense of the two countries' separate
vitalities in the earlier part of the show _ and a welcome look at
an Australia we never saw before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
