<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BROADDRICK26-     02-25 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BROADDRICK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN'S GROUPS CALL RAPE CHARGE 'CREDIBLE,' 'DEVASTATING'
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Feminists said Thursday that although a rape charge
leveled at President Clinton by Juanita Broaddrick could be
impossible to prove 21 years later, they nevertheless found it to
be ``credible'' and ``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I genuinely believe she didn't want to come forward, and I
understand why she wouldn't, 21 years ago, want to bring this story
forward,'' said Patricia Ireland, president of the National
Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the sometimes tearful 56-year-old Broaddrick tell
NBC's ``Dateline'' of the alleged assault in a Little Rock, Ark.,
hotel, Ireland said, ``The story was devastating because she
doesn't have an apparent political motivation and she doesn't seem
to be in it for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's organization, which has been skeptical of women in the
past who have made sexual allegations against Clinton, moved
quickly to warn the White House and its supporters ``not to launch
a broadside'' against Broaddrick, an Arkansas nursing home
executive.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ireland joined other feminists in concluding that no
action should be taken in the matter. ``It is almost inconceivable
that the charges could be proven, or defended against, this many
years later,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland also said that she would not demand an explanation from
Clinton, who has issued a statement rejecting the charges through
his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A denial from Bill Clinton or anyone speaking on his behalf
has historically been proven not to be worth the air that it takes
to say them or the paper it takes to write them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Broaddrick also won verbal support from the group 9to5, the
National Association of Working Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many things about her that were very credible,
particularly her reason for not coming forward earlier,'' said
Ellen Bravo, co-director of the Milwaukee-based group. ``She's
certainly accurate that most people at that time would not have
believed her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is undeniably true that unless you're a saint or have a
witness or hard evidence, coming forward can be humiliating,
expensive and demeaning,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by the executive director of the District
of Columbia Rape Crisis Center, who said she found Broaddrick's
story very familiar. ``What she describes and how she responded is
fairly typical of people who are raped,'' Denise Snyder said. ``I
was talking to a person who was assaulted a week ago, and she was
raising virtually the same fears and concerns (about going to the
police). She was concerned about her own life and reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder added that the problem is worse if the alleged attacker
is prominent: ``Every time a person brings a charge against a man
of prestige, she ends up getting ground in the mill.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ireland and Bravo urged no action in the Clinton case,
some more conservative groups are unwilling to drop the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't say it's 21 years and it doesn't matter,'' said
Barbara Ledeen, executive director of the Independent Women's
Forum. ``They sure cared when it was (Sen. Bob) Packwood,'' a
Republican who was forced to resign after being accused of unwanted
sexual advances on women.
</P>
<P>
   Ledeen called on Clinton to answer the charges directly. ``He,
the president, being accused of rape, says 'Go talk to my lawyer,'
`` she said. ``A normal man being accused of such a thing would
rise up on his hind legs and say 'How dare you?' ``
</P>
<P>
   She called on the White House to release Clinton's calendar from
April 1978, when the incident allegedly occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the calendar, White House spokesman Jim Kennedy
referred a reporter to the written statement released Friday: ``Any
allegation that the President assaulted Ms. Broaddrick more than 20
years ago is absolutely false. Beyond that, we are not going to
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
