<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Feb. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   As much as 10 inches of snow had fallen by early Thursday
afternoon across eastern Long Island as a formidable but sluggish
low-pressure system swirled impressively off the Northeast coast.
Friday, as the system heads slowly toward Nova Scotia, Atlantic
moisture will wrap inland around the low, paving the way for light
to moderate snows across Maine. Broken areas of snow will develop
as far south as Rhode Island, but winds blowing from the northwest
will dry on descent toward the coast, limiting the coverage and
intensity of snow. Mild weather will prevail over much of the rest
of the eastern third of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, humidity rose dramatically across east Texas as
winds from the south imported Gulf moisture. On Friday, Gulf
moisture will stream farther northward ahead of a cold front
approaching from the Rockies, setting the stage for showers and
thunderstorms to develop early in the day across parts of eastern
Oklahoma, Arkansas and southern Missouri. Showers and storms spread
eastward during the day. Farther south across Texas, warm air 5,000
feet above the ground will act like a lid to limit thunderstorms.
However, if the lid is eroded during the day, heavier thunderstorms
could erupt over northern and central Texas Friday afternoon and
night. A few of these storms could approach severe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rain will arrive later in the day at the Pacific
Northwest coast as yet another Pacific disturbance takes aim on the
region. Rain and wind will intensify Friday night, with more snow
slated for the Cascades above 4,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Heavy Snow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow fell over eastern Long Island, Cape Cod and interior
southeast Massachusetts Thursday while air temperatures hovered in
the lower 30s. Typically, the greatest snowfalls occur with surface
air temperatures near 32 degrees. The underlying principle that
supports this observation is that rates of evaporation of water are
determined by temperature; the higher the temperature, the faster
the evaporation rate. Thus, as surface air temperatures rise toward
32 degrees, the amount of potential moisture evaporated into the
air increases, raising the likelihood of heavier snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
