<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS SHAKEUP MAY BOOST SIDELINED STADIUM PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE,  
 JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 and SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With co-owner Edward DeBartolo Jr. banished from
a managerial role in the San Francisco 49ers, the team's sidelined
plan for a new stadium may get new life.
</P>
<P>
   Denise DeBartolo York consolidated her control over the 49ers
Wednesday, putting her husband in charge of the team and moving to
end her brother's access to club cash to pay his personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   York issued the orders to all 49ers personnel after she
consulted with National Football League Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
and following clashes within the organization over demands by
DeBartolo to pay his bills, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The development is the strongest sign yet that DeBartolo's
banishment from managerial involvement in the NFL is not likely to
end soon, and could be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic development may mean good news for the 49ers'
proposal to build a new stadium at Candlestick Point with an
adjoining retail center, at a cost of $525 million. Sources said
the management shakeup clarifies an ambiguous ownership situation
and puts control in the hands of York, a wealthy, credit-worthy
owner.
</P>
<P>
   York is chairwoman and chief executive of the privately held
Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. of Youngstown, Ohio, the company that
owns the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denise DeBartolo York taking control of the team is a good
thing as far as the stadium goes,'' said company spokesman Sam
Singer, ``because lenders or bank officials can now look to one
entity, one person, and they have an individual to deal with,
rather than two different parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Her brother no longer may be given club funds or information
about club operations without approval, according to a memo _
obtained by the San Francisco Examiner _ that was issued to club
personnel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familiar with DeBartolo Corp. finances and
York's decisions, DeBartolo incurred a $91 million debt to the
Youngstown corporation as a result of ``lifestyle choices and
investments'' he purportedly made using advances and loans obtained
over more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it mildly,'' one source said, ``Eddie lives large.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, DeBartolo and the 49ers' chief financial
officer, Bill Duffy, got into a heated dispute when DeBartolo
demanded salary increases and special playoff-appearance bonuses
for his daughters, Lisa and Nikki, both of whom work for a
charitable arm of the club, the 49ers Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa DeBartolo confirmed Wednesday that salaries for her sister
and herself had been a contentious issue in the organization.
Following a hastily called meeting Wednesday at club headquarters
in Santa Clara, she said, in reference to her sister and herself:
``We were the only ones in the building not to get a raise last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa DeBartolo said her father had seen his sister's memo, but
she declined to comment on his reaction to it. Neither DeBartolo
nor Duffy returned telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, 52, co-owns the corporation with York, but holds no
office in it. He is under suspension by the National Football
League for his involvement in a federal gambling and bribery case.
According to the league, the suspension is likely to continue
through the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   In October, DeBartolo pleaded guilty to a felony _ failure to
report an alleged extortion attempt _ in connection with the
federal government's investigation and prosecution of former
Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards. He is expected to testify in the case
this year.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello declined to comment on York's move,
saying only, ``It's club business.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain York's dramatic steps, Singer said: ``There
have been a series of practices, financial and otherwise, that
Eddie has carried out in the past that are going to be different
under the stewardship of Denise DeBartolo York.''
</P>
<P>
   York gave her husband, John York, and an aide, Keith Lenhart,
oversight responsibility for the team. John York is a DeBartolo
Corp. senior vice president and member of the board of directors.
Lenhart is the corprate controller. Both men will become vice
presidents of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Denise York also named former 49ers head coach Bill Walsh as
team vice president and general manager, giving him day-to-day
command of the team. In recent weeks, Walsh served the organization
as an informal adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Wednesday that he anticipated ``no difference''
between DeBartolo and York in club operations or progress on
building a new stadium at Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stadium-wise, John York and Denise are doing the same kinds of
things I think Eddie DeBartolo would be doing ... There are some
people working on line working on it now,'' Walsh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
