u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-HNS &LR;      02-25 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESIDENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO DECIDE ON FIRST STAGE OF PRESIDENTIAL RUN IN TWO WEEKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has enjoyed lavish
attention from around the country, said Thursday he will announce
in the next two weeks whether he is taking the first formal step to
a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But an aide said Bush will spend the summer traveling the
country after the Texas Legislature ends in May and will not make a
final decision about running for president until late summer or
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also complained about the ``garbage'' rumors circulating
about his wild past and urged Texas reporters not to ``fall prey to
the Washington, D.C. game'' of spreading personal rumors about
politicians' pasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two weeks I'll make an announcement,'' Bush told reporters.
``I've made up my mind to answer the question yes, no or maybe.``
</P>
<P>
   But Bush signaled his intentions when asked whether the string
of advisers and politicians from other states who have visited him
at the Governor's Mansion would be upset if he decided not to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the answer would have been no, people would understand,``
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said if Bush, as expected,
announces the formation of an exploratory committee it will just be
the first stage of making up his mind on whether to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect he will make a final decision on seeking the
presidency until late summer or early fall,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up an exploratory committee allows a potential
presidential candidate to raise money without formally entering the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that after the legislative session ends in May and
the 20-day period for the governor to sign or veto bills passes,
then Bush would start traveling the nation to test the presidential
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be his opportunity for first-hand exploration of
whether he wants to run,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been the toast of GOP circles in the nation's capital
whether he is there _ as he was Tuesday when a dozen of his
colleagues said they backed a Bush campaign _ or not, such as his
almost daily receptions of visitors and letters from state
lawmakers and members of Congress from all over the country urge
him to run.
</P>
<P>
   But with the adulation comes what Bush said might keep him out
of the race _ ``the meat grinder of national politics.'' Potential
opponents have begun to take their shots, and, with the impeachment
of President Clinton over, national political talk shows are
beginning to question whether Bush has a troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Thursday called such stories ``garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the serious press helps flush the garbage out of the
system,'' Bush said. ``The press ought to take a deep breath before
they try to diminish anybody's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as he has said before, dismissed as irrelevant any stories
about what he has called his ``young and irresponsible'' years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters is: Did you grow up? When you put your hand on
the Bible did you swear to uphold the dignity of the office to
which you were elected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A New Hampshire television reporter last month asked Bush if he
had ever used marijuana or cocaine. The governor responded with his
standard refusal to answer questions about his ``youthful''
indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's answer quickly became fodder for commentators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say I found his answer about whether he had used
marijuana and cocaine interesting,'' Newsweek's Eleanor Clift said
on ``The McLaughlin Group'' recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have a gift for redefining the life cycle.
Childhood now goes through probably the early 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MSNBC gossip columnist Jeannette Walls heightened the
rumor mill with a story that a source close to Bush said he would
not run for president because ``he has a past ... If he declares
his candidacy, that jerk from Hustler is going to unearth all the
dirt on him.'' Hustler publisher Larry Flynt pursued stories of
congressmen's marital infidelities during Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gossip and innuendo is never pleasant. Unfortunately, it's a
fact of political life. We try to ignore it, because we know it is
not true,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's long and tentative presidential prospecting harkens back
to the non-campaigns of Ronald Reagan and former New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1975 Reagan ended what Newsweek called ``a year's
suspenseless deliberation'' by announcing he would challenge
President Gerald Ford for the GOP presidential nomination. Reagan
lost, but it set the stage for his 1980 presidential victory.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Cuomo considered a presidential run in 1991 by
announcing he was ``without any plans to make plans.'' Draft
committees formed. Political advisors visited him in Albany. ``You
don't get drafted for the presidency,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, the perceived front-runner for the Democratic nomination,
dropped out of the race. Three years later, he lost his bid for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of Bush's deliberations has been keeping his
promise to stay in Texas while the Legislature is in session,
except for a few trips such as this week's governors conference in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, who jumped right into a presidential race, only
to be among the first to drop out in 1996, predicted to reporters
that Bush's front-runner status was secure.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the governor needed to decide to run before taking the
lead, Gramm replied: ``Nah. Does he look undecided to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush already has been gathering his potential fund-raisers
around him who would likely serve on his exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime friend Don Evans, the finance chairman of Bush's
re-election campaign, is moving from Midland to Austin and is
expected to step down as chairman of the University of Texas board
of regents.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the Governor's Mansion have included Los Angeles
investment banker Bradford Freeman, an unnamed Florida fund-raiser
and New Hampshire cable television executive Craig Benson, who last
week returned home to tell local supporters that Bush is definitely
running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has sent videotapes of his Election Night and
inaugural speeches to potential supporters across the country,
primarily drawn from a list of people who donated money to his
governor's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that this is a campaign, it's adroit to this
point,'' said University of Texas political science professor Bruce
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an advantage to being a little coy, in that it frees
you from some of the rugged scrutiny that the already-declared come
under,'' Buchanan said. ``It also highlights the fact, especially
if you are someone who can get people to come hat in hand to beg
you to run, it highlights the fact you are desirable and attractive
commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
