<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS CRITICIZE INS BUDGET AS INADEQUATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas lawmakers accused the Clinton administration
Thursday of surrendering the drug war with a budget that fails to
add U.S. Border Patrol agents in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee
on immigration, attacked the administration's budget priorities,
saying that 70 percent of illegal narcotics entering the United
States crosses the border with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Border Patrol is our primary line of defense, yet the
administration requested not one additional Border Patrol agent in
its next budget,'' said Smith, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also criticized a plan _ which the INS has now abandoned _
to release illegal immigrants with criminal records from crowded
deportation facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's record on release of criminal aliens and
refusal to fund additional Border Patrol agents should be
disturbing to everyone in the country,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, defended the administration against the
charges and said ``criminal aliens'' would not be released as a way
to relieve crowded detention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said that a year of consolidation was needed before
more Border Patrol agents are hired to ``ensure that we continue to
safeguard the highest standards of law enforcement professionalism
for this new work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony did little to sway critics of the administration's
policies and budget proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Silvestre Reyes, an El Paso Democrat and former Border
Patrol sector chief, said it was ``inexcusable'' for President
Clinton to send a budget without provisions to hire ``even one''
new agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in desperate need of agents in El Paso and across the
entire Southwest border,'' said Reyes, who testified via a
satellite television link.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol is part of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston, the ranking Democrat on the
immigration subcommittee, also questioned the lack of new Border
Patrol agents in the budget, but she cautioned her colleagues
against imposing hiring mandates on the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intent is not to scold the INS, but to point out the
deficiencies that need to be corrected,'' Jackson Lee said. ``And
that perhaps it is bad policy to engage in a massive hiring without
proper screening, background checks and training.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the subcommittee would seek an additional 1,000
agents for the Border Patrol for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1.
The Senate is expected to consider a similar increase.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Border Patrol agents has grown from 3,965 in 1993
to almost 9,000 this year. Smith, though, said the number is
inadequate for the borders with Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reyes was even more critical of the administration after meeting
with all five Border Patrol sector chiefs in Texas last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each and every one of them stated that they desperately need
more agents. They need more agents _ period,'' Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have voiced concern that the rapid hiring of
agents will lead to more brutality complaints from illegal
immigrants on the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the time needed to train new recruits, Meissner
said, the agency's recruiting efforts have been hampered by the
robust U.S. economy, meaning INS has to compete for workers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to release non-violent criminals who were awaiting
deportation hearings prompted Smith to call last week for
Meissner's resignation, if the proposal was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not resigning,'' Meissner told reporters after she
testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
