<SLUG> BC-BKC-AMEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BU, NORTHEASTERN FACE SEASON'S DEFINING MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, Del. _ A year ago, they came into the America East
tournament as defending champions, a favorite to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Not so this season. If anything is consistent about the Boston
University basketball team this season, it is the Terriers'
inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   So many mistakes, so many moments of frustration. ``It's been
like Groundhog Day,'' BU coach Dennis Wolff said as he prepares his
eighth-seeded team for a first-round game against Towson State
Friday night at the University of Delaware's Carpenter Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, No. 7 Northeastern will face No. 10 New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The winners advance to Saturday's quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   BU (9-17, 5-13) comes into the tournament with as experienced a
team as any in the league, with four starters returning from last
year's squad that tied Delaware for the regular-season
championship. But almost from the get-go, the Terriers have not
played with the kind of poise and skill that they showed last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a loss meaning the end of the season, Wolff hopes his
team can recall its past to prolong its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know,'' he said. ``I'm hopeful our older guys
want to go out and play hard. It's a new season and this is an
opportunity to try and play good basketball and redeem ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff says he is at a loss to explain what has happened this
season. ``In a nutshell, we were somewhat fragile,'' he said. ``But
whatever it was, the fragile nature of our team became exposed. We
didn't continue to have the will to win we had in the past years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers have swept Towson this season, including a 30-point
victory in January.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern has struggled as much as BU. The Huskies (9-17,
6-12) also have played below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The consistent bright spot for the Huskies has been
6-foot-2-inch sophomore Marcus Blossom, who has averaged 16.1
points and 4.2 rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for NU is that New Hampshire (4-22, 2-16) has been
far and away the worst team in the conference. The bad news is that
one of New Hampshire's two America East victories came against
Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Top seed Delaware, which can play all of its games on its home
court, comes in as the hottest team. The Blue Hens have run off 10
straight victories and have an average winning margin of 15.6
points during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise _ other than the decline of BU _ has been
the rise of Maine. The Black Bears were 4-14 in conference play
last year and jumped to 13-5 this season, going from the No. 10
seed to No. 4, the biggest jump in league history.
</P>
<P>
   The odds against either NU or BU getting past the second round
are enormous. The top four seeds _ Delaware, Drexel, Hofstra, and
Maine _ are a combined 41-3 against the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling our team that this is now a three-game season,''
said Drexel coach Bill Herrion, whose Dragons came from below .500
last season to earn a co-championship with Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   A three-game season, or in the case of BU and NU, maybe a
one-game season. It all will come to a head beginning Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
