<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT26-COX     02-25 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT CHARGES MICROSOFT WITH PLAYING WINDOWS FAVORITES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government accused Microsoft Corp. on Thursday
of having discounted the price of its Windows operating system to
personal computer makers who agreed to give the software giant
preferential treatment in its Internet browser battle with Netscape
Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most acerbic sessions to occur in the 18-week-long
Microsoft antitrust trial, Microsoft official Joachim Kempin
admitted on the witness stand that, Dell and Compaq, two
``friendly'' computer makers, pay a lower royalty for their Windows
licenses than does Gateway Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But Kempin branded as ``ridiculous'' that the favoritism shown
to the two Texas-based computer makers reflects their affinity for
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Kempin had testified that Gateway was the sole hardware
outlet to have asked Microsoft's permission to offer its customers
the Netscape browser early in the Windows ``boot-up'' cycle.
Kempin, the Microsoft senior vice president who supervises dealing
with all such firms, said he had approved the verbal request,
although, he added, Gateway had yet to follow up.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose when David Boies, the lead counsel for the
Department of Justice, showed Kempin a 1997 Gateway confidential
memo which said Microsoft's browser policy ``definitely crosses the
line of what is legal.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo cited Microsoft's account manager, Brian Fujiwara, as
having told company officials that Microsoft viewed Gateway's use
of Netscape on its own Intranet as ``a huge issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It further quoted Fujiwara as telling his client that ``Dell
turned Netscape down because they did not want to hurt their
relationship with Microsoft. Therefore, they got special things
because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Kempin shot back. Kempin also could not
recall meeting with Fujiwara on the browser issue even though the
memo said that Fujiwara had told Gateway officials about such an
upcoming session.
</P>
<P>
   The favoritism shown Dell, Kempin suggested, stems from Dell's
willingness to build its extensive Web site around Microsoft
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without going into details, is Compaq charged a lower price
than Gateway?'' Boies asked the witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct,'' Kempin replied.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said he would clear
the courtroom and take further testimony under seal if Boies sought
to delve too deeply into sensitive pricing issues.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jackson superseded Boies' cross-examination to
question Kempin closely on Microsoft's dealings with Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   The judge cited a September 1997 memo brought into evidence that
Gateway officials had submitted at the request of government
trustbusters. It said Microsoft had told Gateway that its
insistence on continuing to offer its customers the rival Netscape
browser was ``a serious issue that could affect our whole
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by that statement,'' Kempin told Jackson. ``I
don't even know if they offered Netscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Boies sought to show that Kempin had changed
his testimony many times in listing the reasons that lay behind
various Microsoft licensing decisions, as well as their timing.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson kept the court in session well beyond the usual late
afternoon closing in a bid to recess the trial by Friday evening.
Kempin is due to be followed by the last of 12 Microsoft defense
witnesses in this phase of the trial: Bob Muglia, a Microsoft vice
president who deals with Java programming issues.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
