<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ARIZONA-HNS &LR;      02-25 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARIZONA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES PLAN TO EXTEND LIFE OF MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Speaking in a state that has become a mecca for
retirees, President Clinton on Thursday plugged his plan to extend
the life of Social Security and Medicare by devoting a big chunk of
the surplus to shore up these programs for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to a friendly crowd at the convention center in
Tucson, the president backed off anticipated criticism of
congressional Republicans for initially pushing a 10 percent tax
cut that could threaten his plans for the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton praised Republicans for agreeing with his
proposal to devote 62 percent of the surplus over the next 15 years
to Social Security. Furthermore, he said, ``there seems to be, now,
some movement in the Republican majority away from having a large
across-the-board tax cut if it would take away the surplus' ability
to save Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments were far more conciliatory than the prepared
statements for the event given to reporters shortly before Clinton
spoke, which had the president saying, ``I am pleased that
Republican leaders are rethinking their indiscriminate tax cut that
would squander our surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   The president may have tempered his remarks as more and more
Republicans have acknowledged that they will not be able to pass an
across-the-board tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also said that he had not yet persuaded Republicans
to accept his proposal to devote 15 percent of the surplus to shore
up Medicare, the health insurance program that faces fiscal strains
far sooner than Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Medicare will be in trouble in about a decade
despite efforts to crack down on fraud and ``the easy savings that
could be squeezed out from managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sustain the present budgeted cost of Medicare. We're
going to have to put some more money into it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the president defended one of the more controversial aspects
of his Social Security plan, allowing the government to invest a
small portion of the retirement funds in the private market.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including many Republicans, have said such a plan would
give the federal government too much control over private
enterprise. They complain such investments would be susceptible to
political pressure from lawmakers who wanted to boycott certain
companies or products.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said that state and municipal retirement plans
already invest in the private market. He added that his plan would
stipulate that an independent board oversee investment decisions to
deter politicians from trying to influence the investments. He also
noted that his plan only calls for the investment of 4 percent of
the retirement money in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   The president also stressed a politically appealing aspect of
his Social Security plan; that it would involve eliminating the
national debt in 19 years. That would mean lower interest rates and
economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton avoided overt partisanship, the lingering tensions
and resentments from his impeachment trial were still evident.
Outside the convention center, protesters chanted and held signs,
including ``I believe Juanita,'' a reference to Juanita Broaddrick,
who claimed Clinton sexually assaulted her in 1978 when he was
Arkansas Attorney General.
</P>
<P>
   And inside the hall, many in the crowd booed Rep. Jim Kolbe, a
Republican congressman from Tucson who voted to impeach the
president but nevertheless sat on the stage with Clinton at the
event and spoke before the president. Kolbe, who accompanied the
president on Air Force One from Washington, said he did not view it
as unusual or strange to work so closely with someone he wanted to
oust from office.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was in the Republicans' best interest to work with
Clinton on Social Security for their own political survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans know that fixing Social Security is the only thing
that gives us hope of staying in the majority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe acknowledged that the Republican proposal for a 10 percent
tax cut is dead, saying that the public is more interested in
paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by a number of those who came to see
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of using the money to pay down the national
debt,'' said Mike Carnahan, a 45-year-old airline employee who said
he was a Republican who did not vote for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, however, said he was wary of plans to let the
government or individuals invest too much of their Social Security
money in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market is a fickle beast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Ridgley, 62, said she liked Clinton's ideas about Social
Security but doubted that Republicans in Congress would work with
him because of their anger that he emerged victorious in the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dirty, long drawn-out trial, and I think they're
going to make him pay for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgley and her two daughters said they were annoyed that Kolbe
had attended the forum after he voted to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of nerve coming up there,'' said Vanesia Ridgley,
28, a medical receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   After the Social Security event, Clinton visited the Arizona
Diamondbacks spring training baseball facility. He later flew to
San Francisco where he attended a $12,500 per person Democratic
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
