<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     02-25 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: fear (Maslin).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE,' starring Kevin Costner, Robin Wright Penn
and Paul Newman. Directed by Luis Mandoki (PG-13, 110 minutes).
Nicholas Sparks' best-selling novel, about a lonely, sensitive man
who sends a message out to sea and the lonely, beautiful woman who
finds it, is now a long and soggy film. Kevin Costner crosses the
line from teasingly laconic to stodgy and seems as likely to have
written ``Bleak House'' as the love letter in question. Robin
Wright Penn makes an appealing heroine, but there's not much room
for real emotion in a film with the tenor of a commercial for
hazelnut-flavored coffee. As the hero's crusty old father, Newman
steals what's left of the show (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `OCTOBER SKY,' starring Jake Gyllenhaal and Chris Cooper.
Directed by Joe Johnston (PG, 100 minutes). By far the most moving
scenes here are home movie snippets, circa 1957, that show the real
people on whom the film's characters are based. Otherwise, despite
being closely based on a best-selling memoir (``Rocket Boys'') by
the NASA engineer Homer H. Hickam Jr., this earnest, nostalgic film
has a way of seeming too good to be true. The film's simplicity is
appealing, as is Gyllenhaal in the central role of a boy in a West
Virginia coal mining town who becomes obsessed with rocketry. But
the story, filled with father-son conflict and down-in-the-ground
versus up-in-the-sky contrasts, often follows a familiar trajectory
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `PAYBACK,' starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry. Directed by
Brian Helgeland (R, 110 minutes). In this inept, excessively
sadistic film-noir spoof adapted from the same Richard Stark novel
(``The Hunter'') that inspired the 1967 genre classic ``Point
Blank'' Gibson is a thief named Porter who retaliates with a
vengeance after an attempt on his life. Determined to recover
$70,000 that was stolen from him by a double-crossing partner in
crime, he works his way up the pecking order of a crime syndicate
brutally dispatching all who stand in his way. The hard-boiled
dialogue is ludicrous, the storytelling clunky, the acting fair to
awful, the gore ankle deep. Credit the star with being able to keep
a straight face through this loathsome mess (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RUSHMORE,' starring Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray and Olivia
Williams. Directed by Wes Anderson (R, 93 minutes). A dryly
hilarious portrait of the mogul as a young man, with Schwartzman a
real find as its perfectly horrid little hero, Max Fischer. Max's
prep school, Rushmore Academy, does have a faculty, but none of the
grown-ups have anything like Max's natural authority. Murray is
sneakily fine as the steel tycoon and Rushmore benefactor who
happens to be on Max's own wavelength as they vie for the same
beautiful teacher. A particular treat for its skewed, outrageously
funny memories of a cutthroat boyhood (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,' starring Joseph Fiennes and Gwyneth
Paltrow. Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy
and merrily literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise
that only gets better as the film unfolds. The screenplay,
originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard
into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his ``Rosencrantz and
Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine whatever it likes about
the link between Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad
yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile this
tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an Elizabethan theater
fraught with the same backbiting and conniving we enjoy today and
has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo and Juliet,''
glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous
duo, and she gives the first great, fully realized starring
performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `A SIMPLE PLAN,' starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and
Bridget Fonda. Directed by Sam Raimi (R, 120 minutes). This onetime
cult horror director makes a flawless transition to mainstream
storytelling with a quietly devastating thriller. And its fine cast
plays out the consequences of a harmless-sounding error in judgment
that winds up leveling everything in its path. The catalyst is $4.4
million that literally falls out of the sky, and Scott B. Smith's
story proves how deadly the morality of expediency can become. When
you get the shivers watching this wintry tale, which features an
especially memorable performance from Thornton, it won't be from
the cold (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TANGO,' starring Miguel Angel Sola. Written and directed by
Carlos Saura. Cinematography by Vittorio Storaro (PG-13, 100
minutes). A thrilling display of tango heat and virtuosity. And
it's no slight to the actors who play lovers to say that the
dancing here is steamier than any kiss. In his most electrifying
dance film Saura offers transfixingly beautiful glimpses of the
dance and the great range of emotions it can conjure. Storaro's
dazzlingly fluid cinematography captures all the nuances this
material demands. Everyone in the film is utterly consumed by tango
fever; audiences will be, too (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE THIN RED LINE,' starring Jim Caviezel, Ben Chaplin, Nick
Nolte and Sean Penn. Directed by Terrence Malick (R, 166 minutes).
From the first frame of this huge, drifting war epic loosely
derived from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, it's viscerally clear
that Malick is back. The exquisite, oddly detached visual style
that made ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' the most beautiful
films of the 1970s is instantly apparent here, even if the
narrative vagueness and brooding voice-overs are also familiar. The
film sprawls, gets lost and occasionally delivers visual poetry,
the kind that could have been greatly helped by tighter editing.
Bottom line: No one who admired Malick's early work should miss
this. But those expecting anything simple will not find it here
(Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
