<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWSUITS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      02-25 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWSUITS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDES CONTINUE BATTLE OVER CLASS-ACTION LAWSUITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Business people seeking restrictions on
class-action lawsuits told a Senate subcommittee that class actions
often force businesses into costly settlements even if they may be
innocent of alleged wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates testified that the right of people with a
common complaint to band together in a class-action suit was one of
the ``last remaining recourses'' that consumers have against
deceptive business practices.
</P>
<P>
   The fight is another chapter in the ongoing effort by business
groups to put more restrictions on civil suits and damage judgments
awarded by the state courts.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 274 by state Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, would
require consumers with a beef against a business to first try to
resolve their problem before a state agency with regulatory
authority over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   To give the agency time to tackle the problem, a judge would
have to postpone action on a class-action suit at least six months
_ or longer if the court determines that the agency is ``proceeding
diligently to resolve the matters.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge would be required to dismiss a suit if the court
determined that a state agency had granted ``all or a substantial
part of the relief'' sought by claimants.
</P>
<P>
   If a judge eventually determines that a class-action suit is
warranted, the proceedings could again be delayed to give the
defendants time to appeal the certification to the Texas Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Ratliff, an Austin attorney representing the Texas Civil
Justice League, a business group, said the restrictions were
necessary because class actions have been abused.
</P>
<P>
   Some cases, he said, can involve hundreds of thousands or even
millions of plaintiffs in a certified class, representing a huge
potential loss for a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been very few class actions that have gone to
trial,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, he added, the defendants settle to avoid higher
losses even though the claims against them haven't been proved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is so extreme from bankers, they go in and make a
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some business owners also contend that class actions are
manipulated by plaintiffs' lawyers to get high fees, while their
individual clients often are paid only modest damages.
</P>
<P>
   But two retired teachers, Billy and Donna Davis of Krum, said a
class action was the only way they and thousands of other retired
educators could recover retirement funds, which they lost in a
deceptive insurance company investment scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The former teachers said they went to court after a complaint
they had filed with the Texas Department of Insurance languished
for two years without action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anyone to have to go through what we went
through. But this could happen to anyone,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Lambe, executive director of Texas Watch, a consumer
research and advocacy group, said the state insurance department
and other state regulatory agencies aren't adequately funded to
handle the additional chores that Bivins' bill would impose.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee postponed action on the bill, which also was
opposed by the Texas Trial Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
