<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9565 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-OWENS-LADN     02-25 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-OWENS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTERN SIERRA FISHERY YIELDS YEAR-ROUND TROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISHOP, Calif. _ In winter you can almost wade across the Lower
Owens River. Doesn't that make a drift boat to shuttle anglers down
it overkill?
</P>
<P>
   My doubts were largely reconfirmed after Mammoth Lakes fishing
guide Tom Loe scraped the hull of his aluminum McKenzie-style drift
boat along the gravelly bottom last Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A cold snap had sent the resident rainbows and browns into a
state of lethargy. Casting the heavy sink-tip fly line was a chore
in the face of a stiff wind.
</P>
<P>
   The only action was a beaver that disappeared with the slap of a
tail as we rounded one of the river's many oxbows that can make a
compass schizophrenic. Sure, there was also a hat that blew into
the water and a rare foul in lines in which two anglers' hooks
became enjoined, but to say things were slow is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   My suspicions began to wane an hour into the seven-hour odyssey
when the first brown, about a foot long, was caught. As the
afternoon water temperature rose enough for the fish to take a more
serious look at our offerings, I warmed to the adventure. A few
minutes after 2 p.m. I boated a 19{-inch, 4\-pound rainbow, my
largest ever fly-fooled trout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a believer now?'' asked Loe, who in November quit his
commercial pursuits of harpooning swordfish and hook-and-line
rockfishing to open Sierra Drifters Guide Service to guide
full-time.
</P>
<P>
   I was sold.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful size No. 8 spruce-adaptation streamer pattern had
done it's job; meant to mimic a baitfish, the fly proved
irresistible when the line was pulled underwater with short,
irregular strips through the guides on the 9-foot, 5-weight
graphite rod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever size trout you catch on streamers _ which imitate
sculpin, squawfish, carp and other small prey _ they hit it real
hard, so you think you have Moby Dick on the line,'' said Gary
Gunsolley, a Bishop tackle-shop proprietor who cast a No. 10 olive
Hornberg fly while sharing the boat's bow with me.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant crimson that defined the fish during the fight had
faded to a mere blush by the time she was returned to her chilly
home. A metal clip on the gill plate designated it as a trophy
trout.
</P>
<P>
   I might not have had a chance to release the fish, let alone
land it, had I been wade-fishing, Gunsolley explained; one surge
from the trout's tail could have pushed it around a bend in the
river, snapping the line. But with the boat's favorable
positioning, the fish was kept closer to the middle of the channel,
tiring sooner from the force of the current.
</P>
<P>
   Wading was not a likely option on this section of the Lower
Owens anyway. The banks are lined with an impossible tangle of
willow, wild rose and tule. Access is further impeded by a lack of
nearby roads.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown tired of failing to navigate the dense brush on
previous excursions, Dana Point stockbroker Bill Sidenfaden
surprised his girlfriend, Kelly Lee, with a Valentine's weekend
trip with Loe's outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't hear a person, didn't see a person. The fresh air and
the scenery is spectacular, with the snow-capped Sierra mountains
and the ospreys and all kinds of birds,'' Sidenfaden said of his
recent drift. ``You can see it's a classic fishery, with perfect
water and unpressured hole after unpressured hole.''
</P>
<P>
   While wading on earlier outings, he said, ``I would fish a
section for an hour and then want to move down river, and you can't
because of the brambles. You're stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple put three dozen trout in the boat; Sidenfaden lost
what was thought to be a 7- or 8-pounder in the weeds before any
real battle began. He plans to fish again with Loe in March and
April.
</P>
<P>
   Wind makes casting from the boat difficult, but that's only if
you manage to keep the line out of the bushes on the back cast. The
problem is solved by rollcasting, a relatively simple technique in
which the line is not cast above the angler but instead rolled out
while it lays atop the water.
</P>
<P>
   Loe offered other tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to stay in contact with the line,
so you can feel the fly through the line and detect a strike,'' he
said. ``By having the rod tip actually in the water you are
minimizing the slack in the line and keeping the fly deeper and
closer to the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Cast to either side of the foam, which flags the swiftest
current. It is here in the ``neutral zone,'' as Loe calls the slack
water, where the fish hover comfortably, close enough to the main
channel to dart in and grab a meal while expending the least amount
of energy. In winter, when their metabolisms are slow, these trout
need an excuse to move. By bringing the bait to them, dangling a
faux meal just above their maws, logic dictates it might entice a
bite.
</P>
<P>
   The day produced just 10 boated trout, but Gunsolley was happy
with a 16-inch rainbow and I'm still bragging about my prize.
</P>
<P>
   Loe is hoping to buck the odds and sway anglers to target
Eastern Sierra waters in the offseason. Most trout anglers take a
hiatus from traveling Highway 395 from November to late April, when
the bulk of the region is closed to angling. The Lower Owens River
is but one of a handful of fishing holes that are open year-round.
Loe has his work cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a resource here that is 98 percent underutilized in
the winter,'' said Mike Seefeldt, assistant manager of the Mount
Whitney and Black Rock state fish hatcheries to the south.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager living in Bishop in the 1950s, Seefeldt and a
buddy floated and fished the Lower Owens in a pair of
torpedo-shaped airplane fuel tanks that were welded together. ``It
was a real Huck Finn experience,'' he said. ``I grew up in an
environment where what we took from nature supplemented the dinner
table, heavily. We took what we needed _ rainbows and a lot of
browns.''
</P>
<P>
   While the river can still be treacherous and Seefeldt urges
newcomers to be cautious, fishing has changed a lot since then. The
boats are better and catch and release is practiced. But Seefeldt
can't figure why someone didn't think of making a business
enterprise out of drift-fishing the Lower Owens earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised it didn't materialize years ago,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To reach Tom Loe Sierra Drifters Guide Service, call (760)
935-4250 or visit www.mammothlakes.com./driftfish
</P>
</TEXT>
