<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      02-25 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTED TO FORM EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush inched closer to a run
for the White House, saying Thursday he will make a ``major
announcement'' in two weeks on a possible campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has sidestepped making a commitment, he continues
to receiving overtures from Republicans pressing the second-term
governor and son of former President George Bush to declare his
candidacy in an increasily crowded field of declared and potential
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two weeks I'll make an announcement. So I'll see you in two
weeks,'' Bush said, declining again to give any specifics. ``If I
told you what I'd announce, you wouldn't even show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made up my mind to answer the question yes, no or
maybe,'' Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   The ``maybe'' would be an announcement that he is forming an
exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several weeks, people from across the nation have
beaten a path to the Governor's Mansion either to encourage him to
run or advise him on a potential bid. In essence, Bush has been
able to assemble an unofficial team of advisers who could become
part of an official organization.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, he spent several days in Washington where he
was urged by a number of Republican governors to declare his
candidacy. And on Thursday, Alabama Republican leaders urged Bush
to join the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush represents America's best hope for returning
integrity to the White House, tax dollars to working families and
keeping criminals off the streets,'' Alabama Attorney General
William H. Pryor Jr. said in a letter to Bush and signed by a
number of GOP officials from that state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heartened by the support, needless to say,'' Bush said.
``But I've got a job to do here as governor of Texas. I know that
there's some who are saying, `Why won't he come out and leave the
state?' Because I was elected to do a job, and I intend to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, was elected to a second term in November in a
landslide victory. His appeal among minorities and women has made
him a sought-after candidate for Republicans seeking to broaden the
party's constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has insisted time and again that he has not made up his
mind about running, but recently he did acknowledge he is ``warming
to the task.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there seems little doubt in the minds of political observers
that he will announce that he is forming an exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel dead certain that's what he is going to do,'' said
Austin political consultant Bill Miller. ``It will allow him to
establish a structure and more importantly raise the money to
launch his candidacy when he chooses to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suit is being tailored, and when the (legislative) session
is over, he'll put the suit on and run for president,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would continue meeting with various policy people
in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest,'' Bush said. ``When my name started
to surface, people started calling in. There seems to be a lot of
interest, genuine interest, obviously which is part of testing the
waters. So we've tried to make time for them to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted those visits haven't interfered with his work here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to allow anything to crowd out the main job I
have, which is governor of the state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of advisers includes Stephen Goldsmith, a leading
advocate of privatization; Larry Lindsey, who served on former
President Ronald Reagan's council of economic advisers; and
Condoleezza Rice, former provost of Stanford University and a
family friend.
</P>
<P>
   He also has consulted with former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
and former Secretary of State George Shultz.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading would-be Republican candidate is Elizabeth Dole,
former president of the American Red Cross who campaign vigorously
for her husband, Bob Dole, during his 1996 bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Other likely GOP primary candidates are Lamar Alexander, the
former Tennessee governor; conservative commentator Pat Buchanan;
publisher Steve Forbes; Arizona Sen. John McCain; former Vice
President Dan Quayle; and Christian conservative leader Gary Bauer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
