u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-500(2T     02-25 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WHITE SUPREMACIST SENTENCED TO DIE FOR DRAGGING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
 (fe) 
 By RICK LYMAN 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ After two days of testimony from psychologists,
law-enforcement officials and the killer's weeping father, an East
Texas jury decided on Thursday that the world would be better off
without John William King in it.
</P>
<P>
   The seven men and five women on the jury _ its sole black
member, a corrections officer, acting as foreman _ decided in just
under three hours that the white supremacist should die by lethal
injection for the 1998 murder of James Byrd Jr., a black man, whose
body was torn to pieces when dragged behind a pickup truck down a
rough rural road in the pine woods east of Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any prosecutor who enjoys getting a death penalty has just got
something wrong,'' District Attorney Guy James Gray said. ``You
temper your enthusiasm. But I am proud that my community stood up
and did what was right.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the 110-year-old courthouse, where journalists
and several dozen onlookers awaited the decision on the lawn, King
was jeered by some, with taunts of ``Bye-bye!'' and ``Rot in
hell!'' Asked if he had anything to say to the Byrd family, King
smirked and responded with a vulgarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect him to say, `God bless the Byrd family,'''
said Mary Verrette, one of the murdered man's sisters. ``It just
sums up the total personality of this young man.''
</P>
<P>
   After voting on Tuesday to convict King of capital murder, the
jurors had only two choices left on Thursday: death or life
imprisonment. Under a life sentence, King, 24, could have been
eligible for parole in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Only one white man has ever been executed in Texas for killing a
black person: a farmer who killed another white farmer's favorite
slave in the 1850s. Seven inmates have been executed thus far in
Texas in 1999, bringing the total number of executions in the state
to 171 since the death penalty was reinstated in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In voting for death, the jury rejected defense arguments that
King would not pose a threat to society if given life in prison and
that the virulent racism that led him to the murder was caused by
the conditions in Texas prisons, where he served a two-year
sentence for burglary in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The foreman, Joe Collins, said the jurors used District Judge
Joe Bob Golden's written instructions to guide them, step by step,
through their deliberations. Each time the judge's instructions
told them they needed to make a decision about the facts, they
talked it out and then voted, until finally they were left with the
ultimate votes of whether to convict and how to punish.
</P>
<P>
   Every single one of the votes, Collins said, was unanimous on
the first try.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence was overwhelming,'' he said. The decisive factor
in going for the death penalty, he said, was an 8-inch homemade
knife that Jasper jail officials recently found in King's cell.
``Obviously, the man still had a lot of hatred in his mind,''
Collins said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed no signs of remorse for his actions,'' said Karen
Flowers, another juror. ``It's so terribly sad. When I first came
here, I kept looking at him, how young and handsome he is. I have a
son about the same age. I wanted to find something to save him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she said, she could not.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said King had a rough night
in jail before the decision. ``He was cussing and throwing things
around,'' Rowles said. ``I think probably reality hit him sometime
in the last 24 to 36 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   King, usually a talkative prisoner, was moody and silent on
Thursday on the way to the county courthouse. ``He was not a happy
camper this morning,'' Rowles said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when his father tearfully begged the jury to spare
his son's life, King had asked to be taken out of the courtroom. He
returned after his father's testimony with red, swollen eyes.
``That was a sign of humanity,'' Ms. Flowers said. ``It was the
first we had seen.''
</P>
<P>
   King was hustled out of town immediately after the sentence was
announced and by early afternoon was already at the James Byrd
Diagnostics Unit _ named for a former warden, unrelated to the
murdered man _ in Huntsville. From there, he will join the other
451 prisoners on Texas' Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said King, an avowed white supremacist whose arms
and torso are covered with racist tattoos, had killed Byrd, 49, a
man he did not know, after picking him up after midnight on June 7,
1998. With King, prosecutors said, were two other white men:
Lawrence Brewer, 31, whom King met in prison, and Shawn Berry, 23,
whom King has known since high school. Trial dates for the other
two have not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   King, who had joined a racist group called the Confederate
Knights of America while in prison, had written his own
constitution and bylaws for a chapter he hoped to start in Jasper,
to be called the Texas Rebel Soldiers. The murder of Byrd,
prosecutors said, was to bind the three white men together and to
gain enough attention to attract more members to their group.
</P>
<P>
   The trio picked up Byrd, who was walking home from a party and
was partially intoxicated and drove him to a remote area east of
town where he was beaten. Chains were tied around his ankles and he
was dragged behind Berry's pick-up truck for about three miles,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   A pathologist testified that Byrd had been alive and probably
conscious until he hit a roadside culvert that sheared his body in
two.
</P>
<P>
   The elder King had been present for all of his son's trial but
decided on Thursday he was not up to staying to hear the sentence.
Instead, early Thursday morning, the father and son were allowed a
moment together in the courthouse. The Rev. Ron Foshage, pastor of
St. Michael's Catholic Church in Jasper, accompanied the father to
the meeting but stayed out of earshot.
</P>
<P>
   He said the father and son embraced and talked quietly together
for a few moments. ``I think both of them know it was probably the
last time they would have physical contact with one another,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the death sentence was announced, Foshage read a statement
from the elder King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please pray for the Byrd family who have endured unimaginable
pain and loss,'' he read. ``Please pray for these jurors who have
shouldered a terrible burden. Please pray for our town of Jasper, a
community that remains strong though scarred by this unspeakable
act.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger King also left a written statement behind as he was
taken away to prison. Neatly written on lined paper and handed to
his lawyers, it read: ``Though I remain adamant about my innocence,
it's been obvious from the beginning that this community would get
what they desire; so I'll close with the words of Francis Yockey:
``The promise of success is with the man who is determined to die
proudly when it is no longer possible to live proudly.''' It was
signed, ``Sincerely, John W. King.''
</P>
<P>
   Yockey was a pro-Nazi writer who died in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, meanwhile, said they were simply trying to do their
job and render a fair verdict, not to send any statement to the
world. They were just ``common citizens who felt going on the jury
was an obligation, not a privilege,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the selection of Collins, the sole black juror, as foreman
had not been intended as a message to the world, Ms. Flowers said,
though she knew that many would take it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was just one of us, that's it,'' she said. ``We got in
there and kind of stumbled around and nobody wanted to do the job
and Joe volunteered to do it. It was never any statement. We never
looked at Joe as a black man. He's just a fine man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
