<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASA-AIRTRAN26-COX     02-25 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASA-AIRTRAN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Path untaken: ASA mulled buying AirTran, filing says
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before agreeing to a buyout by longtime partner Delta
Air Lines, Atlantic Southeast Airlines weighed alternatives that
included buying AirTran Airways, a regulatory filing shows.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of a low-fare carrier called ``Asteroid'' _ a
code name for AirTran _ is listed as one of the strategies
Atlanta-based ASA might have launched had it spurned Delta's bid.
</P>
<P>
   That and other ``strategic alternatives'' are disclosed in a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing on Delta's $34-a-share
tender offer for the 72 percent of ASA Holdings it doesn't already
own.
</P>
<P>
   There's no indication any of the options, which also included
mergers with other regional airlines, was ever pursued. They are
presented only as theoretical scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ASA's board also considered rejecting the tender offer and
standing pat as a partially owned affiliate, the filing shows. In
the end, it decided taking Delta's bid was the best option.
</P>
<P>
   Filing shows that decision came under intense pressure from
Delta, which proposed the buyout in late January. At the same time,
it was demanding changes in the two carriers' existing partnership
that would cut ASA revenue and profits if it stayed independent.
</P>
<P>
   Delta used those prospective cuts to justify a bid price that
included only a slight premium over current trading levels for ASA
stock, which closed Thursday at $33.12 1/2, down 12 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either accept a $34 bid or watch the stock go to $20''
after the changes took effect, PaineWebber analyst Sam Buttrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   The $700 million tender offer was announced Feb. 16. If a
majority of shareholders approve by March 19, ASA will become a
Delta subsidiary. On Thursday, Delta said it got notice from
federal regulators they won't raise antitrust objections.
</P>
<P>
   ASA spokesman Sam Watts declined to comment on the Asteroid
option, other than to confirm the carrier's board ``did look at
potential alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   One was the purchase of Asteroid, described in the SEC filing as
an unprofitable low-fare airline with a strong presence on
Concourse C at Hartsfield International Airport. AirTran, which
shares Concourse C with ASA, is the only airline fitting that
description.
</P>
<P>
   A combined ASA-Asteroid would control an entire Hartsfield
concourse, the filing notes. Also, ASA would retain control over
deployment of its highly profitable new regional jets _ one of
several issues creating tension with Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Obvious disadvantages, however, also were noted. Chiefly, ASA
would be saddled with Asteroid's poor balance sheet and its
low-fare passenger base, diminishing its profitability and stock
price outlook. Also, the carriers have dissimilar fleets and
operations, and it was unclear how they would be combined.
</P>
<P>
   The filing gives no indication there was ever any discussion
between ASA and Asteroid. But there are personal links among
directors and executives of ASA and AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Priddy, who founded AirTran forerunner ValuJet and sits
on AirTran's board, was a co-founder of ASA, along with George
Pickett and John Beiser, who have remained as its top executives.
They'll leave after the Delta buyout closes.
</P>
<P>
   ASA's other alternatives included merging with another regional
carrier, dubbed ``Star,'' or offering itself for sale to one called
``Comet.'' Evidence in the filing suggests those are actually
SkyWest and Comair, respectively, Delta affiliates in other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   By combining with them, ASA would gain greater leverage in
dealings with Delta, the filing said. But either deal also carried
serious drawbacks for shareholders, it added.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and ASA have been allies since 1984, when Delta first
contracted with ASA for connecting flights from its Atlanta hub.
ASA has a strong financial record _ stronger than Delta's,
historically _ but has suffered service and staffing problems since
the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said in the SEC filings it began reevaluating affiliate
relations in 1997, with an eye toward changing certain aspects of
its contract with ASA. Ongoing discussions over those issues and
service problems culminated in the buyout bid last month.
</P>
<P>
   By taking full ownership, Delta will not only gain control of
ASA service and schedules, it also will boost its own bottom line
by absorbing ASA's higher profit margins, and it will gain access
to ASA's Hartsfield gates. Some observers think those are bigger
factors than service problems, which ASA had largely repaired by
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The filing shows Delta leaned hard on ASA to sell. For instance,
just before it first pitched the buyout, Delta threatened to
replace ASA on certain routes from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Delta renewed an effort to change the formula used
to divvy up revenue from the 80 percent of ASA passengers who
connect from Delta flights. The changes would cut ASA's annual
revenue by up to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single message that comes through from this deal is that
Delta is going to be much more aggressive and proactive in managing
regional partner relations,'' said analyst Buttrick. ``To a certain
extent, the message is, `No more Mr. Nice Guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   SkyWest and Comair, Delta's other two primary affiliates, remain
partly owned by Delta. Some analysts wonder about the future of
those relationships and whether Delta will try to bring all of its
affiliates under an umbrella subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll see how it goes with ASA first,'' Buttrick predicted.
``I do not expect anything more from them in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   The filings confirmed that Delta plans to install John
Selvaggio, a recent hire who previously ran US Airways' commuter
division, as chief executive of the ASA subsidiary, replacing
Pickett and Beiser.
</P>
<P>
   Two other top ASA executives, finance chief Ronald Sapp and
operations chief Ed Paquette, will remain in those roles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
