A9593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FCC26-COX     02-25 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FCC ruling makes per-minute charges for Internet possible
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A ruling Thursday by the Federal Communications
Commission throws open the door for per-minute charges for Internet
users and threatens current offerings of unlimited access to the
Net for a flat monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators ruled that dial-up Internet connections are
long-distance even when made through a local number. FCC officials
Thursday said they will now start considering how those charges
should be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision has the potential to change the pricing model
that we've seen in the last few years,'' said Jeff Kagan, an
Atlanta-based telecommunications analyst. ``This is a big decision
that should keep everything tied in knots for months longer.''
</P>
<P>
   While the FCC decision would directly affect only what phone
companies pay each other for Internet traffic, many Internet
Service Providers buy lines from upstart phone companies competing
with big regional companies like BellSouth. If the upstarts lose
out on profit, they may have to raise their rates to the ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This threat is that Internet Service Providers could be in the
position where they cannot offer flat rates,'' said Peter Lucht,
spokesman for MCI WorldCom, the giant telecommunications and
Internet company. ``Then the ISP must either pass on the costs or
find another form of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   FCC members have so far shown no inclination to chill the Net _
and they know that predictable, reasonable rates spur consumers to
log on. Moreover, the political danger of using regulation to
strangle the Net's growth makes the FCC unlikely to set a tough
rate scheme, said Dave Baker, vice president of MindSpring
Enterprises, the region's largest Internet Service Provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sum this up in two words: don't panic,'' he said. ``This
just shouldn't affect what consumers pay to use the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But local communications are for state regulators to monitor,
and the FCC also seems eager to keep a handle on the nation's
fastest growing medium.
</P>
<P>
   Most users of the Net now use a computer modem that dials the
local number of an Internet service provider (ISP). After that _
depending on what the user wants _ the signal could be routed to a
computer server anywhere in the United States or around the world.
</P>
<P>
   To the user, it only matters that he or she can get to the Net
and surf indefinitely without worrying about the kind of per-minute
charges that pile up on a long-distance voice call. That is
possible because users are charged for a local call only _ and most
get unlimited local calling along with their monthly fee to the
phone company.
</P>
<P>
   All calls and connections _ voice and Net _ depend on agreements
between the various phone companies that handle the transmissions.
Those agreements generally include a provision for companies to pay
each other when they transfer local calls: The calling company pays
the one that takes the call.
</P>
<P>
   Big regional phone companies like BellSouth have been arguing
all along that calls to the Internet are long-distance. That's
because the law says that when they pass along a local call from
one of their customers to another local phone company, they have to
pay the other company. With voice calls, that rule seemed likely to
mean that both companies paid each other about the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the payments are called reciprocal compensation. But
Internet calls tend to be one-way only. The Net customer dials an
ISP _ not the other way around. And since regional companies still
have a near-stranglehold on the residential market, they are nearly
always on the wrong end of the compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the Net calls are not local, regional companies
have not paid reciprocal compensation. For $23 billion-a-year
BellSouth, that means holding back several $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   For ICG Communications, whose revenue is $300 million, the
amount is a lot more important, said Cindy Schonhaut, executive
vice president. The Denver-based company offers a variety of
services, including local service in competition with various
regional companies, and is owed reciprocal compensation of about
$60 million, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 29 states, the public utility commissions have sided with the
competitive local exchange companies like ICG against the Bells.
The FCC Thursday ruled that current contracts between phone
companies must be honored. To BellSouth's rivals, that means
BellSouth should pay the compensation, but a quick payment by the
Bells is not expected. ``I wish they would respond by writing
checks,'' Schonhaut said. ``I think they'll respond by
litigating.''
</P>
<P>
   That expectation seemed bolstered by Bill Barfield, BellSouth's
associate general counsel, who said the company does not see the
FCC order as a mandate to pay what competitors say they are owed.
</P>
<P>
   ``BellSouth's position has always been clear: calls to the
Internet are interstate in nature. With the FCC's decision, they
are interstate now. And they were interstate when BellSouth signed
interconnection agreements with competitors. BellSouth must examine
the FCC's order in detail. With the inescapable logic of this
ruling, BellSouth has a strong legal basis for not paying
per-minute compensation for calls that terminate on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
