<SLUG> BC-CRUISESHIP-DUMPING-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE LINE IS INDICTED IN OIL-DUMPING CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Ala., Calif., N.Y.)   (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal grand jury in Los Angeles has indicted
Royal Caribbean Cruises on charges of making false statements to
the Coast Guard about oily waste discharges in 1994. Similar
charges are expected in the coming weeks in Alaska and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The three-count indictment returned late Wednesday said crew
members aboard the company's Nordic Prince presented records
covering up illegal discharges of oily waste into the ocean during
three Coast Guard inspections in Los Angeles from January to
October 1994. Each count carries a maximum fine of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Royal Caribbean pleaded guilty in Miami and San Juan
to similar charges covering the same time period involving five of
its ships, including the Nordic Prince. As part of the plea
agreement, the company paid $9 million in fines and agreed to
institute new environmental compliance programs aboard all of its
ships.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement did not insulate the world's second-largest cruise
company from potential charges in other federal jurisdictions
because prosecutors said that Royal Caribbean did not cooperate
fully. As a result, a company official acknowledged Thursday,
indictments are also expected in Alaska and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean officials said the company had already
acknowledged the illegal practices from 1990 to 1994, bought new
equipment and introduced extensive monitoring and compliance
programs. ``As we have said before, these acts were wrong and are
totally inexcusable,'' Jack Williams, the company president, said.
``We are doing everything we can to operate our ships above and
beyond compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges to which Royal Caribbean pleaded guilty last June
represented the largest criminal case of ocean pollution ever and
focused attention on difficulties in regulating the fast-growing
cruise industry.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean and the other major cruise companies are foreign
corporations and their ships fly foreign flags, leading to
questions about the jurisdiction of the U.S. authorities in
environmental cases and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean's lawyers had argued that the company was not
required to provide records to the Coast Guard because it is a
Liberian corporation. A judge rejected the argument and the company
pleaded guilty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both the old and new charges stem from dumping contaminated
water directly into the ocean. On any ship, oil drips from
machinery and collects along with seawater in the bilges.
Environmental regulations require ships to operate a device known
as an oily water separator to filter the oil out of the water. The
oil is stored on board while the cleansed water is discharged into
the ocean. Each time the separator operates, the results are to be
recorded in an oil record book.
</P>
<P>
   The Nordic Prince, which was later sold, was one of five Royal
Caribbean ships equipped in the early 1990s with makeshift pipes to
bypass the oil water separator and dump contaminated bilge water
directly overboard. The record books were falsified to show that
the waste was filtered before its discharge and then presented to
the Coast Guard in Los Angeles and elsewhere in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean acknowledged falsifying the books and lying
about the bypass systems in its two guilty pleas last June.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers said Royal Caribbean's failure to
turn over its complete files on the earlier incidents required
bringing charges in separate jurisdictions to discover the full
extent of the dumping violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
