</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EXPEDITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT BARS EXTRADITION OF MARYLAND YOUTH CHARGED WITH
MURDER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Thursday that an
American Jewish teen-ager who was charged with murder in Maryland
should not be extradited because he is an Israeli citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-2 decision means that the 18-year-old youth, Samuel
Sheinbein, who fled to Israel after the killing, will be tried in
an Israeli court despite pressure for his extradition from the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein fled in September 1997, two days after the dismembered
and burned body of an acquaintance, 19-year-old Alfredo Enrique
Tello Jr., was found in a garage in a Maryland suburb of
Washington. Sheinbein was later indicted in the slaying. To avoid
extradition, Sheinbein, who never lived in Israel, claimed Israeli
citizenship through his father, who immigrated to the United States
in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein appealed to the Israeli Supreme Court after the
Jerusalem District Court ruled last year that he should be
extradited despite his citizenship because he had not lived in
Israel and had not maintained close ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's ruling, the court said that ``no further affinity
with Israel is required for the appellant to be considered an
Israeli citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1978 Israeli law, citizens of Israel cannot be
extradited to stand trial abroad. The law reflected the view that
Jews should not be handed over to gentile courts, where they might
face an unfair trial.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and Attorney General Janet Reno expressed
disappointment with the ruling, which overturned a decision by a
lower court.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu defended the ruling, saying:
``Israel, as you know, is a state of law, and in a state of law the
interpreter of the law is the Supreme Court, whose decision we must
honor. I'm sure that the United States, which is also a state of
law, understands this.''
</P>
<P>
   David Libai, Sheinbein's lawyer, said, ``The Supreme Court
proved its independence by signaling that that it does not yield to
pressures from the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Maryland pressed for the extradition of
Sheinbein, who was later indicted in Montgomery County, Md. His
suspected accomplice, Aaron Needle, 18, hanged himself with a
bedsheet in a Maryland jail last April.
</P>
<P>
   Most European countries also do not extradite their citizens,
but this is not the practice in Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the majority opinion, Justice Theodor Orr noted that the
Israeli law contradicted extradition treaties with the United
States and other countries, and he urged that it be amended. But he
added that as long as the law was in force, it must be upheld. A
bill to amend the law is pending in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Israeli Justice Ministry said Sheinbein would
be indicted for murder at the Tel Aviv District Court as early as
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice will be done because the youth will be tried in
Israel,'' said Irit Kohn, director of the ministry's international
department. ``He's not getting up and going, but he is being tried
for murder, which is a very serious offense, and we will explain
this to our American colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Gansler, the Montgomery County prosecutor, remained
unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been our position and remains our position that
Sheinbein is a citizen of the United States,'' Gansler said in
Maryland. ``Sheinben was born, raised, went to school and lived
here his entire life, and only took a few vacations to Israel.
Sheinbein's guilt or innocence should be adjudicated here, and he
should be held accountable here.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder victim's mother, Eliette Ramos, urged Americans to
lobby Congress for the extradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very upset and disappointed with the Israel government
and the judiciary system,'' Ms. Ramos said. ``Each American should
be very concerned, outraged and angry at this outcome. I personally
will not rest in peace with this decision. How can the United
States government provide billions of dollars to Israel if they do
not support the U.S. treaty?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
