<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALL-SALE-BOS &LR;      02-25 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER KARP AGREES TO SELL 14 REGIONAL MALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Taking advantage of a strong economy and rapid
consolidation in the mall industry, local developer Stephen R. Karp
agreed Thursday to sell off a big chunk of his mall operations to
the nation's largest mall owner, Simon Property Group, for $1.725
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would make Indianapolis-based Simon New England's
dominant mall owner.
</P>
<P>
   After his New England Development Co. completes the sale of a
portfolio of 14 regional malls to Simon, Karp said NED will turn
its focus to developing projects in South Boston's Seaport
District, on New Haven's waterfront, in Plymouth, Mass., and in
suburban Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   While all these projects will have a retail component, several
also include plans for hotels, offices, and condominiums. In that
respect, they are different from the type of shopping malls Karp
helped build in the 1970's and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Karp, 58, was looking to cash
out his mall empire so he could help the Red Sox build a new
stadium to replace Fenway Park. But Karp dismissed such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing to say'' about the Red Sox, he said.
``I haven't had any recent conversations with them. It's not the
reason for the transaction (with Simon).''
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Simon _ which owns or has interests in 243
mall properties in the United States _ to assume management
responsibilities from NED's affiliated company, WellsPark
Management LLC.
</P>
<P>
   As for the timing of the proposed transaction, Karp cited the
robust economy and the maturity of the regional mall business.
</P>
<P>
   David Flick, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood Walker who follows
Simon, noted that malls commanded higher sales prices a year ago,
but added, ``You can never time the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months ago, Karp attempted to merge his malls with those
of the Richard E. Jacobs Group of Cleveland with the idea of taking
the combined company public, but that deal collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier attempt at a merger between Jacobs, Karp and a third
company fell through when 12 malls run by the third company were
purchased for a premium price by Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Karp's willingness to sell may reflect a rapidly changing retail
landscape. After 50 years of expansion, America is saturated with
malls. There is little space left to build them, and no great
demand for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   As the century draws to a close, many consumers are squeezed for
time. In the name of convenience, some have abandoned big malls to
do more of their shopping at smaller strip malls, which are easier
to get in and out of. Some consumers have even turned to Internet
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Convenience is everything,'' and today's consumer is spending
less time at large malls, noted Kathleen Seiders, a professor of
retail at Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   While Karp's malls last year had one of their best holiday
seasons of the 1990s, shopping trends suggest big malls may be at
or near their peak.
</P>
<P>
   For small privately owned companies, ``regional malls are a
one-generation business,'' said Karp, who developed his first mall
in 1972, the Liberty Tree Mall in Danvers. ``Now the public
companies are buying up the local regionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because 1999 may be a good time for Karp to switch his
focus from traditional malls to mixed-use development projects,
that doesn't mean Simon is making an unwise acquisition, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Big mall companies such as Simon have been consolidating rapidly
since the early 1990s when real estate investment trusts began
attracting the attention of Wall Street, said John Konarski, vice
president for research for the International Council of Shopping
Centers. As a result, big publicly owned REITS, with Simon in the
lead, have been snapping up small privately owned mall companies in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   With few opportunities to build new malls, mall REITS have to
achieve growth mostly through acquisitions, Konarski said.
</P>
<P>
   With their size, REITS can squeeze more efficiencies out of a
mall than a smaller owner. In addition, big REITs can use their
muscle to negotiate more favorable rents from big retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   For Simon, the proposed deal with Karp is an opportunity to bulk
up its presence in New England by adding such properties as
Northshore Mall in Peabody and Square One Mall in Saugus to a
portfolio that already includes the Burlington Mall and South Shore
Plaza in Braintree.
</P>
<P>
   That would give Simon just about every major regional mall in
Greater Boston except Natick Mall and the Mall at Chestnut Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Simon will have ``an incredibly dominant position'' in the local
marketplace, said Brian Kavoogian, managing director of the Boston
office of Holliday Fenoglio Fowler, an investment banking firm that
provides financing to malls, including Karp's.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing a widely held view, Kavoogian said, ``Steve Karp's
malls are viewed as some of the best in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of REITs, Simon's reputation is also impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon is the big gorilla in this market,'' analyst Fick said.
Simon will be ``nearly four times the size of its nearest
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of NED's malls were not included in the transaction _
CambridgeSide Galleria, Worcester Common Outlets, and Pheasant Lane
Mall in New Hampsire.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the malls in NED's portfolio are partly owned by other
investors. And in the case of CambridgeSide and Pheasant Lane, an
agreement could not be reached on the sale to Simon. As an outlet
mall, Worcester does not fit Simon's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Karp held out the possibility that CambridgeSide and Pheasant
Lane could be sold at a later date, possibly to Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the transaction, Karp will be invited to join the
Simon board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why Karp was willing to sell to Simon is that part of
his payment would come in the form of partnership shares that would
allow Karp to defer paying taxes on the capital gains, sources told
The Boston Globe earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts told Bloomberg News Simon is in talks with J.P. Morgan
Investment Management Inc. and its pension fund clients about
forming a venture to complete the buy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bloomberg, Simon will pay for the transaction with
$200 million of equity; J.P. Morgan will provide $500 million and
the venture will assume $995 million of debt.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Simon's shares closed unchanged
at 25 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Karp and his family have extensive investments on Nantucket.
They own a marina and such hotels as the Wauwinet, White Elephant
and the Harbor House. Those family investments are not a part of
NED, Karp said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
