<SLUG> BC-MACEDONIA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRESSES CHINA TO BACK CONTINUED U.N. ROLE IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States and its principal allies are
pressing China to allow the U.N. peacekeeping force in Macedonia to
continue operating for at least a few more weeks, despite Beijing's
veto of a resolution Thursday extending the force's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the 15-member Security Council was 13 in favor of a
six-month extension, with China opposed and Russia abstaining. The
negative vote by China, which as a permanent council member has
veto power, was sufficient to block continuation of the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said they effectively want China to reverse
its veto before the mandate's expiration Sunday, when the
peacekeeping force will be obliged to stop patrolling Macedonia's
borders with Albania and the troubled province of Kosovo in Serbia
and preventing illicit arms across the borders. But this would
require a new Security Council vote by this weekend with China
voting in favor or at least abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   China's action apparently came in retaliation for Macedonia's
diplomatic recognition of Taiwan in January in return for a
reported gift of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said they saw the peacekeeping force's
continuation as important to their efforts to promote stability in
the Balkans and did not want its operations interrupted before they
have had time to devise alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Those could include turning the task over to NATO or another
coalition of like-minded countries. But such a force would lack the
prestige of a Security Council mandate and would not be financed by
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, these diplomats said, Chinese officials have
rejected any such compromise and are threatening another veto if
other council members propose even a limited extension of the
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Defending Thursday's veto, China's representative to the United
Nations, Qin Huasun, made no allusion to Beijing's dispute with
Macedonia over Taiwan. Instead, he said the peacekeepers were no
longer needed because the situation in Macedonia ``has apparently
stabilized in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other Council members expressed regret that China was
endangering efforts to promote stability in a severely troubled
part of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
