<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL CONSIDERS HOLDING OLYMPIC HEARINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate committee is considering whether to hold
hearings into the Olympics bribery scandal, a proceeding that could
lead to financially crippling sanctions against organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, an Arizona Republican who chairs the Senate
Commerce Committee, is expected to decide Monday whether hearings
should be held into $1.2 million in enticements Salt Lake City's
Olympics organizers used to lure the 2002 Winter Games to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympics Committee, based in Switzerland,
already is reeling after an independent ethics panel found that 24
of the IOC's 114 members accepted cash payoffs, lavish gifts,
university scholarships and paid holidays.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been consulting with Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska and a
Commerce Committee member, about the possibility of hearings and
what kind of penalties Congress might levy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the options open to lawmakers are fines, taking away
revenue from broadcast rights or lifting the International Olympic
Committee's tax-exempt status. The latter would hamstring the
committee, since nine of the IOC's 11 worldwide sponsors are U.S.
firms that reduce their tax burdens through tax-exempt donations to
the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid them (sanctions) at all cost, but we want
people to understand that they're possible,'' Stevens said. ``It's
essential that confidence be maintained and that the integrity of
the system for the benefit of the athletes be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing a role in McCain's decision, an aide said, will be a
report from the U.S. Olympic Committee's ethics oversight
commission, led by former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell.
The Mitchell commission, appointed by the USOC in December, is
expected to issue its report Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hampered by the lack of subpoena power and key figures' fears of
criminal liability if they talked, the Mitchell commission report
is expected to contain no major revelations, but will pin the major
blame for the Salt Lake scandal on a small circle of local bid
committee officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the Internal Revenue Service already
are investigating the scandal. Congress' General Accounting Office
is looking at how taxpayer funds are being used for roads, mass
transit and other infrastructure improvements linked to the Salt
Lake City Games and whether local organizers benefited personally
from the federally financed projects.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also has conducted a probe of the Salt Lake City
scandal. To date four IOC members have resigned, five have been
suspended, three are under investigation and one has received a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
