</P>
<P>
   TAX-POLICY (Washington) _ While the political fight this year
and probably into the 2000 elections will center on _ tax cuts
versus saving Social Security _ there is also a growing focus on
another, older and more fundamental issue. Should tax policy focus
simply on raising the revenue needed to pay for the activities of
government? Or can the tax code be used as an effective instrument
to address the nation's social and economic ills? By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-KIDS-EDUC (Undated) _ The 1998 tax year offers new
possibilities for families who are saving for their children's
college education. By David J. Dent.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SPOUSE (Undated) _ Until recently, proving that an
individual was truly innocent _ that he or she had no knowledge of
the violations of the tax laws and did not benefit from the money
kept from the government _ was virtually impossible. A new law that
took effect in July, however, makes innocent-spouse status easier
to claim. By Michelle Leder.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-FILING (Undated) _ So eager is the IRS to have us file by
computer that its World Wide Web site (www.irs.ustreas.gov)
provides links to private companies offering electronic filing
services. Only about a quarter of all tax returns will be
electronically filed this year. By Neil Genzlinger.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-YUPPIE (Undated) _ Lowering the tax bill for young urban
professionals. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic and Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SIGNING (Undated) _ The signing of income tax returns, an
American ritual now in its 86th year, is being swept into the
dustbin of history. Replacing traditional John Hancocks with
digital signatures will make filing returns easier, but the way the
Internal Revenue Service has chosen to sweep aside old-fashioned
written signatures will also mean continuing annual costs for
taxpayers _ and revenues for tax software companies. By David Cay
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-GAIN (Undated) _ Keeping records of stock purchases and
sales and completing the tax forms to report capital gains and
losses is tricky enough for the average investor. But for day
traders, who spend their days flipping stocks, and for a growing
army of other investors who trade often, lured by the bull market
and the ease of trading on line, compliance with tax reporting
rules creates a mountain of paperwork each year. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-RETIRE (Undated) _ Tax laws affecting retirees are already
