<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ EXPECTS FEWER DIGITAL LAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. says higher-than-expected attrition of
former Digital Equipment Corp. employees will result in fewer
layoffs this year than previously anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   In Compaq's annual report to the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the Houston company said Thursday 14,700 Digital jobs
will have been terminated from between July 1, 1998, and June 30,
1999. However, only 12,400 will be ``involuntary separations.''
That's because 2,300 Digital workers have left the company and
found other jobs since Compaq acquired it last year.
</P>
<P>
   A Compaq spokesman said the higher-than-expected attrition will
result in fewer Digital layoffs between now and June. Compaq
currently employs about 7,000 people in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher attrition reflects the good times in the Greater
Boston area _ particularly for getting jobs at companies like Sun
Microsystems in Chelmsford and at other companies,'' said Terry
Shannon, editor and publisher of ``Shannon Knows Compaq,'' a
newsletter that tracks the nation's second-largest computer maker.
``Compaq in Massachusetts today is not your father's Digital _ it's
a different environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's goal, announced last June, was to reduce its worldwide
head count by 17,000 between July 1, 1998 and June 30, 1999 to
67,000 employees. Of those cuts, 14,700 jobs were targeted from
Digital and 2,300 from Compaq. When Compaq completed its
acquisition of Digital last year, the combined companies had 84,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Compaq said many of the remaining layoffs at
the combined company will come from Europe, where the cost of
terminating people is significantly higher and takes longer to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 12,800, or 75 percent of the 17,000 employees Compaq is
shedding left the combined company by the end of last year, a
Compaq spokesman said. That included 10,542 employees who were
terminated by the company and received a severance package as part
of the corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   In Compaq's annual SEC report, the company said it set aside
nearly $1.5 billion last year to cover the Digital layoffs and
about $286 million for the Compaq terminations. Last summer, Compaq
underwent a significant restructuring that included closing plants
in Texas and consolidating operations.
</P>
<P>
   A Compaq spokesman noted that despite the hefty Digital layoffs,
it was hiring people in Massachussetts, most notably at the Compaq
services organization in Stow. However, he declined to discuss how
many people were added last year.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Compaq told the SEC it expects to complete the
purchase of Shopping.com, an on-line retailer based in Corona Del
Mar, Calif., for $220 million next month and finalize its $300
million acquistion of Zip2 Corp., an electronic commerce provider
based in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq shares closed at 41, down 1 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
