<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ALICE-525&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGICAL `ALICE' A BENCHMARK OF TV FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Alice in Wonderland,'' one of the sturdiest of all perennials,
springs up brimming with new life at 8 p.m. Sunday night on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour production is such a sparkler that it's a shame
NBC didn't schedule it an hour earlier for children.
</P>
<P>
   This version follows the familiar pattern set by the 1933 film
of Lewis Carroll's wild masterpiece. Which is, to stud the cast
with marvelous character actors and let their cameo performances
carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1933, it was the likes of W.C. Fields and Jack Oakie. On
Sunday, NBC showcases Whoopi Goldberg (Cheshire Cat), Ben Kingsley
(Major Caterpillar), Miranda Richardson (Queen of Hearts), Martin
Short (Mad Hatter), Peter Ustinov (Walrus), Christopher Lloyd
(White Knight), Gene Wilder (Mock Turtle), Pete Postlethwaite
(Carpenter) and Robbie Coltrane and George Wendt (Tweedledum and
Tweedledee).
</P>
<P>
   They're directed by Nick Willing (``Photographing Faeries''),
surrounded by dozens of creations from Jim Henson's Creature Shop
and abetted by zippy special effects from the FrameStore in London.
</P>
<P>
   And Alice? She's Tina Majorino, a child actress who's been in
the failed TV series ``Camp Wilder'' and several films, including
``Corrina, Corrina,'' ``When a Man Loves a Woman'' and
``Waterworld.''
</P>
<P>
   Majorino comes across at first as an unattractive and
disappointingly dour Alice. But she's a decent actress, and she
gains ground through the course of the show. When she does venture
a smile, it's an event.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cameo stars, the standouts are the shrieking
Richardson (``Chop off more heads _ it's wonderful''), the gentle
Wilder in his turtle get-up and the comically uninhibited Short.
</P>
<P>
   Short might, in fact, be the definitive Hatter. By some
photographic magic, his shoulders have been pinched and his body
narrowed, and his head ballooned into funhouse proportions. He
sings, he dances, he cringes and he vamps, all to delightful
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Short's Mad Hatter is part of the amazing midsection of ``Alice
in Wonderland,'' taking Alice in stunning sequence from the Mad
Hatter's tea party, to the helter-skelter croquet match with the
Queen of Hearts, to a sweet song and dance with Mock Turtle, to
Lloyd's claptrap Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice'' isn't quite that good from start to finish. But when
it is, you might find yourself thinking that television has come up
with its own inventive classic in the vein of ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's annual special-effects extravaganzas _ ``Gulliver's
Travels,'' ``Ulysses,'' ``Merlin'' _ reach a peak with ``Alice in
Wonderland.'' Characters tumble in and out of books, sets inflate
and deflate to match Alice's growths and shrinkages, humans
interact with Creature Shop creations, and actors morph into
strange beings. The set design and costuming are sumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   The fun is in the journey; what ``Alice'' means as an integrated
story is anyone's guess, except that Alice is dreaming in the real
world to avoid having to sing for guests at her parents' garden
party.
</P>
<P>
   But if you choose to look at it this way, you're obviously
welcome to sink your imagination into the tale's more, uh,
psychedelic aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Alice expands and shrinks as she partakes of mysterious potions
and magic mushrooms, all in her quest to reach a verdant garden.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, isn't the White Knight talking backward? Go ask
Alice. I think she'll know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While NBC experiences a high of sorts, HBO stubs its toe
Saturday night with ``Lansky,'' a cable movie starring Richard
Dreyfuss as Meyer Lansky, the Jewish immigrant turned Mafia
kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has a pedigree. It's directed by John McNaughton
(``Wild Things''). The script is from David Mamet (``Wag the Dog,''
``The Spanish Prisoner''), no less. And Dreyfuss is joined by Eric
Roberts, Anthony LaPaglia, Beverly D'Angelo and Illeana Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie jumps around in Lansky's life without traction and
sometimes without logic. In the midst of the highly impressionistic
technique, the viewer is unlikely to feel an attachment to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a shrewd and powerful performance, Dreyfuss can't buck
the obstacles. If you do watch, though, just for the heck of it,
pay special attention to a brief World War II scene aboard a
military plane.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why, nor can I swear it's deliberate, but in that
scene Dreyfuss lapses into a dead-on impression of Robert Duvall.
Not only that, but it's seemingly the Duvall character from ``A
Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
