<HEADLINE>
CHECK FUND CUSTODIAN ACCUSED IN ALLEGED THEFT FIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Veteran Treasury employee John Trischitta, arrested
last Friday for his role in the alleged theft of $6.5 million from
the state's Unpaid Check Fund, has been fired.
</P>
<P>
   New Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien Thursday sent a short, direct,
dismissal letter to the 20-year department employee after he spent
nearly a week on paid leave while the investigation ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, who rose from a teller at the now-defunct State
House bank to become the gatekeeper of the enormous Unpaid Check
Fund, is out on $10,000 bail after pleading not guilty in Boston
Municipal Court on Friday to charges of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly alleges Trischitta accepted a
$50,000 bribe from Martin Robbins, an ``heir finder'' who would
comb the Unpaid Check Fund for large sums that he could return to
their owner for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins was also arrested last week, charged with larceny,
forgery and uttering, after a BankBoston employee tipped off the
AG's office that he was trying to withdraw $6.5 million from an
escrow account there.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who is being held at the Nashua Street Jail, allegedly
forged documents that enabled him to siphon the money out of the
Unpaid Check Fund into the escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly asserts that the suspect paid Trischitta a cut of the
stolen money in exchange for directing him to the uncashed checks.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the two suspects declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And as of Friay, Trischitta's boss, Robert E. Foley, the deputy
treasurer in charge of cash management, will also be out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said she had planned to replace him with her own
political appointment before news of the investigation broke.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Reilly and O'Brien declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
