<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: KEEPING CHILDREN OUT OF DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Pa., Fla., N.M., Idaho, Mich., Minn., Miss., Ohio,
S.C., Wyo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In three separate accidents last summer, 11 small
children climbed into car trunks, pulled them shut and died from
the heat when they could not get out.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in March, after a complicated design effort, General
Motors is offering an illuminated release handle that many children
could use to escape. The handles, which dealers will install as
options inside trunks, stay lighted for half an hour after the
trunk is closed.
</P>
<P>
   The device can be installed in most family passenger vehicles
made since 1990, GM said, though it cannot fit in some specialized
vehicles, like Corvettes. For cars that have rear seats that fold
down to give trunk access, the kit includes a catch to make it hard
for a child to fold down the seat. The whole package costs $50.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, car trunks are not by any means the biggest
danger for small children, but they came under scrutiny in August
when five girls, aged 2 through 6, crawled into the trunk of a
Saturn in West Valley City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   When the mother of two of the girls realized they were missing,
she drove around the neighborhood looking for them _ not realizing
they were in the trunk. One of the police officers who were called
in to search opened the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Two more children died in Greensboro, Pa., and four in Gallup,
N.M.
</P>
<P>
   GM set its engineers to work on the problem, but they
immediately called for outside help. ``We have no in-house
expertise with human factors for 3-year-olds,'' said William Kemp,
a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The company went to Fisher-Price, the toy maker, for advice, and
ended up at Exponent/Failure Analysis Associates of San Francisco,
where Christine Wood, a child psychologist, helped run more than
200 tests of nine designs.
</P>
<P>
   One early choice was a knob, but the smallest children lacked
the finger strength to twist it. Another was a lighted pull cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured it would really be so obvious,'' Dr. Wood told a
news conference in Washington. ``We adults were sure it would work,
but we found that very young children believe they shouldn't touch
things that looked electrical, and they wouldn't even try it.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineers tried a lighted switch that looked like a wall
switch for a light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work,'' Kemp said. ``A light switch doesn't
telegraph being an opener. We interviewed the children and they
said things like, `I wanted to get out, not turn the light on.'''
</P>
<P>
   The lighted handle, he said, ``looks somewhat like a door
handle; it screams out `handleness.''' But it did not work with all
children; some, especially the youngest, lay passively in the
trunks and did not try the handle. Researchers believe their tests
may not duplicate the real world: some children will panic and will
not find the release.
</P>
<P>
   The kits are available as a dealer-installed option on new cars.
GM is not installing them as standard equipment because it is
waiting for the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to
write a standard, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   First, Buckle the Adults
</P>
<P>
   Auto accidents are the leading cause of death for young
children, killing about 2,000 people age 14 and under each year.
Fewer would die if more were in seat belts or car seats; over half
the children killed are not in seat belts or other restraints.
</P>
<P>
   But how can states raise the proportion of parents who buckle up
children? Advocates for child safety are trying a new approach:
focusing on the laws that cover adults.
</P>
<P>
   While all 50 states have laws regarding car seat restraints, the
laws on children are strong but those covering adults are much
weaker. In all states, police officers who observe an unbelted
child can pull over a car and write a ticket; in 35 states, police
cannot write tickets for non-use by adults unless they first pull
over a car for some other offense.
</P>
<P>
   The determining factor in whether children wear belts is not
whether the state has a law, according to researchers, but whether
the driver is buckled. According to the Air Bag and Seat Belt
Safety Campaign, an organization financed by insurers, auto
companies and the federal government, in cars in which the driver
is buckled, 87 percent of the children are appropriately
restrained; if the driver is unbuckled, only 24 percent of the
children are buckled in. In other words, drivers who don't buckle
themselves don't bother with the children either.
</P>
<P>
   So organizers are bringing school-aged children into state
capitols in several states to buttonhole legislators for stronger
laws on adults. This month, they hit Idaho, Michigan, Minnesota,
Mississippi, Ohio, South Carolina and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is also advertising. In Florida, it is going beyond
public service ads and spending $500,000 on print and TV spots. The
TV ads show emergency workers at crash scenes wheeling away dead or
injured children. ``Most grown-ups who don't wear seat belts don't
buckle kids,'' says an actor in one who appears to be 9 or 10 years
old. The Florida ads are in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, where the legislative session starts on March 2, has
been a target of the campaign. It is among the states that require
that the police first stop vehicles for some other offense before
they can ticket adults for not using belts. Last year, the Florida
House of Representatives passed a bill to provide ``standard''
enforcement, but it died in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never sponsored a bill where I had so many groups and
resolutions supporting it and not been able to pass it,'' said
Dennis Jones, a former chairman of the House Transportation
Committee and now Speaker of the House. Some voters, especially in
rural areas, strongly oppose seat belt laws for adults.
</P>
<P>
   But children, Jones said, will be effective lobbyists, and
persuading more adults to buckle up will also help insure
compliance among children who are old enough to buckle themselves.
``Kids have the tendency to do what they see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Right Seat, Wrong Car?
</P>
<P>
   Sell a baby seat to parents and most will install it
incorrectly, government studies have found. Give the parents
written or verbal instructions, and most will still install it
wrong, says the National Transportation Safety Board, which wants
to try a new approach. The states should establish permanent
clinics where drivers could go with car and car seat to have the
two linked up correctly, the board decided in January.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that dozens of different seat belt designs are in
use in cars as well as dozens of different child seat designs. They
all work together differently.
</P>
<P>
   A properly used child restraint cuts the risk of death or
serious injury 71 percent; an improperly used one cuts the risk
only 59 percent, according to a study by the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration. That suggests that dozens of
children die each year because their seats were attached to cars
incorrectly or because they were not properly in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term solution is a standardized car and baby-seat
design, which President Clinton may announce Friday. But cars
already on the road will be carrying children for years to come;
hence the recommendation for clinics.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA Chairman James Hall said in an interview that auto
dealers, volunteer fire companies and others had held one-time
clinics at which parents could have their car seats checked, but
that ``any event you go to, you're finding misuse or
misinstallation of 80 percent plus.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, is ``there are literally hundreds of
thousands of different possibilities out there, given all the car
seats and the different back seats in passenger and sport utility
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Hall went to Australia and visited its network of
permanent fitting stations. Ninety percent of seats there were used
correctly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Safety board officials say Kiwanis International, the American
Automobile Association, Ford Motor, DaimlerChrysler, GM and the
National Safe Kids Campaign, a safety group, have all expressed
interest in helping bring permanent car seat clinics to the United
States. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
