<HEADER>
A9641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISAKSON26-COX     02-25 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAKSON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isakson sworn in, marking departure from Gingrich era
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where his predecessor loved to talk, Johnny Isakson
kicked off his congressional service Thursday with a pledge to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican brought 150 family members and friends
with him from Atlanta on a campaign-chartered Delta jet to watch
him take the oath of office and receive a warm welcome from
Democrats and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling some advice from his first days in the state
legislature, Isakson said, ``The best way to learn is to keep your
mouth shut. I intend to be a very good listener.''
</P>
<P>
   His first speech in the House of Representatives, delivered
inadvertently from the lectern on the Democratic side of the
chamber, and his comments throughout the day were filled with
modesty and self-deprecation _ Isakson trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   In tone and substance, his words marked a departure from the
20-year tenure of Newt Gingrich, the former speaker whose seat
Isakson took Thursday. Gingrich was not at the Capitol, but he was
not far from anyone's mind, including Isakson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am well aware that to all of you I am nothing more today
than the fellow that replaced Newt. I hope in the years to come
I'll be a respected friend and one who joined with you to make a
difference for the United States of America,'' Isakson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), the dean of the state's delegation and
frequent critic of Gingrich, welcomed Isakson to the House and
praised him as a bridge builder. The 54-year-old real estate
executive took the oath from Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.), whose
lower profile also stands in sharp contrast to Gingrich's
never-a-dull-moment style of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Isakson nor Hastert would have played the roles they did
on Thursday had Gingrich not decided in November to give up his
role as speaker and his seat in Congress following the GOP's
disappointing performance in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, in all likelihood, would Thursday have been Rep. Robert
Livingston's (R-La.) last work day in the House.
</P>
<P>
   A half hour before he was sworn in, Isakson had a chance hallway
encounter with Livingston, the speaker-to-be who decided to resign
from Congress on the heels of revelations of marital infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're coming in as I'm going out. I hope you have a long and
wonderful career,'' Livingston told Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his farewell speech in the House, Livingston said,
``Compromise is the glue that renders democracy possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are words that Isakson lives by, as he noted when he
arrived at the Capitol in a taxi cab shortly after 9 a.m. ``That
line about compromise still works pretty good,'' he said. ``I've
been married to the same woman for 31 years. I know all about
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   In his convincing win in Tuesday's special election, Isakson
made a virtue of criticism from some Republicans that he is
insufficiently committed to conservative principle.
</P>
<P>
   The victory spurred calls from Hastert and Majority Whip Tom
DeLay (R-Texas), as well as constituents and corporate interests
who wanted to know how he would vote on a variety of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   After just a few hours of sleep, Isakson awoke at 4:30 a.m.
Thursday, gathered his family and headed to Hartsfield
International Airport. He helped flight attendants serve breakfast
on the flight to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He and his backers were in high spirits when they filed off a
Boeing 727 at Ronald Reagan National Airport. And why not? Isakson
scored his first big political win after two failed statewide
campaigns, including a 1996 battle for the Republican nomination
for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Dianne, three children, Kevin, John and Julie, and
mother-in-law Gay Davison joined Isakson on Thursday. So too did
Georgia School Superintendent Linda Schrenko, Marietta Daily
Journal publisher Otis Brumby and prominent Georgia Republicans
Oscar Persons and Jeanne Ferst.
</P>
<P>
   The new House member admittedly did not know his way around the
Capitol, and passed one new colleague after another without either
party knowing who the other was.
</P>
<P>
   But after being shown his new office in Rayburn House Office
Building _ Gingrich's former district office in a desirable suite
with a view of the Capitol dome _ Isakson acquired a voting card
and a lapel pin that identified him as a member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang in his office as soon as an aide de-activated
the answering machine. The caller was former Sen. Bob Dole, whose
1996 presidential campaign Isakson supported. Isakson said they
plan to have coffee once he settles in.
</P>
<P>
   He fulfilled his first request from a constituent when he
procured a copy of the House rules for a woman who is working on a
project for a college course.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson cast his first vote for a noncontroversial
telecommunications bill that passed 403-3. His emotions normally
held in check in public, Isakson allowed that walking onto the
House floor for the first time was an ``awesome moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid jokes about not knowing where to go and what to do, Isakson
exuded a confidence that he said comes from 17 years in the
Democratic-controlled Georgia Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the lingo and I know some of the rules,'' Isakson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Isakson put it succinctly: ``He is very effective and he
loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his first taste Thursday of being in the majority,
remembering that in his first year as minority leader in the
Georgia House of Representatives, Democrats outnumbered Republicans
161 to 19. Republicans have a six-seat margin in the House now that
Isakson is among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more vote!'' Rep. Billy Tauzin (R-La.) quipped to House
Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas after Isakson took his seat.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, after a tour of the Franklin Roosevelt memorial,
Isakson and his entourage boarded their flight back to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He will return in time for the next session of the House on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But before then, Isakson said he must complete paperwork to
resign as state school board chairman and sever his daily ties to
Northside Realty, his family real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson and his wife are not planning to move to Washington, but
Isakson said he does not expect to have trouble finding an
apartment for the three- or four-day House work week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing, that's something I know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
