A9643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGAL-DEFENSE-FUND26-     02-25 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-DEFENSE-FUND26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texans' contributions to Clinton defense fund top $86,000
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans, including big-name Democrats and plain
old citizens who thought their president was getting a raw deal,
poured more than $86,000 into Bill Clinton's legal defense fund in
the last half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the whole screwy (Kenneth) Starr group is out of
balance for justice,'' said Austinite Wally Ellinger, who three
times responded to fund-raising letters by sending a total of $30.
``When there comes a letter, I just throw in 10 bucks and say good
wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of Texas donors was topped by a $10,000 contribution
from Dallas housewife Hayden McIlroy. At the bottom of the list,
which includes 1,226 donations, were $1 contributions from Abilene
housewife Sadie Smith, Celeste retiree Isabele Magedson, San
Antonio nurse Allen B. Eastman and Midland businessman Raymond
Horton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made mistakes like all of us, but I judge that for the
American people he has done a good job,'' said Horton, who has
never voted for Clinton for president.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the president's legal defense fund collected more than
$4.5 million in 1998. About $2.3 million came in after Clinton
admitted in August that he had had an improper relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The funds will be used to help pay the Clintons' mounting legal
bills, which, thanks to the fund, are now down to $5.2 million.
More than 50,000 Americans made contributions to the fund, formally
known as the Clinton Legal Expense Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more than half the contributions were for $25 or
less. Only 5 percent were for $200 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more well-known names on the list of Texas donors to
the fund are former U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright of Fort Worth,
$200; state Rep. Al Edwards of Houston, $100; University of Texas
System General Counsel and former state Sen. Ray Farabee, $100; and
former state Rep. John Hirschi of Wichita Falls, $100.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Treasurer Azie Taylor Morton, who served in the
Carter administration and now lives in Austin, is the trustee for
the fund, which used mailing lists from the Democratic National
Committee and other political sources.
</P>
<P>
   Austin retiree Robert Gronlie said he sent $100 because he did
not like how Clinton was being treated. ``I think the guy is being
persecuted,'' he said. Mark Batterson, an Austin publisher, sent
$350 to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the kind of guy, when I was going to school I used to
defend the little guys against bullies,'' said Batterson, adding
that he was not ``thrilled'' by Clinton's behavior. ``But at the
same time I think he has been a good president and apparently most
people agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
