<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-EXPULSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC TO DISCUSS MORE EXPULSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beleaguered International Olympic Committee begins deciding
this weekend whether to expel another dozen or more members in what
is already the worst scandal in modern Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's six-man investigative panel will meet at Olympic
headquarters in Switzerland to weigh more evidence of wrongdoing by
IOC members submitted recently by the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee as well as numerous bid cities for five other Games.
</P>
<P>
   Though four members have already resigned and another five have
been forced out for taking improper payoffs or gifts from the Salt
Lake City bidders for the 2002 Winter Games, another 10 were
implicated earlier this month and more names are expected to
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many? I don't know,'' said IOC vice president Richard
Pound of Canada, who chairs the panel. ``It's kind of a movable
feast at the moment. The number of cities we've heard from is in
the teens and some are still coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the IOC has vowed to clean house definitively at its
special session on March 17-18 in Lausanne, the inquiry panel plans
to finish its work Sunday and make an immediate report to the
executive board, which will vote to expel, warn, or exonerate those
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to give the members as much notice as we can,''
said Pound. ``Anybody who may be subject to expulsion would want an
opportunity to get ready to defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A 300-page report issued this month by the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee's ethics panel unveiled a second wave of members who
allegedly took cash and gifts: Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western
Samoa, Shagdarjav Magvan of Mongolia, Austin Sealy of Barbados,
Phillip Coles of Australia, Anani Matthia of Togo, Ashwini Kumar of
India, Ram Ruhee of Mauritius, Willi Kaltschmitt of Guatemala, and
Mohamed Zerguini of Algeria. The report also provided fresh details
about executive board member Kim Un-yong of South Korea and Louis
Guirandou-N'Diaye of Ivory Coast, who were already under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The payoffs ranged from a $100,000 job for Kim's son to a
$30,000 loan to Wallwork's wife to $3,000 monthly payments to Sealy
to Super Bowl trips for Coles and Kaltschmitt. The Nagano bidders
also forwarded names of nine IOC members who took multiple vacation
trips to Japan at Nagano's expense; other cities have said they
provided gifts far in excess of the $150 limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's inappropriate? It's like saying I can't define
obscenity, but I know it when I see it,'' Pound said. ``If you get
a gift that's $151, that's clearly not a problem. If you get a
Mercedes, that clearly is.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, who has vigorously denied wrongdoing, and one or two
other members are expected to appear in person before the panel.
They and others will also have a chance to explain themselves next
month to the executive board and to the full body, which is
expected to expel any guilty members who have not stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   Pound also said that the investigative panel would quickly
exonerate any members it found blameless. ``We don't want this
thing to be hanging over the heads of IOC members who are not
guilty of anything,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
