<SLUG> BC-OAKLAND-INVASION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON TOUTS BENEFITS OF MOCK OAKLAND INVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Marine and Navy officials on Thursday defended a
planned mock invasion of Oakland, Monterey and Alameda, Calif.,
next month as an opportunity to try out new military equipment and
tactics in an urban setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps said in a statement that the war games, which
have provoked strong local opposition, will help the service
prepare ``for urban battlespaces of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Bruce Nichols, of the Navy's Maritime Battle Center in
Newport, R.I., said the mock battles will test ``new concepts and
technology'' needed in future conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the war game will ``directly influence'' future
Navy budgets and military tactics, according to a Navy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials planning the exercise spoke at a Pentagon news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The event will involve some 6,000 troops and five Navy ships.
Officials said no more than 700 Marines, from a Marine
Expeditionary Force at Camp Pendelton, Calif., will be brought to
shore at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corps Col. Gary Anderson, chief of staff of the Marine
Corp Warfighting Laboratory in Quantico, Va., said that any
disruption in the California cities will be minimal. He also said a
mock battle scheduled in Oakland during daylight hours won't add
significantly to the area's noise pollution. ``We are not going to
be all that loud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise is scheduled to begin with an amphibious landing
and helicopter assault on Monterey March 13. It will shift to
Alameda and Oakland March 15-18 with some Marines conducting
reconnaissance operations at the Naval Weapons Station at Concord
and at Moffet Field and other Marines staging a pitched ``battle''
at Oakland's shuttered Oak Knoll Medical Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines view the exercise, dubbed Urban Warrior, as an
important step toward shifting away from traditional strategies in
fighting a foe like Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The military also sees the battles of tomorrow taking place in
ethnically divided, war-torn Third World cities, like Mogadishu in
Somalia where 18 U.S. servicemen died in 1993 as part of a United
Nations humanitarian mission.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the war doctrine that currently drives Marine Corps
planning is that troops are supposed to avoid fighting in cities
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But when they cannot do that, the standard tactic is to shell
the cities with artillery and then send in infantry units with guns
blazing. The result is significant loss of life and property.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach will not be suitable in the future,'' the
service said, adding that future conflicts in such cities will be
limited in scope.
</P>
<P>
   The exercises in Northern California are meant to help devise a
new urban war doctrine and military tactics to replace the old
ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the March war games, troops will operate under the following
scenario: A nation friendly to the United States requests help in
dealing with a humanitarian crisis. Along the way, U.S. forces
encounter a factionalized population, some of whom oppose the U.S.
presence and may be preparing a biological weapons attack. American
commanders will then have to devise tactics to protect themselves
while defusing the crisis. In the process they will be testing new
weapons and communications equipment, which could also be used in
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Local opposition to the war games led the National Park Service
to bar the military from conducting some of them at the Presidio in
San Francisco because of possible damage to environmentally
sensitive dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the military switched those exercises to Oakland,
Mayor Jerry Brown supported the plan. Peace activists accused him
of shedding his old skepticism of the military and now ``promoting
violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
