A9651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESPRIT-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-25 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPRIT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPRIT DE CORP. STARTS A REVIVAL CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An advertising and marketing effort is seeking to rekindle the
sprightly spirit that a decade ago propelled Esprit apparel into
the front ranks _ or is it racks? _ of clothing brands.
</P>
<P>
   The revival campaign by the amusingly named Esprit parent,
Esprit de Corp. in San Francisco, is getting under way with
advertisements in March issues of magazines and posters in New York
and San Francisco. The campaign, with an estimated budget of $5
million to $6 million, is the first by Toth Brand Imaging in New
York and Concord, Mass., since the agency was awarded the Esprit
account in October.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be comeback for the Esprit lines of sportswear,
footwear and accessories, which are sold at retail stores and
through catalogs, is indicative of ambitious plans by marketers to
capitalize on strong consumer demand for name-brand products. That
is particularly true in categories like apparel where shoppers
display intense image-consciousness. The inherent value perceived
in moribund brands is a leading reason for the increase in attempts
to resuscitate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, Esprit was the embodiment of a life-style look,
weekend clothes and San Francisco,'' said Tom Julian, the trend
analyst for Fallon McElligott in New York. ``There was always a
good feeling about Esprit: free spirited, casual, somewhat
individualized, ethereal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The brand still does have some cachet,'' he added. ``But is it
the right time to bring Esprit back now?''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively new top management of Esprit de Corp. thinks the
timing is propitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to re-establish a relationship with the consumer,''
said Jay Margolis, the chairman and chief executive at Esprit de
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody grew up with Esprit, but it lost touch with us over
a period of time,'' he added. ``We want to bring back Esprit, but a
new Esprit versus the 1970s and 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolis, a former top executive at Tommy Hilfiger and Liz
Claiborne, became an owner of Esprit de Corp. in October 1996 when
he, Oaktree Capital Management and Cerberus Partners bought out
Susie Tompkins. She co-founded the company in 1968 with Doug
Tompkins, then her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Under the previous ownership, Esprit became known for campaigns
created in-house that included work by the Italian fashion
photographer Oliviero Toscani and embodied so-called cause-related
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1991, Esprit introduced television and print
advertising that gave voice to opinions expressed on thousands of
postcards it received after asking consumers, ``If you could change
the world, what would you do?'' The thoughts ranged from the
idealistic (``I'd reverse the status of celebrities and
educators'') to the controversial (``Keep a woman's right to choose
... unless George Bush is free to baby-sit'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea behind'' the new campaign, according to Michael
Toth, president and executive creative director at Toth, is to
evoke ``those wonderful values Esprit always had,'' but ``in a way
that's relevant today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something extraordinary about where Esprit was,'' said
Toth, who has created ads for fashion brands like Coach, Hilfiger
and London Fog, ``but trying to re-create it, you fall short. You
have to refresh and modernize.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision was made, Toth and Margolis said, to concentrate on
women 24 to 28, slightly older than the original Esprit customer,
yet not to exclude those outside the primary audience. Margolis
identified the parameters in a personal way by declaring, ``My
daughter is 19 and my wife is 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian said he thought that approach represented an ``emotional
opportunity for the brand,'' making sense because many ``Esprit
teen-agers are now 30-something.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign carries the theme ``I am Esprit,'' typifying a
trend in creative content that was recently labeled ``affirmation
advertising'' by Business Week magazine; Coldwell Banker, Lotus,
Mattel and Molson are among marketers that are running campaigns in
which individual consumers declare ``I am'' confident or empowered
or independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Esprit ads and posters feature striking head-and-shoulders
shots of women by the photographer Christian Witkin. There are
captions in the corners meant to describe the ``sensibility'' of
the subjects, Margolis said, ``in terms of what they're thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   These are among the captions: ``She believes that words haven't
lost their meaning,'' ``She changes without any warning,'' ``She
surprises even herself'' and ``She believes in hopeful romantics.''
Adjacent to the captions are a listing for the Esprit World Wide
Web site and a toll-free Esprit telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are running in magazines like Cosmopolitan, Elle,
Entertainment Weekly, Glamour, Jane, Marie Claire, Martha Stewart
Living and Self. The posters are appearing on bus shelters and
telephone kiosks and as ``wild postings'' pasted up at construction
sites and on vacant storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Toth also produced a video reel to run on television monitors in
stores, in which women quietly are heard expressing such sentiments
as ``I listen to every voice'' and ``I am natural.'' A 30-second
version is being considered for a television commercial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
