<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-COUNSEL-BOS     02-25 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-COUNSEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A succession of excesses and abuses culminating in Kenneth
Starr's investigation of the Monica Lewinsky scandal have persuaded
many in Congress that the Independent Counsel Act should either be
allowed to lapse when it expires on June 30 or be substantially
revised.
</P>
<P>
   When investigating members of an administration, there is the
same need to prevent a conflict of interest as there was in 1978,
when the law was first adopted. Then as now, public trust in
impartial justice can best be preserved if members of the executive
branch are not investigated by colleagues in the same
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But if a revised Independent Counsel Act is to satisfy the
requirements of impartial justice, the revisions will have to be
thoroughgoing and rooted in basic constitutional principles.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsels must be made accountable, like every other
official in the American system of government. A good start would
be to impose the same kinds of budgetary limits and time
constraints that all other prosecutors accept as necessary checks
on their power.
</P>
<P>
   An independent counsel should also have limited jurisdiction and
not be able to hop from one investigation to another, as Starr has
done. The alleged crimes should be committed during the target's
current government service and meet the Constitution's requirement
of acts that subvert the state or the American political system.
</P>
<P>
   To preclude partisanship, the attorney general and Congress
could agree at the start of each new administration on a list of
experienced prosecutors with reputations for independence. When
need be, a commission of bipartisan elder statesmen from all three
branches of government would appoint prosecutors from this pool.
</P>
<P>
   These revisions would endow the independent counsel statute with
some of the checks and balances and some of the accountability that
the framers of the Constitution created to shield citizens from the
overweening power of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRIVERSLICENSE-PICS26     02-25 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVERSLICENSE-PICS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. House votes to allow sale of driver's license photos
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A state House committee voted Thursday to allow
a state agency to continue selling South Carolina driver's license
photos to a fraud prevention company, even as legislators and the
state's attorney general accused the company of invading peoples'
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Image Data President Bob Houvener rejected Attorney General
Charles Condon's request that the company ask drivers' permission
before it uses their photos in the check and credit card fraud
program it plans to roll out across South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am opposed because I do not think it would be cost
effective,'' Houvener told a legislative hearing crowded by South
Carolinians incensed that their photos might someday appear on a
screen in the check-out line at local stores.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby in the Blatt legislative building, the House Ways and
Means Committee renewed the state Department of Public Safety's
authority to sell photos to Nashua, N.H.-based Image Data, a small
privately held company which last year paid $5,000 for the
information on 3.5 million South Carolina driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative approval is required for the contract to remain in
effect. Image Data downloads driver's license information from a
state data base as part of the company's test of its fraud
prevention system in several South Carolina stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans a statewide roll out of its program this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuffed by the governors in Flordia and Colorado, Image Data
has ignited a privacy controversy in South Carolina. Gov. Jim
Hodges has refused to break Image Data's contract with the state
Department of Public Safety, fearing the state could be liable for
substantial legal damages.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency signed the deal with Image Data in January
1998, but the controversy arose only recently after news reports
that the company received nearly $1.4 million in start-up funds
from the Secret Service, the federal agency responsible for
fighting wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Houvener said neither the Secret Service nor any other agency or
business has access to Image Data's data base. But several
legislators and residents who attended Thursday's long, contentious
public hearing were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why South Carolina? We do not appreciate being an experimental
station,'' said state Rep. Chip Limestone (R-Charleston), who has
introduced a bill to stop the sale of driver's license information.
``Our citizens are not white mice.''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers criticized state officials for cutting the deal
with Image Data, even though driver's license information is
available for sale to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Condon said he opposes the sale of driver's license photos on
constitutional grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not draw the line, where will we end up next?'' he
said. ``Medical information, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past several weeks, more than 50,000 people have
contacted Image Data or the Department of Public Safety to ``opt
out'' of the Image Data program. According to Houvener, those
peoples' photos will not appear on a small check-out screen when
they write a check or use a credit card at a business using Image
Data's system.
</P>
<P>
   Houvener said the company's data base is secure from computer
hackers and that the company will not sell the driver's license
information to other companies. In the stores, the photos appear on
the screen for a few second, long enough for the clerk to match the
customer's face with the photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``No data base is secure,'' said Steven Yates, 41, a graduate
student at the University of South Carolina in Columbia who
attended the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
