<HEADLINE>
THE LION IN WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winter lives. It seemed dead for most of the season, a
disappointment to people who like their climates strong.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Jan. 14 storm, sort of, dumping its small dose of
reality. But even that single-digit howler dissipated into a
60-degree melt the next day. ``Just kidding,'' said the season,
reclosing its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of sunny days with temperatures in the 40s and 50s
lulled the region into barometric ennui, accentuating the winter
blahs and crankiness over the small stuff of dry skin and drab
landscapes. Picking at chipping paint around baseboard heaters, a
person grumbled about the need to shift out of neutral and into the
dramatic sweep of spring chores.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Monday, fierce and raw, like an icicle between the
shoulder blades. No jokes this time _ the beast was awake, hungry,
and out for a long run. A forecast of ``snow later in the week''
meant only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Media storm desks snapped into battle-ready position. This was
the big one of '99 _ and maybe the only one. Had it hit during the
record-breaking winter of '94, it would have been considered
routine, and the weather reporters might have sounded a bit tired.
</P>
<P>
   They thundered their news with the enthusiasm of sportscasters
covering a playoff week. ``Baltimore is completely out of it!'' one
TV meteorologist announced, dismissing the Orioles with a wave of
his hand and closing his fist around Red Sox Nation. The words
``wallop,'' ``punch,'' and ``pounding'' rumbled through the
reports, deepening the angst of the listener, who was not only
expecting the worst from the weather but dreading a Boston season
without Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beaster of a nor'easter,'' predicted the Bell Atlantic
forecaster, and he was right. The small stuff is off the radar
screen. The mind is absorbed by the bigness of a landscape
transformed. As many times as a person has seen this whitewashing
of the world, it still amazes.
</P>
<P>
   Winter lives, and in opening the spirit to full contemplation of
its brutal splendor, so do we.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2019EST &QL; 
