<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PESKY PESTICIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The endless war between agriculture and the insect world
requires a delicate balance between the immediate gains offered by
chemicals in warding off bugs and the potential risks from eating
pesticide residues along with the fruit and vegetables. Consumers
Union, the watchdog organization, has urged additional caution by
producers and users of pesticides about some foods, especially for
children. Federal regulatory agencies have to step up monitoring
and review standards for tolerable levels of consumption.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, published in the March issue of the organization's
magazine Consumer Reports, found no glaring violations of legal
limits on a variety of pesticides but did raise concern that some
produce skirted the limits. It warned that children, who eat
proportionally more fruit and vegetables than adults, are more
vulnerable to damage because of their developing nervous systems.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union has a number of practical suggestions. Prominent
among them is that people continue to eat fresh produce because of
the nutrients they provide but that precautions be used, such as
washing and peeling fruits like apples, peaches, and pears. It also
recommends against giving large quantities of certain foods to
small children: peaches, winter squash, apples, spinach. And it
suggests organically grown produce, which has little or no
pesticide residues.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that much more work needs to be done to develop less
toxic pesticides and to fine- tune the quantities needed to protect
crops. Expanded inspections during various phases of growing and
distribution are important because many pesticides break down to
harmless components with time but should not reach consumers while
still potent. More inspections would reinforce consumer confidence
in an area where doubts and fears can undermine healthy diets.
</P>
<P>
   American food production and distribution are astonishingly
efficient, and great strides have been made in making food safer.
Experience and hard work can extend those gains _ but there must be
close attention to detail all along the chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
