<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYONS26-COX     02-25 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptist leader's fate in Florida jury's hands
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. _ Hands clasped as they stood in a circle outside
the courtroom, supporters of the Rev. Henry Lyons sang and prayed
for the Baptist leader's earthly redemption Thursday as a jury
began deliberating his fate on racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   The six-person, all-white panel broke for the day after about
three hours' work, saying they had reached no verdict. They will
resume deliberating this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Lyons joined in the prayer circle with
his co-defendant, Bernice Edwards, and about 30 supporters, many
from the National Baptist Convention USA. Lyons is president of the
group, one of the largest African-American denominations in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you to work on their minds,'' the Rev. Charles Emery
of the Pilgrim Baptist Church in Gary, Ind., prayed, referring to
the jury. ``We need you to get in their hearts. This is an
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   The group sang the hymn ``What a Friend We Have in Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons and Edwards, formerly the group's public relations
director, are charged with stealing some $4 million from companies
wanting to do business with the convention. Prosecutors allege they
were having an affair and spent much of the money on luxury items
that included a waterfront home, a Lake Tahoe time-share
condominium, expensive cars, jewelry and furs.
</P>
<P>
   During her testimony, Edwards staunchly denied any romantic
involvement with Lyons. After the prayer circle broke up, she
clasped hands with Lyons' wife, Deborah, who touched off the
scandal in July 1997 when she set several small fires in the
$700,000 waterfront home her husband had purchased with Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The fires led to a flood of media accounts and separate criminal
probes by state and federal prosecutors. Both Lyons and Edwards
face a federal trial later this year on charges that include
extortion, money laundering and income tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   As the scandal unfolded, many convention officials rallied to
Lyons' side, although some called on him to resign. A hurried
investigation by a convention committee found Lyons had done
nothing wrong and that no convention money was missing.
</P>
<P>
   But state investigators found plenty of documents they felt
justified the charges. Through witnesses, they showed Lyons and
Edwards took huge checks from insurance, credit card and burial
services companies, depositing the money in what prosecutors
described as ``secret accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who was on probation for embezzlement at the time,
opened accounts under five different Social Security numbers and
violated her probation by keeping the accounts secret, prosecutors
allege.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for the companies _ which include Globe Insurance of
Oklahoma, the Loewen Group of Canada and Union Planters Bank of
Nashville _ allege they were duped into believing the pair could
provide a mailing list of the convention's members, who supposedly
numbered 8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such list, several witnesses testified, although
Edwards and others scrambled unsuccessfully to provide one.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys contend the pair broke no laws, but simply
participated in what turned out to be failed business deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case really should be about corporate deals that didn't
work out,'' attorney Grady Irvin said in his closing statement.
``Not enough profit was made by the corporations. But nobody held a
gun to their head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons and Edwards could each face up to 30 years in prison if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
