<HEADER>
A9660 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-INDIANINK-SFC     02-25 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-INDIANINK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPPARD'S SMART, SENSUAL PASSAGE TO INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ ``It's your country,'' the English poet says
to the Indian painter in 1930, ``and we've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the paradox at the heart of ``Indian Ink,'' Tom
Stoppard's play about the stamp of British colonialism on 20th
century India. It received its American premiere Wednesday in an
American Conservatory Theater production at the Geary Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Both the 1995 script and director Carey Perloff's three-hour
staging of it have their faults. But even when Stoppard is working
below the standard of ``Arcadia,'' a work this one strongly echoes,
he can do more things at once than any other living playwright.
That's recommendation enough for a rewarding night at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The action centers on free-spirited Flora Crewe (Susan Gibney),
a poet who travels from England to India for her health. There she
meets the diffident painter Nirad Das (Art Malik), who's drawn to
her immediately and wants to do her portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a technique reminiscent of ``Arcadia,'' a second
set of characters observes and interprets the events 50 years
later. The characters share stage space and furniture. Loy Arcenas'
set surrounds and sometimes dwarfs them with its shuttling panels
and architectural fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Stapleton plays Flora's sister Eleanor, now 75 in the
mid-1980s. She entertains two guests with vested interests in her
sister's past.
</P>
<P>
   Eldon Pike (Ken Grantham) is a fumbling Flora Crewe scholar who
proves Stoppard's epigram that ``biography is the worst possible
excuse for getting people wrong.'' His reading of Flora's letters,
which he footnotes aloud, links the two halves of ``Indian Ink.''
Firdous Bamji, in a tenderly nuanced performance, plays Eleanor's
other tea table guest, the son of Nirad and a painter himself.
</P>
<P>
   The play's mystery, more ruminative and less compelling than the
one that drives ``Arcadia,'' turns on a portrait that may have been
done of Flora in the nude. History's not about to give up its
secrets too easily, a recurring theme in the playwright's work.
</P>
<P>
   Stoppard links his two narratives to spin out a complex pattern
of lives and cultures fatefully intertwined. ``Indian Ink'' is
smart and sensual, mournful and funny, caustic and hopeful,
leisurely and issue-packed. It's awfully hard to get all that
right, and the experience for the audience is at once stimulating
and a little stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ACT's production, which was still coming together Wednesday,
doesn't mine everything in Stoppard's script. It also bungles some
of the playwright's carefully calibrated rhythms. But it gets the
key relationship right.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Gibney gives a sly, sexy and lyrical performance as the
heroine. The slim actress, in tightly crimped curls, seems to sell
Flora's eccentric fervor too hard at first. But the performance
ripens beautifully and gives everything Flora does a magnetic hold:
the lustrous voice-overs of the poems, the way she gleefully
wriggles her bare toes, her terrible wilting in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Art Malik reprises his London role as Nirad. With his mix of
boisterous enthusiasm for all things English _ he loves London,
Shakespeare and Agatha Christie _ his demure demeanor and
reservoirs of passion hidden behind his cryptic looks, he's a
formidable match for her.
</P>
<P>
   In delicate counterpoint, the two explore everything from
customs in the British Raj to political insurrection, cultural
determinism, artistic inspiration and the ``color'' of erotic love.
A crisis breaks into their wide-ranging conversations when Flora,
struggling for breath, sheds her clothes and retreats to a
gauze-draped bed. It's a breathless, erotically charged moment, a
spasm of deep feeling played with great truthfulness by both
actors.
</P>
<P>
   Stoppard's dialogue is at once heady and droll, and it demands
sparkling delivery. A miscast Stapleton falls short of the mark.
Her character has some of the most delicious lines, and her rattled
spontaneity scores laughs. But Eleanor's measured wit breaks down
in Stapleton's erratic timing and poor projection.
</P>
<P>
   Grantham had his share of fumbled lines on opening night, and
this normally reliable actor never quite hit his stride as the
obtuse editor of Flora's letters. Things improve in his scenes with
Anil Kumar, who plays Eldon's ebullient companion in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian Ink'' is a kind of mural of English-Indian relations,
with gin-swilling colonials, coyly deferential servants, a romantic
English pragmatist (David Conrad), a sybaritic Rajah (Shelly Desai)
and word of Gandhi on the march against the salt tax. The
characters are never the simple emblems they seem.
</P>
<P>
   It's Stoppard's ``Passage to India'' _ Flora and Nirad discuss
E.M. Forster's novel at one point _ a study of two cultures
struggling to connect even as they're about to come apart. What the
Indians consider ``rebellion'' the English see as ``mutiny.'' The
imperialist English language is also, paradoxically, the path to a
nationalist independence.
</P>
<P>
   In its final fluid movement, ``Indian Ink'' rises to a kind of
theatrical grace. First Flora bids farewell to Nirad, a moment too
heightened for them to look each other in the eye. Then time
flashes back to Flora and her young sister (Roxanne Raja) at a
bittersweet beginning. It's a long and sometimes jerky ride to get
here, but the company rides out on one of those soaring reveries
that are precious, unmistakable Stoppard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
