<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HMOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY PRINCIPLES FOR HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade association for managed care companies has taken a
major step toward greater protection for patients enrolled in HMOs.
The association's support for outside review of medical decisions
in dispute ought to form the basis of a compromise bill that
Congress can pass this year.
</P>
<P>
   The ``statement of principles'' by the American Association of
Health Plans is merely advisory, but it does signal an awareness of
the need to reassure patients that they are not being denied
necessary treatment. The association wants a way to ``provide fast,
fair, and efficient review of medical evidence by medical experts
that are independent of health plans and physician associations.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement follows a decision by Aetna US Healthcare, with 16
million members, to set up an external review procedure, a
precedent that ought to guide the actions of other plans. In the
Boston area, Harvard Pilgrim has a mechanism in place, and Blue
Cross's will be ready this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The association issued its statement while meeting in Washington
to discuss congressional attempts to regulate the plans, which it
fought last year. With support for the concept widespread in
Congress, opposition will be difficult to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   The chief point in dispute is whether patients will be allowed
to sue the plans. Lawsuits are an unwieldy weapon to improve
medical care, since they rarely succeed unless a patient has
already suffered grievous harm.
</P>
<P>
   Health plans are especially worried about the huge settlements
that can sometimes result from the imposition of ``punitive
damages,'' penalties over and above the actual harm done by the
faulty decision. Rhode Island's Senator John Chafee and six other
senators have filed a bill that would allow patients to sue only
for actual damages. This plan might form the basis of a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Several other issues, from emergency care to guidelines on the
use of prescription drugs, need to be thrashed out before a bill is
ready for approval. The health plan association has shown, in the
words of its president, Karen Ignagni, that ``we want to be part of
the discussion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
