r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-A     02-25 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-ARBITRATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMILE FROM THE GRAVE: CHARLIE O. TOLD THEM SO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late Charles O. Finley, renegade baseball owner of another
era, loved nothing better than being different. Particularly when
he could be different and also end up being right.
</P>
<P>
   Although lone gone, Finley left behind a told-you-so legacy that
continues to haunt baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '70s, when the new players' union was considered
more pest than today's beast, Finley constantly yelped to the
heavens on one point.
</P>
<P>
   Give the players all the free agency they want, he said, but
don't, under any circumstances, cave in on salary arbitration. The
worry by others, however, was strictly about free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Once the original Basic Agreement was hammered out between the
owners and the up-start union, arbitration was included. Finley,
owner of the Oakland A's, cast the lone vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward 30 years, and listen to what Rangers president Tom
Schieffer said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Arbitration is the worst thing we do in baseball. It's nothing
but a destructive process.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley called this calamity long ago, except no one in his era
was listening. Not listening is now a very costly mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scorecard on arbitration was made public this week.
Sixty-two players filed for arbitration and collected a record 169
percent pay increase. Out of 11 cases actually heard by
arbitrators, the owners ``won'' nine, but in all nine the players
received raises. Salaries for those who filed rose from an average
of $781,000 to an average of $2,009,000.
</P>
<P>
   Home-run king Mark McGwire, noting the massive salary gains for
players in both free agency and arbitration, spoke the unthinkable
this week.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire wondered aloud if a repeat of the disastrous shutdown of
'94 wasn't coming in 2001, when the current Basic Agreement
expires. Privately, most in baseball, players and owners, think so.
</P>
<P>
   The outta-sight salaries of today are fueled by many factors,
not the least being a handful of team owners who create financial
havoc for the others. But the engine that drives the entire salary
process is arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   It works like this _ free agency is granted to a player with six
years of major-league service. But a player can be
arbitration-eligible after two years and a 100 days of time.
Shortstop Derek Jeter won an arbitration case against the Yankees
last week, making him a $5 million player after just three years in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   With the same production on the field, Jeter will be a $10
million player, minimum, before he's eligible for free agency. And
how high does it go from there?
</P>
<P>
   The player has two shots at the owners when it comes to running
up the salary _ arbitration and then free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free agency, we can control by either not signing a player or
releasing a player who is eligible for free agency,'' said
Schieffer. ``But there is no control on arbitration. The arbitrator
is looking at numbers and comparative salaries. We lose on
comparative salaries, and will then lose again when it comes to
free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed outrageous when Rangers pitcher Aaron Sele asked last
month for a $6.2 million paycheck in 1999. The Rangers offered $4.8
million, more than fair.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of allowing an arbitrator to decide, the club
settled with Sele for a club-record $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no guarantee we could win the case,'' said general
manager Doug Melvin, ``not based on other salaries this
off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the team ``wins'' an arbitration case it only means its
salary offer doubled or even tripled what the player previously
made. There is no ``lose'' for the player.
</P>
<P>
   And what can result are hard feelings by the player over an
arbitration hearing. As good as Jeter is, he complained about
hearing the Yankees talk of his negatives before an arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been preached the owners should finally follow the
advice of Finley and do everything to eliminate arbitration. But
they blew their chance in '94.
</P>
<P>
   In the shutdown nastiness five years ago, the union agreed to
give up arbitration, if free agency would be reduced to four years
of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our club was all for it,'' said Schieffer. ``but the
small-market clubs opposed it, saying they needed the extra two
years to hold on to players. But arbitration makes the numbers so
out of whack, they can't hold the players anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 2001 season, the new Basic Agreement with the union
will be negotiated. ``I think then you'll see the end of
arbitration,'' predicted Schieffer.
</P>
<P>
   By listening to Charles Finley long ago, the problem would never
have existed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
