<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COMMITTEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SETS DATE TO SET UP COMMITTEE TO SET UP CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Texas, Tenn. )   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of ruminating publicly about whether
he planned to seek the Republican Presidential nomination, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas has decided to embark on a campaign and
will take the first step of establishing an exploratory committee
in two weeks, his advisers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt he's going to file the exploratory
committee,'' Karl Rove, a top Bush adviser, said in a telephone
interview from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a contrast to former Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, who
dithered for months about running for president in 1992, then
backed out, Rove insisted that Bush was not about to turn back.
``We haven't been Mario-ized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, at a news conference in Austin Thursday, made clear that
an announcement was imminent. ``In two weeks, I'll make an
announcement,'' Bush said. ``So I'll see you in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he had decided, Bush replied, ``If I told you what
I'd announce, you wouldn't even show up.''
</P>
<P>
   He is widely viewed by Republicans as the candidate to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said Bush could not put off assembling an exploratory
committee any longer because he needed one to finance his initial
steps toward setting up a presidential campaign, like travel and
staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's move helps give shape to the Republican field. Sen.
Robert Smith of New Hampshire formally announced his candidacy last
week. Pat Buchanan, the conservative commentator, said Thursday
that he would make his announcement on Tuesday in Manchester, N.H.
The week after that, former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee is
expected to formally begin his campaign. A half-dozen others are
campaigning but have yet to make formal declarations.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Bush said he would probably make his official
announcement of candidacy some time after the Texas Legislature
adjourns at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has long been expected to run, he encouraged the
naysayers over the past year by repeatedly citing concerns about
the toll the White House would take on his two daughters. In an
interview three weeks ago, Bush insisted that he was struggling
with a decision, saying: ``My conflict is making a decision that
will commit my family to what I've called the meat grinder of
Washington life. I've got girls who would be entering college. It's
less to do with me and more to do with my family. I love those
little girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, who ran the 1996 campaign of Bob Dole, the
Republican nominee, said Bush's talk about his family, while
genuine, was also ``a thoughtful delay tactic to do things on his
own time line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the Bush team has learned that you need to put
filler out there or the void will be filled by somebody else,''
Reed added. ``Since Jan. 1, he's really dictated and dominated the
agenda in Republican politics.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is drawing on some of the past lieutenants of his
father, former President George Bush, his informal network of
advisers also includes conservative Republicans from the Reagan
era.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers include Condoleezza Rice, who was a Bush
administration foreign policy adviser, and Paul Wolfowitz, who
worked in the State and Defense department posts in the Reagan and
Bush administrations. His economic advisers include Martin
Feldstein, a professor at Harvard, and Lawrence Lindsey, who was on
President Ronald Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers and later
was appointed to the Federal Reserve by President Bush. Mayor
Stephen Goldsmith of Indianapolis has been advising Bush on
domestic matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
