<HEADER>
A9674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPO     02-25 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPORT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says he will speak on candidacy in 2 weeks
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A day after sources close to Gov. George W. Bush
said he has decided to form an exploratory committee that will be
the precursor to a full-blown presidential campaign, the governor
confirmed Thursday that he will make an announcement in two weeks.
He declined to give details of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will deal with all the issues related to my future in a
couple of weeks,'' Bush said. ``Prepare yourself for a day of
announcement in a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Word is that Bush will announce the formation of the exploratory
committee and say that means he has decided ``maybe'' to run for
president. The ``maybe'' is for public consumption. All signs
indicate the Bush presidential candidacy, to be formally announced
in June, is a go. On Thursday, Bush's noncampaign picked up support
from a group of leading GOP elected officials in Alabama, including
Attorney General Bill Pryor, Lt. Gov. Steve Windom and Secretary of
State Jim Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS BACK CLASS-ACTION SUITS
</P>
<P>
   Two Dallas teachers who benefited from a class-action lawsuit
urged a Senate subcommittee Thursday not to limit such lawsuits.
Donna and Billy Davis told the panel that they had put nearly
$90,000 in annuities at an Austin insurance company, which then
refused to pay interest on their money. They told the panel,
chaired by Sen. Troy Fraser (R-Horseshoe Bay) that they would have
been out of luck without joining a class action filed on behalf of
thousands of other teachers taken in by the company's sales pitch.
In the end, their insurance agent spent three years trying to get
action by the Texas Department of Insurance before finding a lawyer
to act for them.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was considering a bill by Sen. Teel Bivins
(R-Amarillo) that would channel class actions through state
regulatory agencies before they go to trial. Supporters say it
would allow problems to be solved without going to court.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee did not vote on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   TESTIMONY GIVEN ON EPHEDRINE
</P>
<P>
   The dietary supplement ephedrine is risky and should be
regulated like a prescription drug, not just marketed with warning
labels and recommended dosage limits, doctors told the Texas Board
of Health on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not food additives. These are drugs,'' said Dr.
Donald Gordon, chairman of the department of emergency medical
technology at the University of Texas Health Science Center at San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of ephedrine products _ which offer weight loss
and an energy boost _ say proposed rules that require warning
labels and recommended daily limits are sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you get too much ephedrine? Absolutely,'' said Ruth Ann
Box, chief general counsel for Dallas-based dietary supplement
marketer AdvoCare. ``When I get a headache, I don't take 50
aspirin. I don't want to die. These regulations are the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   State health officials heard three hours of testimony on
ephedrine Thursday and are expected to decide in June whether to
adopt the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE PASSES ID-POSSESSION BILL
</P>
<P>
   Possessing someone else's ID without their permission with the
intent of committing fraud would be punishable by up to two years
in state jail under a bill approved by the Senate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Corona, R-Dallas, said it's already a crime to misuse
someone else's identity. But it's not a crime to possess another
person's identifying information.
</P>
<P>
   ``As technological developments continue to automate our
financial transactions, the threat to our wallets is no longer the
pickpocket or purse-snatcher on the street, but rather the criminal
intercepting our mail or using a computer to assume our identity
and obtain access to our credit,'' Corona said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to the House.
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS TEST BILL GOES TO HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday signed off on a bill to allow hospitals
to test patients for hepatitis B and C, even without patients'
permission, if a hospital worker has been exposed to those
patients' blood or bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Corona, R-Dallas and sponsor of the bill, said
hospitals can already test patients' blood for HIV/AIDS without
permission in similar situations. He said tests for hepatitis are
also needed.
</P>
<P>
   On a voice vote, the Senate sent the bill to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
