<HEADLINE>
FAST FILLIES MIGHT KEEP UP WITH COLTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The San Rafael Stakes, a prep for a prep for
the Kentucky Derby, has extra significance this season as
handicappers try to compare the season's outstanding 3-year-old
fillies with their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever in recent memory, fillies are being included on
the lists of contenders for the May 1 Derby. When Churchill Downs
held the first parimutuel ``future-book'' wagering last weekend,
the fillies Excellent Meeting, Silverbulletday and Honest Lady were
among the 11 most heavily bet horses.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for fillies to show ability comparable to colts
at age 2. Five times in the 15 Breeders' Cups, the Juvenile Fillies
winner ran as fast as or faster than the Juvenile winner under
identical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But it's rare that fillies continue to run as fast as colts at
age 3, as they have this year. That's why only three fillies have
won the Derby in 124 runnings _ Regret (1915), Genuine Risk ('80)
and Winning Colors ('88).
</P>
<P>
   Gauged by Beyer speed figures _ which allow the comparison of
horses running different distances on different tracks on different
days _ three of the four fastest races by top Derby hopefuls were
recorded by Excellent Meeting (winning the Las Virgenes earlier
this month), Honest Lady (winning the Santa Ynez last month) and
Silverbulletday (winning a November stakes at Churchill).
</P>
<P>
   And although she hasn't been mentioned as a Derby prospect,
Olympic Charmer registered a speed figure in that class in her
maiden victory at Santa Anita in December.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, one reason the fillies are getting so much attention
is that none of the major Derby prep races has been run and only
Exploit among the colts has shown Triple Crown credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the colts are just getting cranked up (for the
season),'' said Bob Baffert, who trains Excellent Meeting and
Silverbulletday as well as Exploit and other top 3-year-old colts.
``You have to remember that these fillies haven't been facing the
toughest competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kent Desormeaux, the regular rider of both Excellent Meeting
and Honest Lady, said the fillies deserve the acclaim they're
getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're phenomenal. They're freaks,'' Desormeaux said. ``I
don't think it's what the colts don't possess, it's what the
fillies do possess.''
</P>
<P>
   We can judge for ourselves Sunday when the genders collide for
the first time this season in the San Rafael, which serves as a
prep for the April 3 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The expected eight-horse field will include Honest Lady, one of
those hot fillies, and Prime Timber, one of Baffert's top colts.
Santa Anita morning-line writer Jeff Tufts said Thursday he'll
probably make Honest Lady a slight favorite even though no filly
has won the San Rafael and it's believed no filly has run in it
before.
</P>
<P>
   Honest Lady, a daughter of Seattle Slew and Toussaud who's
unbeaten in two starts, will be racing around two turns for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good timing because she'll have had five weeks since her
last race,'' said Bobby Frankel, who trains her for owner Aaron
Jones. ``And we won't have to run against Excellent Meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber, a son of Sultry Song who will be ridden by Gary
Stevens, will be racing for the first time since he finished a good
second to since-injured Tactical Cat in the Dec. 12 Hollywood
Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected for the $200,000 San Rafael: Aristotle, Capsized,
Buck Trout, Desert Hero, Lethal Instrument and Love that Red.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a clean race, a victory by Honest Lady will be
interpreted as a sign the fillies are as good as the colts this
year. Then it'll be up to their trainers to keep aiming for the
Derby or aim for the April 30 Kentucky Oaks against other fillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of glad Frankel's filly is running in (the San
Rafael),'' said Baffert, who hopes the result will help him make up
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   64 days to the Derby: Horses on the rise: Vicar and Cat Thief
ran a close 1-2 in the Fountain of Youth at Gulfstream Park on
Saturday; Certain was third; Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner Answer
Lively improved on his '99 debut by running second to Ecton Park in
Louisiana; Baffert's Straight Man is aiming for the Gallery
Furniture.com Stakes (the former Jim Beam) on March 27 after
winning a late debut in 1:08.82; Apremont is 2 for 2 after winning
a 7-furlong allowance race at Santa Anita by five lengths over
Charismatic and Forestry; Exploit was the 6-1 favorite in the first
round of Churchill Downs future betting last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Horses on the decline: Maryland-based Millions' '99 debut is
delayed by illness; a fracture will sideline Louisiana prep-race
upsetter Some Actor for three or four months; The Groom is Red and
Doneraile Court ran poorly in the Fountain of Youth.
</P>
<P>
   Big 'Cap next: Silver Charm worked out for the March 6 Santa
Anita Handicap in tandem with Real Quiet on Wednesday, which might
be the first time Kentucky Derby winners have worked together.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, with Stevens aboard, and Real Quiet, with Dana
Barnes, finished together in 1:25 2/5 for 7 furlongs. Baffert is
pointing Real Quiet for the March 7 New Orleans Handicap at the
Fair Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm's Big 'Cap opponents are expected to include
Richard Mandella's Puerto Madero, Event of the Year and Malek, and
Free House and Dr Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The Big 'Cap hasn't attracted Eastern runners even though it's
part of the NTRA Champions on Fox series for older horses. Then
again, outside of Victory Gallop, what Eastern horses would it
want?
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Saturday's Gulfstream Park Handicap, which dropped in
value and prestige when the Donn Handicap joined the NTRA series,
has an all-Florida-based field led by Behrens and Sir Bear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
