<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REWARD FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - With Luc Robitaille's overtime goal paving the way,
the Kings went from the doghouse to the penthouse on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And as a result, they never made it to Johnnie's Ice House, the
Chicago rink where they had been scheduled to practice Thursday in
preparation for tonight's game against the Chicago Blackhawks at
the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kings had a light workout at a fitness center near
their Michigan Avenue hotel, then were free for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reward for playing well,'' said Kings coach Larry
Robinson, who hasn't often felt like rewarding his team this
season. ``And we're into February. How many hours have we spent on
the ice passing pucks and shooting pucks? We had as much of a
workout as we would have had on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were coming off a 3-2 victory in which they rallied
from a two-goal third-period deficit against the two-time defending
Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings to win on Robitaille's
acrobatic goal.
</P>
<P>
   The victory drew the Kings (22-32-5) to within three points of
Calgary and Edmonton, which share the final playoff berth in the
NHL's Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Robinson was pleased with the important victory,
he was just as happy that his players had stayed with his patient
game plan even when they fell into a 2-0 hole.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Robinson said, ``We've always strayed from it. Even
if we were only down one goal, we got away from it. We'd forget
about getting it deep, forget the game plan. You have to stick to
the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they trailed Wednesday, the Kings stayed calm,
forwards helping out in the defensive zone and consistently getting
the puck deep into the attacking zone. Eventually, they found
cracks in the Red Wings' defense and capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also got strong performances from the players they
count on most. Donald Audette and Glen Murray had seven shots
apiece, Rob Blake six and Robitaille five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pretty good team,'' Blake said, ``but we've got to
be disciplined every night.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings stay disciplined tonight, they'll have a good
chance to win again.
</P>
<P>
   They have won all three meetings with the Hawks this season and
seven in a row dating to last year. But Chicago will have a
different look tonight with new coach Lorne Molleken behind the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Molleken had been an assistant coach with the Hawks until
Monday's firing of first-year coach Dirk Graham. In Molleken's
first game, the Hawks surprised the Blues in St. Louis, winning by
a 3-1 margin Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He already has won the favor of his players by freeing them
offensively from the patient dump-and-chase style Graham favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look at this as an opportunity and try to make a
step forward,'' Blackhawks center Doug Gilmour said. ``Our approach
has to be: Let's make something out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Visheau has surgery (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Mark Visheau, who has missed the last 10 games
because of a congenital urinary tract obstruction, underwent
successful surgery Wednesday night at Centinela Hospital Medical
Center in Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Visheau, 25, had four points and 107 penalty minutes in 28 games
this season. He will be sidelined for the rest of the year but is
expected to be ready for the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   An overlooked factor in the Kings' success in Detroit was
faceoffs. The Kings won 57 percent of them, with Ian Laperriere
winning five of eight and Yanic Perreault winning 12 of 18. ``It's
a huge part of the game, Robinson said. ... Robinson said he
probably will rotate defensemen Garry Galley and Philippe Boucher
in and out of the lineup the rest of the season, to keep both ready
in case of an injury or if one of the other defensemen is playing
poorly. He said he will do the same with enforcer Matt Johnson,
whose ice time has been sporadic recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
