A9688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYDAY-LOANS26-COX     02-25 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYDAY-LOANS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas officials set out to stop 800 percent interest payday
loans
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cash-strapped Texans are paying rates as high as
800 percent on an annual basis for loans to tie them over from one
payday to another, the Southwest Regional Office of the Consumers
Union said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called payday lenders disguise their transactions _ and
avoid conflicts with state law _ by claiming they charge ``fees,''
not interest rates which are subject Texas' usury laws. The fees
can, over time, amount to an interest rate of several hundred
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumers Union and American Association of Retired Persons
have asked two Texas agencies _ the Consumer Credit Commission and
Attorney General's Office _ to step up enforcement to stop the
growing problem of payday lending.
</P>
<P>
   Payday lending has had ``substantial growth'' in the last 12 to
24 months in Texas, said Consumer Credit Commissioner Leslie
Pettijohn.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn is ``very interested in protecting
Texas consumers and halting this practice'' of payday loans, said
spokeswoman Andrea Horton.
</P>
<P>
   Payday lenders require a personal check that serves as
collateral for a loan, said Rob Schneider, an attorney for
Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a borrower cannot repay or renew the loan at the end of the
loan period, typically 14 days, the lender cashes or threatens to
cash the check,'' Schneider said. ``One business told Consumers
Union, 'If you don't repay us, we will cash your check. If your
check bounces then we will file for a hot check.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the payday lending practice, borrowers with insufficient
funds to cover the check risk criminal theft-by-check charges if
they cannot keep up with the steep renewal payments. Payday lenders
thus enlist justices of the peace to act, in effect, as their
collection agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumers Union has asked the Texas Legislature to make it
illegal for lenders to pursue or threaten to pursue hot check
collection against borrowers on payday loans. Bills calling for
such a ban have been introduced in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unconscionable that these lenders use the criminal hot
check collection system to enforce these high-cost loans,'' said
Wilhelmina Gladden, chair of the AARP's Texas Legislative
Committee. ``The threat of criminal hot check prosecution is a
powerful tool lenders use to get people to renew these loans that
should not have been made in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consumers Union surveyed 27 payday lenders in Texas,
including 12 in the Austin area, and found several payday loan
variations. A large number called themselves ``sales-leaseback''
companies that claim to buy home appliances from their customers
and lease them back for a ``rental fee.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies all advance money for an initial period of less
than one month, taking a personal check as collateral. They
typically charge $33 per $100 borrowed every 14 days. Borrowers may
renew this advance over and over, quickly repaying the lender in
fees more than was borrowed. The fee is the equivalent of nearly
800 in annual percentage rate interest, Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   One company included in the survey disputed the results.
</P>
<P>
   Cash Plus, a sales leaseback company in Austin that was included
in the survey, denied it loaned as much as the $270 maximum per
loan amount listed by Consumers Union. Cash Plus manager Patricia
Mings also said the $33 fee listed per $100 borrowed also was not
accurate. She said she could not disclose the amount for
competitive reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very customer-oriented,'' she said. ``We are probably
one of the few that gives the customer something back for the fee.
They get something in return from us for our fees, which are lower
than all the competitors to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' Constitution bans usury or exorbitant rates for loans.
Still, signature lenders may charge more than 90 percent on an
annual percentage rate, including $4 per month per $100 borrowed
and an up-front fee of $10 to cover processing costs. Signature
lenders in Texas make more than 3.5 million loans for $1 billion
annually, according to Pettijohn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
