<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-RECONCILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS' `CALL FOR RECONCILIATION' GOES LARGELY UNANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Conn., Mo., Pa., Conn., Hawaii., Va., Okla., Alaska,
Ala.)  (mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As signs go, it was not a good one.
</P>
<P>
   Striving to bury the biliousness of impeachment, Sens. Sam
Brownback, R-Kan., and Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., issued press
releases early this week announcing a bipartisan ``call for
reconciliation.'' All senators were invited to ``pull together and
face the future with a collaborative spirit,'' as Lieberman put it.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday morning, in a meeting room bulging with gospel
singers, ministers, a rabbi and a priest, who all intoned about
tolerance, mercy and forgiveness, it was not at all evident that
``the call'' had been heard. There, at the very front of the room,
sat the attending senators, all six of them _ three Republicans and
three Democrats, though a flash sighting of Sen. John Ashcroft,
R-Mo., at the back of the room would bring the count to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Why the low turnout? Could it be, after all is said and done,
that the Senate is not so different from the House, where a
scheduled retreat on civility and congeniality in Hershey, Pa., has
prompted an onslaught of snickers instead of kisses, and threats of
a boycott?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, no,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. ``It's so
acrimonious there,'' in the House, he added. ``It's so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning's poor attendance was disappointing, senators
said. Those who showed up were the Democratic Sens. Daniel Akaka of
Hawaii, Charles Robb of Virginia and Dodd, and the Republicans
Sens. James Inhofe of Oklahoma, Ted Stevens of Alaska, Jeff
Sessions of Alabama and Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   But the meager showing was not a bad sign, many of them said: It
simply demonstrated how much progress members had already made in
reconciling their own differences over impeachment. With all 100 of
them thrust together on the Senate floor day after day, senators
bonded during the ordeal. The House, on the other hand, came
unglued, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This very divisive, troubling episode actually united us, as
men and women, as individuals who happen to be senators,''
Lieberman, who is co-chairman with Brownback of the Center for
Jewish and Christian Values, said Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The trial had ``its own salutory benefits,'' Dodd agreed. ``So
it may be that many members felt they had already, in a sense, gone
through a reconciliation with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the image of acrimony that the House is trying to buff
clean with its annual retreat on civility. This year, though, the
retreat has prompted even more eye-rolling than usual. Democrats
are not at all keen on the idea, calling it superficial. And some
Republicans aren't too enthused themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Richard Gephardt, said Friday that he
had encouraged Democrats to attend ``this thing in Hershey,'' but
he cautioned, ``you only make progress slowly and incrementally.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconciliation between President Clinton and Republicans in
Congress may be no less tricky. Brownback, for one, who voted to
convict Clinton and called for his resignation last year, has
invoked a lot of prayers to try to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had harbored a lot of ill will and dislike and, really,
hatred for the president,'' Brownback said after the meeting. ``I
have been praying for him and that has gone. I have forgiven him
and I hope he forgives me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in the same breath, Brownback and other Republicans warned
that forgiveness and comity have little to do with policy and
legislating. Brownback will turn the other cheek, not give up his
backbone, he said, especially over abortion, tax cuts and
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure to separate out the difference between
reconciliation and genuine policy issues,'' he told reporters. ``I
will confront you on policy issues, and I will love you
personally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
