A9701 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-HEALTH-WORKERS-2     02-25 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-HEALTH-WORKERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION WINS RIGHT TO REPRESENT 74,000 LOS ANGELES HEALTH-CARE
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Winning the biggest unionization drive in more
than half a century, the Service Employees International Union
gained the right on Thursday to represent 74,000 Los Angeles County
home-care workers who feed, bathe and clean for the elderly and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing drive _ more than twice as large as any other
drive in decades _ demonstrates the labor movement's newfound
aggressiveness, its new focus on recruiting workers in large clumps
and in recruiting low-wage workers, women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County's home-care workers earn $5.75 an hour, and
many said they voted to join the union because they want it to
fight to raise their wages and to obtain two benefits long denied
them _ health insurance and paid vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something big for us,'' said Maria Alvarez, who
complained that after 14 years on the job she still earns just
$5.75 an hour, the minimum wage in California. ``I'm so happy about
the union, I feel like flying. They'll help us win benefits, like
health insurance and vacations. Right now, we don't have nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials who counted the ballots, which were mailed in
over the past month, estimated on Thursday that about 90 percent of
the 20,000 workers who cast ballots voted for the union. As a
result, the Service Employees Union will represent the county's
74,000 home-care providers, making the drive labor's biggest
organizing victory since 1941 when 75,000 workers at what was then
the nation's largest factory _ the Ford Motor Co.'s River Rouge
plant _ voted to join the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a home run for labor amidst the sea of a lot of
strikeouts, in that it is huge victory in a pivotal sector of the
economy, the service sector,'' said Harley Shaiken, a labor
specialist at the University of California, Berkeley. ``And it
represents the new face of labor _ women workers, minority workers,
low-paid workers, people who have often been so hard to organize.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials said on Thursday that unionization, by
improving wages and benefits, would create a more stable, better
trained workforce allowing the elderly and disabled to receive
improved home care. Zev Yaroslavsky, a member of the Los Angeles
County Board of Supervisors, even predicted that the better trained
supply of home-care workers brought about through unionization
might discourage many elderly people from moving into nursing
homes, persuading them instead to remain at home and receive
home-care assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are expected to begin in the next few weeks between
the union and the county authority that supervises home care.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing drive highlights the shift in the economy and in
labor's focus away from manufacturing and toward the service
sector, especially toward health care, an area in which only one
million of the nation's 12 million health-care workers are
unionized.
</P>
<P>
   In wooing the home-care workers, the Service Employees Union,
the nation's fastest-growing union, underlined labor's effort to
organize low-wage workers, who are seen as fertile ground for
labor's message. With this strategy, the labor movement hopes to
transform itself into a high-minded movement, like the civil rights
movement, that focuses in large part on those on the bottom rungs _
a sharp departure from past decades when labor was viewed as
preoccupied with representing pampered, high-paid auto and steel
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign represents a new direction for the labor
movement,'' said David Rolf, 29, who worked more than 14 hours a
day for the past year spearheading the organizing drive. ``It is a
campaign where we reached out to low-income, women workers, workers
of color and immigrant workers. If you look at the demographic
changes in Southern California, the labor movement has to figure
out how to bring these workers in because they are the backbone of
the new, low-wage service-sector economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Spearheading the drive, 40 young organizers went to apartment
houses, churches and bus stops to urge home-care aides to support
the union. All told, they visited 33,000 workers at home. But the
unionization campaign was unusual not only in its size, but also in
its length. It took more than 11 years and required the Service
Employees Union to persuade the California Legislature to enact a
statute enabling these workers to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the organizing drive began in 1987, state courts
ruled that home-care aides were independent contractors without the
right to unionize. Although their salaries were paid by a
combination of federal, state and county funds, the courts ruled
that neither the state nor the county was the employer for these
workers. Instead, the courts said the individual clients were the
employers, making the workers and union recognize that if they were
to negotiate better wages and benefits, they would need to bargain
with large entities.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago people thought we were crazy to try to organize
California's 180,000 home-care workers once the courts said they
were independent contractors,'' said Andrew Stern, president of the
Service Employees International Union. ``We said, `if we can't
organize the fastest growing occupation in America, then what does
that say about the labor movement?'''
</P>
<P>
   Eager to help _ and sign up _ these low-paid workers, the
Service Employees persuaded the Legislature to pass a law in 1992
that authorized counties to create authorities that would
administer the home-care programs and serve as the workers'
employers. In 1997, Los Angeles County set up such an authority, a
consumer-dominated body called the Personal Assistance Services
Council.
</P>
<P>
   This enabled the union to organize 6,100 home-care workers in
Alameda County in 1994, 5,500 in San Francisco County in 1996 and
4,000 in Contra Costa County in 1997. In 1997, Los Angeles County
set up an authority to administer its own authority, a
consumer-dominated body called the Personal Assistance Services
Council.
</P>
<P>
   In California, county officials interview the elderly and
disabled to determine whether they qualify for government-paid home
care. Government officials prefer providing the elderly with
home-care aides to sending them to nursing homes because nursing
homes are far more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The unionization vote covered the 74,000 workers who participate
in a program for low-income elderly and disabled persons. The more
than 10,000 home-care providers in Los Angeles County working for
private agencies were not covered by the unionization vote.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders assert that unionizing these home-care aides will
help worker and client alike. Many elderly and disabled clients
grow alarmed when their aides quit for higher-paying jobs, and
raising their wages is expected to reduce the 40 percent annual
turnover of these workers. In addition, the union and county
authority are expected to provide some training for the workers.
Several workers interviewed said they have received no training.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alvarez, the home-care worker, said she was pleased that the
union would help provide training for handling clients who are
extremely heavy and who have Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   One of her clients, Mercedes Dacosta, an 85-year-old widow with
serious knee problems, said it would be a disaster for her if Ms.
Alvarez left her after six years for a higher-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day she was complaining that she couldn't afford to
buy a new set of eyeglasses,'' Mrs. DaCosta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
