u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-APPOINTMENTS-5     02-25 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-APPOINTMENTS-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY GIVES NEW JOBS TO 2 OF ITS TOP MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In key management reshufflings Thursday, Walt Disney Co. named
Robert Iger to the new post of president of Walt Disney
International and also made him chairman of ABC Group.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bornstein, the former chairman of ESPN and president of
ABC Sports, replaces Iger as president of ABC. Though Bornstein
will report to Iger, some longtime Disney experts saw the
appointment as a graceful way to remove Iger from direct day-to-day
responsibilities at ABC, which continues to face ratings problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network has continued to perform poorly, and there is a
troubling trend in the decline in viewers 18 to 49, a key Disney
demographic,'' said Ed Hatch, who follows Disney for Cowen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a telephone interview Thursday, Michael Eisner,
Disney's chairman, went to great lengths to say that the move was a
promotion for Iger, emphasizing how important it was for Disney to
systematically strengthen and integrate its businesses overseas.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed any notion that Iger was being pushed aside, saying
the appointment ``was definitely a promotion.'' He also insisted it
was ``not anything else,'' alluding to investors' desire to see him
name a second in command. Eisner cited a list of recent
appointments to support his effort to bolster top management.
</P>
<P>
   But one executive who has long followed the company said
privately that Disney might have wanted to give Bornstein a larger
role in programming because he had done an impressive job at ESPN.
This person said the appointment had a second benefit for Eisner,
who had heart surgery several years ago and is not an enthusiastic
traveler. By appointing Iger to the new position, Eisner can
somewhat reduce his own need to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Iger, 48, has been president of ABC since 1996 and had risen to
chief operating officer of Capital Cities/ABC before Disney bought
the company in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bornstein started at ESPN in 1980 and rose to increasingly
responsible positions within the network's programming and
production divisions. Three years ago, he also became president of
ABC Sports. Eisner said, ``Bornstein grew up in charge of
entertainment programming.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Iger's new job, Eisner said Thursday that one of the
company's important areas of growth was overseas. ``We have to act
more like a multinational company,'' Eisner said. Around the world,
``McDonald's has one brand,'' he said, ``3M has many brands. We are
right in between. We are one brand _ the Disney brand _ and then we
have many properties inside the brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Iger's task will be to bring the same kind of corporate focus
overseas that Disney has domestically. ``I am the country manager
for the U.S.,'' said Eisner, who added that he met with executives
every week to discuss matters like the Go Network, the company's
Internet portal, and the integration of other properties.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company needed to integrate its efforts better
overseas. ``Take Japan,'' Eisner said. ``It is our biggest market
outside the U.S. and Canada. However, we have not been able to make
our animated movies work there like everywhere else. We have Disney
stores in Japan. If we had somebody living there, just working in
Japan, they could get our video releases more strongly in our
stores and help the parks cross-promote our animated stores. We
want someone to protect and grow the Disney brand and do
appropriate things with it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David Londoner, who follows Disney for Schroder Inc., said that
Disney, which now gets about 20 percent of its revenue overseas,
could benefit from improved performance overseas. The revenue
percentage has dropped since Disney bought ABC, which is primarily
a domestic business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really trying to focus on foreign, where it is likely
the major growth is going to happen in the next five years, and
they want to have a high-visibility executive running those
operations,'' Londoner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it, 4 to 5 percent of the world's kids, who
represent about 20 percent of the world's income, are here,'' he
added. ``But Disney still gets maybe 80 percent of its income here,
so there is room for growth abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Iger will be traveling far more than he had previously
and thus will be farther away from ABC's day-to-day operations,
even though Bornstein will report to him. As Eisner described the
new job, Disney will appoint an executive in several important
territories to help integrate operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
