<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9719 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN     02-25 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALBERSTAM HAMMERS THE HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Pulitzer Prize-winning author David Halberstam
wrote a book on the sports communication empires, it would be on
Disney, News Corp and Time Warner, which own ESPN, Fox and CNN. He
could call it ``The Powers That Beat It Over Our Heads 24 Hours A
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam, best known for his literary works on the Vietnam War
and the Civil Rights movement, won't give a very glowing report on
today's sports media based on his experience writing two
NBA-related books nearly 20 years apart.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1979-80 season, Halberstam hung out with the Portland
Trail Blazers for his first sports-based book, ``The Breaks of the
Game.'' His latest book, ``Playing For Keeps: Michael Jordan and
the World He Made'' (Random House) hit the shelves not long after
Jordan's retirement was official.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Halberstam discovered something interesting
about the process. As imposing as it may have seemed working within
the budding TV-driven sports media in the late '70s, it was nothing
like the late '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger? Yes. But better?
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam, whose most recognized work may be his dissection of
the New York Times' clout in ``The Powers That Be,'' ran into a a
drastically changed process of information gathering and reporting
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Which might not be news to us, but it was a sports culture shock
for Halberstam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quantum jump we didn't know about back then was cable,''
Halberstam said during a stop in Los Angeles earlier this week.
``When TV came along in the late '50s, the first beneficiary was
football. It captured the violence and ferocity that radio
couldn't. But football was one game a week. As cable got bigger and
the cameras and technology got better, it could capture the
artistry of basketball live four nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rare confluence of satellite technology and corporate
commercial drive and the individual artistry of a Michael Jordan
came together. Michael would never be anything in the radio age. It
would be like describing ballet on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't realize how powerful cable could be. Nor
did the people at ESPN, I'm sure. To borrow a phrase from Faulkner,
it was as if no one knew the world was round.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, Halberstam had almost unlimited access to
players like Bill Walton and his Blazers teammates, as did all
newspaper beat reporters. TV was a key media component, but
remember, the NBA Finals were still televised on tape-delay at
11:30 p.m. because CBS feared the ratings during sweeps would
plunder. It was also a time when CBS cut straight to a golf
tournament after the Blazers' 1977 Finals win because that sport
was more important to corporate suits.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam found that the one media element that remained _ TV
hype _ has not been much of a benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing I remember well was the beginning of NBA hype
of the networks,'' said Halberstam. ``It'd be Brent Musburger
shouting `It's the Bird man against the Magic man!' . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But 20 years later, it's still all about hype, individuals and
stardom rather than teams. Is it a good thing? Some players can
handle it. Michael knew how to. Shawn Kemp thinks it's all about
being on ESPN `SportsCenter' dunking, what gets the clips on.
That's not an undivided plus.''
</P>
<P>
   For today's print journalists, covering an NBA team means seeing
coaches fired live on cable TV. They have to come up with new,
deeper stories. It means also elbowing for room with those who put
the pictures on the air.
</P>
<P>
   In his author's note in ``Playing for Keeps,'' Halberstam said
he spent a season following the Chicago Bulls and never asked a
question in the locker room, calling that ``perhaps a journalistic
first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more access (to players today) but really
less,'' Halberstam said. ``They open the locker room after a game
and instead of five or six beat reporters who are doing their job,
it's for 200 more people, no one knows who they are, sticking
microphones in front of anyone, and asking blow-away questions.
There's obviously less trust and less substance coming out, and
it's easier for players to dismiss the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's less accountability on the part of the players today
and that showed during the lockout . . . there was no connection to
how the rest of the world saw what they were doing. As you get more
cut off, you get guys without much connection, much more print
journalism with attitude, much more stinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It heightens the lines drawn between players and reporters.
There's a lot to be said on both sides about accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity-driven media surrounding Jordan that Halberstam
notes in ``Playing For Keeps'' often keeps the superstars from
revealing anything about their personal lives to even their
teammates, since reporters end up probing them for the information.
It's a symptom that Halberstam wishes would disappear, but has no
reason to believe it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society would be well served if we all knew less about the
private lives of celebrities,'' said Halberstam, who got a taste of
being the target of media scorn when, as a young Vietnam reporter
in the early '60s, he was accused of being a Communist sympathizer
because of what he revealed about the U.S.'s participation in the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country would be better served without Monica
Lewinsky, Ken Starr, the President's wretched, reckless personal
life and the private lives of many celebrities that really aren't
that interesting. Society used to erect something of a firewall.
That's come down in this new media age. I'd like to (put it up
again), but that's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an entertainment world and all the tabloid shows
have infiltrated the networks and increasing popular culture has a
foothold in serious journalism. We pry at a level we don't have a
right to.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
