<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonderful writing carries sweet `Cider'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be put off by the badly titled ``Cider With Rosie'' on
Sunday's ``Masterpiece Theatre'' (9 p.m. on WGTV). It's a delicate,
sometimes absorbing retelling of writer Laurie Lee's early years in
rural England in the days before and after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Lee does have a fabulous way with words. Read his thoughts about
his dear mum: ``Deserted, debt-ridden, flurried, bewildered, doomed
by ambitions that never came off, yet our Mother possessed an
indestructible gaiety which welled up like a thermal spring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider'' often relies on Lee as narrator, speaking his own
written words as the 90-minute tale unfolds, introducing us to the
kooky characters populating the countryside where he lived as a
boy. There's the two warring old women, the crabbiest of
schoolmarms, the somewhat Boo Radley-like shell-shocked soldier
and, ultimately, the schoolgirl Rosie young Laurie sips cider with
before experiencing his first kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie's mom Annie (wonderfully played by Juliet Stevenson
(``The Politician's Wife'')) is as charming, gay and tragic as
Roberto Benigni's clown Guido in ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the adolescent Laurie, Joe Roberts has the kind of
remarkable, big-eared, dopey kid look you just know you've seen
somewhere before. Then it hits you. He played the rat-loving John
Webster in ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   On the down side, PBS' adaptation of ``Cider With Rosie'' isn't
as Gothic, as wide-eyed, as just plain big as you'd want from a
world seen through the eyes of a bright, intuitive kid. ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' it's not. But it is charming at times. Enough so to
make you yearn for a sip of cider.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   This is only a test
</P>
<P>
   A test of the Emergency Alert System apparently freaked out a
few viewers of CBS' ``Late Show With David Letterman'' and other
shows Wednesday night. The scheduled ``alert,'' which usually comes
on during low-viewership times, popped on the screen on all of
MediaOne's channels for 15 seconds and told viewers to tune to WSB
for more information.
</P>
<P>
   The new testing system replaces the old Emergency Broadcasting
System, which used to come on radio and TV stations, followed by a
long, annoying beep. The Federal Communications Commission requires
cable systems such as MediaOne to test the system once a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer, TV writer for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Gangster flick falls flat
</P>
<P>
   Oy. A movie this promising that's this disappointing.
Slow-footed when it's not ham-handed, foggy when it's not obvious,
HBO's ``Lansky'' (8 p.m. Saturday (874621)), a bio-pic about Jewish
gangster Meyer Lansky, shudda been a contender. It was written by
David Mamet, -- Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright (``Glengarry Glen
Ross'') and acclaimed screenwriter (``Wag the Dog''). Richard
Dreyfuss (``Mr. Holland's Opus'') stars as Lansky, with the
supporting cast filled out by Eric Roberts, Anthony LaPaglia,
Ileana Douglas and Beverly D'Angelo. John McNaughton (``Henry:
Portrait of a Serial Killer'') directs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this virtually cradle-to-grave tale of the brainy immigrant
bad guy, who with Bugsy Siegel (Roberts) and Lucky Luciano
(LaPaglia) helped assemble a Prohibition crime syndicate he once
described as ``bigger than U.S. Steel,'' never finds a way to
involve us. Is that even possible? 'Tis. Told through flashbacks of
a 70-year-old Lansky, waiting in Jerusalem to hear if he can take
up permanent residence there (he wound up standing trial in the
United States on racketeering-related charges, but wasn't convicted
and finally died in Miami in 1983), we're left to divine that
anti-Semitism drove him to a life of crime, and also drove him to
be very good at it. We're never convinced. Dreyfuss as the
in-his-prime Lansky brings brief moments of the thinking-man's,
wise-guy charge you expect from this film, but ``Lansky'' otherwise
is snuffed out of its own too-vague intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Drew Jubera, TV critic for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
