<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TAKES STOCK OF BORBON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ When Dodgers manager Davey Johnson ventured
to the Dominican Republic in December, Pedro Borbon couldn't pitch
because his reconstructed left elbow was giving him problems.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon has come a long way. Through the first week of spring
training, the left-hander is the biggest surprise at Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd be throwing this good,'' Johnson said
after watching Borbon throw eight minutes on Thursday. ``He looked
pretty good. I think he's ahead of where anyone thought he would
be. It looks like he has pretty good arm strength and endurance. .
. . I won't abuse him in the spring, but I'll give him a lot of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would like to know if the former Atlanta Braves
reliever is healthy enough to fill the left-handed void in the
bullpen. Borbon, a non-roster invitee, is a long way from making
the Dodgers' roster, but even making it this far is somewhat
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Borbon suffered a torn medial collateral
ligament in his left elbow. A week later, he underwent
reconstructive surgery. He said damage was done to elbow ligaments,
his flexor muscle and the capsule that holds the elbow in place. He
spent last season in the Braves organization but was 0-3 with a
5.52 ERA at three stops in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `Tommy John' surgery-plus,'' said Borbon, who was 3-0
with a 2.75 ERA with the Braves before the injury. ``It's been two
stressful years for me. I feel more relaxed for the simple reason
of what I've gone through the last 2{ years. Nothing is going to
bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Borbon said he's healthy and added he was clocked at 89 to 92
mph while pitching in a Dominican winter league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury, it made me a better pitcher,'' said Borbon, who
signed a minor- league contract with the Dodgers. ``I think the
Dodgers presented the best opportunity to come out of the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup talk: Johnson said he's played the fantasy baseball game
in his mind for the past few months, and there's one thing he
continuously returns to when thinking about right fielder Raul
Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Are you going to be on base enough to hit third?' ''
said Johnson, who wants to make sure cleanup hitter Gary Sheffield
has enough RBI opportunities. ``It has to work right in front of
Sheffield. Otherwise, I'll load it up behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi had a solid 1998 season, hitting .279 with 30 homers and
90 RBI, but drew only 30 walks in 580 at-bats for an on-base
percentage of .316. Last season he batted third 58 times and fifth
83 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're third, they don't want to walk me to face the
fourth hitter,'' Mondesi said. ``I want to hit third, and I'll show
everybody what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson likes Eric Young leading off, followed by Devon White,
Mondesi, Sheffield, Todd Hundley and Eric Karros. When Mark
Grudzielanek plays shortstop, he would hit seventh and Adrian
Beltre would bat eighth. If Jose Vizcaino is the shortstop, Beltre
would bat seventh and Vizcaino eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: The Dodgers announced an agreement with
the LG Twins of the eight-team Korean Baseball Organization that
could include an exhibition game. As part of the agreement, the
clubs will exchange scouting information and the LG Twins will
train at Dodgertown. . . Beltre, who slammed his right pinky in his
car door and needed two stitches Wednesday, threw on the side
Thursday but didn't hit. . . Dodgers president and CEO Bob Graziano
is expected to arrive in Dodgertown tonight. . . Closer Jeff Shaw
remains at his Ohio home awaiting the birth of his third child.
He's expected in camp a few days after his wife, Julie, gives
birth. He's the only Dodger not in camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
