<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back on track: Assist from coach Kersee worked for Jordan
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ When Brian Jordan had a bulging disc in
his back that kept him out for the second half of the 1997 season
for St. Louis _ the last in a succession of injuries that has
slowed his career _ he had all kinds of advice thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   Fans sent a stack of mail with advice on exercises, miracle
healers, drugs. One fan even sent him some pills with instructions
on what to take when.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that day at the Chesterfield Mall in St. Louis,
when Jordan bumped into a man he hardly knew, Bob Kersee, Olympic
track coach and husband of heptathlon champion Jackie
Joyner-Kersee. He offered to be Jordan's personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me and laid it on the line: `Hey, it's your
career. If you want to blow it, fine,''' Jordan said. ``I don't
even know this guy, he's telling me this, and I want to punch him
in his mouth. But he kind of woke me up. He said `It's your body.
You've got to take care of it. It's your career.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan thought about it and called Kersee back. He went to
Orlando to work out with Kersee, Jackie Joyner-Kersee and sprinter
Gail Devers. The results included faster sprint times, stronger
legs and a lower percentage of body fat. And then came his 1998
season with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had career highs in average (.316), games (150), at-bats
(564), hits (178), home runs (25), runs (100), on-base percentage
(.368) and triples (7). He also drove in 91 runs.
</P>
<P>
   And Jordan did all that in the last year of his contract,
hitting in front of or behind Mark McGwire during the year of The
Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Two years and $40 million later, Jordan is in Orlando again,
this time with the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty much the complete player,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox said. ``I don't know one thing he does poorly or even below
average. Plus arm, plus defense, plus speed, plus power, plus
batting average.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves latest free-agent pick-up, Jordan arrived in a
position to make a good lineup that much better. That changed with
the loss of Andres Galarraga to lymphoma. Jordan might have to come
in, hit cleanup and be a key contributor right from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that news, it messed me up a little bit,'' Jordan
said. ``You think you're coming in, putting your piece of the
puzzle in and relaxing with that lineup. Now I may be the cleanup
hitter. Not that it matters. As long as I'm in the lineup, I'm
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is that matter of hitting in the same spot where fans
watched Galarraga produce 44 home runs and 121 RBIs. But Jordan
doesn't expect that kind of production from himself. He's not that
kind of hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He's got power, but he thrives in a situation that requires him
to bear down with two outs, two strikes and a runner in scoring
position. Jordan led the National League in 1996 by hitting .422
with runners in scoring position. Last season, that number was
.311.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't strike him out very often,'' Cox said. ``He's always
going to put the ball in play. When a guy does that, he has a knack
for driving in runs. He fights the pitchers. Pitcher gets him 0-2,
pitcher's still not ahead of him. He'll foul a lot of balls off. He
stays on breaking balls real well. Tough out _ that's how I've
always seen Brian Jordan from the other dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice between hitting 30 home runs and driving in 100
runs and scoring 100 runs, Jordan will take the RBIs and runs.
</P>
<P>
   And for Cox, that will be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him just the way he was _ tough out, get in the
runs,'' Cox said. ``He does everything good. He's probably pretty
close to what he wants to be now. Let's face it; he just signed a
huge contract. We think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan returns to Atlanta where he played for the Falcons
1989-91. He lives in Alpharetta during the offseason. It seems a
natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   There are only the little changes to make, like adding another 3
to his number. The Braves retired No. 3 for Dale Murphy, so Jordan
will be wearing 33. The stage is set for Jordan to make his own
name in the Braves outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to blend in,'' Jordan said. ``I don't consider
myself a superstar. I didn't hit 70 home runs or anything. I just
want to put my piece in, get 100 RBIs, score 100 runs.''
</P>
<P>
   One teammate who knows Braves fans well figures Jordan will fit
in just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already got the foundation set,'' Chipper Jones said.
``He's played in Atlanta for the Falcons. If he does anything that
resembles what he did in St. Louis last year, the fans are just
going to adore him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
