<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graffanino sure trade imminent
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Tony Graffanino, who hit only .211 last
season, returned to camp knowing he's likely to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino knows Bret Boone is expected to start at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the roster. I can see what the team is going to look
like,'' Graffanino said. ``Now, I've got to take care of myself.
I've got to come in here and be the best player I can be and,
hopefully, make a situation for myself somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino is out of options, which means that if he's sent back
to the minor leagues he has to go through waivers, in which case
other teams can claim him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping I was in the (Boone) trade, just so I didn't have
to worry about this kind of situation,'' Graffanino said. ``But I
wasn't, so I just took care of the things I could take care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino worked out at Life University near his Marietta home,
shed 10 pounds and tried to get himself close to midseason form.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino came up through the Atlanta organization as a
promising second baseman, broke into the majors in 1996 and became
a starter when Mark Lemke got hurt in August, 1997. But an ankle
injury last spring slowed Graffanino, and he never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the season started, I wasn't in any kind of
shape,'' Graffanino said. ``A couple weeks in, I wasn't playing as
much as I hoped, and when I did get in there, I tried to do too
much. In one game, I tried to make myself the every-day starter.''
</P>
<P>
   A .275 hitter in the minors, Graffanino managed only 61 hits and
22 RBIs in 289 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm a better baseball player than that,'' Graffanino
said. ``I'm not going to dwell on it, because there wasn't too much
good that came out of it, except that I know I can handle it.
Mentally, I can deal with anything that comes my way.''
</P>
<P>
   TALK, TALK
</P>
<P>
   The trade rumors are swirling. Published reports are circulating
that the Braves are interested in Frank Thomas and Barry Bonds.
They leave Braves manager Bobby Cox and general manager John
Schuerholz incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they do that because you lose a big guy (in Andres
Galarraga),'' Cox said. ``First, there was Frank Thomas; we haven't
talked to the White Sox. Then, it's Barry Bonds. We haven't talked
to the Giants. They assume you have interest in those guys. We're
set to do with what we've got here unless something pops us.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Gerald Williams reported to camp Thursday, bringing
the total in camp to 51 players, all that had been expected. ...
Minor-league first baseman Randall Simon agreed to terms on
Thursday, leaving only two players on the 40-man who have not yet
signed _ Andruw Jones and Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
