<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cink hoping to repeat history with Woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ A successful old college try fortifies
Stewart Cink today in the third round of the Andersen Consulting
Match Play Championship at the LaCosta Resort. Meeting Tiger Woods
with an eventual $1 million on the table, Cink enters the 10:20
match neither intimidated by the situation nor lacking confidence
in his game.
</P>
<P>
   While a 1995 match at Druid Hills Golf Club is found in none of
golf's history books, it remains prominent in Cink's 25-year-old
mind. Granted, it was only an exhibition between Georgia Tech and
Stanford, but Cink shot a brilliant 6-under-par 66 to totally
domiante the freshman Woods. A few days later at Dalton, Ga., in
the Carpet Captial Collegiate tournament, Cink beat a field that
included Woods, who was on his way to
</P>
<P>
   Augusta in his first appearance as U.S. Amateur champion.
</P>
<P>
   Most players have no clue what they might do in a head-to-head
encounter with Woods. At least Cink knows how he did it once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a little bit of history with him,'' Cink said
Thursday. ``There's probably not that many matches in this
tournament that have happened before. I know I haven't forgotten
about it and he hasn't forgotten about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Having noticed early in the week how the bracket could fall,
Cink did his part to make it happen by beating Australia's Craig
Parry 3 and 2 Thursday. Woods, meanwhile, was taken to 18 holes by
former Marietta high school player Bob Tway before winning, 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of playing with or against Woods is dealing with
the hoopla that surrounds the world's No. 1 player and the Match
Play's top seed. One of the PGA Tour's most focused, unflappable
players, Cink does not promise to be rattled out of his game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around him enough to know what to expect,'' Cink
said. ``I've seen him hit before. It's not like I'm going to drop
my jaw if he hits a 330-yard drive. . . . The golf course is still
the opponent. If I play my game and make some birdies, I can put
some pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is the only player seeded in the top 10 to remain in the
tournament after a second day of big-name pillaging. Falling
Thursday were No. 2 David Duval, No. 8 Vijay Singh, No. 9 Nick
Price and No. 10 Justin Leonard. The highest-seeded player on the
opposite bracket from Woods is No. 27 John Huston.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to survive a match like this and to get through to
the next round,'' said Woods, ``I am relieved, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   WORLD MATCH PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's highlights
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernhard Langer (25) def. Vijay Singh (8), 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Maggert (24) def. Nick Price (9), 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Glasson (34) def. David Duval (2), 3-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Mickelson (12) def. Lee Janzen (21), 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Couples (13) def. Scott Hoch (20), 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stewart Cink (48) def. Craig Parry (49), 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eduardo Romero (60) def. Greg Norman (28), 21 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's top matches
</P>
<P>
   _ Tigers Woods (1) vs. Cink.
</P>
<P>
   _ Romero vs. Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
