<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfocused Duval `ready to go home'
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ David Duval could not deny it. Anxious for a
break from the PGA Tour and admittedly no fan of match play, his
mind might not have been totally focused in his second-round match
Thursday against Bill Glasson. His body was in Southern California.
His head already was back home in Jacksonville Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably didn't do too good of a job with that,'' said
Duval, who has dominated the PGA Tour for much of the past two
years, but could not handle Glasson, losing 2-1. ``I'm ready to go
home. I'm ready to get some rest and get focused for The Players
Championship through Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a sweet 16 remaining in the $5 million Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship, which plays third-round and
quarterfinal matches today. Duval led a second-day parade of more
big-name players to exit and never seemed pyched enough for a
five-day, seven-round battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there's two people who expected him (Glasson) to win,
and that was him and his caddie,'' Duval said. ``But I knew he
could beat me. I knew I'd have all I could handle and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My key was to stay with David, not let him get on a roll,''
Glasson said. ``I was lucky. If a guy is off, he's going to lose.
David was just a little off today.''
</P>
<P>
   ROMERO DOES IT AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's Eduardo Romero took three sudden-death holes to
defeat Greg Norman, adding a second scalp to his 60th-ranked
seeding. On Wednesday he knocked off England's Lee Westwood. Romero
was 3-down with four holes to play and pushed the match into
overtime by knocking a 7-iron to a foot at the 18th. Norman halved
the 20th hole despite driving the ball out of bounds. ``I pulled
it, landed it on the cartpath and went OB,'' Norman said. ``That is
just nothing but bad luck.'' His goals aimed beyond this week,
Romero wants to push himself into the top 50 on the world rankings
for a spot in the Masters. ``If you can play in the Masters, it is
fantastic. It is my dream.'' .. . Phil Mickelson faces Romero this
morning, having defeated friend Lee Janzen 2 and 1 Thursday.
Mickelson eagled the 12th hole with a 210-yard 6-iron to a foot,
then birdied the 13th with a 9-iron to four feet. ``This format is
the most mentally draining event,'' said Mickelson. ``My match
tomorrow is already creating a lot of anxiety and nervousness. It's
very difficult to sleep at night and knowing who you have to play,
but not knowing what you have to shoot.'' ... Fred Couples
continues to win while sounding like a beaten man. ``Tiger won a
close match because he's playing good,'' said Couples, who beat
Scott Hoch 1-up and faces Steve Pate this morning. ``I won a close
match because I was lucky. ... This stuff makes me so nervous, I
will be choking like a dog. . .. Emerging in the Presidents Cup as
a surprise hero, Japan's Shigeki Maruyama continued his U.S.
mastery, defeating Justin Leonard, 4 and 2. Asked whether the
Americans should be afraid of him, Maruyama said, ``No problem. I
want everybody to think I am a really funny guy.'' . . . Tway
passed three putts over the hole on his last three holes without
success in his bid to upset Woods. Emotionally drained in the
locker room, Tway also was in disbelief about the small crowds at
La Costa. ``There's more people at Quad Cities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
