<HEADER>
A9738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-ATLANTARACE26-COX     02-25 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ATLANTARACE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spinning wheels: Grand Prix hits finish line
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time in eight years, professional
cyclists will not race through the streets of Atlanta this spring.
The Atlanta Grand Prix is dead, or at least critically wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The event fell victim to Atlanta city officials, who wanted the
race to be held in the autumn and would not grant a spring permit,
and to last year's sponsor, which did not want a fall date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not come to a meeting of the minds,'' said Robin
Morton, competition director for race promoters Advantage
International.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1992, the race was held each spring for six years as the
First Union Grand Prix. In 1998, after First Union did not renew
its affiliation, the Outdoor Life Network assumed the $500,000
title sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   The event, held at Midtown's Piedmont Park and adjacent
neighborhoods, was one of the top two one-day races in the United
States. It drew top cyclists from throughout the world,
particularly in 1996, when the race was held three months before
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour cable Outdoor Life Network wanted to sponsor this
year's race, but only if it could be held in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (fall date) just didn't make sense to us,'' said Peter
Englehart, senior vice president for programming at OLN. ``We'd be
competing against some big events down there. ... We had concerns
about getting lost in the fall menu of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern to OLN, Englehart said, was competition
from college and professional football. The sponsors also did not
like a fall race date because the world cycling championships are
held in the autumn and not many athletes would have committed to
the Atlanta event.
</P>
<P>
   The city did not want to allow the race to continue in the
spring because there are too many events already scheduled for that
time of year, according to a letter from the mayor's office. The
letter did not specify, but two of the biggest springtime events in
Atlanta are Freaknik and Music Midtown. Both draw thousands of
visitors and tax the city's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The springtime is the busiest time of the year for major
events,'' City Hall aide Holly Mull wrote in a Sept. 2, 1998,
letter to Dave Chauner, the main promoter for Advantage
International. ``Each of the events we have in April and early May
negatively impact the adjacent neighborhoods and area businesses.
The City of Atlanta government is also impacted during this time
because manpower resources are stretched. For these reasons, we
will not be able to grant a permit for your event in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Mull no longer works at City Hall, according to a telephone
receptionist there. The mayor's office did not return a reporter's
telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Halstead, the race promoter from 1992-98, acknowledged that
some Virginia-Highland residents had complained about the race
making its way through their neighborhood. Halstead said last year
he was planning to change the course venue away from Piedmont Park
and move the main staging area to Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Halstead sold his company, International Cycling
Productions, to Advantage in June 1998. And then Advantage ran into
the scheduling problems when it went to obtain the city permits.
Advantage and OLN say they would like to see the race return to
Atlanta, but both admit that they have not had any further
discussions with city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Chauner said, ``we're hustling to nail down
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
