<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-GREENE26-COX     02-25 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-GREENE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprinting toward a record
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask him about the chances of breaking the world
record, and a slight smile crosses the face of Maurice Greene.
Then, he catches himself. The bold predictions have been tempered,
if ever so slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Greene lines up as the favorite in the 60 meters in Saturday's
USA Indoor Track and Field Championships. A year ago, he clocked an
indoor world-record 6.39 seconds over a fast track in Madrid,
Spain. He rates the Georgia Dome oval equally fast. And after a
week of training and resting up here following competition in
Europe, he sounds ready for a show-stealing performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll produce something great,'' Greene said. ``That
track is so fast, I'm liable to go low 6.30. You might think I'm
just talking. If it comes out in the race, it's going to be a
beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, I'm not caring about the world record. I can't run
after the world record any more. That's not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Been there, done that _ and it didn't work. Greene, bodacious
like most sprinters, spent last summer chatting about and chasing a
100-meter world record that never budged. Still, he ran away with
eight of 12 finals he entered and was ranked No. 1 by Track &AMP; Field
News. All of that came after he beat Olympic champion Donovan
Bailey at the 1997 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 24, still lives with the disappointment of failing to
advance from the quarterfinals of the 1996 Olympic Trials, where he
was slowed by a season-long strained hamstring. Soon after, he
relocated to Los Angeles to train with esteemed sprint coach John
Smith, whose current stable features Ato Boldon and Jon Drummond.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Greene is the top man at his craft, he aspires to notch
a gold medal in Sydney next year _ the license plate on his new
Mercedes SL500 reads MO GOLD _ and eventually go down as the best
sprinter ever.
</P>
<P>
   Better than Bailey and Linford Christie. Better than Carl Lewis,
even.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the biggest drives I have right now _ Olympic
gold medal,'' said Greene, who carries 175 pounds on his 5-foot-9
frame. ``I just want to keep getting better and better. I want to
be known as the all-time greatest sprinter. At this time, I'm not.
I have a lot of people I have to do stuff better than, because Carl
Lewis did so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that would help me is to just blow the (100-meter)
world record out of its misery right now. Everybody in 100 meters
right now _ me, Ato, Donovan, Frankie (Fredericks), Jon Drummond _
every time we step on the track, we run close to the world record.
I want to put it somewhere where it's not so close every time we
all step on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   While he's working up to it, Greene joins training partner
Drummond as a noble pitch man for the sport. Sunday, he lectured
the Atlanta Track Club on the comparison of sprinters and distance
runners. The next day, he and Drummond engaged in a
conflict-resolution discussion with a seventh-grade class at John
F. Kennedy Middle School, where top high jumper Tisha Waller is
doing a graduate-school internship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just clicked with the kids,'' Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   Following his usual script, Greene will throw T-shirts into the
stands after taking on the sprint field, which includes among
others, his older brother Ernest, Drummond and Barcelona Olympic
bronze medalist Dennis Mitchell. Greene ordered before the season
more than 1,000 white shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always asking, 'Do you have a T-shirt? Do you have
a card?''' he said. ``I always said no, because I didn't. A lot of
us don't have stuff, so some of us give the shirt we have off our
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Greene may be the world's fastest man, his sponsor,
Nike, is glad to help.
</P>
<P>
   MAURICE GREENE
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 24.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size: 5 feet 9, 175 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Residence: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Training partners: Jon Drummond, Ato Boldon, Inger Miller,
Marie-Jose Perec.
</P>
<P>
   _ Career highlights: Holder of indoor 60-meter world record
(6.39 seconds); No. 1 ranked 100-meter runner in 1998; 100-meter
gold medalist at the 1997 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
