A9742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-USAMOBIL26-COX     02-25 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-USAMOBIL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presence of past, future Olympians may boost attendance
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Repeating a familiar theme, U.S. track czar Craig
Masback says it's not time to give up on Atlanta as host of the
national indoor championships.
</P>
<P>
   Better days are ahead, Masback predicts. Even so, nobody is
billing this as the breakthrough year for the USA Indoor Track and
Field Championships, six years into its 10-year contract at the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be (that) the meet came to town, took place and
left,'' said Masback, head of the U.S. track federation. ``You have
to have local people (involved), and we have to recognize the meet
as the most tangible athletic legacy of the '96 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this point, the event hasn't been given a fair chance, but
we're getting a significant outpouring of local sponsors (including
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution) and citizens stepping up to be
involved in the organization of the meet. I would be surprised if
it paid off this year. It's a multiyear effort, and next year will
be the first year we see the benefits of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Masback revealed plans Thursday for the federation to open an
Atlanta office, staffed by a full-time administrator, to market
future indoor championships better.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of a crowd the latest edition will draw Saturday,
after preliminary events tonight, is anybody's guess. The meet's
average for its first four years here was 17,000, based on
exaggerated estimates. With an accurate count last year, it drew
8,874, only 6,474 paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly would hope to exceed that,'' Masback said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the 1996 indoor championships, this year's field is
the strongest since the meet relocated from New York. A significant
reason is that the top two finishers here qualify for the indoor
world championships in Maebashi, Japan, where gold medalists can
earn $50,000, silver $20,000 and bronze $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene, the world's fastest man at 60 meters, figures to
be challenged by training partner Jon Drummond. Jeff Hartwig and
Melissa Mueller have cleared American records in the pole vault
this winter. The high jump has an equally dominant couple in
Atlanta resident Tisha Waller, who cleared an American women's
record 6 feet, 7 inches to win last year, and Atlanta Olympic gold
medalist Charles Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic decathlon champion Dan O'Brien is booked for the 60
hurdles and the long jump. Olympic gold medalist Gail Devers is
entered in the 60 meters. Suzy Hamilton, fresh from tying the
American record in the 800, moves up to the 1,500, and Regina
Jacobs figures to make a run at the American record in the 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The meet also is a showcase for some possible future Olympians,
most notably ex-Southwest DeKalb teammates Angelo Taylor and
Terrence Trammell. Taylor, a Georgia Tech sophomore and the world's
No. 2-ranked 400-meter hurdler, is entered in the open 400.
Trammell, a South Carolina sophomore, is running the 60 hurdles
after clocking the second-fastest collegiate time ever in the 55
hurdles last weekend at the SEC championships.
</P>
<P>
   USA INDOOR CHAMPIONSHIPS
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Preliminaries and high school events tonight, finals
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $5 tonight. $17 reserved, $12 general admission, $8
students Saturday. Available at Ticketmaster and Dome box office.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: 5-6 p.m. Saturday, NBC (live); 12:30-1:30 a.m.; Sunday,
4:30-5:30 p.m. ESPN (taped).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
