<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMS offering $25 tickets for March race
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NASCAR Winston Cup circuit stops at Atlanta Motor
Speedway next month, and AMS is offering $25 tickets for the
Cracker Barrel Old Country Store 500 on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everyone who follows Winston Cup on television to be
able to attend the (race),'' AMS president and general manager Ed
Clark said. ``We know the fans will love (AMS) and the experience
of being at the race in person.''
</P>
<P>
   The tickets, available while supplies last, are for seats in the
Weaver Grandstand overlooking the back straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets can be purchased at the AMS ticket office, 8 a.m.-6 p.m.
today, 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday and 1-5 p.m. Sunday. Tickets also can
be purchased through Ticketmaster at 800-249-6400 or by direct
purchases at select Publix supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the AMS ticket office at
770-946-4211.
</P>
<P>
   TV TIME
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials seem to be eyeing a $400 million price tag for
television rights to its Winston Cup and Busch Grand National races
when current contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR announced Wednesday that it would retain the negotiating
rights from individual venues, beginning with some races during the
2000 season. The projected price would quadruple the $100 million
NASCAR is set to receive for its 34 Cup races this year.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the NFL commands $2.2 billion per year, the NBA
gets $660 million, Major League Baseball receives $340 million and
the NHL gets $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's TV ratings are consistently higher than all other
sports for regular-season events, except the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 25 years, we've been so undervalued by TV,''
Humpy Wheeler said. Wheeler is president and chief operating
officer of Speedway Motorsports Inc., which owns six NASCAR venues,
including speedways in Atlanta, Charlotte and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The last three contracts negotiated for Winston Cup races at
Homestead, Fla., Las Vegas and Phoenix delivered about $5 million
per event, Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA TESTING
</P>
<P>
   Although the NASCAR circuit has a rare off week this weekend,
several Winston Cup and Busch drivers tested at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mast had the fastest lap at Atlanta at 190.909 mph,
followed by Steve Grissom (190.843), Ricky Craven (189.344), Kenny
Wallace (189.150) and Robert Pressley (188.700).
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers say a second groove has formed on the 1.54-mile
oval of AMS, which allows more handling on the high side of the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a full second groove has finally worn in,''
Pressley said. ``We should be able to race side by side with very
little problem in March. When we were here in November, the second
groove was beginning, but it wasn't completely there.''
</P>
<P>
   MCREYNOLDS LEAVING CHILDRESS
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Winston Cup crew chief Larry McReynolds says he is
leaving Richard Childress Racing after this season. McReynolds, who
led Dale Earnhardt's crew in '97, was switched to Mike Skinner's
team after 13 races last season. Skinner leads the points standings
after two events this year.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds, 40, plans to form his own team with John Dangler,
president of Indianapolis-based Performance Marketing Group. A
sponsor or potential car manufacturer for the new team, Motorsports
Performance, is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
