<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO-TEXAS 
 
STATE TRIES TO SNUFF OUT LAWYER'S BID FOR $260 MILLION FEE FROM
ANTI-TOBACCO SETTLEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General John Cornyn asked a federal
judge Thursday to dismiss a claim by a Houston attorney who is
seeking as much as $260 million for legal fees in the state's
anti-tobacco suit, despite complaints by other lawyers that he did
little work.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said attorney Marc D. Murr, a friend of former Attorney
General Dan Morales, should go to the Texas Legislature if he wants
more than the $1 million he was awarded by a national arbitration
panel.
</P>
<P>
   But the Legislature's two chief budget-writers indicated that
Murr would have a hard time getting money from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my belief he added nothing to the process,'' said state
Rep. Rob Junell, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the national arbitration panel that awarded $1
million to Murr, a state arbitration panel of retired judges _
handpicked by Morales and Murr _ awarded the Houston lawyer $260
million. Junell called the state panel ``trumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said he would ask Murr, ``Where were you?''
</P>
<P>
   Junell and Ratliff spent several months last year helping
Morales negotiate a share of the tobacco settlement for counties
and hospital districts. They said they never saw Murr before he
showed up for a mediation session in federal court in Texarkana
last summer and they wouldn't let him participate. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cornyn is still investigating Murr's role in the tobacco suit,
which resulted in a $17.3 billion settlement with cigarette makers
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has said that Murr, who first
requested as much as half a billion dollars in fees, also is the
subject of a preliminary investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has agreed to pay Murr the $1 million
awarded by the national arbitrators in December. But cigarette
companies aren't bound to honor the state panel's $260 million
award, and Cornyn said the difference would have to come from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Murr hasn't asked U.S. District Judge David Folsom of
Texarkana, who presided over the tobacco suit, to confirm the state
arbitration award. But an aide to the attorney general said Cornyn
wanted to act before that happened.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion to Folsom, the attorney general said the court
lacked jurisdiction over Murr's claim because it had been separated
from the tobacco suit and didn't involve federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn also said Murr's claim amounts to a suit against the
state in federal court, which is barred by the 11th Amendment. And,
he said, the Legislature has not waived sovereign immunity to the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motion does not seek to answer the question of whether Mr.
Murr is entitled to any compensation for his work as outside
counsel, but instead seeks to transfer his claim from a federal
courtto the Texas Legislature, where it belongs,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said the state's settlement wouldn't be
affected by his action. Neither, he added, would the $3.3 billion
awarded by the national arbitrators to five other private lawyers
who represented the state.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry will pay the $3.3 billion over as many as
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murr nor his lawyer, Roy Minton of Austin, returned
phone calls from the Houston Chronicle. Morales also was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The former attorney general, who left office Dec. 31, has called
Murr's assistance ``critical'' to the state's settlement. Murr has
claimed in documents to state and national arbitrators, that he
contributed as much as 2,000 hours of work to the anti-tobacco
effort and that he was an active adviser to Morales even before the
state's suit was filed in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other people on both sides of the hard-fought case, however,
said Murr's participation was largely invisible until shortly
before the settlement was announced in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During months of pretrial preparations in 1996 and 1997, Murr's
name didn't appear on hundreds of court documents filed in the
case, and according to other lawyers, he made no courtroom
appearances during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Morales told the Houston Chronicle earlier this month that Murr
did most of his work behind the scenes. In supporting Murr's fee
request last year, Morales told arbitrators that he consulted with
Murr ``on occasions far too numerous to count.''
</P>
<P>
   But phone records and sign-in sheets obtained by the Chronicle
indicate that Murr infrequently visited the attorney general's
office and was only occasionally called by Morales until shortly
before the settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Murr, who met Morales when both were young lawyers at Houston's
Bracewell &AMP; Patterson law firm in the early 1980s, was given a 3
percent contingency contract in the tobacco case by Morales in
October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's contract was revised only a few months later, in January
1997, to remove the contingency and provide only that a
``reasonable fee'' be awarded.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement was reached, Murr agreed to submit his fees
to arbitration. He and Morales picked the three state arbitrators _
former Texas Supreme Court Justice Bob Gammage, retired state
District Judge Sol Casseb of San Antonio and former federal
District Judge James DeAnda of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said the $3.3 billion paid to the other five private
lawyers was ``obscene, but they're real lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales has said he chose Murr for the tobacco case because he
had experience in negotiating damage suits for large numbers of
plaintiffs, including litigation over the 1989 Phillips Petroleum
explosion in Pasadena and defective plastic pipe used in plumbing
systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
