<HEADLINE>
DUNN GETS SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA -- It's time for Jim Dunn to get serious. And that could
spell trouble for the rest of the Funny Car teams in the National
Hot Rod Association, which continues its 22-race tour today with
qualifying for the Checker, Schuck's, Kragen Nationals at Firebird
Raceway near Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, a former driver turned team owner/crew chief, has always
made the most out of a little, fielding a consistent top-10 team
despite a lack of major corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   So one can only imagine what the La Mirada resident will do this
season with major backing from Penthouse Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we did it for fun,'' said Dunn, who had a
limited-budget deal from Mooneyes Auto from 1993-97. ``The Mooneyes
deal was for fun. It was like the old days. Now it's time to get
serious and go after the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will have a hard-running race car, capable of
running with anyone in the top 10. We will be competitive from the
first race of the season until the last one. We plan to do our best
and win our share of races. We have a qualified team, good
equipment and a driver eager to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to Penthouse, some money as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough money and enough equipment,'' Dunn said. ``Now
we have to get out there and get our act together. The first year
we'll try to do the best we can but if you win the championship,
it's just pure luck.''
</P>
<P>
   That has worked for Dunn in the past when he tuned Kenji Okazaki
to a pair of victories in 1997, including the Big Bud Shootout, a
special event that features the top eight competitors on the
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, who retired as a driver in 1990, knows the championship
will not come overnight, but he is ready for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the challenge, throwing more parts at it,'' said Dunn,
the father of Top Fuel driver Mike Dunn. ``I have to learn to step
up. Last year when we shut down, I went to work for Brad Anderson.
He had a pretty good sponsor, so I was able to twist the screws a
little more. So when we ran (a 4.84-second pass), that gave me a
little more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do it if we have the money. Now we have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Dunn's talent as first-rate crew chief could be the key to
the effort. And he has the driver in Frank Pedregon, who was one of
just three drivers in 1998 to win back-to-back national events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a driver who can win races,'' said Dunn, who
also tuned Covina native Randy Anderson to a runner-up finish at
the U.S. Nationals in early September. ``There are some big drivers
who can't win races. To win a championship, you need a good driver
and a lucky driver. (John Force) wins about 20 percent of his races
on luck. That's what makes him a champion -- he's a very good
driver and he's lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon has already had luck shine on his side. The original
deal with Penthouse was to have Kelly Magrath drive, but the La
Jolla resident is sidelined indifinitely with a recurring eye
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year so far,'' said Pedregon, the oldest of
three racing brothers. ``I got married New Year's Eve and couple
weeks later I'm picked to drive. We had a pretty good record last
year. There are guys who race for years and don't have a win. I
already have two. So I'm glad to be back with Jim. I'm back at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be a winning combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have gone to the opening event in Pomona last year
if I didn't think Frank could do it,'' Dunn said. ``After two wins
last season, I have confirmed my instincts. With the addition of
Penthouse Magazine, this season should be even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank wants to go racing. He's making straight runs. His
attitude is one that says `I want to do well and win races.' He is
ready for what I can throw at him. Well keep adding a little bit
each race. We think this Penthouse Magazine Funny Car is capable of
winning any race we enter. Winning an event is only a matter of
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
