<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RESOLUTELY SUNNY CLINTON BEGINS SIX-DAY TRIP WEST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ President Clinton may not have been gloating
Thursday, but he sure was celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Indulging a former antagonist and delighting in his own economic
record, Clinton basked in bright sun and warm ovations here as he
shopped, talked baseball and promoted his proposals to preserve
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers welcoming the president to the convention
center was Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., who voted to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Kolbe praised Clinton's leadership on trying to make
the retirement system more secure and noted twice to the boisterous
crowd of 2,000 that he had flown in with the president on Air Force
One. He sat down beside Clinton, leaning toward him and whispering.
</P>
<P>
   In his own remarks, Clinton thanked Kolbe _ perhaps generously,
perhaps pointedly _ for ``crossing district and party lines to be
here with us today.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later if he still believed Clinton was unfit for office,
Kolbe paused and then said: ``The impeachment's over. Let's talk
about Social Security here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe also has proposed detailed repairs to the Social Security
system, and aides to Clinton insisted that he was fond of the
congressman and harbored no grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was so sunny in his own remarks that he converted even
his bad news to good. The fact that Social Security and Medicare
were in trouble, he said, was ``a high-class problem'' _ evidence
that medical care and prosperity were letting people live longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing to wring your hands about,'' he said. But, he
added, ``we have a responsibility to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in such a generous mood that he skipped right over a
dig at Republicans' tax cut plans prepared by his speechwriters and
released to the press before he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton and Kolbe may be trying to put impeachment behind
them _ at least in public _ the same could not be said of the few
dozen protesters outside clamoring for the president's resignation
or of the Democrats inside, many of whom booed Kolbe.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the convention center, Clinton stopped at a store
to inspect some silver and turquoise jewelry and then visited the
Arizona Diamondbacks baseball team, which is in spring training. He
wandered onto the field to chat with players and to collect a
jersey bearing the number one and the name Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to fly Thursday to San Francisco, where he was
to raise about $1 million for Democrats. He is on a six-day trip
that will include three days of vacation with his family in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Several elderly people who waited said that they were confident
the politicians would find a way to protect Social Security or
Medicare. But then, in the balmy Arizona weather, they seemed to
have few complaints about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they call the good life, baby,'' said Herb Bloom,
84, with a slow grin.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said he trusted Clinton to preserve the retirement
security system. ``The Republicans are sort of hanging back on it,
as usual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also hung back Thursday. While he advocated
strengthening the retirement system by paying off the national debt
_ even envisioning a ``debt-free'' nation in 2018 _ he avoided any
talk of cutting benefits or raising taxes. He spoke vaguely of
``somewhat controversial'' decisions that policymakers would have
to make, and he urged his listeners to support their congressman as
he makes them.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' affection for Clinton seemed undimmed by the
sexual assault accusation against Clinton that had been televised
the night before on NBC. In an interview, Juanita Broaddrick, an
Arkansas woman, said that Clinton had assaulted her more than 20
years ago. Through a lawyer, Clinton has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   People came to see the president dismissed the accusation as
unbelievable or ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Killian, a 31-year-old homemaker, noted that Ms.
Broaddrick had once signed an affidavit saying she had had no
sexual relationship with Clinton. ``She must be a liar, too,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Van Sant, a 42-year-old a pharmacist, said that she had
voted for Ross Perot, but that she had come to support Clinton over
the last year. ``After all of this fiasco, I have a lot of respect
for the man for standing up for what he believes in,'' she said.
``It shows character in a person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
