2-24 -- A woman looks out the window of a tram. Just a decade ago,
when Ukraine was part of the Soviet Union, Lviv was a prime
supplier of tanks, bombsights and military electronics to the
Soviet military. When the Soviet Union vanished, so did Lviv's
weapons orders, scores of thousands of factory jobs and then, bit
by bit, the city's hope for faith in a capitalist future. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) KIEV, Ukraine -- Feb. 25, 1999 -- UKRAINE-OUTLOOK-2,
2-25 -- A woman sells coffee at a bus stop in the Ukraine capital.
Local political leaders say they can see the future in Europe and
the capitalist, democratic philosophy it represents. But Ukraine's
basket-case economy remains lashed to its Russian past and the
longer it stays there, the tighter the bind becomes. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) IN THE ADRIATIC SEA -- Feb. 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-5, 2-25
-- Two F/A-18 Hornets wait to be launched to join another just
catapulted from the flight deck of the USS Enterprise on Tuesday as
the aircraft carrier sailed in the Adriatic Sea off the Coast of
Yugoslavia. The Pentagon is tracking Serb military build-up near
border with Kosovo. If deployed into Kosovo, the troops and tanks
would violate terms of the October agreement with President
Milosevic that averted. (Benjamin D. Olvey/New York Times Photo)
