<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL26-C     02-25 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King curses family of fatal dragging victim after death sentence
levied
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ John William ``Bill'' King's last public act in
Jasper was to curse the family of his murder victim as he was led
away to become the only white person on death row in Texas for
killing a black person.
</P>
<P>
   A Jasper County jury took just less than three hours to hand
King a death sentence for the torture and killing of James Byrd
Jr., who last June was dragged behind a pickup truck until his body
was torn apart.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, did not react when State District Judge Joe Bob Golden
read the death sentence. He released a hand-written statement that
proclaimed his innocence and declared he was ``determined to die
proudly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he is,'' said Joe Collins, the foreman and only black
person on the jury of seven men and five women. ``He's in a place
where he's going to.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins and another juror, Lequeta Flowers, spoke on behalf of
the panel. They said the jury tried to find a redeeming quality in
King but could only conclude that he was without remorse, full of
hate and capable of killing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No crime of this nature is acceptable in any situation,''
Flowers said. ``Society just cannot accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   As King left the courthouse, reporters asked him if he had a
message for the Byrd family. He tossed off an obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just sums up the total personality of this young man,''
said Mary Verrett, one of Byrd's six sisters. ``He has no remorse,
even in the face of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Byrd family, who attended the entire eight-day
trial, declined to address King in the courtroom when it was time
for victims to speak after the sentence was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy,'' the victim's daughter, Renee Mullins, said
later. ``They did what they should have done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a closure, but the anger's still going to be with
us because of the way he died,'' said Stella Brumley, a sister of
Byrd's.
</P>
<P>
   The Jasper community has openly shared the hurt of the Byrd
family since the June 7 murder that was so gruesome it rocked the
nation _ and the world. Seeing King sent to the execution chamber
as punishment for the shocking crime appeared to relieve many local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to ease the pain here,'' said Booker T.
Hunter, president of the Jasper chapter of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People. ``They got justice. That's
what they were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Clark, special agent in charge of the Houston FBI office,
said, ``The people of Jasper County, Texas stood up and spoke to
the world and said, `This is what justice is all about. This is
what America is all about.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County officials have not yet decided whether to put
King's two co-defendants on trial in Jasper, an economically
depressed logging town of 8,000. The county had to raise property
taxes and rely on government grants to help pay for King's trial
and the upcoming trials of his white co-defendants, Shawn Allen
Berry, 24, and Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31. The cost of all three
trials is estimated at $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   King's disabled father was not in the courtroom when his son was
sentenced to death. Ronald King, a retired lumber worker, listened
to the 35-minute closing arguments and then had a 20-minute private
visit with his son, whom he adopted as a three-month-old baby. The
two men cried and hugged in a small room adjacent to the courtroom
while the jury deliberated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the last time he'll ever touch his daddy again,'' said
defense lawyer C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. ``Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder King released a written statement asking for prayers
for the Byrd family, for his son, for the jurors and ``for the town
of Jasper, a community that remains strong though scarred by this
unspeakable act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we all can find meaning from this tragedy, from
the needless and senseless death of James Byrd Jr.,'' the statement
said. ``We all are human beings, black and white. We all are
children of God. We must learn to love one another and not hate.''
</P>
<P>
   His son becomes the first white person condemned in Texas for
killing a black person since the state resumed capital punishment
in the mid-1970s. The only white person to be executed in Texas for
killing a black person was a farmer who killed another white
farmer's favorite slave nearly 150 years ago, according to research
by a University of Florida professor published in The Sociological
Quarterly in 1989. Prosecutors told jurors in closing arguments
Thursday morning that Bill King deserved to be executed because he
was a hate-filled racist who would hurt again.
</P>
<P>
   ``By giving Mr. King a life sentence, you're giving him at least
40 years to catch a black guard, a black nurse, a black doctor, a
Jewish guard, a Jewish nurse, a Jewish doctor, or anybody else,''
said assistant district attorney Pat Hardy. Prosecutors presented
evidence that King had a homemade knife in his cell while awaiting
trial for this case. In their deliberations Thursday, jurors asked
to see the shank.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys asked for a life sentence, which would have
made King eligible for parole after 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your vote is not going to bring Mr. Byrd back; I wish it
could,'' lawyer Brack Jones Jr. said. ``Your vote is not going to
change the stigma this Jasper community is going to have for years
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether you vote life or death, John William
King is a dead man walking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
