<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9760 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-SENTEN     02-25 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-SENTENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEATH SENTENCE FIRST IN TWO DECADES FOR WHITE KILLING A
BLACK
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies DRAGGING-DEATH) 
(EDS: Subs for DRAGGINGDEATH-REACTION) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
And JEFF CLAASEN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday's sentencing of John William King marks the first time
in two decades that Texas has sent a white to Death Row for killing
a black, prompting several death penalty experts to say the
punishment is not even-handed.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, 41 black prisoners have been executed in
Texas for killing a white person _ including one execution earlier
this week, said Tonya McClary, criminal justice research director
for the NAACP Legal Defense Fund in New York City. Norman Evans
Green, a black man, was executed Wednesday for killing a store
clerk in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Racial discrimination is partly to blame for the disparity, but
balancing the numbers is not the solution, McClary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying we want them to send more white people to
Death Row for killing black people,'' said McClary, whose
organization opposes the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination based on skin color is not the only factor that
makes capital punishment unfair, McClary said. She said the poor
and uneducated, regardless of race, are more likely to be executed,
while ``someone of stature can escape the ultimate punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson, a black man and former professional football star
who was acquitted in California of murdering his white wife, is a
prime example of how money and fame can save someone from the death
penalty, McClary said.
</P>
<P>
   King was sentenced to death on Thursday for the killing of James
Byrd Jr., a black man who was dragged by a chain. If King's
punishment is carried out, he will be the first white man in Texas
this century to die for killing a black person.
</P>
<P>
   Only one white man has ever been executed in Texas for killing a
black man, and that was on June 2, 1854, said Michael Radelet, a
death penalty expert and chairman of the sociology department of
the University of Florida. That case involved a feud between two
powerful farmers that peaked when one of them killed the other's
slave, Radelet said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the death penalty in the United States has
involved a history of racism in its worst sort,'' he said, adding
that ``evidence of racism'' continues to exist in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Capital punishment resumed in the United States in 1977. Since
then, 11 whites have been executed for killing a black, while 142
blacks have been sent to death chambers for killing a white,
according to records compiled by the NAACP Legal Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 executions involving white inmates, five occurred in
South Carolina, two in Oklahoma and one each in North Carolina,
Missouri, Alabama and Virginia, the NAACP said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Todd, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice, said King will be isolated from other Death Row inmates
because of the nature of his crime. He will remain alone in a cell
23 hours a day, allowed only one hour for recreation _ also in
isolation, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will shower alone, and he will not have any type of
communication or relationship with any of the other inmates, other
than hollering down the cell blocks,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting King, there are 452 inmates on Death Row, including
161 white men, 188 black men, 91 Hispanic men, 5 white women and
three black women. Four Death Row inmates are classified as being
something ``other'' than white, black or Hispanic, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small percentage of homicides in Texas involves white
perpetrators and black victims, or vice versa, according to
statistics compiled by the FBI. Between 1980 and 1997, 57 percent
of the state's cases involved ``white-on-white'' killings, 31
percent were ``black-on-black'' homicides, 6 percent involved black
assailants and white victims, and 3 percent involved black victims
and white assailants, the statistics show.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
