<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9762 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     02-25 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY QUICKLY DECIDES ON DEATH PENALTY FOR DRAGGING DEATH DEFENDANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ After eight days of often-gruesome testimony, a
jury took less than three hours on Thursday to decide that John
William King must die for the dragging death of an African-American
man he didn't know but killed because of a hatred of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first white person in Texas to be sent to Death Row
for the murder of an African-American since the state revived
capital punishment in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant King, the first of three defendants to be tried in the
June 7 slaying of James Byrd Jr., responded with a crude sexual
reference when he was asked outside the courthouse if he had
anything to say to Byrd's family.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister Mary Verrett said she wasn't surprised by King's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect for him to say, `God bless the Byrd family.'
It just sums up the total personality of this young man,'' she
said. ``He has no remorse, even in the face of death.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two rows of the Victorian courtroom in the small East
Texas town were filled by relatives of Byrd, 49, a vacuum cleaner
salesman who was walking home after attending two parties.
Prosecutors said he was picked up by King and two friends who took
him to a country road, beat him, sprayed his face black, chained
his ankles to a pickup bumper and dragged him three miles along a
rural road. His decapitated body was dumped at a black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the trials of the other two defendants,
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, and Shawn Berry, 24.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing of King is ``one point of closure but the pain is
still with us,'' said Stella Brumley, a sister of Byrd. ``It's not
going to bring back our brother, but now another family won't have
to go through this devil's station of agony. Justice has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant's father, Ronald King, 67, who on Wednesday
pleaded with the jury to spare his son's life, was too ill to
attend court yesterday but issued a statement in anticipation of a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to pray for healing and reconciliation,'' he wrote.
``Please pray for the Byrd family, who have endured unimaginable
pain and loss. Please pray for these jurors who shouldered a
horrible burden. Please pray for our town of Jasper, a community
that remains strong though scarred by this unspeakable act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also ask for prayers for my family, and for my son, for
redemption and healing even on death row,'' Ronald King wrote. ``I
hope we can find some meaning from this tragedy, from the needless
and senseless death of James Byrd Jr. We are all human beings,
black and white. We are all children of God. We must learn to love
one another and not hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush issued a statement commending the jury ``for
its hard work and its verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The brutal beating, dragging and murder of James Byrd was a
horrible, despicable crime, and those responsible deserve the
ultimate punishment,'' Bush said. ``The jury has sent a clear
message that Texas will not tolerate hate and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, King was escorted in a bullet proof vest to
an unmarked car that whisked him to the prison system's James Byrd
Diagnostic Center in Huntsville, which was named for a former
warden who is no relation to the victim. After medical and
psychological examinations, he will be placed on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement issued through his attorney, King said,
``Though I remain adamant about my innocence, it's been obvious
from the beginning that the community would get what they desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'll close with the words of Francis Yockey,'' he wrote.
```The promise of success is with the man who is determined to die
proudly when it is no longer possible to live proudly. ...'''
</P>
<P>
   As the jury foreman and only black member of the jury, Joe
Collins, a prison guard and former classmate of King, announced
that a verdict had been reached in the punishment phase. When
Collins was told later of King's intention to ``die proudly,'' he
said: ``I hope he is. He's going to a place where he's going to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Billy Rowles, who arrested the three suspects in less
than 24 hours, said King was up most of Wednesday night, throwing a
tantrum and speaking threateningly to the black officer who guarded
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He nutted up, cussing, kicking the door,'' Rowles said of
King, who on Tuesday had been found guilty of capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments during the penalty phase of the trial on
Thursday, defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs argued that
King's guilt was mitigated by his experience when he served in the
Texas prison system previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a racist when he went in,'' Cribbs said. ``He was
when he came out.''
</P>
<P>
   King's other attorney, Brack Jones, said that executing King
would ``not bring Mr. Byrd back and you're not going to change the
stigma that this Jasper community is going to have for years to
come. Nothing but time will heal that.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued that even in maximum security, King still
poses a threat.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray said that King would become a
white supremacist cell block leader, and able to recruit others to
his racist cause. Then, ``he'll send as many missionaries out as he
can to do his work.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most emotional appeals to the jury, Assistant
District Attorney Pat Hardy referred to the victim's son, an Army
soldier, when he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Ross Byrd would like nothing better that to stick
his fist into King's chest and rip out his satanic heart for what
he did to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy noted that King was able to fashion a homemade knife from
television parts while locked in the Jasper County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give him life in prison, you are giving him 40 years to
catch a black guard, a black nurse, a black doctor _ a Jewish
guard, a Jewish nurse, a Jewish doctor,'' Hardy said. ``You are
giving him a chance to take another life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gray contended during the trial that King killed Byrd
either to help launch a hate group in Jasper or to carry out an
initiation rite for his prison gang, the Confederate Knights of
America, jurors said they relied solely on physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to find something to save him,'' said juror Luquita
Flowers, 41, a schoolteacher from nearby Buna. But, she said, ``I
feel like he didn't feel any remorse for his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Flowers said, the jury was of one mind about King's
guilt and his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any dissension, never a situation where one
person had to be persuaded,'' she said.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
