<HEADER>
A9768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-NY     02-25 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS LEAD WAY IN POST-IMPEACHMENT SCANDAL COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With President Clinton's acquittal on impeachment
charges, round-the-clock television news scrutiny of his personal
life began to subside, to the relief of many a viewer. But the
ebbing of Clnton-Lewinsky mania has clearly hurt the 24-hour cable
news networks, whose ratings had been pumped up by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In the week after the acquittal, each of the three main cable
news networks _ CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel _ saw their Nielsen
ratings drop, by 25 to 30 percent, from the average they had been
getting during the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   And the latest coups in television coverage have been by the
major broadcast networks _ NBC News with an interview with Juanita
Broaddrick, the Arkansas businesswoman who accused Clinton of
raping her 21 years ago, and ABC News with Barbara Walters'
interview with Monica Lewinsky, scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, ``Dateline NBC'' got a ratings spike from
the interview by the correspondent Lisa Myers with Mrs. Broaddrick.
Up against the Grammy Awards show on CBS, ``Dateline'' got a 10.3
rating for its first half-hour, representing about 10.2 million
households, about 10 percent more than average.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's sister cable channel, MSNBC, also got a slight boost on
Wednesday night for related shows. Brian Williams interviewed Ms.
Myers live on his 9 p.m. newscast, and at 10 p.m., she was
interviewed by John Hockenberry during ``Hockenberry,'' his
interview show.
</P>
<P>
   The next big exclusive is Ms. Walters' two-hour special next
Wednesday, for which ABC has raised its price for a 30-second
commercial to $800,000 from the usual $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is some concern about whether that interview will
deliver the audience being paid for, because some elements of what
Ms. Lewinsky told Ms. Walters were reported Thursday in The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're far more concerned that information like this can be
leaked to the press without our authorization and without being
accurate,'' Eileen Murphy, the spokeswoman for ABC News, said
Thursday. ``There are several inaccuracies in what was printed, and
that's of more concern than what it might do to the ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post's account was reported on CNN's morning news Thursday,
and the reporter, Howard Kurtz, was interviewed on CNN's 5 p.m.
program, ``Inside Politics.'' His report got brief mention on Fox
News Channel's 6 p.m. news Thursday night, and on ``Equal Time'' on
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most unusual plan for capitalizing on interest in
Ms. Lewinsky's story comes from the producers of MSNBC's
``Hockenberry.'' Conceding that most viewers will tune to Ms.
Walter's interview, MSNBC is running promotional ads urging viewers
to simultaneously log on to MSNBC's Web site, or to watch both ABC
and MSNBC using the picture-within-a-picture gadgetry if they have
it, and then to send their reactions to MSNBC, by telephone or by
e-mail, which will then be read on the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
