<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNE-BUGGY-CAPITAL-AR     02-25 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNE-BUGGY-CAPITAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAND PIT CAN BE FUN IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Two photos and a locator map are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLAMIS, Calif. _ Alan Hamada chuckled as a bucket's worth of
sand landed in his face.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed harder when another load hit him, pouring onto his
lap and seeping into his jeans, socks and high-tops. ``Ha,'' he
said, ``I got used to that a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Very little can get in the way of Hamada's good time when he
rides his dune buggy on the undulating sands of the California
desert. Not the deafening roar of thousands of other dune buggies
and assorted fat-wheeled vehicles (``it's music''), not the burning
sun (``just beautiful''), not the many accidents (``I'm careful''),
and definitely not all the sand that slaps him when riled by his
buggy (``part of the fun!'').
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the experience for Hamada, a Los Angeles
sheet-metal worker who travels 270 miles, near the Arizona line,
just to play road warrior. Officially, his playpen, which is
overseen by the Bureau of Land Management, is known as the Imperial
San Dunes Recreation Area. But to most people who come here, the
125,000 acres of dunes that they joy ride in is simply ``Glamis,''
the sand-toy capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   During the big holiday weekends from Thanksgiving to Easter _
and usually the weekends immediately around those holidays _ the
dunes draw 40,000 to 60,000 sand fans to an outpost where the
permanent population is 13. So many trailers line the desert road
that Glamis becomes a weekend city, complete with different
neighborhoods, grandmothers in lawn chairs and dogs tied to the
trailers' doors.
</P>
<P>
   The off-roaders are a decades-old tradition, but they are not
entirely welcome. In the nearest city, Brawley (population 20,000),
which is 25 miles west of Glamis, residents brace for the Glamis
crowd the way coastal towns brace for a hurricane. They either
clear out or stay in, and the local hospital, Pioneers Memorial,
stocks up on staff members and supplies to handle the inevitable
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Glamis weekend it's total chaos,'' said Jennifer Smith,
manager of the Townhouse Hotel in Brawley, as she watched the
flatbed trucks carrying dune buggies and motorcycles pass by on the
Saturday of Presidents' Day weekend. ``Cars speed through town like
they're in a race, and you hear ambulance sirens day and night.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have a complaint, too _ that the motorcycles,
all-terrain vehicles, dune buggies and other machines that tear
through the sand are literally tearing up the fragile desert,
scarring it for decades and destroying unique animal and plant
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The off-road vehicles are probably the single most destructive
force in the California desert,'' said Nick Ervin, who is active in
the Sierra Club in San Diego and is a member of the federal
California Desert Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, largely because of environmental concerns,
off-roaders have been restricted to 12 areas in the 25-million-acre
desert. And off-roaders, who must be licensed and registered by the
state, contend that they have been restricted enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hamada, who started riding 30 years ago and still comes six or
seven weekends a year, considers the desert remarkably resilient.
</P>
<P>
   ``One sandstorm will wipe this all away,'' he said as he
surveyed the maze of tire treads on the dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Hamada's son, Neil, 27, began riding on a motorcycle with his
father when he was 2, and on his own, on a motorized baby-sized
buggy, when he was 4, like so many other children here. He is now
the dunes manager, the lone ranger in residence at the Cahuilla
Ranger Station in Glamis.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Hamada bristles at the reputation of the off-roaders, which
is that of a beer-guzzling fraternity that howls at the moon. In
truth, they are a varied group. There are people who fly
Confederate battle flags on their trailers and belong to a Glamis
paramilitary group that curses the government and advertises coming
off-road events on the Internet. There are also average suburban
families, serious off-road clubs that spend the weekend in
organized races up a 300-foot-high dune called Oldsmobile Hill, and
yuppies trying out their new SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Too many off-roaders believe that falling in the dunes will be
like landing in several feet of new snow. Instead, the sand might
as well be marble. When people fall, lips split, arms and legs
break, ribs snap and skulls crack. Each year, several people die
and several hundred others are seriously injured on the dunes,
usually because someone was driving too fast or drinking too hard.
</P>
<P>
   On Presidents' Day weekend, when more than 40,000 people
converged in the dunes, Pioneers Memorial Hospital tallied 71
serious injuries, including four sheared spleens, a punctured
liver, a broken neck, a broken leg that had to be amputated, and
many fractured legs, clavicles and arms.
</P>
<P>
   Hamada was riding his dune buggy without a helmet, a no-no, but
he wore goggles and a blue kerchief over his nose and mouth as a
shield. He has never broken any bones, he said, but has had an
uncountable number of bruises and cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I got hurt riding a motorcycle many times,''
he said. ``But then, when you're young, you do a lot of stupid
things.''
</P>
<P>
   He was driving only 35 miles an hour, though it felt much
faster. The wind was whipping and the motor sounded like a small
plane as Hamada drove around and around in a sand pit, thoroughly
enjoying himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNINSURED-ART-1STLD-W     02-25 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKESNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS OFFER INFORMATION ABOUT AMERICANS WITHOUT HEALTH INSURANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Inserts a new 3rd graf about why the large number of
uninsured is bad for the whole health care system. Subs 4th graf to
smooth the transition from new 3rd graf.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who are all these 43.4 million Americans, at the
Census Bureau's last count, who do not have health insurance? Who
runs the least risk in going without it? (Children.) Who runs the
most risk? (Sick people approaching 65.) Who is most likely to have
it? (People over 65.) Not to have it? (Adults who work for low
wages.) Who doesn't care? (Invincible youth.)
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, a average of a million Americans a year
have either lost their health insurance or failed to obtain
insurance for which they became eligible. The reasons vary:
prohibitive premiums, reduced employer coverage, the welfare
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the causes, the unrelenting growth in the number of
uninsured is taking a toll. Studies show that the uninsured, in
typically forgoing care until they need a hospital emergency room,
wind up far less healthy than the rest of the population. Further,
emergency rooms cannot provide them follow-up care, and treatment
there is much more costly than preventive services in a doctor's
office, adding to the burdens on the nation's health care system.
</P>
<P>
   The vast number of uninsured is a startling anomaly in an
economy that has been able to subdue inflation, unemployment and
budget deficits. Much to the dismay of advocates for the uninsured,
the United States, despite its bounty, stands almost alone among
industrial nations in not providing free basic health care for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number is going in absolutely the wrong direction,'' said
Grace-Marie Arnett, president of the conservative Galen Institute,
a health and tax policy organization. ``It shows something is wrong
with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the rise in the cost of insurance and health care
outrunning wages gains, said Paul Fronstin, an analyst at the
nonpartisan Employee Benefit Research Institute, ``this is going to
get worse unless something is done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The what to do about it _ long primarily the concern of liberals
_ is now being weighed by politicians across the political
spectrum. The still-evolving proposals range from expanding
government insurance programs to tax breaks helping more people buy
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general,'' said Judith Feder, dean of policy studies at the
Georgetown University Public Policy Institute, ``there is
acknowledgment across ideological and partisan lines that the
reason people don't have coverage is they can't afford it and that
the way to provide it is through subsidies. Then the question is
how the subsidies are to be given and whether to focus on
particular populations.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is debate on how to help them, few experts disagree
on who they are.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, not many are elderly or seriously disabled
because Medicare covers most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, some five million to six million have family
incomes exceeding $75,000 a year and can usually afford the
insurance that they forgo for a number of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 11 million are children, from indigent to well off. But
to many health system analysts, children raise less-compelling
concerns than large numbers of the other uninsured. First, they are
generally healthier than adults and cheaper to treat.
</P>
<P>
   And second, alone among the uninsured, they have already been
singled out for help, under a $24 billion, five-year program for
non-Medicaid eligible children that was approved by Congress in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the rest of the uninsured, those who need coverage
most: 25 million to 30 million people who have the greatest chance
of becoming ill and who cannot pay for care when they do.
Demographically, they run the gamut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some work, and some don't,'' said Katherine Swartz, an
associate professor at the Harvard School of Public Health. ``Some
don't work because they're sick. Some are very young adults not
covered by their parents' health insurance. They take jobs serving
latte in coffee shops that are not likely to have health insurance.
They just don't think about the risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The income of some is so low that they cannot afford to buy
insurance, Ms. Swartz said, but not so low that they qualify for
Medicaid. Others may qualify but fail to apply, because of
ignorance, language barriers or a general sense of intimidation. So
they rely on emergency rooms for all their care.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the uninsured in the greatest need of coverage ``are
working adults who are not quite in the middle class,'' said David
B. Kendall, health policy analyst at the Progressive Policy
Institute. ``They are the folks who don't have a job that's going
to be there for a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority groups account for a disproportionate number of the
uninsured, Kendall said. Among Hispanic Americans, nearly half of
those under 65 are uninsured; the Hispanic category makes up only
11 percent of the population but 21 percent of all the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there are several reasons, some of which reflect a
conscious choice to forgo insurance: Hispanic people who have
immigrated to the United States tend to be healthy and to value
self-reliance. They may also be intimidated by language and
cultural barriers from applying for Medicaid and other assistance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The travails of the uninsured are often dismissed because the
law assures them the last-resort, safety-net care of emergency
rooms, says Drew E. Altman, president of the Kaiser Family
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time they call the ambulance, many have gone without
the preventive care that might have averted the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of adults under 65 by Kaiser and the Commonwealth Fund
found that in a single year, 24 percent of the uninsured declined
to fill a prescription that had been given to them by a doctor,
compared with 6 percent of those who had insurance. Fifty-one
percent had difficulty obtaining care compared with 10 percent of
the insured, and 42 percent never saw a doctor during the prior
year, compared with 17 percent for the insured.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the uninsured are sicker than others, according to
a study last year by the Center for Studying Health System Change,
a research group supported by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation.
The study found that 16.3 percent of uninsured people under 65 were
in fair to poor health, compared with 10.6 percent of all people
under 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``The uninsured use less care,'' said John Holahan, health
policy analyst at the Urban Institute. ``When they do get care,
they get less of it.''
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the rise in the uninsured is the shift of
people from welfare to work. More than six million have left the
welfare rolls in the last five years, many for low-wage jobs that
do not offer any insurance or that charge a lot for it.
</P>
<P>
   For these workers, there is help for a while from Medicaid, the
federal-state insurance program for the poor, which is
automatically granted welfare recipients. In most states, families
can remain on Medicaid for a year after leaving the cash-assistance
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But then, said Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families
USA, a consumer advocacy group, ``their reward is the loss of
health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the swelling in the number is the rising cost
of health care _ for hospital stays, physician visits and
prescription medicine. It is climbing faster than workers' wages,
and on top of the general increase in the cost of care, employers
are asking workers to a larger share of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, nearly two-thirds of all businesses with 100 or more
workers paid the full cost of an individual worker's care, a Kaiser
Family Foundation study says. A decade later only a third did so.
Kaiser says employers that ask workers to pay part of the cost
through payroll deductions raised the workers' share from 13
percent in 1988 to 22 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a survey by the federal Agency for Health Care
Policy and Research found, one in four workers who were offered
employer-subsidized insurance in 1997 declined to sign up. A decade
ago, only one in ten declined.
</P>
<P>
   These changes, analysts say, have spawned the largest segment of
the uninsured, the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   In a study this month of the uninsured in 1997, the Center for
Budget and Policy Priorities, a liberal research group in
Washington, reported that nearly half the nation's 4.5 million
working parents with incomes below the federal poverty line _
$13,650 for a family of three _ were uninsured. And of the 15.8
million who made up to twice the poverty wage, or $27,300 for
three, it said a third were uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Young adults, some poor, some not, represent another large group
of the uninsured. Of 65 million people up to 34 years old, nearly
25 percent are uninsured, compared with 13 percent of the rest of
the population, and they represent nearly 40 percent of all the
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Of the youngest among them, those 19 to 24, the Center for
Studying Health System Change says 30 percent are not offered
insurance through their jobs. Of those who are offered it,
typically for a few hundred dollars a year, 30 percent turn it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Some who reject it are working poor and cannot afford it.
Others, feeling immortal, use their wages for something else. But
in forgoing regular care, the youngest appear to pay a toll as they
age. The center reports that nearly 18 percent of the uninsured
aged 25 to 34 are in fair to poor health, compared with 10 percent
for all people their age.
</P>
<P>
   However much some young adults feel they can do without
insurance, the nation has an incentive to help them buy it,
analysts say. Like safe drivers who never have accidents and still
buy car insurance, young adults' health insurance premiums help
defray the cost of care for people who are frailer and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we need these people for cross-subsidies?'' asked Fronstin
of the Employee Benefit Research Institute. ``Or should we wait
until they get sick or have an accident?
</P>
<P>
   While many analysts may have arrived at an answer, he said,
Congress has not.
</P>
<P>
   Among the beneficiaries of cross-subsidies would be a less
obviously needy group of the uninsured: the poorer and sicker,
often retired and homebound, among the 23 million Americans aged 55
to 64 who are not yet eligible for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Studying Health System Change,
people in that age group have average family incomes of $45,800,
about $4,000 more than the average for all families and enough to
permit nearly 90 percent of them to pay the age group's high
premiums of close to $3,000 a year, even if the employer pays no
share.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3 million among them who are uninsured earn an average
of only $18,000. The center reports that one third of them are in
particularly perilous straits. These 1 million are in ill health
and have average incomes of just $9,600, which puts private
coverage far out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   This year, President Clinton has revived a proposal he made last
year to allow people aged 55 to 64 the option of joining Medicare
by paying $300 to $400 a month until they are 65. But at $400 a
month, the one third in peril would be spending half their incomes
for health insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
