A9779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-NYT &LR;      02-25 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DRUG BENEFITS IN MEDICARE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   As a bipartisan commission wrestles with restructuring Medicare
financing for the next century, it needs to modernize Medicare's
benefits. That means adding a prescription drug benefit to the
program. Liberal Democrats in Congress and on the commission
consider a drug benefit crucial to Medicare reform. But Republicans
are worried that expanding coverage to drugs could add upward of
$20 billion a year in costs to a program already headed for
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   The political reality is that neither camp can achieve what it
wants without the other. The commission is considering a plan
drafted by Sen. John Breaux, the group's chairman, that would
replace the existing Medicare system with a market of private and
government-run health plans. The hope is that competition will help
control growth in Medicare costs over time.
</P>
<P>
   But radical restructuring will be a hard sell politically
without adding drug coverage. Conversely, it is unlikely that the
federal government can afford to cover drugs without making
substantial changes to traditional Medicare, including injecting
more managed care into the system.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which was supposed to produce final
recommendations for Congress next Monday, is now expected to work
past that date. Two swing votes on the commission, Stuart Altman, a
professor at Brandeis University, and Laura D'Andrea Tyson, the
former chief economic adviser to President Clinton, have both said
they cannot support the restructuring plan without a new drug
benefit. They have good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs are more important therapeutically than ever.
New drugs can save money overall by keeping patients out of the
hospital. When Medicare was created in the 1960s, prescription drug
coverage was not a standard feature of private insurance policies.
Now most employer-based health plans provide drug coverage because
drugs have become an integral part of modern health care. Medicare
has never caught up.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of Medicare beneficiaries have to pay for all
drugs themselves. The rest have drug benefits through plans
provided by former employers, Medigap plans they buy themselves, or
through Medicaid. But employer-paid plans are becoming more rare,
and Medigap plans that cover drugs are too costly for many
low-income retirees to afford.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for elderly patients to pay thousands of
dollars a year for drugs. Many simply go without. That situation
needs to change. The debate over the future of Medicare has focused
on ways to control costs and shore up the finances. Equally
important is revamping benefits to reflect the prescription drug
needs of the elderly population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
