<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-INSURANCE26     02-25 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-INSURANCE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texans juggle choice of health insurance vs. other expenses
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ All the blood drained from the boy's face. He
lay motionless on the couch, and the veins in his neck were ``going
about 90 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Authenreith knew that his 5-year-old son Barry, who has a
heart condition, was in trouble on that day last December.
Authenreith works at a local engineering consulting firm that
doesn't provide health insurance, and he couldn't afford his son's
$75 medication that month. Barry had been without the medicine for
about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the boy recovered after a weeklong stay at the
hospital. Now his father isn't sure how he'll pay those hefty
medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Many Texans face a similar predicament: Almost 500,000 Texas
children live in households that can't afford private health
insurance for their children but earn too much to qualify for
Medicaid, the federal-state health care program for the poor. So
they forego insurance and hope for the best, skipping the checkups
_ and sometimes the medications _ that could keep their kids
healthy and prevent financially disastrous major illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' soon-to-be-launched Children's Health Insurance Program
would use federal and state money to cover Texas children like
Barry Authenreith who are in that gap. But Gov. George W. Bush and
state lawmakers are still wrangling over whether the program will
cover people making up to twice the federal poverty level or only
150 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agree on the amount of state money to launch the
program _ an annual average of $151 million, which would come out
of the state's tobacco settlement. But they are struggling over how
far that money will go.
</P>
<P>
   The physical and budgetary health of hundreds of thousands of
Texas families hang in the balance: An estimated 220,000 Texas
children live in families with incomes between 150 percent and 200
percent of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The wage-earners in those families are legal secretaries and
mechanics, who make an average of close to $28,000 in Austin, or
175 percent of the poverty level for a four-person family. Austin
plumbers and accountants make an average of about $33,000, or twice
the poverty level for four.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Authenreith, a computer-assisted draftsman, makes a
full-time salary of about $18,000 a year, a little more than 150
percent of poverty for a family of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any other parent, I worry about what's going to happen
next and how I'm going to handle it when it comes along,''
Authenreith said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the 150 percent threshold say it would be fiscally
irresponsible to go any higher because future federal CHIP
contributions are uncertain, and nobody knows how many people will
enroll in the program. The federal government will put in about $3
for every $1 from Texas. Privately, some also have philosophical
objections to spending money to insure people making as much as
twice the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, Bush must sign off on the CHIP plan that is
sent to Washington for federal approval, and the Health and Human
Services Commission has drafted a proposal that would cover
families making up to 150 percent of the poverty level. Discussions
between the governor and lawmakers are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the 200 percent threshold say advocates of the
lower level are overestimating the number of people who will enroll
in the program. They also note that Republican governors in other
states have chosen the higher threshold. Rep. Glen Maxey (D-Austin)
has portrayed the question as a test of Bush's professed
``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the money's available and children up to 200 percent of the
poverty level need health insurance, there's no logical reason why
we shouldn't cover them,'' Maxey said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush rejects the notion that he'd be betraying his
``compassionate'' philosophy by choosing the lower level.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can use all the kinds of slogans they want. If you get up
to 150 percent we are going to be covering a lot of children that
aren't covered today,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the debate concerns the 598,000 uninsured Texas children
who are eligible for Medicaid but not enrolled. Many families who
have left the rapidly shrinking welfare rolls mistakenly believe
that because they no longer receive welfare benefits, their
children aren't eligible for Medicaid. Others are daunted by the
Medicaid bureaucracy, or dissuaded by the stigma of getting
government help.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state will mount an aggressive outreach program as
part of CHIP, it is likely that many families will discover that
their children are eligible for Medicaid and enroll them.
Proponents of the 150 percent limit note that because no one is
sure how much Medicaid ``spillover'' there will be, the state
should concentrate on serving the poorest group.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, either CHIP option would help thousands of children.
About 24 percent of Texas' children, a total of 1.4 million, are
uninsured. The uninsured rate ranks Texas second to last behind
Arizona, and only California has more children who aren't covered.
</P>
<P>
   California's CHIP currently covers children in families making
up to twice the federal poverty level, while Arizona has adopted a
CHIP plan that will phase in the 200 percent threshold by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For many working Texans, health insurance is still a luxury they
simply can't afford. Nearly two-thirds of uninsured children in
Texas live in households with a parent who works full-time. Only 12
percent are in families where nobody works.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, Authenreith didn't have to worry about
paying for Barry's medication or his regular visits to the
cardiologist. His wife worked for an eyeglass manufacturer that
provided health insurance for their son _ but she died in a 1997
car accident.
</P>
<P>
   After his wife's death, Authenreith quit his job in motel
maintenance _ because it took him away from home too often _ and
worked part-time and went to Austin Community College to learn
computer-assisted drafting. He was on welfare, and Barry qualified
for Medicaid. Now, he earns too much for that help _ and maybe too
much for CHIP, depending on what the final income limit is.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors tell him that Barry can have an operation when he's 10
that could correct his problem _ but Authenreith isn't even sure
how he'll pay the bills from the boy's last hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude now is take things one day at a time and deal with
things the best that I can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
