</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMILTON, LEFFLER TO BE BUSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE -- Tony Stewart will not be the lone driver to be
piling up frequent flier miles this year and traveling to more than
one racing series.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Hamilton and Jason Leffler will also be pulling double
duty. Both plan on racing on Irwindale's Opening Night Spectacular
on March 27 and then fly to Phoenix to race in the IRL Phoenix 200
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler will be racing the midget portion at Irwindale and
Hamilton will be in every race, midgets, sprints and the
Super-Modifieds, on opening night. Both say they plan on running
select USAC events in addition to their IRL schedule, if time
permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This facility is like a superspeedway, except they put it in a
half-mile,'' Hamilton said during a tire-testing session last
Sunday. ``The track is perfect. It's the best short track in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton finished second in the IRL for the second consecutive
season. He finished fourth at last year's Indianapolis 500, but has
yet to win an IRL race in 25 tries. He placed eighth at the IRL
opener Jan. 24 in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He compares the Irwindale track to Tucson and Erie, Colo., but
says those track's facilities don't compare to Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler says the speedway surface, which he compares to
Indianapolis Racing Park, will eventually be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real quick,'' said Leffler, who is an IRL rookie. ``This
track is in a league of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Leffler is one of only six drivers to win two USAC titles in the
same season. The Long Beach native won the Silver Crown and midget
series last year. He finished 28th in the IRL opener in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will only get better once they get some laps on it,'' said
Leffler, whose right front wheel tapped the wall when he got in the
``gray area'' and spun out in the apex of Turns 1 and 2 on Sunday.
``It's surprising that we're not sliding around.''
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers got up to about 120 mph on the track. They toured
the half-mile circuit in 15 seconds, about 3 seconds faster than
the NASCAR cars did in tire testing two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hunt, USAC's vice president of Western States Operations,
was on hand, watching his son, Tony, test the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 18 (Western States series) races and there will be
seven events here, so I think that gives you an idea of what we
think of the facility,'' Hunt said. ``This place is a palace. It's
like comparing a local saloon against the Hollywood Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Other USAC Western States events will be held in Tucson, Madera,
Shasta, Carson City, Nev., Salt Lake City and in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Tires were a problem during Sunday's session. Every Hoosier tire
tested had blisters within 10 laps on the half-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they call it tire testing,'' said Glenn Howard,
whose So-Cal Performance Inc. will be supplying the Irwindale
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's Super-Modified car came off the track near day's end
with the rear tires at 310 degrees and blistered. It was the
second-hardest compound brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to have to re-group,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoosier representative Rick Gerhardt and Howard say they were
unconcerned that even the stiffest compounds were blistering. Both
say it's just a matter of getting tread down before blistering
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate any problems by the first race,'' Gerhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   It really wasn't very surprising that the 6,500 seats for
opening night sold out in less than 48 hours. But track general
manager Ray Wilkings says those who were shut out appeared
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been coming up to us and saying, `How come I
didn't know?''' he said. ``We've said all along that Feb. 15 was
going to be the (first) day (to buy tickets).''
</P>
<P>
   So, will those who missed out get to see the event on
television?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on it, but there are no guarantees,'' Wilkings
said. ``I've talked to people and it's wait-and-we'll-see.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkings says the track will not buy television time, which
means either an independent producer would have to line up the
advertising time and buy air time, or a network will have to decide
to do a show in its own.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary bleachers will be built in the pit area, but the seats
-- up to 1,000 -- will be available only for pit crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be building permament ones,'' Wilkings said. ``They
will be just to accomodate those in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   A CART championship car made its first visit to Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   Robby Gordon wanted to test the car's gearbox on Sunday, but the
crew had trouble getting the car running, cancelling the impromptu
session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
