<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHOME-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHOME CUSTOMERS FRUSTRATED  &HT;     BY DEBORAH SOLOMON
</HEADLINE>
 HOME _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In towns across the nation, users of AtHome's cable modem
service say they are frequently unable to access the Internet or
get the lightning-fast speeds the company promises.
</P>
<P>
   Customers in cities such as Portland, Ore., Nashville, Tenn.,
and Birmingham, Ala., are complaining of sluggish connections and
the inability to use the Internet service for the simplest tasks,
such as e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated users say they are angry with AtHome for not
delivering what it promised and for lax customer service. Some
users who have called the company with service complaints say
they've been kept on hold for up to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are similar to what AtHome users in Fremont
experienced late last year. Some Fremont users, who get their
AtHome service from TCI Cable, were unable to log on to the Web and
faced molasseslike connection speeds for about three weeks. Answers
about what was causing the problem were in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome eventually fixed the problems in Fremont, blaming them on
human error. The firm said it would not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But the complaints of customers in other cities echo those of
Fremont. Users say they are upset with the lack of answers from
AtHome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely frustrated with AtHome,'' said Dave Roznar, a
TCI AtHome user in Portland. ``Every other day, something else goes
wrong, and nobody in customer support ever seems to know what the
problem is.''
</P>
<P>
   Roznar said his connection is sluggish, and he's often booted
off the Internet when he accesses popular Web sites. The only way
to get back online is to reboot his computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Redwood City company is supposed to give users a super-fast
pipe to the Internet by connecting them via cable TV lines. AtHome
markets its service as being 100 times faster than a traditional
dial-up modem and touts its always-on connection. Unlike telephone
modems, cable modems are always connected to the Internet, and
customers don't need to log on each time they want to surf or check
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome has agreements with 16 cable providers in 24 states to
sell the service. It currently  &LR; has about 331,000 subscribers
nationwide who pay between $40 and $45 per month.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome officials denied there is any widespread problem but said
some users may experience glitches as the company rolls out its
service and deals with rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get more and more subscribers out there, there are going
to be people who have a problem in one area or another,'' said Dave
Bagshaw, senior vice president of AtHome Network. ``We're going
through a learning curve every single day. This is the first time
that this kind of networking technology is being delivered to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   AtHome points to a recent contract with AT&AMP;T as proof that the
company is trying to help users. That contract is intended to
increase the capacity of AtHome's network to accommodate more than
5 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshaw said the company aims to answer 75 percent of customer
calls within four to five minutes and tries to resolve every
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Customers first call their cable provider for support, then are
routed to AtHome if the cable company can't solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   TCI, which handles all AtHome accounts in the Bay Area and has
about 40,000 AtHome users nationwide, admits some customers have
had problems with the service and with contacting technical
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it's such a dynamic and sophisticated product there are
a lot of areas that customers have questions on,'' said Katina
Vlahadamis of TCI. To address the situation, TCI plans to add an
additional 90 people to its customer support unit for a total of
320 representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Customers say that when the service works, AtHome is great at
providing instant access to the Net and ending the World Wide Wait,
but many said that doesn't happen often enough and claim the
company treats its customers like guinea pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Barrett, an AtHome user in New Canaan, Conn., said she's
been unable to get onto the Internet through AtHome since she got
the service four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I can't get on at all and sometimes it's really
slow,'' Barrett said. ``I told AtHome many times that I was ready
to go back to my old ISP because, while the speeds weren't as fast,
the service was reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to AtHome, Scott Lewis of Birmingham vented his
frustration at not being able to get the promised speeds. Lewis
said his calls and e-mails to TCI AtHome have gone unanswered and
he has been unable to get any response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you had a very good product but now (I) see that it
is all hype,'' Lewis wrote. ``I really want to know when I can
expect, if ever, this service to be performing properly again.''
</P>
<P>
   Vlahadamis said customers such as Lewis should see a more
responsive AtHome with the additional TCI customer service reps.
She said the company is also reopening an online support center to
help answer customer questions.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for AtHome's TCI customers, but for those who
get their AtHome product through a different cable provider, TCI's
solution is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined the service just over three weeks ago, and in that
three weeks, I have placed more than nine calls to service,'' Dave
Burne, an AtHome user in Canada, said in an e-mail. Burne, who gets
his AtHome service through Rogers Cable, said it took five phone
calls before the company would admit there was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``AtHome can't even seem to resolve one person's difficulties.
Kinda sounds like AOL a few years back. Maybe someone should file a
class-action lawsuit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
