<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASPRICES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer may bring higher gas prices, experts say
 &HT;    WITH GRAPHIC
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ We're living in the good ol' days when
it comes to gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   They fell to their lowest point in 50 years this month,
according to the often-cited Lundberg Survey and historical
government data. The survey, which checks 10,000 gas stations
nationwide, found the average price for all grades of fuel was 99.8
cents a gallon in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   But enjoy it while it lasts. Experts say prices at the pump will
soon rise, spurred by summer travel, air conditioners and a
decrease in production by oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   When adjusted for inflation, today's prices are the lowest
motorists have been paying for gas since the government began
recording prices in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a gallon of gas in 1949 _ about 27 cents _ equals
$1.86 in 1999 dollars, according to the U.S. Energy Information
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Florida mirror the national trend. AAA Auto Club South
reported that the state's average price for self-serve regular
unleaded gas was 96.8 cents per gallon this month.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, gas prices hit their peak in 1981, when a gallon
cost $1.37 _ or $2.48 in 1999 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Even a small change can make a big difference for some drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practically live in our vehicles,'' said Nancy Smoot of
Delray Beach as she pumped gas into her large white van at a local
Shell station. ``Lower gas prices are great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This car has a 40-gallon tank, so it's not cheap to fill,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many energy analysts believe that after several years of
plunging, gas prices have reached the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Large fuel reserves, continued production by oil companies and
low demand due to a mild winter have kept prices down, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   When temperatures start rising, air conditioners will begin
working around the clock, meaning power plants will burn more fuel.
That, combined with a traditional increase in auto travel during
the summer, will push up demand, said Yoli Buss of AAA Auto Club
South.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the cheap gas is causing big losses for oil
companies, which are now cutting back on production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are delaying and cutting back on their big capital
projects, and many are cutting down on employment,'' said Don
Norman, research manager for the Washington, D.C.-based American
Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   So prices should level out over the next few months, and begin
to slowly rise again during the summer, said Buss.
</P>
<P>
   ``But keep in mind, a year ago they said prices would rise,''
she said. ``So no one really knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
