<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER KILLER GETS DEATH PENALTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER _ A predominantly white jury sentenced John William
``Bill'' King to death Thursday for chaining a disabled black man
to a pickup and dragging him to his death in the Texas Piney Woods
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating three hours, the jury returned its verdict,
making the 24-year-old white supremacist the only white man in
modern times sent to Texas' death row for killing a black.
</P>
<P>
   The family of King's victim, 49-year-old James Byrd Jr., gasped
as the verdict was read in a packed courtroom, and several burst
into tears. They then approached the railing to hug and thank each
of the white prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no remorse, even in the face of death,'' said Byrd's
sister, Mary Verrett. ``Justice would not have been served if he
could still spread his hate to other young people. It's like
gangrene. It spreads, and it is deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sister, Clara Taylor, said her family does not advocate
the death penalty, but believed the evidence against King was
overwhelming and the sentence just. She described her parents as
relieved, and said her father smiled when the verdict was read.
``If you know my dad, that's rare,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   King, whose body is covered in racist and satanic tattoos,
including one depicting the lynching of a black man, had sat
stone-faced throughout two weeks of testimony and showed no emotion
to the verdict. Outside the courthouse, when asked if he had
anything to say to the Byrd family, he uttered a vulgar insult
before being pushed into a waiting car that was to take him to a
Huntsville prison.
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald King, who attended the trial every day and
had pleaded with the jury to spare his son's life, left the
courtroom because of ill health before the sentence was returned.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, he visited briefly with his son and hugged him.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King later released a typed statement through a friend,
asking people to pray for the Byrd family and for the jurors, whom
he said had shouldered ``a horrible burden.'' He also requested
prayers for his son ``for redemption and healing, even on death
row.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger King released a handwritten statement through his
attorney: ``Though I remain adamant about my innocence, it's been
obvious from the beginning that this community would get what they
desire; so I'll close with the words of Francis Yockey. `The
promise of success is with the man who is determined to die proudly
when it is no longer possible to live proudly.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yockey, who died in 1960, was an author of Nazi doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of 11 whites and one African-American, whom they
elected foreman, had convicted Bill King of capital murder after
deliberating only 2{ hours on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, shortly before 10 a.m., they returned to the jury
room to decide his punishment. Twenty minutes later, they sent out
two notes, asking to see a knife and a hangman's noose King had
fashioned in his cell at the Jasper County Jail while awaiting
trial. They also requested letters King had written to young girls
in Jasper while he was imprisoned for burglary in 1995-97, and a
jailhouse note that he wrote to a co-defendant shortly after their
arrests last June. That note, intercepted by jailers, was a virtual
confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked for redeeming factors,'' said juror Karen
``Lequeta'' Flowers. ``Then we read those letters and they weren't
there.''
</P>
<P>
   On the courthouse square outside, as word of the jury's decision
filtered through the crowd, Sheriff's Sgt. James Carter, an
African-American, was approached by five of his white colleagues,
who one-by-one embraced the black officer in a show of solidarity.
Several times, Carter removed his glasses and wiped his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As burly officers blocked the sidewalk, guards escorted a pale
but smirking King from the courthouse. He was greeted by a chorus
of taunts and demands that he address local residents. King
remained silent until he uttered the vulgarity directed to the Byrd
family.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later he was in Huntsville at the James Byrd
Diagnostic Unit, named for a deceased prison warden unrelated to
his victim of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   King, an ex-con accused of masterminding Byrd's gruesome killing
to publicize a hate group he was trying to start in the Jasper
area, was the first of three white men to be tried for Byrd's June
7 kidnapping and killing. Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31, and
Shawn Allen Berry, 24, will be tried later.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Thursday, prosecutor Pat Hardy told jurors
if they gave King a life prison sentence instead of death by
injection they could put someone else at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give him life, you give him at least 40 years to catch
a black guard, a black nurse, a black doctor, a Jewish guard, a
Jewish nurse, a Jewish doctor,'' he said. ``You're giving him that
long to take another life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he admired the Byrd family for its ability to control
its anger, saying that Byrd's 20-year-old son Ross would probably
like to jump over the courtroom rail and ``stick his fist into the
chest of John William King and rip out his Satanic heart.'' Then he
asked the jury, ``Didn't you, for a second, feel the same way?''
</P>
<P>
   King's court-appointed defense lawyer, Brack Jones Jr., urged
the jury to send King back to the penitentiary, where he learned
his racist ways, and let them deal with him. And he pleaded with
the jury to consider King's father, who suffers from debilitating
emphysema and other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your vote is not going to bring Mr. Byrd back. I wish it
could,'' Jones said. ``Your vote is not going to change the stigma
on this community, but I do think your vote could save two lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray countered that
King would kill again. ``And I don't care if he's 64 years old when
he does it,'' he said, referring to the fact that a life sentence
would mean King would be eligible for parole in 40 years. ``The
option is, do you take this man's life, or do you let him kill
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Jones later said that a life prison sentence in
a 10-by-10 foot cell with only a guard for companionship could have
been worse for his client than death. ``The penitentiary is a bad,
bad place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same news conference, defense lawyer C. Haden ``Sonny''
Cribbs Jr., who earlier had pleaded with the jury, ``please don't
kill this young man,'' was asked whether King had ever expressed
remorse for his crimes. After a long, thoughtful pause, an
exhausted Cribbs sighed and answered, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   What King did display, though, was a growing anger at his fate,
said Sheriff Billy Rowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality hit him in the last 24 to 36 hours,'' the sheriff
said, adding that on the eve of his sentencing, King had been put
under a closer watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bowed up about that, cussing, raising Cain, kicking doors,
acting the fool,'' he said. ``He was still bowed up this morning _
obviously mad, didn't sleep, very withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   After court adjourned for the day, two jurors, including the
foreman, Joe Collins, who was an 8th-grade classmate of King's,
said jurors had been struck by the brutality of King's crime. Many
had trouble dealing with color photographs of Byrd's body, which
had been ground to the bone as he tried to keep his head up while
being dragged more than two miles.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's agony finally ended when he slammed into a culvert and
was decapitated. His killers left the rest of his corpse outside a
black cemetery east of Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be tortured like that,'' Collins said. ``That's
not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, the other jury spokeswoman, said the panel had not been
swayed by King's tattoos, which she described as offensive, but not
illegal. She also said the jury had not intended to send a
``message'' by choosing Collins, the only black member, as foreman.
She said he was the only one to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was just one of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, outside on the courthouse square, white and black
Jasper residents discussed the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sorry it's lethal injection,'' said B.W. Sanderson, a
white lifelong resident. ``It should be the electric chair and they
should turn up the power volt by volt. It should be little bit by
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Singletary, a middle-aged white woman, agreed the sentence
was appropriate. ``You take a life, you need to give a life,'' she
said. ``That's God's word.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Glenn, an African-American, also welcomed the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hadn't sentenced them to death,'' she said in a
subdued voice, ``he would have festered like a sore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that he's a white man. He was a person,'' she
said. ``He did what he set out to do, and he was ready to die for
what he had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accomplished his goal _ that's the sad thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
