u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-FAMILIES-1STLE     02-25 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-FAMILIES-1STLEDEWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER-FAMILIES-1STLEDEWRITETHRU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: Changes copyright to 1999 
 
`WE'RE ALL VICTIMS': TWO FAMILIES IN PAIN &HT;     
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   JASPER _ When John William ``Bill'' King dragged James Byrd Jr.
down Huff Creek Road last summer, he did much more than just kill a
defenseless black man more than twice his age. He destroyed two
families _ Byrd's and his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of victims,'' said Byrd's sister Clara Taylor.
``We're all victims.''
</P>
<P>
   During two weeks of sometimes gruesome testimony, a dozen or so
members of Byrd's family sat at the front of one side of the
courtroom while King's frail father, Ronald King, sat on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   The elder King, 68 and suffering from emphysema, usually sat in
his wheelchair, breathing oxygen through a tube from a container he
kept between his legs.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't there when the jury delivered the death verdict
Thursday. As the jury deliberated, he had a final visit with his
son and hugged him for what might be the last time. Prisoners on
Texas' death row aren't allowed contact visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we could always do, hug,'' Ronald King said
much earlier. ``Always hug your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at her son's grave on a shaded hillside in the Jasper
City Cemetery, Stella Byrd said before the trial started that she
wished she could hug her son again. ``Whenever I want to see him, I
have to come out here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was one member of her family who chose not to come to court
to hear the horrible testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King quickly condemned Byrd's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts me deeply to know that a boy I raised and considered
to be the most loved boy I know could find it in himself to take a
life,'' he said in a statement released a few days after the murder
last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he didn't do it, and I have to stick by my boy,''
he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King said Jasper shouldn't be blamed for James Byrd's
murder. ``This isn't a racist town,'' he said. ``It just isn't that
kind of town.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that shortly after he moved to Jasper 22 years ago,
he was driving home after working a late shift at a sawmill when a
police car stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if I'd done anything wrong, and he said he had
seen my out-of-state license plates and wondered what I was doing
in a residential area at that time of the morning. That told me
that this was a community where the law enforcement looked out
after things. They were keeping us safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The police officer who stopped him was black, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Bill King got his deadly racism, it clearly wasn't from
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``King's father is the nicest person in the world,'' said Deann
Armstrong, a nurse's aide whose fourth anniversary celebration Byrd
attended just before he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked at the hospital for four years, and he would come in
for treatment,'' she said. ``That hospital was pretty ugly _ lots
of people would say `nigger this, girl that.' But if you'd take Mr.
King a glass of water, he would always thank you. He never acted
like he was better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   After the murder, it was religious faith that helped the two
families with their grief. James Byrd Sr. and his wife had long
been active in Greater New Bethel Baptist Church, where the senior
Byrd is a deacon. But just going to church wasn't enough, his
children said. ``You have to have it in your heart,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King is a lifelong Baptist but said he hadn't been active
in church. He had participated in some social activities at St.
Michael's Catholic Church. The Rev. Ron Foshage, pastor of the
little church and three other East Texas parishes, said he called
King and offered to be his spiritual adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless that man,'' King said. ``I couldn't get through this
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   King asked the priest to talk to his son, who had announced in
prison that he had changed his religion to Odinism, based on Norse
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill King refused to talk to the priest. ``I was relieved,''
Foshage said. ``I really didn't know what to say to him.''
</P>
<P>
   While waiting to hear the jury sentence him to death, the
younger King hugged the priest and thanked him for taking care of
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Overcome with emotion, the elder King had to leave the
courthouse before the jury's pronouncement. The priest was left to
read his statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to pray for healing and reconciliation,'' he read.
``Please pray for the Byrd family, who have endured unimaginable
pain and loss. Please pray for these jurors, who have shouldered a
horrible burden. Please pray for our town of Jasper, a community
that remains strong though scarred by this unspeakable act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also ask for prayers for my family, and for my son, Bill,
for redemption and healing even on death row.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the elder King said in his statement that he hopes some
good can come from the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we all can find meaning from this tragedy, from
the needless and senseless death of James Byrd Jr. We all are human
beings, black and white. We're all children of God. We must learn
to love one another and never to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's siblings said hate was something that was never brought
into their home as children.
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Sr., who turned 74 the day jury selection began in
King's trial, said he thought race relations had improved in Jasper
over the decades. He remembered as a boy sometimes being taunted by
white boys while walking to school, ``and sometimes we'd want to
fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt empathy for Ronald King. ``I had wanted to talk
to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The night after the jury found Bill King guilty the elder King
called the Byrds to tell them he was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he did,'' James Byrd Sr. said, adding that the two
fathers talked for 15 minutes and he told King that he too was
sorry for his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Mullins, James Byrd Jr.'s daughter, hugged the elder King
the next afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his (Bill King's) son I feel sorry for,'' she said.
``What will it be like for him growing up?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Verrett, another of Byrd's six sisters, said she can relate
to Ronald King's sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand his grief because our parents suffered like
grief. But we also want him to know it was his son who made this
choice, who brought pain upon the father. It was not the criminal
justice system. It was not the Byrd family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Byrd family has said it intends to set up a foundation
funded by money donated since the murder. That foundation will
operate some sort of educational program to fight racism, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the murder, the town of Jasper has started a multifaceted
task force to look at racial issues in all aspects of the town's
life. Foshage is a member of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   His particular group has drawn up three goals, he said. One was
to hold a community prayer vigil. There have already been two, and
another is scheduled for March 8. Another was to dismantle an
ancient wrought iron fence that once divided the white and black
parts of the city cemetery. That has been done.
</P>
<P>
   The third might be much tougher, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stop using the terms `black community' and `white
community,' '' he said. ``We want to end that distinction. We want
us all to think of ourselves as `we.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Byrd's
murder and its aftermath have caused both black and white leaders
to reconsider their beliefs. When Ku Klux Klan and armed members of
the New Black Panther Party arrived, leaders on both sides were
frightened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at those groups and realized that they had a whole
lot more in common with each other than they did with those
extremist groups,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ronald King and the family of James Byrd Jr. had a
lot more in common than they had differences. They were both
grieving the loss of a son.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
