<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9822 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LAD     02-25 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCH PLAY A VOLATILE EXPERIMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That strange thing going on this week down at the
posh but time-worn La Costa Resort and Spa is golf's version of
Russian Roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday we'll find out if the game does catch a bullet as
the first Match Play Championship, part of the new rota designed to
showcase Planet Earth's best golfers, draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   So far the golf has been exciting. The problem, though, is that
the two who survive for Sunday's 36-hole final may be guys we've
never heard of from places we cannot pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't feature the world's best (Tiger Woods)
against No.2 (David Duval), which is always the hope in these kinds
of things. Duval got a ticket out of town on Thursday courtesy of a
2 and 1 loss to Bill Glasson, ranked 34th.
</P>
<P>
   The stoic Duval had lots of company as famous names like Tom
Watson, Mark O'Meara, Greg Norman, Justin Leonard, Nick Faldo and
Colin Montgomerie, always a crowd favorite, all made quick exits.
</P>
<P>
   And they had little to say as they left.
</P>
<P>
   When play starts today, only three players in the top 20 of the
world ranking will tee it up. Fortunately, Woods will be among
them. So will Fred Couples (13) and Phil Mickelson (12).
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid I can't two-putt from 30 feet,'' Couples said
Thursday. ``This is nerve-wracking stuff. I don't even know who I
play tomorrow, but this stuff makes me so nervous I will be choking
like a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those left from the bottom of what is proving to be a very
talented group are Stewart Cink (48), Andrew Magee (50), Loren
Roberts (39), Shigeki Maruyama (42), Steve Pate (61), Eduardo
Romero, Steve Jones (51) and Patrik Sjoland (54).
</P>
<P>
   And to some of the players and spectators, the format is as
foreign as the field. Match play, where the winner is the one
winning the most holes, not the one with the fewest swipes at the
ball, is usually reserved for big amateur events and team
competitions like the Ryder and Presidents cups.
</P>
<P>
   There's no Friday on which to recover from a bad round on
Thursday. Those players that had bad rounds, bounces or luck are
all gone now.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say match play is bad. Lots of people, including
myself, like it. Especially in this format, where the brackets are
set up like the first round of the NCAA basketball championships.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference, though.
</P>
<P>
   Top to bottom, these were the 64 best players in the world.
There is no team nicknamed the Silverswords served up to a Duke or
Kentucky in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   No one thought that the lowest-ranked player in the field,
Faldo, was overmatched in his first-round match with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   And there is none of this ``I'm just going to go out and play
the course and see what happens'' stuff.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are at each other's throats as soon as the starter
says ``play away gentlemen'' or however he gets them going.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Stadler, who dispatched Montgomerie on Wednesday, refused
to concede a short putt during their match, drawing a sharp look
from the Scotsman.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe some bad blood still lingered from the last two Ryder
Cup matches.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine players on Europe's winning team at Valderrama, only
Bernhard Langer and Jose Maria Olazabal remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got beat,'' Stadler told the Associated Press of the
rest. ``And they've got a long flight home.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: While the Match Play Championship looks like it will
flourish and become a really big deal, a couple of other
tournaments are suffering at its expense.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the Tucson Open, being played this weekend at the
Omni Tucson National Resort. Duval is the defending champion, but
he isn't defending. Seventeen others who played Tucson last year
aslo skipped this year to play at La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   So after the first day's play, the well-known R.W. Eaks was the
leader, shooting an 8-under-par 64. In hot pursuit were Tom
Scherrer, Tommy Tolles, Tim Herron, Jerry Kelly, Doug Dunakey,
Steve Flesch, Dennis Paulson, Robert Allenby and Gabriel
Hjertstedt.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday and Sunday television coverage is being provided by
CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Then, next week is the Doral tournament that traditionally
signaled the start of the Real Season, as that was the first event
for the European players.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Lots of the top 64 are taking a pass this year to
recover from the pressure of preparing for and playing in the Match
Play Championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even the LPGA Tour is feeling the cold shoulder. Many of that
tour's top players decided to skip this weekend's Australian Ladies
Masters because of the travel and expense involved.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes 1995 champion and world No.1 Annika Sorenstam
of Sweden, South Korean star Se Ri Pak, Meg Mallon, Beth Daniel,
Betsy King, Helen Alfredsson and Liselotte Neumann. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
