A9845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-BLITZER-NYT &LR;      02-25 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLITZER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES BLITZER, FOUNDER OF WOODROW WILSON CENTER, DIES AT 71  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Blitzer, a founder and director emeritus of the Woodrow
Wilson International Center for Scholars in Washington and a past
president of Phi Beta Kappa, died on Friday at his home in
Washington. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pulmonary disease, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer founded the Woodrow Wilson center in 1971 with Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., as an affiliate of the Smithsonian
Institution dedicated to advanced academic research in
international relations and political and social studies. He served
as its third director, from 1988 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer prepared the center for its recent move to larger
quarters in the Ronald Reagan Building on Pennsylvania Avenue,
where it serves about three dozen scholars on annual fellowships
with still others who visit to do research. After his retirement
and election to director emeritus, he was succeeded by former Rep.
Lee H. Hamilton, Democrat of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Blitzer, a native New Yorker, graduated from Williams
College in 1927 and earned a master's degree. in 1949 and a
doctorate in 1952 at Harvard University. He began his academic
career as a political science instructor at Yale University and in
the early 1960s worked as executive associate at the American
Council of Learned Societies in New York.
</P>
<P>
   His association with the Smithsonian began in 1965, when he
joined the staff as director of education. He served as assistant
secretary for history and art from 1968 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   At Phi Beta Kappa, he held several official positions, beginning
in 1979. He was a former member of the academic honor society's
senate and served as vice president and then president from 1991 to
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer was also a longtime member and recent chairman of the
Indo-United States Sub-Commission on Education and Culture and
served on the United States-New Zealand Council, among other
international affiliations. He was a past trustee of Smith College
and in recent years served as chairman of a publications
subcommittee at the Holocaust Memorial Museum.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a brother, Dr. John R. Blitzer, of Bradford,
N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
