<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPED BY BLOCKBUSTER UNIT, VIACOM POSTS SOLID QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viacom Inc. reported a strong fourth quarter Thursday, as
earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization rose
24 percent, to $502.4 million, from $406.1 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter, ended Dec. 31, rose 15 percent, to $3.34
billion, from $2.9 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons between the two quarters were difficult to make,
however, since each included a significant number of one-time
charges and gains.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent quarter, for example, included a $3.4 million
gain related to the $4.6 billion sale of Simon &AMP; Shuster in
November to Pearson PLC, and represents the difference between the
proceeds and the book value. Last quarter also included a loss of
$74.7 million for early redemption of debt, and a $30 million gain
related to the redemption of preferred stock at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 quarter included a $1.1 billion gain from the sale of
Viacom's half-interest in USA Networks to Seagram Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hatch, an analyst with Cowen &AMP; Co., said that results at
Viacom's Blockbuster unit were very strong; the chain of video
rental stores saw a 15 percent increase in same-store sales.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Hatch said, the vibrancy of Viacom's cable network
brands was evident. The success of ``The Rugrats Movie'' also
helped the entertainment division.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said Thursday that it would switch its listing to the New
York Stock Exchange from the American Stock Exchange, where it had
been one of the most widely traded stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom also said it planned a 2-for-1 stock split. The split,
which is to be in the form of a dividend, is scheduled for March
31.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said that its cable networks _ MTV, Nickelodeon/Nick at
Nite and VH1 _posted an 18 percent increase in cash flow to $291.7
million, from $246.7 million, as advertising revenue rose.
</P>
<P>
   Profit at the entertainment division jumped 21 percent, to $98.5
million, fueled by the success of ``Rugrats'' domestically and
``The Truman Story'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Blockbuster rose 28 percent, to $127.6 million, which
makes it increasingly likely that Sumner Redstone, the chairman of
Viacom, will proceed with a two-step plan to spin off 20 percent of
the company to the public and sell the balance later.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were particularly pleased with Blockbuster's
performance since the future of the home video business seemed
threatened by the advent of pay-per-view and other technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster's earnings improved even as the company added 146
new video stores in the third quarter, ending the year with 6,379
stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
