A9863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON-RETIRES-NY     02-25 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-RETIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON BIDS FAREWELL TO HOUSE THAT HE MIGHT HAVE LED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thursday was the last working day for Rep. Robert
L. Livingston, the almost-speaker of the House, who plans to go
into business as a lobbyist here starting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a short farewell address on the House floor, Livingston
referred obliquely to ``a few failures'' and ``a few moments of
heartache'' in the institution he had hoped to lead. Without naming
names, he suggested that some of his colleagues had been less than
``statesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tolerance is a necessity,'' he said. ``And compromise is the
glue that renders democracy possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, after admitting to having had extramarital
affairs, Livingston renounced the speakership, to which he had been
designated, just before the House began voting to impeach President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, R-La., also said at the time that he would leave the
House, to which he was first elected in 1977, in six months. But he
pushed up his official retirement to Feb. 28 to allow for an
earlier special election in the state's First Congressional
District.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, 56, the chairman of the Appropriations Committee for
four years, can now start to make some serious money, a goal that
led him to consider quitting Congress a year ago, until he decided
to stay and run for speaker. As a representative, Livingston made
more than $136,000.
</P>
<P>
   He and his long-time chief of staff, Allen Miller, are starting
a lobbying firm called the Livingston Group. It is affiliated with
the New Orleans firm of Jones, Walker, Waechter, Poitevent, Carrere
&AMP; Denegre, which also has offices in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a former member of Congress, Livingston is barred from
lobbying directly on Capitol Hill for one year, but can offer
advice and guidance to clients with business there.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of the committee that oversees federal spending,
and as the onetime speaker-designate, Livingston is highly familiar
with the levers of power in Congress. There is no doubt of his
access. On the House floor Thursday, Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., whom
Livingston anointed to succeed him as chairman of the
Appropriations Committee, said he hoped Livingston would ``feel
free to stay in touch with this member.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston follows several other retiring Republicans into the
ranks of lobbyists. Former Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, of Glens
Falls, N.Y., has opened his own firm, which will be affiliated with
a lobbying shop headed by former Sen. Paul Laxalt of Nevada. Former
Rep. Bill Paxon of Buffalo, has joined Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP;
Feld.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the House floor Thursday, Livingston told reporters:
``I feel lighter. I don't have to worry about all the problems, all
over the world, all the time. And I just have to worry about the
next paycheck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
