<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI VS. SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC; 
ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The review is in:
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a unique combination of a lot of size and quickness,''
Michael Olowokandi said. ``He's quick, big and strong. I really
can't wait to get it out of the way. If he's gonna beat me down,
he's gonna beat me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like Olowokandi, the Clippers' rookie center, is filing a
scouting report on Godzilla. But this was worse. He was calling
roll on the list of woe presented by Thursday's individual
challenge ... Laker center Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first skirmish between O'Neal, the NBA first draft
pick in 1992, and Olowokandi, who achieved that distinction last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a handful,'' the 7-foot, 270-pound Olowokandi said of
O'Neal, who checks in at an inch taller and 60 pounds - give or
take a missing steer - heavier. ``Our entire defensive philosophy
has changed because of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi's philosophy? The first time, it's not personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not a personal battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thinking. O'Neal could finish the season as the league's
top scorer. Olowokandi, now in just his fourth season of organized
basketball, is only hoping the officials start giving him the same
latitude in trotting out his entire offensive repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the same moves they get me for are working for him,''
Olowokandi said. ``Hopefully, they'll start working for me.
</P>
<P>
   subhead Board meeting scheduled
</P>
<P>
   Clippers power forward Maurice Taylor completed Thursday's
pre-game maneuvers with this prediction: ``I feel a monster game
coming on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed Taylor was referring to himself as the monster.
He certainly was that in the team's first game at The Pond this
season, a double-overtime loss to Vancouver last last week. Taylor
scored 21 points and grabbed 20 rebounds in that one.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, he figures to go at it with the newest Laker,
rebounding mercenary Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as just another game,'' Taylor said of matching
rebounding wits with Rodman. ``Sure, I want to do well against him,
but I want to do well against everybody. I'm really not having any
consistency rebounding.
</P>
</TEXT>
