<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELECOM ITALIA SAYS NEW BID FROM OLIVETTI IS STILL FLAWED
</P>
<P>
   The board of Telecom Italia has called the revised $60 billion
unsolicited takeover offer from rival Olivetti seriously flawed and
decided to study how to integrate its fixed-line operations with
the mobile phone unit Telecom Italia Mobile, in which it holds a 60
percent stake. Such a move would increase Telecom Italia's net
worth and raise the price Olivetti would have to pay by several
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti first proposed buying Telecom Italia over the weekend
with a $60 billion package of cash and securities that marked one
of the biggest hostile takeover attempts of any company. Italian
stock market regulators ruled the bid invalid earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD HEALTH HAS A SMALLER LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans said that its fourth-quarter loss narrowed
as the company worked to turn around its finances. The health
maintenance organization reported a loss of $18.8 million, or 23
cents a share, while analysts had expected a loss of 78 cents.
Shares of Oxford fell $1.3125, to $18.375.
</P>
<P>
   PENNEY PROFIT NEARLY FLAT; GAP UP
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney reported disappointing earnings as it continued to
struggle against competition from cheaper discount chains and
trendier retailers like the Gap, which beat expectations with its
latest quarterly report.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL EARNINGS MORE THAN DOUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Novell reported that its first-quarter profit more than doubled
compared with year-earlier figures. The company cited the improved
performance to strong sales of products using its Directory
technology, which helps find multiple users across a network.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, the World Wide Web gateway that is being bought by USA
Networks, reported that it lost $9.3 million partly because of
costs of its acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit, the maker of personal-finance software, reported
better-than-expected fiscal second-quarter earnings, buoyed by
sales of its Turbo Tax tax-preparation software.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER PROFITS RISE 28%
</P>
<P>
   Reporting its financial results as a combined company for the
first time, DaimlerChrysler said that 1998 earnings rose 28 percent
on the strength of improved sales of vehicles and Airbus planes.
Results from the world's fourth-largest car maker and Europe's
biggest industrial company were at the low end of financial
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE POSES QUESTIONS TO MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson posed several pointed questions to
one of the last witnesses testifying for Microsoft at its antitrust
trial. The questions, which cut to the core of the company's case,
concerned why Microsoft had chosen to combine the company's Web
browser with its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ESPRIT ATTEMPTS A SALES COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   An advertising and marketing effort is seeking to revive the
Esprit lines of sportswear, footwear and accessories, which were
popular in the 1980s. The would-be comeback is indicative of
ambitious plans by marketers to capitalize on strong consumer
demand for name-brand products.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM EARNINGS UP 24% IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Viacom reported a strong fourth quarter as earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization rose 24 percent, to
$502.4 million. The publishing and entertainment company also plans
to move to the New York Stock Exchange from the American Stock
Exchange in April.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE LINE FACES DUMPING CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Los Angeles has indicted Royal Caribbean
Cruises on charges of making false statements to the Coast Guard
about oily waste discharges in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
