u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-EARNI     02-25 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-EARNINGS-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FIRST COMBINED RESULTS, DAIMLERCHRYSLER PROFIT RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER and STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reporting its financial results as a combined company for the
first time, DaimlerChrysler AG said Thursday that its 1998 earnings
rose 28 percent on the strength of improved sales of vehicles and
Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures from DaimlerChrysler, the world's fourth-largest
automaker and Europe's biggest industrial company, were at the low
end of financial analysts' expectations, and contributed to a 5
percent drop in the company's share price. DaimlerChrysler closed
at $95.8125 on the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday, down
$5.125.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the earnings also coincided with increased
speculation that the company was nearing an agreement to buy a
significant part of the ailing Nissan Motor Co. of Japan. Shares of
Nissan surged nearly 6 percent on heavy trading in Tokyo on
Thursday on investor expectations that a deal was close.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time merger costs, DaimlerChrysler's earnings rose
to 5.2 billion euros ($5.72 billion) or 5.6 euros a share, compared
with the equivalent of 4.06 billion euros, or 4.28 a share, in
1997. (The euro came into being in January 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   Sales at DaimlerChrysler, which is based in both Stuttgart,
Germany, and Auburn Hills, Mich., rose 12 percent, to 131.8 billion
euros, or $145 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the gain came on improved sales of both Chrysler and
Mercedes-Benz cars and light trucks in the United States. The
results also reflected increased aircraft sales in 1998 by Airbus
Industrie, the four-nation European consortium in which
DaimlerChrysler holds a 37.9 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 results were calculated on the assumption that
Daimler-Benz and Chrysler were one company at the time.
DaimlerChrysler intends to begin reporting quarterly results after
the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler was formed in November when Daimler-Benz
completed its takeover of Chrysler in the biggest foreign
acquisition of an American industrial company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The combination appears to have started a consolidation in the
global automotive industry, with Ford Motor Co. agreeing in January
to buy the car business of Volvo of Sweden for $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There have been growing expectations that Nissan, Japan's No. 2
automaker and sixth largest over all, would sell at least part of
itself to a foreign automaker because it is $20 billion in debt and
its sales have weakened in Japan and the United States. Nissan
president Yoshikazu Hanawa has made no secret of his effort to sell
the company _ which is highly unusual in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Most frequently mentioned as a possible buyer is
DaimlerChrysler, particularly since its two chairmen, Juergen
Schrempp and Robert Eaton, met with Hanawa a month ago. Speculation
about a possible deal intensified Wednesday when the Kyodo news
agency of Japan said the two sides were close to an agreement that
would give DaimlerChrysler a 33.4 percent stake, although they
denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's attraction for DaimlerChrysler is clear, as are the
risks associated with any deal. DaimlerChrysler's sales have been
running so strong that it is critically short of factory capacity.
Nissan's plants in Europe and North America have not been running
full time because of slow sales. Its complex in Smyrna, Tenn., has
repeatedly been rated the most efficient assembly plant in the
United States by Harbour &AMP; Associates, a manufacturing-
productivity consultant. Nissan's lineup of cars is also similar to
the Chrysler lineup, so a merger could result in considerable
savings by combining models.
</P>
<P>
   But the risks are huge. The biggest involves Nissan's heavy
debt, which has scared off other potential bidders. DaimlerChrysler
is also struggling to bring American managers from Chrysler into
its German hierarchy, and the addition of a Japanese automaker to
the group could cause further cultural difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo on Thursday, large numbers of reporters and camera men
gathered outside Nissan's headquarters in the Ginza district, only
to be disappointed as the day dragged on and the company stood by
its denial of a deal with DaimlerChrysler. Securities analysts who
were calling clients to advise them that the deal was all but done
admitted when pushed that they were betting the Kyodo report was
partly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   There was at least circumstantial evidence that the two
companies are in talks: A group of five or six German-speaking men
headed out of Nissan headquarters late Thursday in the company of a
Japanese man.
</P>
<P>
   People in the auto industry have speculated that DaimlerChrysler
may try to insulate itself from Nissan's debt troubles by buying
less than half the company, giving it at least one Nissan board
seat and veto power. But that could still leave management in the
hands of the same men who have managed the company into its current
perilous state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
