<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIXON-TAPES-1STLD-WRI     02-25 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-TAPES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWLY RELEASED TAPES FEATURE DARK BRAINSTORMING BY NIXON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs lede to change order of references to Kennedy and embassy
break-ins; fixes garble in 2nd graf; also changes head) 
By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newly released transcripts of secretly recorded
White House tapes show President Richard M. Nixon musing about
break-ins at foreign embassies, brainstorming about blaming
President John F. Kennedy for the murder of South Vietnam's leader,
and saying he and his aides would have been ``out of our minds''
not to spy on left-wing Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government murdered him,'' Nixon said of South Vietnamese
President Ngo Dihn Diem, whose assassination in November 1963
preceded Kennedy's by three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it and you know it, too,'' Nixon told his press
secretary in May 1973. But while one of Nixon's aides fabricated
evidence implicating Kennedy in the killing, there is no known
record of a presidential assassination order, although Kennedy
regretted giving tacit American approval to the coup that led to
Diem's death.
</P>
<P>
   In the transcripts, Nixon twice discusses authorizing break-ins
at foreign embassies. In May 1973, he told his military aide, Gen.
Alexander M. Haig, ``There are times, you know, when, good God, I'd
authorize any means to achieve a goal abroad'' _ including ``the
breaking-in of embassies and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   That same month, he told his legal aide, J. Fred Buzhardt,
``When we get down, for example, to the break-in, the Chilean
Embassy _ that thing was a part of the burglars' plan, as a cover .
. . a CIA cover.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcript appears to refer to a break-in at the Chilean
Embassy in Washington by Nixon's secret White House team, known as
the plumbers. That team conducted the June 1972 burglary at
Democratic Party offices in the Watergate complex, which led to
Nixon's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   A break-in at the Chilean Embassy in Washington on May 13, 1972,
was reported to Washington police. No link was made to the White
House at the time, and none has been made since.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a rumor that the plumbers hit the Chilean
Embassy,'' John Dean, Nixon's White House counsel during the
Watergate affair, said in an interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said one of the plumbers, James W. McCord Jr., a former CIA
officer, was thought to have used his knowledge of American
espionage against the Chilean Embassy as a bargaining chip after
his conviction for the Watergate break-in. McCord, now 78, has
rarely spoken about Watergate and could not be reached on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy was a likely target for American intelligence
eavesdropping, since the CIA had been ordered by Nixon to help
destabilize the government of Salvador Allende Gossens, the freely
elected Marxist president of Chile, who fell in a coup led by Gen.
Augusto Pinochet in September 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The 124 transcripts made public on Thursday, some of them
fragments of a sentence, some several pages long, had been kept
secret on national security grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, recorded on a White House system installed by Nixon,
were formally released by the National Archives on Thursday.
Transcripts were prepared by the privately financed Nixon Library
and made public on its Web site (www.nixonfoundation.org).
</P>
<P>
   The material is part of the 201 hours of White House tapes
identified by an act of Congress as evidence of Nixon's ``abuse of
power.'' Those tapes were kept from the public during 22 years of
litigation by Nixon and, after his death, by his estate. They are a
fraction of the 3,600 hours of tape recordings from the Nixon White
House that eventually will be made public.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Taylor, executive director of the Nixon Library in Yorba
Linda, Calif., said in an interview that the abuses of power with
which Nixon was charged should be understood in the context of the
times, more than a quarter-century ago, amid social skirmishes over
race and class and sex, political battles over the future of the
country and more than 50,000 Americans dead in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Nixon was a wartime commander in chief,'' Taylor said.
``We were in a culture war then. And what the culture tends to
remember as the domestic abuses of Watergate can only be understood
in the context of these challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon and his most senior aides spent hours discussing plans to
use federal law enforcement agencies and intelligence services to
conduct domestic spying operations against Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Nixon personally approved the most radical of these
plans. It was called ``the Huston plan,'' after its author, Tom
Charles Huston, a White House aide. J. Edgar Hoover, director of
the FBI, blocked its full implementation five days later. Dean, who
in 1973 decided to cooperate with federal investigators in the
Watergate case, took a copy of the Huston plan with him when he
left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In the new transcripts, Nixon and his aides worry aloud about
the plan becoming public. One fragmentary transcript shows the
White House wondering if elements of the plan survived after Hoover
died in May 1972 and was succeeded by an acting FBI director loyal
to the Nixon White House, L. Patrick Gray.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oval Office on May 16, 1973, Buzhardt told Nixon about
his discussions with the deputy director of the National Security
Agency, Louis W. Tordella, about the Huston plan. The NSA conducts
international electronic eavesdropping, but like the CIA, it is not
supposed to spy on Americans at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything the NSA did is totally defensible,'' Nixon said,
referring to the Huston plan.
</P>
<P>
   Buzhardt replied: ``They move into a broader category with
respect to domestic affairs'' _ an illegal realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?'' Nixon asked. ``Electronic surveillance?''
</P>
<P>
   Buzhardt replied, ``Yes, sir, targeting U.S. citizens'
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon appeared unsure that the Huston plan had been turned off.
``DIA says that _ thinks it was terminated?'' he asked, referring
to the Defense Intelligence Agency, a Pentagon service that was
part of the Huston plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think it was terminated,'' Buzhardt said. ``Now, we're
going to check this thoroughly with NSA'' because ``they were the
most aggressive group.'' Referring to Tordella's notes on the
Huston plan, Buzhardt added: ``They never quite got a handle on it
until Pat Gray was appointed'' in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In that same conversation, Nixon anticipated a story saying
``the president authorized a super-duper activity in 1970''
involving ``burglary, etc., and wiretapping.'' Defiantly, he said
Americans would understand the plan was to control riots by people
protesting the Vietnam War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-25-99 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990225.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-25 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-MARKETPLACE-     02-25 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-MARKETPLACE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA MOVES TO AVOID TAKEOVER BY OLIVETTI 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia's board took some decisive steps Thursday
to thwart a rejiggered $60 billion hostile takeover offer from its
domestic rival Olivetti SpA in what promises to be a rancorous
brawl for control of Italy's biggest phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Without formally rejecting the offer from Olivetti, the board
called the proposal seriously flawed, and it supported a strategy
proposed by the chairman of Telecom Italia, Franco Bernabe, who
said he was more focused on squeezing value out of the company than
brewing poison pills to protect it.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to Olivetti by Telecom Italia's board came after
several hours of meetings in Milan with Bernabe. The board asked
him to present it with an outline of the benefits of his plan,
which mainly calls for integrating Telecom Italia's fixed-line
operations with the mobile phone unit Telecom Italia Mobile, in
which it now holds a 60 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would increase Telecom Italia's net worth and raise
the price Olivetti would have to pay by several billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to show the board how we can create value for the
company,'' Bernabe said in an interview, ``with precise steps and
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti first proposed buying Telecom Italia over the weekend
with a $60 billion package of cash and securities that marked one
of the biggest hostile takeover attempts of any company. Italian
stock market regulators ruled the bid invalid, but Olivetti
submitted a revised offer on Wednesday in the hope that it would
satisfy regulatory objections before Telecom Italia could take
defensive steps.
</P>
<P>
   Under Italian takeover laws, a valid bid prevents a target
company from changing its capital structure. But Bernabe says his
idea to combine Telecom Italia with its mobile phone subsidiary
preceded Olivetti's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to do anything that would look in any way like a
poison pill,'' Bernabe said. ``That only always hurts the company
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy's stock market regulatory agency, known as Consob, now has
two weeks to rule whether Olivetti's revised bid is valid.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the price of Telecom Italia's American
depository receipts, which rose through the week in the hope that
Olivetti would sweeten its bid for Telecom Italia, fell 1.6 percent
Thursday, to $107.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecom Italia board said in a statement that Olivetti's
renewed bid was ``full of holes in numerous aspects,'' including,
among other things, the antitrust implications of a bid by Telecom
Italia's major domestic competitor, the characteristics and quality
of its financing, the indebtedness it would produce and the absence
of an industrial plan and clear time frame.
</P>
<P>
   The board said it wanted to hear Olivetti's intentions in an
industrial plan with particular reference to Telecom Italia Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   It empowered Bernabe to seek clarification from Consob of the
validity of the renewed Olivetti bid without delay, including
clarification of the effects on Telecom Italia's freedom to act.
The ball is now clearly in Consob's court.
</P>
<P>
   The board also told Bernabe to present an industrial plan with
the ``synergy effects and creation of value'' that would arise from
the integration of Telecom Italia and its mobile phone unit.
</P>
<P>
   It said it would rigorously study Olivetti's proposals, taking
as the sole yardstick ``the interests of the shareholders of the
company and the maximization of the company's value.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Olivetti's bid, Bernabe said, did not hurt his ability to
formulate an industrial plan for the board, or to summon a
shareholder meeting for its approval. ``The only thing Olivetti
changes is the pace,'' he said. ``Subjectively, what happened is
that everybody in the company feels threatened, and is much more
willing to accept change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In normal times, it's always a lengthy process,'' he added.
``These are not normal times.''
</P>
<P>
   That was driven home late Thursday, when rumors circulated in
Milan that Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. might be considering support
for Olivetti in its hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors were fueled by the presence of investment bankers on
the Olivetti team who had recently advised Murdoch in an
unsuccessful effort to join Telecom Italia's Stream digital
television unit in a pay-for-view project. Murdoch lost interest
after the Italian government limited how much soccer, the engine
for pay-TV revenue in Europe, the station could sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch uses soccer as the ramrod for his European television
ventures. Support for Olivetti could afford Murdoch another shot at
Stream, the reasoning went.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman in London for the News Corp. would not comment on
the reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
