<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GROUP SEEKS CHANGE IN CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Republicans struggling behind the scenes to
assemble a post-impeachment agenda, a bipartisan group of House
members took advantage of the lull Thursday and called on the new
speaker to allow a vote early this year on a bill to overhaul the
nation's campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what we have been through with impeachment and,
preceding impeachment, the scandals, the campaign financing
scandals of the last presidential campaign in both parties,'' said
Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., ``this is the kind of legislation we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin Meehan, D-Mass., seeks to cut down on the influence of money
in politics. It would ban the unlimited and largely unregulated
donations to political parties that have been increasingly used to
circumvent the limits enacted after Watergate on contributions to
individual candidates. And it would curb independent groups from
running issue advocacy commercials attacking or supporting a
candidate within 60 days of an election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in both houses adamantly oppose the measure,
and the new speaker, J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, has given no
sign that he is any more supportive of it than was his predecessor,
Newt Gingrich. He has committed only to a vote sometime during the
106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give a date certain,'' Hastert said Wednesday, ``but
I gave my word that it would be on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   But his spokesman, John Feehery, gave a strong hint that it
would be put on the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some things that are higher priority right now,''
Feehery said, ``the budget, saving Social Security, providing for
the national defense and tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the House sponsors had to face down several obstacles
before they pulled off an improbable victory, passing the bill
252-179, with the support of 61 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shays and Meehan prevailed, the measure died in a
filibuster in the Senate. Opponents say the bill violates
constitutional guarantees of free speech and weakens political
parties. It would also eat into the Republicans' traditional
advantage in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The House sponsors want a vote early this year, to allow
political pressure to build on the Senate, as well as to try to put
the changes in place for the 2000 presidential election, which is
already getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said the political parties raised $75 million in
unregulated, or soft money, donations in 1992. The sums increased
to $262 million in the 1996 presidential year. And he said the
projections are the parties could raise $500 million to $700
million in the next Presidential cycle.
</P>
<P>
   To press Hastert, the sponsors are turning to Rep. Zach Wamp,
R-Tenn., to try to win over conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fiscal and social conservative,'' Wamp said. ``I plan to
be out there again trying to recruit people who think like me and
vote like me.''
</P>
<P>
   If that fails, conservative Democrats are prepared to gather
signatures on a petition to force the bill to the floor _ the
tactic that led Republican leaders to relent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
