<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTKA HAS BRIEF STINT AT HELM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ By this evening, Larry Drew or Kurt Rambis will be the
acting head coach of the Lakers, provided with a brief, 37-game
schedule to change the team's fortunes and perhaps enhance his own.
</P>
<P>
   That decision was being made by Lakers owner Jerry Buss,
executive Jerry West and general manager Mitch Kupchak late
Thursday and due to be announced this morning. Whichever of the two
Lakers assistants, Drew or Rambis, is hired, he will finish out the
season and have the chance to win the job permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Either choice is fine with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Kurt as a coach, definitely,'' Corie Blount said.
``To me, he always gives you that confidence, that no matter what
happens, stay ready. Whoever gets the job, it's not really gonna
matter, because we know what we have to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   But for one night, it was the Bill Bertka era again. It's an era
comprising not years but short spurts of hours and days spread over
two-plus decades.
</P>
<P>
   A 26-year assistant coach in the NBA, Bertka has had his brief
moments in the spotlight, filling in occasionally for both the New
Orleans Jazz and the Lakers. He figures he's coached probably a
dozen games when coaches took ill or were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's game was just his third, however, as the acting head
coach, an event that comes only after a firing. His lifetime
record: 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my opportunities earlier in my career,'' Bertka said of
taking a head coach position (he did serve as head coach at Kent
State and Hancock College, and has operated, with his wife, one of
the best scouting services for college coaches).
</P>
<P>
   But he wanted to keep his home in Santa Barbara, and he enjoyed
the closer relationship with players that assistant coaches have.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, once again, Bertka played the part of substitute
teacher, with a classroom of students on the verge of academic
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the most challenging aspect is to get them on the right
mental train at this point,'' he said. ``I know that the players
want to get this thing turned around and they're in a challenging
situation right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Worm watch: Even as a signed-and-delivered Laker, Dennis Rodman
was deemed too much a distraction to have in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt if he wasn't going to play, people would be asking why
he isn't playing,'' Lakers spokesman John Black said. ``Because of
the circus atmosphere following him everywhere he goes, it would be
a distraction for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is said to be in shape but needed another day of learning
the Lakers' system before playing. He participated in Thursday's
morning shootaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks as fit as anybody,'' Bertka said. ``Obviously, the
guy's a remarkable athlete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
