</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOTT SCORES TWICE AS DEVILS TIE BRUINS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a game in which both the New Jersey Devils and
the Boston Bruins got breaks Thursday night at the Fleet Center.
And nobody took better advantage than Jason Arnott, who scored
twice in the final period to help the Devils secure a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston scored the first goal for the Devils, who extended
their unbeaten streak against Boston to 10 games (7-0-3), the
longest stretch of domination against the Bruins by any NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison, Ray Bourque and Cameron Mann scored for the
Bruins against Martin Brodeur, who faced 28 shots, including three
in the overtime. The Devils took 39 shots, one in the overtime,
against Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Mann again showed his flair for the dramatic as his third-period
goal lifted the Bruins to a tie. All of Mann's four goals, scored
in the last three games, have been instrumental in Bruins victories
or ties.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, he scored on a shot from the point with 1:41 to
go. Mann scored two goals Tuesday when the Bruins beat Ottawa, 5-2.
He scored the winning goal in Chicago on Sunday. Both teams got a
huge break early in the third period. The Devils got theirs at 2
minutes 15 seconds, when a centering pass on the right by Petr
Sykora bounced off Arnott as he was falling into the goal. They all
count the same and this one counted as Arnott's 14th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's break came 66 seconds later when a shot by Bourque from
near the right boards bounced off the skate of Devils defenseman
Ken Daneyko and past a surprised Brodeur for Bourque's sixth of the
season. It tied the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils broke the tie on Arnott's second of the night, at
10:04, when he found the net from close range on the right after
Sykora's pass went between the skates of Don Sweeney, the Bruins'
usually reliable defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils withstood an early attack by the Bruins, who took six
of the game's first seven shots in the first four minutes. But New
Jersey dominated the rest of the opening period by limiting the
Bruins to just one shot while taking 13 against Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston scored his 18th of the season, with 3:11 left in the
opening period, when he beat Dafoe with a shot from the top of the
right circle after a pass by Bob Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston's goal was his third in two games and extended his
point-scoring streak to six games, matching his career high.
</P>
<P>
   A brilliant save by Dafoe from point-blank range on Patrik
Elias, eight minutes into the second period, after a marvelous
setup on the right by Sykora prevented the Devils from taking a
two-goal lead. The Devils had another opportunity shortly afterward
when they were awarded their second manpower advantage in the game,
but came up empty. The Bruins went on the attack in the second
period and tied the score at 11:32 when Allison dug the puck out
from under Brodeur's glove for his 17th of the season to send the
teams tied going into the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
